Living in a society with unprecedented material prosperity , human beings are faced with severe problems resulting from energy and resource shortage .
In order to sustain stable development for the next generation , people are paying more attention to building an eco-friendly society which makes energy usage reach its optimum potential .
Considering that there is mass energy wastage around the globe , one of the approaches to reducing energy usage is to construct a better transportation system that delivers energy more efficiently .
In engineering design processes , the steps towards solution generation , selection and testing are of vital importance to building an ideal energy transportation system .
Generating multiple solutions stimulates engineers ' creativity and provides impetus to create a technological breakthrough .
Such an approach enables engineers to think out of the box and challenge the old conventions , and subsequently forge innovative breakthroughs in fields such as , transportation systems and construction , that have hardly experienced any remarkable advancement in decades decades .
Following the solution generation step , analyzing and selecting a design ensures that the ultimate solution best suits for implementation .
The systematic evaluation approach applied in the engineering design process then facilitates engineers to generate a reliable judgement of the solutions .
Lastly , the testing state places the final solution into practice in the real world for further improvement . Although restrictions exists,
this step allows the solution to be exposed to the real-world variation and yields an even more trustworthy appraisal .
Nevertheless , simulating the real-world variation in accomplishing a huge project like constructing an energy efficient transportation system can not be fully comprehensive nor to create a full-scale prototype of the system is even more unrealistic .
As a result , the effectiveness and some concealed weaknesses of the design will not be fully traced during the test .
In Summary , although imperfection in the accuracy of testing still exists , the solution generating , analyzing and testing steps in engineering design processes play key roles in forging innovative breakthroughs , verifying the feasibility of the design and upgrading the final solution while designing an effective energy transportation system .
Throughout history , many innovations were created not for its intended application .
According to Rogers ( 2003 ) , the innovation process has six stages : needs/problem , research , development , commercialization , diffusion and adoption , and consequences .
Political , social and economic changes during this period would affect the process of innovation .
One such case is The Global Positioning System ( GPS ) .
Originally The United States government policy and the cold war situation shaped the invention of GPS .
In 1960 , GPS was introduced by US Department of Defense to track down its marines .
policy makers have played an important role in developing the GPS technology to be what it is today . .
Furthermore , in 1994 , since the cold war had ended , the US government decided to fully open the GPS for public use .
The turning point for GPS for civilian use happened in 1983 , when a civilian Korean aircraft was shot down by the Soviet Union for territory trespassing .
It raised the need for a reliable navigation system .
Hence , driven by social concern , President Reagan of The United States agreed to partially open the GPS for public use .
Soon after this , when the surveying market boomed in The 1980'ss , the demand for GPS and the money generated from it further contributed to the development of GPS for civilian use .
With regard to its development , GPS technology had a few setbacks .
The most notable setback was in 1979 , when the economic situation in The United States was bad .
The development of advanced technology was mainly carried out by government agencies .
Hence , when the economic situation worsened , the government agencies were affected .
This example also shows how The economy and politics are interrelated in determining an innovation .
In conclusion , political , economic , and social situations normally determine an innovation as shown in GPS .
Had the situation been different the commercialization of the GPS would not have been possible .
Hence , Technological development is partly socially determined .
As modern society is fast developing , human need becomes more diversified while problems of the shortage of resources becomes more serious .
Such kinds of conflict requires engineers to develop new products to meet all needs .
without creativity and innovation the tasks are never easy for engineers . engineers must design products which are both artistic and practical .
Designing products and finding solutions require a long term process , which is defined as The engineering design process .
According to Khandani , The engineering design process is a very important route for engineers to create products , it can be expressed as a 5-step process : " Define the problem " , " Gather pertinent information " , " Generate multiple solutions " , " Analyze and select a solution " , and " Test and implement the solution " ( Khandani , 2005 ) .
However ; there exist some problems that hamper engineering design processes for innovations .
Among them are the problems of plagiarism and the insufficiency of fund support for scientific research .
The problem of plagiarism is fairly s. A large number of university students do not do the academic work such as research reports and scientific essays on their own .
Many students choose to search sources on the Internet and submit their " work " perfunctorily , never mentioning about the original researchers or writers .
Plagiarism is not only harmful to the original researchers or writers , but is also an impediment for university students to gain creativity and innovative skills .
Plagiarism makes university students or even graduate researchers lazy to come up with their own ideas .
After obtain the information for their academic use , they simply follow the original train of thought and give up thinking about a different solution on their own .
However , such choices becomes harmful in the long run as the innovative skills of university students or researchers will deteriorate .
Plagiarism significantly hinders the five step process of gathering pertinent information in the engineering design process , which is about generating , analyzing , selecting , testing and implementing solutions .
For example , an engineering student who is doing a designing project does not have to analyze or select solutions , which is the fourth step in the engineering design process , if he chooses to plagiarize from other articles .
Therefore , it removes all the experience of encountering problems during the solution analyzing and selecting phase and all the innovative skills he can gain from the process .
Plagiarism directly gives students the final and the best solution , which seems good for him but quite harmful for the entire academic community .
If everyone plagiarizes to do their academic work and only tries to get higher marks , the problem of plagiarism may result in a more serious situation , in that , very few students graduating from universities can manage to develop innovative products as engineers .
If the university can not afford engineering students to do further testing or create an entire product , all the efforts that have been made in the previous steps come to naught .
The problem has a significant impact on the testing and implementing solutions step in the design process , during which an engineer may encounter different problems and choices .
Without the process of testing and implementing , students can not gain their practical skills or develop their innovative ideas for implementation .
Although the academic community in my home country is facing many problems which hamper innovations , the development of science and technology has never been thwarted .
I believe that one day all the problems will be solved and we will become strong in the academic field .
Technology is the application of scientific knowledge in industry and aims to improve our standard of living .
Its effects can be felt in almost every corner of the world and in our daily lives .
Technological innovations can range from household appliances to industrial equipment ,
they can be classified into two categories - research-based inventions such as the laptop computer like Toshiba and serendipitous inventions such as the " Post-it " notes developed by 3M .
when comparing the two technologies , it is clear that that an element of luck is more present in the former invention than in the latter one .
Nonetheless , luck is not the only determining factor for the birth of a technology , whether it is developed via research or resulting from a serendipitous discovery .
There are other contributing factors such as the efforts of the inventors and their determination to succeed that leads to the discovery of the technology .
The smallpox vaccine was first tested by Jenner in 1796 .
Hundreds of thousands people have been saved by these two discoveries .
Both the smallpox vaccine and penicillin are tremendous discoveries that have saved people 's lives and have been milestones in medicine that led people to explore new areas to fight diseases however ; the procedure of finding these two discoveries and the development of them are different .
One similarity of The smallpoxx vaccine and penicillin is that they are life-saving discoveries in medicine .
In the eighteen century before Jenner discovered The smallpox vaccine , smallpox was a widespread killer disease .
Jenner 's significant discovery was praised by the third United States President Thomas Jefferson in his letter 'Letter to Dr. Edward Jenner On his Discovery of the Small Pox Vaccine' .
( Scott , 1996 ) Penicillin is an antibiotic that prevents the growth of bacteria and cures infections .
After penicillin was discovered , the death rate by infection largely decreased .
Another similarity of these two discoveries is that they are landmarks in the field of medicine .
The smallpoxx vaccine was the first vaccine that people used to improve immunity to a certain disease .
After that , people started to develop vaccines to protect people from diseases such as hepatitis B , BCG and pertussis
Similarly , penicillin was the first antibiotic people used to cure infections .
After the discovery of penicillin , people realized that there was a new type of medicine , the antibiotic , which can kill bacteria and this resulted in research being conducted to develop more antibiotics .
More and more antibiotics were discovered and produced like aureomycin , erycin and chloromycetin .
Although the smallpox vaccine and penicillin have similarities , the procedure and development of these two discoveries are different .
Based on the observation that cowpox prevents smallpox , Jenner began researching into using cowpox to build immunity against smallpox .
After testing his theory , he successfully discovered the smallpox vaccine .
( Scott , 1996 ) In a few years time , his discovery was translated into many European languages and the smallpox vaccine was applied to prevent smallpox .
In contrast , penicillin was a serendipitous discovery .
Returning from his holiday to his laboratory in 1928 , Fleming found some penicillium notanum in some lab dishes .
The penicillium notanum could prevent the growth of bacteria .
( RSC , 2009 ) However , this discovery was not put into production
until 1940 , it was ten years after Feming 's discovery that penicillin went into mass production .
In conclusion , both the smallpox vaccine and penicillin are tremendous discoveries that saved the lives of numerous people , and they are milestones in medicine .
the procedure and development of these two discoveries however are different .
from the viewpoint of social construction of technology , many technological innovations and inventions are influenced and shaped by social factors ( Rogers , 2003 ) .
Social factors are classified into economic factors , military demands and government regulations .
These factors mainly include the investment of companies , needs of customers as well as for the purpose of saving energy .
First of all , the main reason for this innovation was that major corporations such as General Electric , General Motors , Kelvinator and Westinghouse considered that to invest in electric refrigerators instead of gas refrigerators would generate more profit ( Rogers , 2003 ) .
Refrigerators with a better mechanism as well as working capacity are demanded by the market .
The needs of customers affected the interests and decisions of investing companies , hence influencing the development of refrigerators as well .
In fact , some of the interests of corporations like General Electric are driven by customers demands .
What the customers were willing to buy gave rise to the preference of companies .
Production decisions are made to meet the market demand and maximize profit , underlyning these decisions lie in customer expectations
And the driving force behind this is for the purpose of saving energy and protecting limited resources on our planet .
Limited resources is a social problem which is of concern to both customers and producers who , facilitate the invention significantly .
This is one instance where social factors have largely influenced and shaped the technological innovation .
Many products in the world did not appear from nowhere but , they were made based on the creativity of engineers in response to human needs .
For instance , the invention of the telephone was to help people with long distance communication ; airplanes were made for shortening travel time ; wheel chairs enables the handicapped to travel about .
Creativity will not stop in one place ; it will move on from time to time to improve appliances or devices .
Based on Khandani ( 2005 ) , there are five phases of design process which will be elaborated in the subsequent paragraphs .
The first step of defining the problem is very important in order that an engineer would not lose his or her way when finding a solution .
Therefore , it is necessary to identify the need from this design activity and make a problem statement to ease the gathering of information choosing a solution and conducting an experiment .
The next step will be gathering information .
A survey related to the existence of similar products should be done to prevent issues of plagiarism .
Material being used for an artificial heart device is very important as human blood carries nutrients to body cells
hence ; , it should not be toxic as toxins could enter the bloodstream .
Size is also one of the factors to be considered
After collecting useful information , multiple solutions can be generated and this is the third phase of the design process .
These solutions could be a combination of strengths from existing products or new ideas to counter the weaknesses of existing products
The latest artificial heart device is made of polyether-based polyurethane plastic and able to withstand 100,000 beats a day ( Ditlea , 2002 ) .
Most engineer design products would factore cost into consideration .
The final step is implementation including testing , building and producing the solution based on the design problem .
Prototyping is important to provide a clearer picture of the real product .
It allows engineers to observe and point out the weaknesses to be improved .
in order that , it could be re- designed until a reasonable solution is reached .
Hence , the testing result will take some time to reach a conclusion .
In conclusion , the five steps of the engineer design process mentioned above has been organized in such a way to express creativity in the product designed for human need .
Although some products may take a longer time such as the artificial heart device . An engineer should not be afraid of taking risk and time .
It would bring great contentment if the product is fully used and is able to save human life .
Hence the reverse happens and technology is shaped socially to a much larger extent than it was in the past .
Hence the sales were poor in the initial years .
It was the same for the other laptops from other companies such as Toshiba and Apple computers .
Since then , the companies that manufacture laptops started doing intensive research and development to improve their products so as to create a product that people would be willing to buy .
Hence from this we can see how technological development was shaped by economic factors .
The low demand for the first laptop caused the companies to suffer losses in the business and thereby forced them to work harder to develop it to be more commercially viable ,to boost their sales to survive with many competitors in this field of portable computing technology .
Today the laptops weigh only a small fraction of their predecessors but with greater computing power .
Hence the sales of the laptops increased substantially and the companies made profits .
But not all commercially available products can withstand the rigorous demands of the military which requires the laptops to be tough , water- resistant and have a long battery life .
The demands by not just the SAF but also other big militaries around the world also shaped at how the laptop was able to adapt to be just as reliable in the extreme conditions .
Moreover , the technology that resulted from developing the toughbooks can be applied and used to some extent in the commercial world .
But people have unlimited wants , they are not content with just the laptop which is considered quite bulky at times , thus they demanded laptops that are smaller and lighter .
The laptop is indeed an important technology that is shaped by economic , military factors , and consumer demands .
However , having been popular for less than 100 years , Electric vehicles had all disappeared by 1935 ( The History of Electric Vehicles,2009 ) .
Rogers indicated in his article " The Generation of Innovations " that the innovation-decision process is very crucial to the adoption of a new technology , because not only the technical factors but also economic , political and social factors play an important part .
Electric cars have a very obvious shortage in their technical design .
Due to the limitation of its weight , size and the battery technology , the battery used in the electric cars at that time was limited to a range of 100 miles ( Rogers,2003 ) .
As a result , they were not convenient enough .
Instead , Hydrogen fuel cell was brought in to substitute the electric battery .
In order to improve the air condition , consumers had to spend more and compromised on a limited range of electric cars .
And since the electric cars did not have engines and some other components , the car companies could no longer benefit from the maintenances of those cars .
As for the oil companies , apparently , they could not make money from oil , if all the engine driven cars were substituted by electric cars .
Moreover , the main stream of the government did not approve of this invention .
Although the California and Arizona state government came up with a mandate that " at least 10 percent of the total sales of automobile companies would have to be nonpolluting " ( Rogers,2003 ) , they had to cancel the command since the electric vehicles failed to act in the public interest .
Moreover , the Federal Government stepped in this case to oppose the California and Arizona state government .
Furthermore , other social factors contributed to the non-adoption of electric cars .
The consumers had many concerns and were unwilling at that time .
Since electric vehicles were very light , they could be quite fragile if they were hit by heavy vehicles .
In conclusion , technology , economic , political and social factors resulted in the non-adoption of electric cars .
We can gain important lessons from the failure of the electric cars , we should not only focus on certain factors to develop a new technology .
Only by addresssing the many needs can a new technology survive and be accepted .
In this essay , I will use the invention of internet as an example to show how this important technology was determined initially by a specific group of users , mainly government and military personnel , and later commercialized into what it is today .
Unlike the development of some inventions like Post-its which was a serendipitous discovery the internet was a strategic innovation that was initiated by the government and developed by their researchers .
In order to understand the reasons for the need of Internet by The U.S. Government , we will need to understand the historical background during the middle of the twentieth century .
During the Cold War period , world politics was divided between democracy and communism .
In the 1950s , the Soviet Union tested their first atomic bomb resulting in the world having two nuclear super powers that were at conflict with each other over world political dominance and military superiority .
This inevitably sparked off the arms race .
Meanwhile , the growing dominance of The Soviet Union over Eastern Europe also threatened the position of the U.S. as the world 's most powerful nation .
The Cold War and the arms race stimulated the research and development of all technological fields in the U.S. including improving communication infrastructure between the government and military planners .
One very important strategic issue that the U.S.Government had to ponder was maintaining command and control between the political and military leaders in the event of an attack by The Soviet Union .
The communication infrastructure that was vulnerable to any attacks via the use Inter Continental Ballistic Missile ( ICBM ) on the U.S. The cities phone lines were dependent on a centralized system of above ground lines .
The Department of Defense needed a more secure and indestructible communication system to survive a nuclear war and so it funded the development of a network that would be indestructible and have technological capabilities to launch a counter-offensive against enemies of the United States .
The packets would then be forwarded from one computer to another computer until the information arrived at its final destination computer .
The packets would be encoded as electrical signals , light , or radio waves and transmitted via copper cables , fiber-optic strands and the ether ; which consists of microwave , satellite , or radio transmissions .
This was an important part of a computer network .
As a result of decentralization , packet switching , unlike the telephone system , will not break down when one part of the network system is faulty since the packets can be rerouted until it arrives at its intended destination .
The next two decades witnessed the improvisation and spread of networking .
Network Control Protocol ( NCP ) was developed by VInt Cerf and Bob Kahn in 1973 to allow network communication between people using different hardware .
For instance in 1973 , the U.S. connected its network to both the United Kingdom and Norway .
In the mid 1970 's , networks began to spread to research universities across America and internationally .
The frustrated Duke students Tom Trusscott and James Ellis , and Steve Bellovin , a student , created Usenet .
Although there were over 230 ARPANET sites in 1982 , Usenet took less than two years to reach that number .
This resulted in hundreds of discussion groups , each discussing different subjects , which range from politics to daily life experiences .
The explosive growth of network usage resulted in all of the networks switching from NCP to TCP/IP in 1983 .
In 1987 , the National Science Foundation , which had funded a program earlier in 1984 to create national infrastructure to provide a variety of academic institutions access to a larger national academic network , backed away from funding the Internet and allowed giant corporation such as IBM , MCI and Merit Corp to manage and support the infrastructure it had funded .
It was not until 1993 when the Internet was transformed from government-funding to commercialization by private sectors .
With the creation of World Wide Web by Tim Berners-Lee at CERN , the European Nuclear Research Centre , the World Wide Web opened up a new era of individualism and creativity that would change the information age once and for all .
In conclusion , it was the historical background during the era of the Cold War that prompted the US government to consider new ways of creating indestructible communication to enable the political and military leaders to communicate with each other during a nuclear attack .
Through the works of brilliant researchers , the Internet , which was limited to a few users at first , was improvised to accommodate increase electronic traffic and finally commercialized to be available to each and every individual .
Technology is an act of designing and inventing of a tool that will either solve a recognized problem or fulfill a particular human need , in other words it is a product of society .
The case study on Cowan ( 1985 ) is a representative example of a failure of a product due to economic factors , in which an aggressively advertised product was preferred over the other that could be more advantageous .
Cowan ( 1985 ) discussed the two types of refrigerators developed , the electric refrigerator and the gas refrigerator .
The gas refrigerator should have been the preferred product since it provided several advantages but it turned out to be otherwise .
The extensive promotion of the electric refrigerator , whose research and development was funded by corporations , influenced the choice of consumers since the gas refrigerator was not widely promoted and made known to consumers .
Such cases are typical examples of how a technological invention is shaped by economic factors , in which the technology made available to the consumer was directed by earned profits of corporations instead of offering the one that benefits the consumer most .
One of the reasons behind such situations is probably due to corporations ' fear of losing their share of the market and thus suppressing new technology to minimize chances of it happening .
Another contributing factor of the success of invention will be the buying power of the consumer , which very much depends on the economic situation .
In times of economic recession , there is a lower tendency for consumers to purchase the more expensive refrigerator when both have the same primary functions that is to store up food at low temperature .
For that , the competition among corporations and the extent of price slashing they are willing to offer , such that they still earn considerable profit may help improve consumer 's acceptance of their product .
Therefore , it can be concluded that functionality may not be the only determining factor to the success of technology since it may not be the priority of consumer 's concern , but rather how the technology is commercialized and diffused to the public or society .
As such , technology nowadays needs not only to prove its functionality but also spend efforts in creating awareness since it is up to the consumers , who come in contact with many advertisements in their life and is eventually conditioned , to make decisions .
Due to the flourishing of construction industries over the years , construction industries worldwide consume resources equivalent to more than what nature is able to produce on Earth .
at this rate of consumption , our environment will not be able to supply us with sufficient resources years down the road .
In order to compensate and preserve the e , there is a need to implement a system whereby waste construction materials can be treated and re-used .
This implementation will help : protect the environment by controlling the amount of resources consumed ; reduce the cost of manufacturing and importing raw materials ; reduce the cost of construction ; andven maximise economic advantages .
Therefore , introducing the and reusing of construction waste materials is wise construction practice and ais beneficial to contractors , owners and communities .
Most of the discarded materials are actually valuable commodities ; such as concrete , wood , asphalt , metal and cardboard , and can be recycled into new products .
These materials make ? up to 80 percent of discarded materials .
In fact , recycling and reusing these materials can benefit the environment , the construction business and the economy
The process of recycling construction waste involves separating and reusing recoverable and useable waster construction materials during demolition .
The advantage of this treatment system is that it only produces low-cost recycled materials , it also produces new composite materials with better characteristics .
However , a considerations should be taken into account during the design process .
During the remodelling of buildings , most construction waste goes into landfillsl , hence the increasing burden on landfill loading .
This waste may be high in chemical content which results in water and soil pollution .
Whereas some can be recycled and re-used as similar material , others are reconstituted to other forms of usable materials .
Moreover , recycling which needs reprocessing may not be economically feasible because it requires a facility using recycled resources to be located near the source .
Thus , site separation is an important step for recycling construction waste .
Khandani ( 2005 ) described engineers as creators as well as problem solvers who invent and design .
He also stated that engineering design is a process of creative thinking , of turning ideas to physical products . IT it is also a system which is created by human effort and does not suddenly appear from nowhere . to fulfil the needs of humans and to help humans ? governments ? people ? solve the planet 's environmental problems. .
In fact , re-cycling waste construction materials is just the same , it is a technology used to support human needs for living by building infrastructures and helping to solve difficulties by cutting down the consumption of natural resources to save the Earth .
The world today is changing continuously causing it to face many global challenges and problems .
As a result , technologies are constantly being constantly developed in order to response to human needs .
an example of such a technology is the development of tomato- harvesting machines as an agricultural scientist at the University of California at Daris predicted that there will be a serious shortage of the labour in California ( Rogers , 2003 ) .
One example is the discovery of Penicillin by Sir Alexander Fleming when he realized the presence of an antibacterial agent while researching on influenza .
This lead to the birth of the Penicillin which is widely used as an antibiotic ( Mary Bellis , About.com ) .
Although the two technologies were created from a very different approach , both underwent the innovation-development process where the final product could be marketed .
According to Rogers ( 2003 ) , the innovative development process consists of all the decisions , activities , and their impacts that occur from recognition of a need or a problem through research , development , and commercialization of an innovation , up until the diffusion and adoption of the innovation by users .
For a technology that is deliberately invented , it generally requires a much longer time frame as compared to fortuitous discoveries .
This is because inventors have to generate multiple solutions to solve the problem identified .
Much research has to be prepared so that the best solution can be found .
In the case of the tomato harvesting machine , there are plenty of factors that need to be considered .
However in the case of the serendipitous discoveries , identifying a problem or need as well as selecting the best solutions are eliminated .
Hence the total time consumed is much shorter than compared to the technology developed through research .
However , no matter whether it is created intentionally or unintentionally , both require the ability to think creativity and innovatively as well as some coincidence and luck .
In the case of a deliberate technology , inventors must not restrict themselves to only one solution but expose themselves to the various possible solutions .
These solutions have to be analyzed and researched further until the best solution is found .
If luck is present with coincidence , the best solution will be generated in a shorter time .
similarly the person must have the ability to view things from a different perspective , have sufficient background knowledge about the serendipitous discoveries , and have some luck for serendipitous discoveries to take place .
Since fortuitous discovery often occurs while research is carried out in a totally unrelated field , scientists must be able to identify the technology that was come by accidentally .
In conclusion , the of inventing a new technology is to meet the needs of humans .
In addition , luck and coincidence must be present for the discovery to happen at the right time , right place and to the right person .
With all these factors , the time taken to develop a new technology will be shortened .
Rogers ( 2003 ) brought forward the idea that society is coming to a generation of innovation , which implies that innovation is gradually becoming the main task of various enterprises and scientific research .
In newspapers everyday , it is usual to find news regarding some business adopting a new technology .
However , the products in the market are not updating as fast as the innovation introduced to the public .
Firstly , the new technology must satisfy consumer needs needs .
Before the refrigerator was introduced to the mass market , there was a competition between two prototypes of refrigerator .
Furthermore , the gas type hardly has noise , which solves the most severe problem regarding noise ( Cowan , 1985 ) .
Because of these overwhelming advantages , people expected that gas refrigerators would dominate the consumer market .
The example of refrigerator competition shows that whether to adopt a new technologor not depends on social factors other than consumer needs .
To continue the previous example , the reason why the gas type lost in the competition is due to high research and development costs , thought electrical refrigerators would make more profit , so they invested large amounts of money into producing electrical refrigerators and developing the market .
The aggressive occupancy of the market compelled smaller companies which prefer producing gas refrigerators to give up .
Mostly , they will give reverse responses after considering different angles , but people can still make decisions based on the more crucial factor or the factor they are concerned with the most .
Apart from consumer needs and production costs , other factors like environmental problems , military demands and government regulations also affect the adoption of a new technology .
To sum up , in the generation of innovation , the development of technology is not just technologically decisive , but also more socially decisive .
When scientists or companies decide to adopt a new technology , social factors will directly affect their decisions .
A good technology without profit will not .
Hence , It can be concluded can conclude that social factors can determine the fortune of a new technology .
However , in recent years , this has been observed by an increasing number of droughts , dried-out wells , and unavoidably , a change in climate pattern across the globe .
The high demand for , and the misuse of water are increasing .
In the last few years , engineers have indeed innovatively managed and minimized water deficit in many countries by conveying solution ideas into engineering designed products and systems .
Throughout centuries , one of the most remarkable engineering structures or products to manage water has been the design of a large water storage tank , otherwise known as a dam .
As science and technology advanced , brilliant engineers began designing dams that were not only for flooding control and storing of water , but were to generate energy .
Some of the latest dams of our time can store water like a reservoir , prevent flooding occurrence , generate energy by means of water pressure ,
These are evident through Singapore 's 'Marina Barrage' .
Water treatment has largely been classified being engineering process which turns used-water into clean , acceptable water for end use , and sometime even drinkable water .
Dirty water is usually collected through piping systems from lakes , drains and household , and transported to a treatment plant .
Water transportation is made possible through engineered piping systems .
This process and system assist in the growing of crops in dry areas especially during periods of inadequate rainfall .
Engineers in recent years have been working creatively and innovatively to properly treat and manage water .
With advancements in technology , these are all made possible and there is even purified drinkable water treated from wastewater .
In certain countries , dried-out lands are even brought alive through water irrigation , where water is stored up somewhere and constantly transported through pipes to these lands .
Engineering products and system designs are not simply a design for aesthetical purposes , but also technologically meet some of the greatest human needs , water deficit .
From five aspects - discovery , creativeness , time taken , acceptance of the project by a and also from problem solving - we can see that there are similarities and differences in these two approaches .
The examples I am using for this essay on and development via research is 3M Post-it pads and Toshiba laptops respectively .
One of the well-known accidental inventions , according to E.M. Rogers ( 1950 ) , happened several decades ago , when a 3M researcher found a new bonding agent , but decided it was worthless because it did not stick paper very tightly to a surface .
This failure was converted into a successful product when a 3M researcher used the new bonding agent to create " Post-it " .
As for laptops which were via research , Mizoguchi foresaw that a portable personal computer could be invented when he visited the United States with an R&D team form Toshiba .
But for Mizoguchi , he set his target on developing a laptop .
However , both inventions required creative thinking in order to produce excellent products .
For serendipitous discovery , the time taken is considered short .
As it happens , producing a new bonding agent that did not stick paper tightly to a surface , which is not originally what the 3M researchers wanted , but was what one of the researchers used to create " Post-it " . This then became one of the most profitable products in 3M company .
Whereas , most developed technology via research took a long time because they needed to keep researching and trialing things out , if they failed , they would try again until it became an invention .
Nevertheless , both of the inventions required time and effort to create miracles in the world .
fourthly the difference between accidental invention and research to develop products is the problem ( that ) researchers are solving .
Last but not least , one of the major problems with serendipitous discovery is that it requires an extra step to get approval from a company in order to mass produce or even continue to do the project .
Be it serendipity or developed through research or inventions developed through research it benefits human lives .
This is made possible due to the innovations engineers have produced to improve the lives of mankind .
According to khandani , Khandani ( 2005 ) , engineering design consists of five steps : defining the problem , gathering information , brainstorming for solutions , selecting the best solution and finally the implementation of the solution .
This process requires certain skills from the engineer , such as creativity , the and to learn from failure .
In Singaporengapore , the local society and education system produces problems that hinder the usage of the engineering design process .
Learning is still heavily dependent on textbooks today .
Whether students learn or not depends on the outcome of major examinations such as GCE 'O ' and 'A ' levels .
These skills are critical to the two stages of the design process , but are lacking in locals due to the effect of the education system .
Another problem faced by Sngapore is society 's mindset .
Life in ingapore is highly competitive and fast paced , hence parents believe that their children must possess outstanding paper qualifications to survive .
Moreover , the majority of the locals are apathetic to their surroundings .
To be able to define a problem , the innovator must be observant enough to see the problem , and be bothered to do something to improve it , hence creating an innovation .
These skills are vital to the two stages of the process , therefore society 's mindset poses a problem to the design process .
If these problems are rectified , then Singapore will have more innovators , and hopefully more useful innovations to improve people 's lives .
This made electric cars more expensive than petrol-run cars .
Besides economic factors , government regulations and laws also played a part in shaping electric vehicles .
In addition , tax rebates and incentives added to the attractiveness of buying an electric vehicle .
These offers made by the government made these vehicles competitive against petroleum cars in price .
Therefore , it can be seen that the government 's involvement in promoting environmentally-friendly vehicles has affected how marketable electric vehicles are .
Moreover , psychological factors of owning an electric vehicle have affected the outcome of electric vehicles in the market .
A technical limitation of the electric vehicle is range of travel it can offer .
Although families who needed a car as a mode of transport did not usually need to travel for long distances , there is a psychological perception of having their freedom being restricted .
Hence , they will prefer a petroleum car which has the potential to allow them to travel farther .
In short , there are several factors that could have shaped electric vehicles .
However , there is a close relationship between the social factors and the technical challenges that electric vehicles face .
Hence , the recognition of electric vehicles by society could be affected by both social factors and challenges faced by the present technology of the electric vehicle .
Human needs and problems are the motivation for conceiving new ideas and designing new products .
In Singapore , and other countries next to the equator , air conditioners and electric fans have greatly contributed to people 's lives and people are able to enjoy cool and refreshing air on burning hot days .
In ancient times heat and humidity tortured people a lot .
Fans were generally made from leather or palm leaves sewed together .
It relieves discomfort in summer .
It was disturbing to shake a fan at work or during sleep .
After careful design and a hard process of trial and error , the first electric fan was created .
The advent of the electric fan was a great success and it was implemented around the world .
People 's needs were met by the air vortex flow which automatically .
As time went by , the electric fan seemed to be unsatisfactory .
It can not really cool the temperature and does not control humidity .
It proved to be effective in manipulating the heat and lowering humidity .
The air conditioner was so effective that despite its relatively high price , it was integrated into people 's lives and installed everywhere .
People feel more comfortable on hot days .
The design was initiated by people 's needs , and it ultimately met people 's needs .
More developed and enhanced functions will be added to improve people 's lives better and better .
Without it , our society could not have progressed , nor would our lives have become convenient .
According to Roster ( 2003 ) , technology innovation development is a process that with recognition of a problem or need , which arouses research and development activities designed to create an innovation to solve the problem or need .
As different countries have different ways of performing these stages .
So during the process , they encounter different obstacles , such as political issues , and financial issues .
In China , currently two factors that hamper the technology innovation process severely are the education system and the economic situation .
Firstly , the education system in China is imperfect in the way it educates engineers as it in someway hinders them from realizing their creativity and innovation .
University is an ideal place to cultivate engineers and to them for their future career .
Due to poor quality research facilities and the imperfect way of teaching , students can not gain enough skills to become a qualified engineer .
As a consequence , they can not successfully the innovation process .
Besides , the connection between universities , research institutions and the commercial sector is not close enough .
Moreover , more efforts are needed if they want to commercialize the product from their research .
Therefore , many issues that serve as anti-force are aroused during the innovation progress .
Besides education problems , the economic situation also produces barriers to the innovation process .
China is still a developing country , and with the boom in the economy , many problems have also arisen .
The mismatch between low levels of technological development on the one hand , and the enormous velocity of the catch-up process on the other makes companies unwilling to innovate on their own .
The main aim of entrepreneurs is to bring higher profits in a shorter time to their company .
Consequently , companies choose to import or imitate them from other countries instead of developing on their own .
In the year 2005 , foreign investment corporations accounted for more than half of China 's export , and research-intensive high value added products are still largely imported .
Compared with 30 million which the US government put in life science research , 0.25 million is really tiny ( Factors that hamper innovation in China , 2004 ) .
In addition , the economic situation and current circumstances , as well as financial problems also create barriers for innovation to take place .
These vectors hamper engineering design process significantly .
Hopefully , these problems can be eliminated in future and the situation can become better and better .
Look around and you will most probably notice people driving in their cars , talking on their phones or busy typing away on their personal computers .
The release of information is usually done by companies which want to flaunt their superiority over other similar companies competing in the same market .
New innovations contrived in skunkworks environments usually revolutionize the world and propel the company which invented it to new heights while that is not the case for conventional technology .
The invention of personal computers in IBM 's skunkworks completely changed the way in which the world operates , and made IBM the forerunner in computers , but the upgrading of the computers with ordinary technical knowledge did not really lead people onto a new path , instead it only resulted in the proliferation of many small computer-based companies .
Despite the differences , both technologies share some common traits .
Secondly products that emerge from both technologies can be used for a long time .
Using the previous examples , the P-80 jet was used for close to 30 years before being replaced completely , while the HIV vaccine may be in use forever if the vaccine undergoes successful research .
With rapid urbanization and the world population increasing into the future , housing may prove to be a challenging issue .
The main steps to consider in a good and proper housing system are affordability , durability and safe living conditions .
Hence the main solution to the problem of improper housing would be the reduction of housing costs without compromising on quality .
Building proper houses or flats usually requires a lot of finance .
On being unable to obtain a proper home , shanty houses are the next and only alternative that the homeless can approach .
Moreover , health dangers are prevalent when certain waste materials are used in the shelter construction according to the article , 'Give Me Shelter : The Global Housing Crisis , ' by Environmental Health Perspectives .
Furthermore , squatters in slums do not have proper sewer systems and a clean water sources .
Being aware of the rising problem the solutions needed for a better housing system can be identified .
Cost and labor friendly procedures for house and flat construction could be adapted for cheaper production .
After consolidating these solutions , their feasibility can then be measured by testing them a real society .
Upon successful implementation , The necessary adjustments or assessments based on the effectiveness of the solutions . can be made .
There are many other processes that can be applied to solve this issue , but an engineering design process is probably the best approach .
Since entering the 21st century , mankind has been with a growing number of challenges and threats .
Global warming is partly caused by the overuse of fossil fuels and the War in Iraq is mainly a result of the need for petroleum by the USA while the threat of China actually refers to China 's huge demands of resources including energy resources to satisfy the high-speed development of China .
Therefore , among all the current human needs , the need for energy , i should be given priority .
In meeting this need , engineering design processes plays an important role .
As we know , the storage and transportation of hydrogen have been two major factors that restrict the wide use of hydrogen .
Engineers need to find the right materials and design a suitable container for hydrogen so that it can be safely transported and stored .
In terms of solar energy , to improve the utilization and to reduce the cost of use is a problem left for engineers .
In China , millions of families have already used solar water heater for years , which saved amounts of electricity .
Otherwise , it would be an embarrassing situation that the saved energy can not pay the cost of solar panels , which would make solar energy .
In the process of exploiting fossil fuels , engineering design helps to find scientific methods to improve resource recovery and reduce resource wasting .
In addition , deep processing of fossil fuels also needs engineering design to improve the utilization of fossil fuels .
For example , during the process of exploiting oil , the byproducts like natural gas are often burned since it is hard to collect and store .
Lastly , , engineering design processes can help to reduce energy waste .
Engineers are trying to find a superconducting material that can work at room temperature to take place of traditional conducting materials .
Furthermore , energy- saving appliances designed by engineers have saved inestimable energy for the world .
In the coming years , human demand for energy will be increasing whereas renewable energy sources are decreasing .
Engineers have obligation to solve this problem .
With breakthroughs different domains in science , engineers should shoulder up the responsibility of making these breakthroughs available for people and therefore benefit humankind .
The survival of humanity in this century is heavily dependent on the role of Engineers and they should be prepared for potential threats and challenges .
In fact , usage of RFID on individuals causes more harm than good as it not only intrudes our privacy ( Channel 3000 , n.d. ) , but our security would also be compromised instead of being enhanced .
Similarly , an individual 's privacy such as 'habits and movements ' should also be kept unknown to the government ( Channel 3000 , n.d. ) .
Arguments have been put forth that the RFID tags on individuals could be programmed in such a way as to minimize information leakage .
Data generated from RFID tags of individuals could also be abused by the intended receivers such as surveillance officers ( BBC News , 2006 ) , adding on a whole new level of security breach .
Although a complete ban on RFID is impossible , its usage on individual tracking should be banned as it intrudes upon our privacy and compromises our security .
[ i ] The controversy was brought up when deciding if individuals have the final say to reveal such testing as genetic discrimination might surface when the results of such testing are made known to a third party .
Since genetic testing is beneficial , some governments have come up with legal procedures that would protect sufferers from genetic discrimination .
However , these laws are usually limited [ ii ] .
[ iii ] In addition , the accountability of such results is questionable considering that the result is often subject to interpretation or analysis .
Similarly , since the disease might not manifest itself even if one is tested positive , no one should have the right to reveal the results as it is difficult to verify the exactitude of the results .
RFID is a kind of surveillance technology which uses tags and readers to gather information about items attached with the tags .
While surveillance technology has contributed a lot to the society , it has also caused troubles such as privacy and security issues ( Anonymous 2007 ) .
Thus proper rules and regulations are needed for surveillance technology ; in other words , the use of surveillance technology should be banned in a certain degree .
Privacy issue is the one that most people are concerned about .
( Anonymous 2007 ) Moreover , it is very difficult to get rid of RFID tags as these chips are too thin and tiny to be found and disabled ( Surinder MB 2008 ) .
Hence , if the information is open to everyone , our safety in daily lives will not be ensured anymore .
However , people may argue that surveillance technology is introduced to help ensure security , and it indeed works very well in preventing crimes from occurring and in providing information for investigation .
In conclusion , surveillance technology should be banned to a certain extent to ensure that privacy is protected and the security issue is solved too .
As an emerging technology , genetic testing is getting more and more related to people 's life as it is being applied to predictions and diagnoses of diseases .
Since it could indicate the onset of diseases in the future , the results of genetic testing may tag a person with " having inherited defects " ( Buchanan , n.d. ) .Therefore , it has sparked a controversy over whether the individual requesting genetic testing should have the final say in whether to reveal the results .
Genetic testing creates tension within a family because it conveys people the information of getting ill and it also implies that other family members have the possibility of having the same defect genes ( Kahn,2000 ) .
Besides , it is disadvantageous for getting a job with results showing that an individual is genetically inferior .
In conclusion , the results of genetic testing do have big impacts upon people 's life in terms of emotional impacts and genetic discrimination .
Therefore , the individual requesting genetic testing should have the final say in whether to reveal the results , and this is also in agreement with protecting human rights .
Genetic testing is a kind of test which determines the vulnerabilities of an individual to inherit genetic disorders ( U.S National Library of Medicine , 2009 , para .
The results obtained from a genetic test can exclude an alleged genetic condition or help verify if a person is a carrier of a genetic disease or have a chance to develop a genetic disorder in future ( U.S National Library of Medicine , 2009 , para .
If the foetus is diagnosed with the mutation , the couple can then choose to terminate the pregnancy ( Norrgard , 2008 , Family Planning , para .
Furthermore , it is also unfair to the insurance companies if the individual with a genetic disease decides to buy life insurance policies without revealing that they have such genetic disorder .
This technology allows for more effective tracing of an individual through an instant identification approach .
The tracking of patients is particularly useful in the protection of infant babies , alzcheimer 's patients and others with special vulnerabilities ( Dr. Counse , n.d. ) It alerts the staff should the patient encounter a mishap or wander away .
The RFID wrist tags also code for information regarding the patient .
Important data such as the appropriate medication and meal requirements can be easily retrieved , thereby facilitating the job of the nurses .
It helps provide increased attention and care for the welfare of the patients .
RFID may revolutionize our society in future but at the very moment , it is still in its infant stage where its benefits have yet to warrant a widespread implementation while its disadvantages are insurmountable .
Secondly , RFID infringes on one 's privacy in the process of tracking the various information associated with that person ( Ahson , 2007a ) .
When these devices are used on items that cost only a few dollars , it makes one wonder whether one is paying for the item or for the delivery process .
Some may argue that at-risk relatives should be informed about their susceptibility to genetic diseases , so that they can take early precaution or seek appropriate treatment to the diseases .
Surveillance technology has brought us many applications in many areas of our life .
First of all , RFID has played an important role in preventing crimes .
From the security 's point of view , RFID can provide more precise and complete information on suspects or criminals , which results in the reduction in time and manpower for an investigation .
In other words , when combined with the " intelligent video security system using image process " technology which can " detect unexpected movement or unusual behavior that can pose a threat to people , property and infrastructure " , RFID will be able to prevent many potential risks from criminals or dire threat like terrorism ( Focus Group Meeting on Technology Convergence , 2008 ) .
RFID can also protect the Homeland security of a country from many threats when it is used on its own .
When travelers cross a border of a country , if they have " an RFID-enabled border crossing document " , the Border Protection Office or Immigration Office can collect identification and citizenship information of travelers and then rapidly determine if they are threats to the country or not , based on the world-wide security information system shared by many Governments ( Use of Radio Frequency Identification ( RFID ) Technology for Border Crossings , 2008 ) .
Another key application of RFID is that RFID helps to improve the healthcare sector .
The wristband with embedded transponder which can be seen in many hospitals all over the world is designed basically based on RFID technology .
Thus , it can warn the management system of the hospital if an unauthorized person tries to break into a restricted area or a patient tries to leave the medical centre ( RFID in hospitals , retrieved from the Internet ) .
For instance , it is more safe now for patients who have mental diseases if they are lost , because they are being tracked all the time in the hospital under the surveillance system like RFID .
However , others argue that RFID technology has infringed upon privacy rights of human beings .
They claim that information from RFID devices can be approached by a third party and RFID can be used to track individuals illegally if the technology is well-known ( Postnote from Parliamentary Office of Science and technology , 2004 ) .
Restricted uses and laws have been applied to RFID technology ; hence , the information of individuals can only be seen by authorized people legally with a positive purpose .
And the fact is that most people will choose safety and security between security and privacy .
To conclude , it is indisputable that the advantages of surveillance technology outweigh the negative effects .
In conclusion , surveillance technology such as RFID should not be banned because it not only improves security system for people and country but also enhances the healthcare sector .
The first reason is related to the patient 's family who may share the risk of inheriting the genetic defects if one of the family 's members is diagnosed with a dominant genetic disease ( Norrgard , 2008 ) .
It is very unfair for his or her family if the result is not disclosed to them . Moreover , if the disease can begin to show any symptom only when it is in the final stage , then the life of the person may be at danger .
For instance , a couple diagnosed with SMA * may think of alternative ways of having children for example by IVF * * .
However , as argued before , everybody 's genes may be linked to their relatives ' genes , so it is possible for the relatives particularly their siblings to inherit the same defective gene .
Others reason for instance in the medical insurance case that it is unfair to charge an individual with genetic defects at a higher rate since the defects are not what they want ( Norrgard , 2008 ) .
But again , if they are charged at the same rate with normal people then they are being unfair to others and the insurance company since the treatment fee for genetic diseases is high .
To conclude , the individual requesting for genetic testing should not have the final say as it is unfair to the medical insurance company and the person 's relatives who may also be at risk of inheriting the same genetic defects .
Since the attack on the London Underground on July 2005 , surveillance technology has generated a lot of attention after it was used to track the movements of the terrorists responsible for the attack .
Reports and articles have shown that the use of surveillance technology to track people can be beneficial to us , particularly in the healthcare and crime prevention sectors and in the enhancement of security .
If a patient suddenly collapses in her room and there is no one to alert the nurse , it will probably take one or more hours for her to be saved when the nurse goes around to check on the patients .
By that time , the patient 's life would be in danger and this would most probably bring about dire consequences such as death .
Not only that , if indeed a crime happens , the prison guards will be able to investigate and know who the culprit is .
Thirdly , surveillance technology can also be used to keep track of our children and prevent kidnapping .
In conclusion , surveillance technology should not be banned to track people as it can not only save life but also improve the healthcare sector while enhancing the security of our society .
The main issue pertaining to this is that when an individual chooses not to disclose the result of the genetic testing , it is actually unfair to and has adverse impacts on both his family and his employer .
The result of the genetic testing concerns parties other than the individual alone , and therefore , the individual requesting genetic testing should not have the final say on whether or not the results should be revealed to others .
Firstly , when an individual is tested to be positive for genetic disorder , he would often be reluctant to share the result with others , even his closest kin .
This is unjust to the family members as they have also the possibility of suffering from the genetic disorder .
They should thus be notified so that they would be able to do the necessary family planning , especially if the individual carries a mutation that may result in a fatal genetic disorder ( { http : //www.nature.com } [ HYPERLINK : http : //www.nature.com ] , 2008 ) .
The importance of sharing the information with family members is recognized , as even during the pretest genetic counseling session , an individual would be advised to share the result with them ( { www.ons.org } [ HYPERLINK : http : //www.ons.org ] , 2009 ) .
Due to the negative consequences of allowing individuals to make the about whether or not to reveal their genetic test results , they should therefore not be given the right to have the final say in the matter .
Secondly , given the choice of not revealing one 's genetic testing result , an individual is likely to , more often than not , choose not to do so to his employer .
This action would have an adverse impact on the company .
If , during the course of employment , the individual 's welfare and safety was being threatened by the work that he was doing , the company would be held liable , despite being ignorant about the dangers that he was vulnerable to ( { http : //www.law.duke.edu } [ HYPERLINK : http : //www.law.duke.edu ] , 2002 ) .
Furthermore , when the individual develops the genetically linked disease , efficiency of work will be reduced , and yet the company would incur additional costs related to problems that arise from having a sick employer ( { http : //www.law.duke.edu } [ HYPERLINK : http : //www.law.duke.edu ] , 2002 ) .
This furthermore supports the stand that the individual requesting for genetic testing should not have the final say in revealing the result of such testing .
In conclusion , due to the negative consequences for both his family and his employer , individual should not have the power to decide whether or not to reveal the result of his genetic test .
With the test , people are able to understand the conditions of the diseases caused by mutated genes inherited from their parents .
This helps to improve their lives .
However , there is also an ethical dilemma and various social issues that accompany it .
In the light of these problems , people who have done the test should have the right to keep their genetic test result from others .
One reason for revealing the result to family members is that the result is not only applicable to the individual but also to his family members , as they may also have inherited the disease .
However , even though the individual may have the responsibility to inform the others about the possibility of them inheriting the genes , he should have the right to decide whether or not to tell .
This is because the result will create psychological distress and harm , which affect or worsen one 's health ( U.S. National Institutes of Health ) .
When family members find out about the test and the possibility of them having the genes , their stress level would increase and their health would be affected .
Moreover , the test result may be faulty and some people carrying the gene never develop the disease .
Thus , revealing the result would only cause a burden to them .
Individuals who have taken the test may face discrimination ( Karen Norrgard , 2008 ) .
For instance , insurance companies may use the information to raise premiums or to deny the person insurance .
Furthermore , the testing only gives the percentage and not the definitive results .
In making the test result known to others , one may have to face others ' judgements throughout one 's life .
In conclusion , people should have the right to restrict others from knowing the result of their genetic test as psychological and social issues make great impacts on people 's lives .
Radio frequency identification ( RFID ) is an example of a surveillance technology used commonly for identification and tracking purposes .
The market for such a device is growing very quickly due to its affordable price and widespread use ( Sieberg D , 2006 ) .
However , there are also several problems arising from the use of RFID .
Most concerns revolve around the fact that RFID invades one 's privacy and violates human rights when it is used for tracking people .
It becomes impossible to know or detect the presence of an RFID tag since it can be read a distance away from the individual ( DiLorenzo , 2008 ) .
Companies which specialise in RFID tags may pass the information obtained from the RFID tags to any buyer if the government does not intervene or control such access .
However , the use of RFID can have undesirable effects on our body because radio waves from RFID are mutagenic and they are harmful when patients are exposed to them in large quantities .
In conclusion , we should prohibit the use of RFID tags on individuals without consent as it violates individuals ' privacy and affects their health .
A lot of surveillance technologies have been invented and developed .
One of them is RFID ( Radio Frequency Identification ) which has been used widely throughout the world , even to track people .
Yet there are many debates on such tracking concerning ethical and moral issues .
Some argue that RFID tracking has bad effects on human life but in reality the tracking gives many advantages to humans .
There are two significant benefits of RFID in tracking people .
Firstly , RFID enables accuracy in medical contexts ( Roberti , 2007 ) .
This tracking also gives access to the patient 's medical information more accurately such as the temperature of the patient and whether the patient is allergic to some medicines . Secondly , RFID increases the security of workers in the workplace ( Mehdizadeh , 2007 ) .
By implanting an RFID in a device worn by a worker , a company can monitor the safety of its workers especially those working in more risky areas like oil exploration sites and mines .
tracking the location of workers helps to confirm that " the right worker is at the right place " ( Mehdizadeh , 2007 ) .
Opponents of people tracking using RFID say that the tracking the important privacy of the people tracked and abuses personal information by unauthorised individuals ( Tan & Li , 2008 ) .
However , the using of RFID to track would only be implemented after obtaining the agreement of the patients and workers affected .
In addition , the RFID technology nowadays come with a high level of security to ensure that the confidentiality of the tracked person ( Tan & Li , 2008 ) .
It has also been said that the implanting of RFID in the human body may cause electromagnetic disturbance in the body ( Roberti , 2007 ) .
However , this effect has not been proved and so far there has not been any issue regarding this disturbance .
In conclusion , RFID tracking should not be banned as it does not infringe the privacy of people and gives advantages in many aspects in human life .
Genetic testing is a development in science that enables early detection of genetic diseases ( Anonymous , 2005 ) .
There is often a concern about whether an individual should reveal his genetic test result as it may bring about several impacts on the individual and on third parties .
Therefore , the individual should bear in mind the consequences of revealing his genetic test results and decide whether to reveal the results or not .
Revealing of an individual 's genetic test results may impact the individual as well as his family members .
Firstly , revealing of such results may cause the individual to be discriminated against ( Norrgard , 2008 ) .
Secondly , it may create psychological distress in family members if the genetic test results were to be revealed .
As genetic diseases can be inherited among family members , anxiety and fear of inheriting the genetic diseases that the individual has been diagnosed with will be created .
Therefore , the individual should have the final say in disclosing his genetic results as doing so may bring about several negative impacts .
However , some may argue that revealing of the genetic test results of an individual would protect the individual 's family members .
Indeed , early knowledge of the risk of developing genetic diseases might help family members to take preventive measures to reduce the onset of such diseases .
However , one should not forget that once the genetic result of the individual is disclosed , it might be difficult for the individual to integrate into the society as he may be discriminated against .
There will be benefits to other parties but adverse implications for the individual .
Therefore , the individual requesting a genetic test should have the final say on whether or not to reveal his test results .
In conclusion , revealing of test results may bring about several impacts on the individual as well as on third parties .
Hence , the individual should bear in mind the impacts that may arise and decide if he should reveal such results .
Genetic testing is a process that diagnoses an individual 's diseases based on their genes through biochemical measurements .
Since it , it has received as much criticism as compliments because of the risk of infringing on the tested individual 's privacy .
There are many controversies about whether individuals have the right to decide whether or not to disclose their results .
I am inclined toward recognising the right of individuals to decide whether or not to reveal their genetic test outcome outcome .
Publicizing an individual 's result can bring about big impacts on them , such as having to face discrimination by their families , .
Therefore , the tested individual should have the right to decide whether to disclose his results to others .
Genetic testing predicts an individual 's inherent risks developing a genetic disease .
Depending on the seriousness of the disease , the individual decides whether or not to reveal his diagnosis .
Sometimes , if his family and relatives know about his result , they may start to change their behaviour towards the individual .
Since moral support is indispensable to , it will evidently cause depression in the individual and exacerbate the individual 's chance of developing the disease .
There is also another noticeable problem , which is that the individual might not even want to worry his whole family .
For example , some African American workers , in the early 1970s , who had the genetic mutation associated with sickle-cell anemia were denied insurance coverage or charged higher premiums ( Andrews , 1987 ) .
Moreover , forcing the individual to publicize his result could bring about a new caste system where people are grouped according to their genome .
This group of people may have their rights denied them as they belong to the lower class .
Would this not be simply a more sophisticated kind of discrimination ?
In conclusion , due to the serious impact on one 's life , we should let the individual decide whether or not to reveal genetic results .
It allows a person to know if he has a genetic disorder .
Some may feel that the revelation of the results may be viewed as invading the tested individual 's privacy , while in fact not revealing the results can be seen as being irresponsible .
There are family members , friends and employers .
Thus , due to the implications of a positive genetic test result for many other people , the tested individual should not have the final say on whether to reveal his genetic test result or nor .
An individual who wishes to start a family with his spouse should reveal his testing result .
Marriage and having children are not just between the couple ; it also involves the two families of the couple .
Some people are carriers of genetic disorders they have the genes even if they do not show the disease themselves ( Genetic Testing n.d. ) .
Thus , the unborn child may have the chance to get the disorder from his parents .
It is hence the responsibility of individuals who are carriers of a genetic risk to tell their family members the possible outcome of the unborn child .
Some argue that revealing the test result will attract discrimination such as being viewed as an outcast of the society .
For instance , they may be denied insurance due to their disorder .
However , revealing the result can be seen .
They can make sure that their workers with genetic disorders are not exposed to any environment that may agitate their illnesses ( Andre , C. , & Velasquez , M. n.d. ) .
However , this can only be done if individuals reveal their testing result .
In conclusion , individuals should not have the final say on whether to reveal their genetic test results as any disorder that they may be found with will affect their family and revealing the result will allow their employer to provide them a safe working environment .
Advances in genetic testing allow one to detect the presence of abnormal genes which could cause genetic disorders .
This has brought about many debates on whether the individual who undergoes genetic testing should have the final say in revealing the results .
While some proponents suggest that this involves the privacy of the individual who undergoes the genetic testing , the test results might also have adverse effects on those who are closely related to that person .
Firstly , an individual with positive genetic test results has no right to keep the test results to himself .
He needs to inform his wife in order for them both make wise decisions if they were to start a family ( When Do Doctors Recommend Genetic Testing ? , n.d. ) .
For instance , they need to discuss whether the disorder can be prevented from being passed on to the next by them not having children .
Hence , affects not only the person with the genetic disease , but also his life partner .
Many critics claim that individuals with positive genetic test results should have the right not to reveal their test results to potential employers .
They argue that the job applicants should not be discriminated against just because of the positive genetic test result ( Andre and Velasquez , n.d. ) .
Employers can use the information acquired from genetic testing to ensure that their employees are not exposed to environmental agents that might cause them to have an increased risk for genetic disorders .
This can ultimately lead to the reduction of work-days lost .
In conclusion , the individual requesting for genetic test should not have the final say in disclosing his test result as it affects not only him alone but also his family and employer .
Nowadays , the development of technology has been progressing rapidly .
An instance of such development is genetic testing .
On one hand , it is very useful for diagnosing many kinds of genetic disease .
IOn the other hand , it is a dilemma .
I strongly feel that such people should not have the final say and
they should n't have the right not to disclose their genetic testing results .
First and foremost , a carrier of a known genetic risk should tell his prospective spouse or fiancee about his genetic testing result because some people who have abnormal genes inherited from their parents do n't have observable symptoms of the disease but will have a 50 : 50 chance of passing on the disease to their children ( Genetic Testing , 2007 ) .
By informing their spouse early , they can take before planning to have children .
The second reason is an obligation to tell his employer about his genetic condition .
Some people may argue that it is unfair to use genetic tests in the recruitment of employees because it is treating people discriminatively based on a fixed characteristic ( Andre , Velasquez , n.d. ) .
However , the main purpose of employment genetic screening is to make sure that the job is safe and does not cause complications or any bad effects for potential employees prone to having certain diseases .
The last reason concerns the sake of people around him .
Carriers of genetic risks perceive a strong sense of responsibility to share information about their genetic condition with others ( Loescher , Crist , Siaki , 2009 ) .
To sum up , anyone who is suffering from a genetic disease or is a carrierr of the disease should not have the final say in whether to reveal or to hide information about his disease .
Instead , it should be a must for him to disclose his disease to his spouse to save their baby from inheriting the disease , to his employer to make sure that his job is for him and to all people around him to fulfil his sense of responsibility .
Revealing his genetic testing result will be beneficial to himself , his employer , his family and all the people around him .
Therefore , the use of RFID to track people should be banned as it would bring about negative impacts on the society .
Firstly , it will impinge on privacy and security .
Such private information may also be accessed by other parties as the RFID can be decoded and may be subjected to viral threats ( DiLorenzo , 2008 ) .
Criminals may have access to such information and this may put our life in danger as these criminals can easily harm us once they know our exact location .
Animal studies on these RFID microchips suggest that RFID implantation in humans may result in cancer ( Paddock , 2007 ) .
Proponents of using RFID to track people argue that such usage of RFID is important in the medical field as it helps to monitor patients ' health and enables the immediate retrieval of patients ' information ( Paddock , 2007 ) .
As such , patients ' medical information may leak out , which in turn may result in social discrimination against and loss of health care coverage for for these patients .
Medical information stored in the RFID may also be altered by hackers and this would lead to error in diagnoses ( Sieberg , 2006 ) .
In conclusion , the use of RFID to track people should be banned as it will cause invasion of privacy , security breaches as well as health problems when RFID chips are implanted into individuals .
However , critics have been quick to point out that this is an intrusion of privacy and are calling for it to be banned .
However , I believe that the benefits of RFID used in tracking people far outweigh the 'uncertain ' disadvantages and thus it should not be banned .
Firstly , RFID has been seen as a solution for tracking medical patients .
This is to ensure " improved continuity and coordination of care " ( Roberti 2007 ) and to reduce the possibilities of " adverse drug events and other medical errors " ( Roberti 2007 ) .
the integration of both RFID and Global Positioning System ( GPS ) is used to locate workers during emergencies .
RFID can also verify if the worker has the right to access certain areas and use certain machineries .
However , critics have been quick to identify the " unauthorised reading and changing of RFID data " ( Tan and Li 2008 ) as an encroachment of privacy .
However , there have been measures put in place such as the usage of " Authentication " ( Tan and Li 2008 ) to identify .
This prevents " counterfeiting behaviours " and helps to " control access to label contents " ( Tan and Li 2008 ) .
Detractors have also argued that " RFID may cause electromagnetic interference " ( Roberti 2007 ) , exposing the user to the dangers of magnetic interference .
Nevertheless , , there has not been a formal report confirming that worry .
In conclusion , I believe that the usage of RFID in tracking humans should not be banned as the advantages of its usage outweigh its disadvantages .
And I have absolute trust in scientists to iron out the flaws to make RFID truly the " perfect " solution to the limitations of many existing technologies .
Genetic testing is used to examine the genes of a patient or a latent patient , in order to find out the causes of some diseases .
However , with the application of genetic testing , some problems are revealed gradually , such as whether patients should tell their families about their testing results .
In fact , everyone has to be responsible for the health of his or her family and himself or herself , hence , the individual requesting genetic testing should not have the final say in whether to reveal the testing results ; these results should be made known to their relatives .
If the person does not tell his family about the test results , his family members would not know their health deficiencies and would not tell their doctors .
In this case , the person 's family members likely suffer from such diseases and will miss early diagnosis .
For example , if a man 's genetic testing results indicated some pathogenic genes but he got married with a woman without telling her about these results , the woman might feel that she has been cheated after she knew the truth because she did not want to marry a man with gene deficiency .
In addition , if they already have children and their children also have such pathogenic genes through heredity , who should be responsible for these children 's health problems ?
A genetic test is a test which uses laboratory techniques to determine whether an individual has a genetic disease or may get the disease
Thus , the individual who requests genetic testing should not have the final say in whether to reveal the results of the test for his own sake and that of his family members .
Firstly , a couple who is planning to get married and one of them or a close relative has an inherited disease , is advised to take up genetic testing .
The result of such a genetic test affects not only the individual but also affects his family and his fiance .
Both sides of family members should have the right to know the result and to be able to take preventive and treatment measures .
Furthermore , if the couple is planning to give birth but one of them has a positive result from such testing , they can discuss with their close family members whether to have a baby or not .
Thus , it is not right for an individual taking such a test to keep the result as a secret .
Furthermore , in my opinion , employers have the right to know such a result to ensure that their prospective or current employees are not placed in environments that might be hazardous to them and also can react immediately if something happens ( Claire Andre and Manuel Velasquez , n.d. ) .
If the individual has the final say to decide whether to reveal the result , it is unfair for his close family and also people who are related to him if the individual decides to keep the result to him .
Others argue that it is unfair for the individual as the result is a kind of confidential information .
However , by not disclosing such a result , the consequences are serious .
The risk of giving birth to a child with an inherited genetic disease is high and also endangers the individual by exposing himself to a work environment that may be hazardous to his health .
In conclusion , the individual requesting genetic testing should not have the final say in whether or not to reveal the results of such testing for his own sake , that of and also his employer .
A genetic test is defined as an assessment of a person 's genes to determine the probablitity of inheriting abnormalities or diseases which he may pass down to future generations .
Thus , many will say the results must also be made known to his relatives even without his consent .
However , one should have the right to decide for himself whether he should reveal his results to a third party e.g .
It is obvious that everyone has the right to ensure his or her privacy , as these are what make us different from animals .
Thus , as fellow Homo Sapiens , each has the right to decide for himself .
Proponents may argue that doctors should also release genetic testing results to relatives as these may also involve them .
However , it would be ridiculous for relatives to know that they might also face this particular genetic disease in the future from the individual 's results since everyone has a unique genome unless they are twins .
And also even if two individuals are somehow blood related , the probability of them inheriting the same particular genetic disorder is different .
When one is denied of the right to his or her own privacy , the consequences are definitely undesirable .
Some of the implications may be in the case of an insurance where some are overcharged according to the results .
For instance , " during the early 1970s , a number of African Americans who were known to be carriers for the mutation associated with sickle-cell anemia were denied insurance coverage or charged higher premiums " ( Andrews , 1987 ) . This clearly shows what had happened when the privacy of the results is not ensured .
This situation could have been avoided if the individual could decide for himself , as he would be able to weigh the pros and cons better since it concerns his life .
In conclusion , there could be some laws passed down to settle all these ethical issues .
Ultimately , it still does not solve the root of these problems and unforeseen situations in the future .
Therefore , rights should be given to the individual to decide for himself , as the decisions made will be impactful and irreversible .
The development and advances in surveillance technology such as Radio Frequency Identification ( RFID ) have made it possible to track anyone , anything , any place , anytime .
Although some argue that the use of RFID to track people brings benefits , it exposes one 's privacy to criminals , which is against human rights and perhaps , threatens one 's health .
Thus , the use of RFID to track people should be banned .
By using RFID technology , one 's personal information , purchased goods and whereabouts can be tracked easily by private corporations or governments ( DiLorenzo 2008 ) .
Although some argue that RFID technology that stores one 's information in RFID such as credit card or identity card provides great convenience , it creates chances for criminals as well .
Health concerns are also related to the use of RFID to track people .
Some companies have implanted RFID microchips in their staff to track their locations and information .
Furthermore , if the microchips react with a strong electrical or magnetic field , the implant could be destroyed and cause serious burns .
For example , an employer might choose not to hire or to fire someone if he is to find out that the person has a certain disease such as cancer or Huntington disease ( Maxwell & Mehlman , 1999 ) .
Another social consequence would be when individuals are discriminated against in health coverage based on their genetic make-up .
While it may be difficult even for the individual to accept the results of the test , sharing the news with his or her relatives and friends may be the larger concern .
While some may feel that it is the moral obligation of the individual to inform his immediate family members of positive results of inheritable diseases such as cancer or HD , since they too may inherit the disease , I feel that there is no need for such an action as the result is after all private and confidential .
Also , certain genetic tests such as the test for disorders of sexual development are a very private matter .
In conclusion , the final say on whether or not to reveal the results of such testing should always lie on the individual who has requested the test .
Besides ethical implications , medical implications such as accuracy of test results are also concerns the general public has about the issue .
Therefore , with these concerns , it is important that the individual requesting genetic testing should have the final say in whether or not to reveal the results of such testing .
Firstly , privacy is one of the worries one will have while considering whether or not to carry out genetic testing .
Furthermore , health care providers might also reveal the person 's genetic status to concerned family members which in turn might weaken our confidence in the providers
( Holtzman , 1996 ) . Secondly , information from genetic testing of individuals with genetic susceptibilities is used by employers and insurance companies to deny them employment as well as to grant lower insurance coverage .
This is generally known as discrimination
( Holtzman , 1996 ) . With reference to a survey conducted by Georgetown University , out of 332 families with genetic susceptibilities , " 22 % reported they had been refused health insurance , and 13 % had been fired from their jobs based on their perceived genetic risks
" ( Of Genes and Pink Slips : Genetic Testing Goes to Work , 2005 ) . Until now , not many laws have been passed down to protect the rights of people with higher genetic risks .
Alternatively , companies should allocate another job which is more suitable and does not put the employee at risk
( Holtzman , 1996 ) . This way , both parties benefit and there is no unfair discrimination .
In conclusion , individuals requesting genetic testing should have the final say in whether or not to reveal the results of such testing to protect oneself from discrimination and invasion of privacy .
Nowadays , genetic testing has generated ethical and moral issues .
One of them is about the privacy and confidentiality of the individual who undergoes genetic testing , whether he or she should reveal the results of the testing to third parties or not .
While it is true that people 's individual rights should be respected , if others can be saved through revelation of testing results , then it should be done .
The reason why most people want to protect their privacy concerning genetic information is because they fear discrimination .
They fear that they would denied insurance or that their policies are canceled ( Mehmaln,1999 ) . In fact , this fear is groundless because in truth several laws at the federal and state levels help protect people from genetic discrimination .
With the approval of GINA ( Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act ) in May 2008 , they do not have to worry anymore .
There are several advantages in revealing the results of genetic testing to third parties .
If genetic testing is revealed to relatives and they end up having the same disease , they could be saved by preventing the disease to develop further .
Another thing is people 's life is obviously more important than privacy , especially if it is one 's loved ones .
Therefore , it is encouraged to reveal the results of genetic testing , especially to relatives .
In conclusion , the individual undergoing genetic testing should not have the final say in whether to reveal the results of such testing as he or she is protected by the laws against discrimination and also because other people 's life could be saved .
Surveillance technology on the public have been an issue for a long time .
Privacy has been commonly used to outweigh concerns for safety and security .
Surveillance technology should not be banned .
By allowing proper usage of surveillance technology , one could increase the level of security and safekeeping in a country as well as improve work efficiency at the workplace .
As reported in the news last year , West Virginia decided to use video surveillance technology on its highways to help find missing children ( Stump , 2008 , p.1 ) which resulted in one hundred percent recovery of these children ( Stump , 2008 , p.2 ) .
Moreover , it can also help improve work efficiency at the workplace , more commonly in office work settings .
The cubicles allow employees to do things unrelated to work and employers are unable to push employees to get the work done when the latter spend more than half the time using the facilities available for their own indulgence .
Thus , by setting up electronic surveillance to keep track of employees ' usage of facilities , the employees will become more 'aware ' of their situation and start taking their jobs more seriously , improving work efficiency ( Heathfield , n.d. , p.1 ) .
Genetic testing is a medical test used to diagnose the disorder in the genome of a person and determine if this mutation can cause a specific disease .
With the development of ability to test for genetic disorder , an emerging problem that has been " the subject of significant debate within the bioethics community " ( Mehlman , 1999 , para.5 ) is the privacy of genetic information .
Generally , the problem is that genetic information should not be disclosed against people 's privacy .
The choice to undergo genetic testing of an individual is personal . However , before deciding to undergo the test , the patient has to face the fear that his testing result may be disclosed and used against his welfare .
The patients ' concerns are their employment and insurance because it is usually difficult for them to obtain these if their genetic information is revealed .
Another case is in sports , where there are situations of birth defect " disorders of sexual development " ( Borenstein , 2009 , para.1 ) .
Some athletes only found out their defects when they were given genetic testing before a competition ; they were banned from the competition and this information then would be all public .
To protect the welfare of patients with genetic problems , their genetic information should not be disclosed over their objection or even without their permission .
But in fact , some argue that revealing this information can protect some third parties from harm , for example , enable the avoidance of inherited disorder .
In conclusion , until these laws are enacted , not revealing such information without patients ' consent and using other method like alias testing are better choices .
Monitoring employees at workplaces and installing video cameras at public places such as banks , stores or restaurants are two of the debatable issues today .
Whereas advocates of such surveillance technologies emphasize on the benefits such as to promote work efficiency and secure communal settings , opponents strike back by stating intensified concerns related to individual privacy .
Firstly , the monitoring system at the workplace indeed effectively drives employees to perform better .
Meanwhile , surveillance on lax supervisors may evidently verify their incompetence ( Heathfield , n.d ) ,
for example , , mutual surveillance guarantees active working environments , as well as brings high productivity and huge profits to employers .
Secondly , as Mr. Gray , Mayor of Lancaster , states , the use of surveillance technologies plays a utilitarian role in public security and detection of criminals ( Gray , 2009 ) .
Sometimes criminals will be deterred if they are aware of hidden surveillance .
Concerns with privacy might be crucial to constructing regulations on implementation , However , the solutions are abundant thus the banning of surveillance technology is utterly unnecessary .
To illustrate , companies shall not be allowed to monitor phone calls which are business related ( Heathfield , n.d. ) .
Simultaneously , safeguards should be ensured so as not to reveal any information obtained through surveillance ; strict penalties should be enforced on those who fail to preserve privacy ( Gray , 2009 ) .
To sum up , surveillance technology should not be banned as its usefulness in the workplace and enhancement of public safety make it an indispensable tool in today 's world .
In the past , surveillance was conducted through human to human tracking .
With advances in technology , surveillance nowadays is aided by equipment such as closed-circuit TV ( CCTV ) , camera , voice recorder and RFID ( radio frequency identification ) .
This has brought about debates on ethical and moral issues with regard to the usage of surveillance technology especially RFID .
While not compromising the benefits it brings , the ethical and moral issues regarding surveillance technology far outweigh the benefits it brings .
They are visual , audio and data surveillance
While it may have its advantages of being able to record down the scene of the location it is allocated , the issue on privacy and effectiveness sets in .
CCTV is installed at homes and offices for employers to check on their employees namely the maids at home and the workers in the office .
This causes employees to have low morale during work , and thus reduces work efficiency when the aim of the CCTV is otherwise .
This is also a human rights issue as it has invaded a person 's privacy ( Bogonikolos , 1999 ) .
It can be used to track down humans , pets and equipment ( Getz , 2009 ) .
It has raised privacy issues as not everyone is willing to let others know of his or her whereabouts .
Therefore , surveillance technology should be banned .
The individual requesting genetic testing should have the final say on whether to reveal the results of such testing .
With current technological advancements in genetics , there are many genetic tests available for the public , from testing for inheritance diseases to terminal illnesses .
The individual should be given the choice , as the emotional hurt from the media release of these ividual .
Firstly , the emotional hurt from the world wide release of the individual 's genetic information be .
Given the outreach of the mass media , reports of genetic disorder of an individual could be known to the world in minutes .
However , many of these genetic disorders are until , inherited and incurable .
Nowadays , as the technology develops , individuals have more approaches to such tests .
When they are informed of the potential risk of the mutation that could lead to a genetic disease that is also hereditary , they can undergo their own genetic tests in order to determine the extent of the mutation risk as soon as possible .
If they are positive , they can undertake a further diagnostic procedure to determine whether any physical symptom will developg .
Secondly , when the result of a particular genetic test is beneficial to the whole society , researchers have the right to disclose the outcome outcome .
As we know , scientists all over the world are working together to make people 's lives better by studying the genome of human and other organisms .
Sometimes discovering an insignificant phenomenon or test results and it can really make a breakthrough .
On the contrary , the results should be shared among scientists and researchers for the whole world 's sake .
In conclusion , individuals who request genetic testing should not have the final say in revealing the results for two major reasons : protecting their blood relatives from genetic disorders and helping the whole society for genetic researchs .
Advances in technology have made surveillance technology very common nowadays .
Surveillance technology is the electronic equipment used to monitor the behavior and activities , usually of people without their permission .
Arguments on banning the use of surveillance technology has been going on for years .
The use of surveillance technology should not be banned because it is useful in ensuring public safety and monitoring workplace in a company .
Employees might seem to be surfing the web for business purposes at all times , but what they are actually doing is personal business such as online banking , shopping and chatting .
The cameras have the function of identifying , detecting and recording vehicles ' number , suspects ' actions and illegal organizations ' .
These help the police to solve cases , especially criminal and traffic cases , in the shortest time .
However , monitoring can take place under suitable circumstances and to an appropriate extent .
However , this only applies to those minority groups spending most of the time online doing personal things and not meeting the company 's goals .
Usage of surveillance technology has no impact on those focusing on work and doing the right thing ( Heathfield , n.d. , p.2 ) .
In conclusion , the use of surveillance technology should not be banned as it benefits us in public security and also in business efficiency .
Development and advancement in the field of genetic research has challenged the scientists and the public on a wide range of issues especially issues relating to ethicall concerns .
Therefore , the result of genetic testing should be revealed without the consent of the person who requested it .
Firstly , result of genetic testing should be fully disclosed as it enables a third party to get treatment or prevention before the condition worsens ( Maxwell & Mehlman , 1999 ) .
The decision to reveal a genetic test result such as that for breast cancer would help early detection and treatment .
However , Science Daily ( 2008 ) notes that Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act ( GINA ) has been approved to forbid an insurance company from discriminating through reduced coverage or pricing and prohibits employers from making adverse employment decisions in order to encourage more people to undergo genetic tests , which could save lives in the long run .
Under this circumstance , the final say of revealing the result should lie with the physician , who has a better understanding on the patient 's condition .
Although the general agreement seems that disclosure of testing result should not override the patient 's objection , this would be an exception if it is to protect a third party to avoid other serious consequences ( Mehlman & Maxwell , 1999 ) .
In conclusion , the result of genetic testing should be revealed without the consent of the person who requested it as this would not only enable a third party to get early prevention or treatment but also help others to make life decisions .
Genetic testing is able to analyze whether a subject is likely to develop or inherit a particular genetic disease .
But are they able to inform the family members to safeguard their personal health and yet not breach the issues of confidentiality and privacy ?
My stand is as long as disclosure has no serious social/ethical consequences , the subject will have the final say .
In the increasing debate on genetic testing , there are three issues which have caused concerns in the society .
Firstly , the ethical aspect of privacy and confidentiality need to be preserved .
If privacy and confidentiality are breached , family members and third parties ' may acquire test results of no welfare to the subject ( Mehlmanm , 1999 , The Privacy of Genetic Information , para .
Secondly , social aspects of genetic discrimination have made subjects reconsider genetic testing testing as the information might be used against them . ( Norrgard , 2008 , Genetic Testing and Privacy Concerns , para 1 ) .
Third parties like employers may sack their employees , or insurers may reject an insurance application if they came to be aware of the results .
Genetic discrimination have placed privacy and confidentiality in jeopardy , because subjects have no control over their genetic makeup .
Last , but not least are family issues as people may have to change their life-style , reproductive decisions , seek medical prevention or treatment .
According to an article ( Mehlmanm , 1999 , The Privacy of Genetic Information ) , using Alias testing , particular information can remaining anonymous .
Anonymity allows subjects to have the final decision to reveal the test results to their family or even third parties parties , so privacy and confidentiality are not violated .
A regulatory framework such as Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act has ensured genetic discrimination is legislated .
By imposing a law , people feel safer when undergoing genetic testing testing as it is the deciding factor to disclose their genetic results to family members or third party under their obligations .
Advances in technology and reduced costs in chip production have led to the proliferation of surveillance technology such as Radio Frequency Identification ( RFID ) to track people .
While the use of this seemingly intrusive technology is shrouded in concerns over privacy , morality and health issues , its benefits benefits,
both current and latent latent,
One pivoting reason why RFID should not be banned is its application to augment public and national security .
With proper regulation and use , RFID tagging may , on the contrary to many arguments , ensure greater freedom and privacy for the person implanted with RFID .
Genetic testing has , however , raised ethical concerns like whether the individual requesting genetic testing should have the final say on whether to reveal the results of such testing ( Chris and Bryn 2002 ) .
There are severe consequences if the results are not handled and communicated properly by third parties .
However , it is very likely that employers will use the results to discriminate against employeess based on unfounded perceptions of health risks and possible future disabilities ( Chris and Bryn 2002 ) ( Neil and Ronald 2006 ) .
Likewise , insurance companies may make use of the results to charge a higher premium or not provide insurance because of possible chances of high medical bills in the future ( Chris and Bryn 2002 ) ( Neil and Ronald 2006 ) .
Doctors have to adhere to medical ethics , namely , they are required to respect the confidentiality of the patients ( Thirumoorthy 2009 ) .
Both the Hippocratic Oath and International Code of Ethics states that without the prior consent from the patient doctors are not allowed to disclose any information which he has obtained ( Thirumoorthy 2009 ) .
There are also considerations like age and maturity ( Gillian , Denise and Bartha 2009 ) .
In conclusion , the individual requesting genetic testing should have the final say on whether to reveal the results of genetic testing .
RFID is a chip that has a small antenna to transmit a vast amount of information from a human 's body to a computer using a scanner ( Sade , 2007 , p. 1 ) .
When a patient goes to the hospital , his medical records which are already stored in a RFID tag can be immediately traced using the RFID scanner .
In doing so , waiting time could be greatly minimized and many more innocent lives will be saved .
Secondly , implanting RFID tags into ex-offenders aids the authorities in monitoring their activities .
This helps to save innocent lives and reduce crime in the country .
Technological advances have brought along pros and cons ever since it entered our daily lives .
Furthermore monitoring ex- criminals will not only forbid them from committing crimes again , but more importantly , allow the public to have a peace of mind employing them , subsequently making them feel accepted by the society .
Secondly , time saved on retrieving essential information of patients during an emergency could be put into treating the patients ( http : //www.verichipcorp.com ) .
Therefore , the RFID technology can improve our healthcare system 's efficiency .
Expediting the cracking of criminal cases is another point why surveillance technology should not be banned .
Tracking is defined as locating the whereabouts of a person and the identification of personal information .
This is supported by statistics done by correctional institutions which show that cases of violence decreased by 65 percent when the RFID system was introduced ( Casciato 2008 ) .
The storage of key medical records and information in a radio-transmitting chip will cut down time spent on rregistration , thus , allowing patients to receive prompt treatment .
In times of emergency key information such as blood type and allergy could be retrieved in an instant by scanning the chip , and the most appropriate treatment can be decided in the shortest possible time .
This can prove to be vital in saving a person 's life .
With the use of RFID to locate a victim , it will allow the authorities to capture the people behind such activities and provide a solution to the problem of human trafficking .
RFID has always been a double-edged sword . It may bring us some benefits . However , it has broughtt us even more disadvantages such as invasion of privacy and abuse of technology .
Therefore , the use of surveillance technology for tracking people should be banned .
RFID can be easily exploited by third parties .
RFID tags can be easily put on one 's clothing so information could be easily available to marketers , government agencies and criminals .
Therefore , all our information is at the trackers ' fingertip and this may include all our particulars-name , gender , photograph etc. For example
the Bush administration announced that all passports in US will be embedded with RFID ( McCullagh & Broache , 2005 ) .
Although privacy issues are addressed by some security measures , it was criticized by computer engineers as their security levels are not advanced enough .
Furthermore , technically speaking RFID would track everyone before detecting a minority group of terrorists , hence efficiency of RFID is low .
However , the research in this field is still in its infancy
Furthermore , some research has shown RFID computer chips may be linked to cancer , based on animal studies .
In all , RFID should be banned as it not only invades our privacy but may impose serious risk to our body .
