As a type of surveillance technology , RFID ( Radio Frequency Identification ) is drawing increased attention and has caused many conflicts with regard to privacy , security and health issues .
Advocators suggest that using RFID to conduct social control and tracking of suspects could benefit the whole society .
On the contrary , it not only leads to an invasion of privacy and identity theft but also poses health risks .
Using RFID to track people raises many issues .
It is hard to guarantee that every tracking is innocent and conducted in proper ways and .
Secondly , because a RFID embedded card can easily be skimmed and cloned , to some extent , it is a loophole for identity theft .
by using the cloned card , anyone could pass into a restricted area through the secure and locked entrance ( Jones 2008 ) .
Hence , using a RFID equipped card to track and control entrance is not secure and effective at all .
sacrificing the health of people when conducting tracking is therefore unacceptable
However , RFID advocators may argue for the purpose of alleviating the fear of privacy invasion .
Furthermore , the individual has the right to decide on whether the result should be disclosed or not .
Firstly , the person would face discrimination by society if the results are declared openly without his consent
The person would be unable to purchase insurance since they would cost the insurance company more money than the company had bargained for ( Henry T. 2005 , ) Moreover , employers would not want to hire them as the employee 's health problem would have an undesirable effect on the company 's productivity , such as , costing the company more money on the employees ' frequent sick leaves and medical reimbursements ( Henry T. 2005 ) .
Secondly , critics at the other end of the table may argue that there is the Genetic Information Non-discrimination Act ( GINA ) in the US that was passed down by the former US president , Mr. Bush on 21 May 2008 which states that 'the genetic carriers would be protect against discrimination when it comes to work and health insurance ' ( Kaiser Family Foundation , 2008 ) .
Tera Eerkes , founder of personal genetic testing company states that 'this measure does not prevent genetic discrimination against people when they are applying for life insurance , or long term care and disability insurance' .
2008 , ) .
If an individual is denied of his right to decide on the disclosure of his test result , probably no one will dare go for testing since they know that they do not possess the right to decide whether the result stays secret .
This will result in dire consequences , for example ; there will not be proper family planning since genetic disorder is not taken into consideration , which might result in continued breeding of undesirable genetic traits in one 's offspring .
In conclusion , the person who went for genetic testing should have the final say on whether to reveal the genetic testing result so that he will not be discriminated against or even denied of his basic human rights .
Recently , Radio Frequency Identification technology , also known as " RFID " has been a hot topic for discussion .
In the past , it was used to track equipmentequipment and data and this did not create much controversy with regard to the issue of privacy .
However , as technology improved RFID is now more frequently used to track people .
In life and death situation , doctors that are in the vicinity of the operation theatre can be called in for help instantly , hence saving time .
Finally , there has been greater concern about RFID not only tracking the data of the patient , but also tracking the patient 's actual whereabouts .
Supporters claim that surveillance technology can increase efficiency and effectiveness in tracking criminals and potential terrorists , and decreasing crime rates or track runaway or Alzheimer patients in hospitals to provide better care for every patient ( Jean , 2007 ) .
In fact , it causes more security than health threats thus using it to track people should be banned to ensure their safety .
If one had their pocket picked , he would know and can take measures to prevent it .
It is against the law to steal another persons identification card but not the information by " skimming " ( Jones , 2008 ) .
The rapid advances in medical technology present genetic testing that is used , to identify specific genes responsible for a significant disease in an individual ( Centre for Genetic Education , n.d. ) .
The perception of whether an individual should have the final say to reveal the results of genetic tests has lead to an ethical dilemma in society and amongst individuals , particularly in family-relationships .
Since , the advantages of revealing the results of genetic tests outweigh the disadvantages in most situations , an individual should therefore not have the absolute authority to reveal their test results .
There are two main benefits of not having the absolute authority to revealing the results of genetic tests .
It also provides understanding of specific gene occurrences to others ( Centre for Genetic Education , n.d. ) .
Secondly , the awareness of deleterious genes in individuals that could lead to disease , like HIV , ensures their responsibility within the community .
The organization involved in genetic care has the authority to disclose the genetic information to appropriate people if harmful genes could lead to serious disease . If an infected individual does not reveal it then little effort is made for diagnosis and treatments ( Minkoff and Ecker , 2008 ) .
This would cause harm to others , like the spread of HIV to the uninfected sexual partner and the future generations .
Today , enterprises found the use of RFID chips in a wide variety of places including hospital , transportation system , corporations , schools , and worryingly , human beings ( Andrea Jean , 2007 ) .
In this paper , I would like to discuss some problems in the use of RFID chip on human beings .
Human implant is experimented and studied deeply in many countries .
However , this has proved to have huge problems unfortunately .
Volunteers participated in a controlled experiment on skimming proved that a hacker is able to skim and clone an access card in a split second and using the card to get entrance to a " secure and locked " entrance ( Jones , 2008 ) .
This absurd result brings into question the security use of the human implant .
This is especially true for elderly patients with Alzheimer 's disease .
Patients suffering from Alzheimer 's have the tendency to wander .
The completion of Human Genome Project has contributed significantly to the rapid development of genetic tests , a valuable tool that aids in diagnosis and prevention of genetic diseases .
An important reason why patients should not be empowered to make the final decision is that it prevents doctors from tending to potential patients who could be at high risk of developing a disease if disclosure is not made .
Due to the need to maintain confidentiality of results , doctors will be compelled to watch patients with the defective gene fall ill when appropriate intervention can be done to avert harm .
This has gone against their 'proper medical and ethical practices ' ( Minkoff & Ecker , 2008 ) of preventing harm or avoiding serious jeopardisation of the health of others ) .
Considering these competing obligations faced by physicians , the genetic care and counselling organisations have devised guidelines which accept disclosure to relatives without the consent of those tested when there is going to be a high degree and immediacy of risk faced by them ( Minkoff & Ecker , 2008 ) .
[ 2 ] Physicians trained to deal with the emotional burdens of a positive test result , are capable of properly counselling the patient of the implications of not knowing the test result and also providing the needed medical treatment for the long run .
[ 1 ] As the medical professionals would know what medical treatment the patient would need , and also understand the encumbrance such knowledge would bring , it is best that the medical professionals decide whether or not to reveal the test results .
Technology has made our life so convenient that we have overlooked the { repercussions that comes with it .
Patients who wish to keep their medical information might choose to have the chip implanted right under their skin .
Another concerning issue is that the " RFID tags may electromagnetically interfere with electrosurgical devices " ( Bacheldor 2007 ) with particular attention at magnetic resonance imaging ( MRI ) scans .
Customers could also be tracked with the products anywhere so long as there is a right reader that could read the frequency ( Free 2007 ) Consumer privacy will no longer be existent as consumers lose freedom of choice and also consistently losing personal information to marketeers .
The user might lose his password for access to areas or monetary items and also his identity .
The possibility that the RFID technology would prove to be more of a hindrance than a convenience is evident .
This has brought about many controversial issues regarding the privacy and health concerns surrounding the use of RFID .
While some argue that the adoption of RFID is a violation of human privacy , it indeed helps to protect the safety of families , the public and to identify patients .
Firstly , RFID protects the safety of loved ones by tracking the movements of kin in cases when they got lost or were kidnapped .
With the help of A RFID tag worn by senile elderly , the police can identify the missing elderly and then contact their family members .
In addition , RFID tags help to assist the police to locate the hostage and kidnappers .
Secondly , RFID ensures the safety of the public by monitoring suspicious people who might pose a danger to society so as to prevent them from causing harm to the public .
RFID is useful in combating crime .
Thirdly , RDIF improves the speed of patient identification in hospitals .
Upon admission to hospital , each patient is given a RFID wristband which reveals the patient name , patient identification number and patient medication record ( Antonio , n.d. ) .
Nevertheless , the current legislation is sufficient to deal with the development of RFID so as to prevent user privacy from being invaded .
Furthermore , the RFID tag does not bring health problems to users .
An example is European council proposal on the limitation of the exposure of electromagnetic fields to the public ( Council , 1999 ) .
RFID serves as a tracking device and an identification system in safeguarding the safety of loved ones , the public and for identifying patients .
Human genetics has made tremendous leaps over the past years , and consequently made a significant impact on many people 's lives .
In any case , it can be advocated that the individual should have the final say in whether to reveal the results of genetic testing or not .
This is due to the legislation polices that have been implemented for genetic testing
Basically , it is far more confidential as it may contain more individual personal health issues such as determining whether one carries any defective genes .
Hence , it is rightful to say that genetic information should be kept confidential and should only be revealed by the individual .
In accordance with federal law in the United States , medical information should be kept confidential and genetic professionals or doctors do not have the right to disclose any information without seeking the consent of the patient .
Though , they may assist patients by informing them of the likelihood of their relatives contracting the same diseases , the final decision ultimately still depends on the individual .
On the other hand , critics may argue that genetic professionals can interpret the genetic testing results more accurately than patients .
Thus , they can explain the implications of the results more precisely to family members .
However , only patients will understand their family members ' different behavioural patterns .
This means that they are more suited to revealing the results by using a more desirable method .
In conclusion , the decision of whether revealing the results of genetic testing should lie only with the individual and not other third parties involved .
Any disclosure of results by third parties will be considered a breach of the genetic privacy and confidentiality law and may cause unnecessary moral implications .
Genetic testing has become more ubiquitous in recent years .
I advocate the idea that patients should have the final say to decide whether to disclose the test results to relatives and families .
First , the law and human rights declaration recognizes the right to privacy of individuals .
et al. , 2009 ) Unless there is mutual agreement on both sides , the final say should lie with the patients .
Secondly , the final say should lie with the patient as he knows what is best for his family members .
The patients knows the different behavioral patterns of his family members and will know the best way to approach them regarding their genetic condition .
In this way , the family members of the patient are protected from emotional harm like stress and anxiety .
In conclusion , the final say in the disclosure of genetic test results should lie with the patient according to the legal jurisdiction and to the fact that the patients understand the different personalities of their families and will have their best interests in mind .
The advancement of Science and Technology has lead to many possibilities , one of which is the ability to predict one 's risk of contracting certain diseases , mostly hereditary , via the study of one 's genes .
Hence this predictive power leads to one of the many controversies- should an individual have the final say in whether to reveal his/her results ?
In fact , this authority should go to medical professionals ; basically physicians undertaking the proceedings of the test and interacting with the patients firsthand .
Firstly , a physician is a profession that is bound by standard protocols and most importantly physicians possess medical ethics .
As the genetics results also apply to the family and relatives ' health risks as well as the patient 's own , many lives are concerned and any unjustifiable reason not to disclose should be overwritten .
The American Society of Human Genetics even propose conditions whereby patient autonomy should be disregarded ( Bioethics Advisory Committee,2005 ) , emphasizing the importance of disclosure of results .
Secondly , there are laws such as the Genetic Information Non-discrimination Act ( GINA ) or the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act ( { HIPAA } [ HYPERLINK : http : //www.hhs.gov/ocr/hipaa/ ] ) ( Norrgand , 2008 ) , which protect the confidentiality and interests of the patient .
These are laws that physicians adhere to , which the patient may be unfamiliar with and overlook , despite pre- test counselling .
Thirdly , society benefits when sound decisions are made by pragmatic , rather than individualistic , individuals .
The opposition may state that leaving the decision to a third party who may be insensitive , may jeopardize the patient 's chances in employment and insurance .
Moreover , physicians still respect patient autonomy unless certain conditions permit otherwise .
It has also been suggested that the harsh truth of inheriting a genetic risk may create an emotional impact , especially when disclosed despite the patient 's reluctance .
Moreover , the mental preparedness of the patient is most likely moulded on the pre-test counselling before genetic testing is carried .
( Lee , 2005 ) In conclusion , physicians should have the final say in whether to reveal the genetic testing results as they have the know-how on managing the entire situation before and after the patient is subjected to the test .
Genetic testing is an issue that mankind has placed great emphasis on .
After test results are analyzed by physicians , there is a dilema about whether the information should be made known to others or whether it should be kept confidential by the individual .
Despite the fact that human rights exist , physicians actually have a clearer understanding of the results and the ethical and social issues that surface by withholding such information .
There are instances when a patient tested positive for a disease , but refused to know their results ( BAC , 2005 ) .
This is clearly true as test results indirectly reflect genetic information related to family members as there is a possibility of them inheriting the disease too .
In such a situation , the authority to release the resultst should lie with the healthcare professionals .
As a result , employers and insurance companies should have the right to request genetic information from their employees or clients directly , or indirectly from medical professionals who have a better interpretation of the genetic test results .
In conclusion , although on the surface there seems to be disturbing issues in sharing genetic information , when observed in depth , the information shared can be an advantage to the individual as well as those around him .
Nevertheless , these concerns are outweighed by its pros due to the benefits it brings in ensuring the loved ones , the public as well as identifying patients .
In the case of kidnapping , those who had RFID implanted can be easily located by RFID readers .
Medical advances in technology have made it possible to detect if one has a genetic disease through genetic testing .
Genetic testing can be defined as the analyzing of one 's DNA to detect the possible risks of contracting a genetic disease .
This has brought about a lot of debate on the ethical and law issues on whether the individual has the final say in revealing the genetic testing results .
Due to privacy and the effects of emotional stress , the individual should have the final say .
( Varga,2008 ) This is not necessarily going to happen as many other factors are needed to occur as well , like non-genetic risks such as smoking ( Varga,2008 ) .
Therefore , revealing results could be redundant if relatives do not have non-genetic risks , and furthermore it could create undesirable emotional stress for the relative .
So , the individual should first observe any signs of symptoms of the genetic disease the relative may have , such as deformity or behavior problems , before deciding whether or not to tell .
In this case , third parties such as doctors should not reveal the results , as doctors are usually more concerned with alerting the person of the possible chances of contracting the genetic disease , rather than the possible negative impacts this news may bring to the person .
In conclusion , due to the law issues and possible undesirable emotional stress caused by relatives , the individuals should have the final say in revealing the results , as it is their personal information , and they understand their relatives better emotionally .
Tracking of an individual 's movement using RFID technology is made possible when it is used in a combination with Global Positioning System technology , as proposed by RFID vendors .
The RFID tag could be in an article of clothing or under the skin in some part of the body and it could also serve as an identifier for the person wearing it .
There are many advantages to using RFID technology to track people 's movement .
Firstly , companies/family members could leverage RFID technology to locate their loved ones/employees if they were missing or working in a dangerous environment .
( Jerry , David , Manuel & Thompson , 2007 p.469 ) Secondly , in hospital , a positive patient identification system using radio frequency identification , RFID , to identify patients can led to fewer patient misidentifications .
Patient misidentification has been the leading cause of medical errors and medical malpractice , posing a serious risk to patient safety .
( Antonio , Putten & Gerald , n.d ) Thirdly , monitoring of RFID tagged convicts in prison can prevent possible prison breaks .
In addition , using RFID to tag offenders that are serving their term in the community can help to enforce home curfews .
However in cases like working in a dangerous environment , safely is prioritized over privacy violation .
There are also worries over leaked confidential information through RFID tags .
However , the tags can be encrypted and cleared of information before being discarded .
But guidelines of recommended limits of EMF exposure have been adopted internationally to prevent any known negative health effects .
In conclusion , tracking people 's movement using RFID technology should not be banned as its benefits heavily outweigh the downsides it might bring .
Advancements in technology have allowed the invention of new devices that have helped improve lifestyles and helped bring convenience into our lives .
RFID is an essential tool used for tracking people .
In hospitals , RFIDs serve as a means for tracking patients as well as indentifying them .
This is especially the case for elderly people suffering from illnesses such as dementia who tend to lose their way .
Hospital staff and family members can thus easily track down the locations of their loved ones with the use of the RFID
( { http : //www.antonio-aguilar.com/files/papers/hisi_paper.pdf } [ HYPERLINK : http : //www.antonio-aguilar.com/files/papers/hisi_paper.pdf ] , 2009 ) . RFIDs are also used in monitoring crimes and in keeping our society safe .
Hence safety of society is ensured .
The main issues concern privacy and health .
The use of such a tracking device would mean that the locations and actions of the person will always be known .
In conclusion , RFIDs should not be banned as it can benefit society widely in many ways .
Despite the disadvantages it may pose , these can be offset by appropriate actions put in place .
Hence , society should not totally shun away from the use of RFID to track people but put in place measures to overcome the problems so as to ensure its optimal use .
However , the use of RFID in tracking people has brought about a lot of controversy .
There are two important reasons why RFID technology to track people should not be banned .
However , with the use of RFID to track people , this challenge may be overcome as hospitals use a " specially developed Hospital Movement Tracking System ( HTMS ) to trace the movements of Health care workers , patients and hospital visitors .
" ( Banks , Hanny , Pachano & Thompson , 2007 p.420 ) Secondly , the use of RFID to track people r the safety of workers who are working in hazardous working conditions .
In the event of an accident , rescue operators can locate workers who are RFID tagged and save them as soon as possible
Moreover , RFID technologies are durable and are able to withstand adverse conditions
( http : //www.rfidconsultation.eu/ , 2009 ) However , the World Health Organization has found out that safe use of RFID will not have any adverse effects on human health health
Moreover , others oppose this as it causes invasion of privacy due to leakage of personal information to the third part
Nevertheless , there is data protection technology that is already in place to prevent unauthorized individuals from accessing sensitive information .
In conclusion , we should not ban RFID technologies to track people as there are many benefits and because of its use as an effective measure to locate individuals during times of emergencies .
This is due to countries becoming more affluent , and thus people better living environment and are also more educated to be conscious of their health .
In order to ease the aging process such that the elderly can live without being neglected and also in comfort , various policies have been implemented .
To a large extent , these have helped to ease the aging process through investing in healthcare for the elderly , giving financial aids to the elderly and also enhancing the psychological well being of the elderly .
( Government of Singapore , 10 February 2009 ) Healthcare professionals like nurses are also trained to be able to handle more complicated procedures as compared to the past ( The straits times , 17 August 2009 ) .This provides quality healthcare for the elderly in a high standard of living environment .
It may be costly to implement these policies , but it is necessary as in future the aging population is projected to soar .
In Japan , it is expensive to create and own a nurse robot , but it is necessary as in future there will be lack of human resources to take care of the elderly .
( James Brooke , 5 March 2004 ) Such technology will allow the elderly to be self equipped to take care of themselves , which is vital in the current competitive society where their children will be overloaded with work to take care of them .
Secondly , the financial aids plan policy makers come up with also manages to ease the aging process .
Governments help to reduce the burden of the elderly by subsidizing healthcare , giving financial aid and also forcing people to save for retirement .
In Singapore , the elderly are entitled to a subsidy of 75 per cent of the fees charged at polyclinics and even free medical service for frail or disabled elderly .
( Government of Singapore , 10 February 2009 ) However , some may argue that the financial benefits may still be inadequate as the elderly may need long term medical treatment and take longer time to recover .
Also , the elderly may abuse the medical services when they are provided with financial aid .
( Government of Singapore , 10 February 2009 ) This will lighten the financial burden of the elderly , easing the aging process as they can retire with more security and less worry .
In addition , enhancing the psychological well being of the elderly can make aging less depressing and cultivates a pleasant lifestyle for the elderly , thus making the aging process more enjoyable .
There are policies like revising the retirement age from 65 to 67 in the United States ( U.S. Social Security Administration , 1 April 2009 ) and also from 60 to 65 in Taiwan .
There are also retraining and upgrading programs , like the Senior Community Service Employment Program initiated by the United States Department of Labor ( U.S. Department of Labor , Employment & Training Administration ( ETA ) , 13 Jan 2009 ) , to make them be as competent as the young people , making the elderly still feel young at heart .
This is particularly the case for policies that aim to increase birth rate .
For example , the baby bonus scheme in Singapore has been ineffective as the birth rate remains at 1.28 .
The attractive financial incentives like giving cash gift of up to $ 4,000 each for the 1st and 2nd child and $ 6,000 each for a 3rd and 4th child and also providing of 4 months have not been enough to make people want to have more children .
This can be due to the lifestyle of Singaporeans like having long working hours and high standard of living ; thus , they prefer not to have any children .
As long as the government considers solutions to these issues like encouraging working from home , the policy may be more effective .
If these policies were successful , they will definitely ease the aging process .
In the coming years , more countries will also be facing this problem and thus different types of policies should be explored to prepare for the future .
That there should be a limit on public spending on the aged so that money could be diverted to other areas of the country 's development ( Peterson , 2001 ) is a suggestion that should be implemented in order to combat the rising cost of healthcare for the elderly .
With the rapid growth of the elderly population , for example in a country like Singapore , where the median age is expected to hit 41 years old from the present 36 ( Wijaya , 2009 ) , increasing public spending in healthcare could further strain the government 's expenditure as more money needs to be poured in to cater to the growing numbers of elderly in the country .
There are several factors that explain the need to limit public spending on elderly healthcare .
This move will be beneficiary in the long run as it does not only ensure that the country is progressing economically , it is also securing a brighter future for the healthcare sector as more money could be spent on it .
The government can now choose to allocate some money into healthcare , invest the remaining money and as time goes by , not only the government will be earning more profits but the healthcare will be getting a bigger allocation .
However , should the government decide to spend all of the 100 dollars on healthcare , there will be no profits and the government will also suffer from a deficit .
Secondly , public spending on elderly healthcare should only be limited to the elderly who really need it to prevent abuse by other citizens .
If no limits are set , other citizens can abuse the system by using it indiscriminately , denying the rights of healthcare to truly needy patients .
An example could be seen in the United Kingdom , where healthcare is fully subsidized by the government .
This may in turn cause a clogging up of cases where there will be more patients waiting longer for their operation , reducing the quality of the healthcare sector ( Press Association , 2005 ) .
This could probably cause a public outcry as the current economic crisis has yet to fully subside and the government should instead focus on recovering the country 's economy first .
Some might argue that it is the government 's duty to look after the welfare of its citizens , but if the government were to look after all the elderly without the help of the children , it would certainly cost the government an enormous amount of time and money .
The government needs to first concentrate on more important matters regarding the country , for example in issues regarding national safety , trade , education , international relations and defense , to ensure that the nation 's interests are safeguarded and that the government does act as a nursery home for the old .
Children should be taught the importance of filial piety since young to ensure that they do not abandon their responsibility of taking care of their parents when they are old .
An example would be the Maintenance of Parents Act in Singapore , where parents could lawfully demand support from their children in court .
In conclusion , there are many reasons why public spending on elderly healthcare should be limited to allow governments to channel the money to other areas of development .
While healthcare for the elderly is still important , governments must ensure that other important areas will not get neglected as well .
Ageing population is a serious problem faced by many developed states .
The ageing population is creating many social problems such as healthcare problems , high government expenses and high income taxes , which are causing stress for young workers and the aged people .
Many states such as the US , the UK , Japan and Singapore start to implement various policies such as increasing child birth rate and introducing plans for the elderly and health care policies to ease the ageing process .
However , most of these policies tend to be ineffective in easing the ageing process because they either have their limitations or fail to solve the social problems behind the ageing process .
This essay is going to examine the limitations and the problems ignored by those current policies .
Health care policies in many developed countries ease the ageing process to a very limited extent , because they create social burden and fail to service minorities most of the time .
For example , the UK has tried to make the nation a welfare state , but this leaves heavy tax burden to the working class and creates low working incentive for the workers .
For example , Japan has introduced medical service which allows its citizens to save for their personal medical account so that they can use the money when they fall sick in their old age .
Similarly , Singapore has introduced the same kind of policies called Medi-save and Medi-shield .
However , these policies can not help those people who have long term diseases because these diseases require a huge amount of money to cure .
Ironically , the World Health Organization has released a report in year 2006 which shows that the number of people who have long term diseases such as heart disease and cancer is increasing sharply .
The data also shows that stressful working life contributes to the poor health of the people .
Moreover , the minorities who do not have proper job or income and do not have a medical care account will not be taken care of by the health service .
They will have nothing to rely on when they fall sick .
Therefore , the health care policy in most developed countries should be improved to help those patients with long term diseases and those who are neglected .
Today , two leading states in the areas of slowing down the ageing population , Japan and Singapore , have implemented " Baby Bonus Policy " .
Basically , families that give birth to more than one child will get economic support from the government as they help ease the ageing process .
This is because many elderly couples only have one child to support them and this always puts a heavy burden on the child .
Hence , with more children , more economic support could be provided and the old parents could be taken care of better .
However , the " Baby Bonus Policy " does not work well although almost everyone is aware of its benefit .
This is because firstly , the stressful social environment forces couples to put their time and effort in their work , so that they are unable to spend time with each other .
Secondly , getting more salary through longer working hours makes life much easier than appealing for limited economic aids by having many children .
Thus , the government fails to notice the two root causes of the evil .
Therefore , baby bonus policy could not increase the birth rate effectively in easing the ageing process .
The modern society today is imbued with modern values that lead to the ageing population , thus causing some government policies to become ineffective in easing the ageing process .
Many states have introduced housing policies , which allow the young couples to live near their parents or which give priority in purchasing houses to those people who have married .
This allows the couples to take care of each other especially when they are old , or to take care of their parents when they are still young .
However , the states fail to realize that people 's values towards family are changing today .
The family bonding in most western societies is very weak and the young generation does not really have a sense of filial piety in their minds .
Also , the stressful working market created by capitalism today is taking away so much time and effort from people that they do not have time with their family , or even can not think of having a family .
It creates a modern value that allows people of opposite sex to live together without having a family .
What if the idea of family vanishes ?
If all these assumptions occur , the housing policy will not be relevant at all .
In conclusion , most of the current policies in easing the ageing process have their limitations or are ineffective .
The fundamental problem is that the states fail to realize the underlying social problems which contribute to the stressful ageing process .
Hence , in order to ease the ageing process , the policies should be designed to solve the root problems of the evil rather than just focus on the surface of the problems .
Population aging , as stated in the introduction of the report World Population Aging : 1950-2050 ( 2002 ) , is the process by which older individuals become a proportionally larger share of the total population .
It was at first experienced by the developed countries , but is now taking place around the globe .
Firstly , the elderly are leading longer lives .
A special report from Economist.com ( 2009 ) states that average life expectancy for the whole world was only 30 years during the 1990s , and that for the rich countries under 50 .
However , the figures have each increased to 67 and 78 , and the increase has no signs of stopping .
The next factor contributing to the aging phenomenon is the declining of birth rates as people tend to have fewer kids than in the previous years .
Despite these measures , the birth rate of Singapore has not increased significantly ( Mui Teng Yap , 2003 ) .
The " Stop at two " policy had been so successful that couples in Singapore saw that they could have a better standard of living with a smaller family .
Educated women prefer to pursue their careers before getting married ; thus , women have a sense of insecurity in losing their job when they have to take maternity leave or when they are about to give birth to their child .
Other than that , educated women do not just want to be successful in their careers , but they also want to be a good mother .
The declining performance of the body limits the ability of the aged to care for themselves .
It has improved our quality of life in many ways , especially in the field of medical science .
However , this leads to an implication that the upper class and middle class people who are likely to have easier access to information will take advantage of this policy .
This , in turn will create a misguided impression that medical fees of the elderly are high , resulting in the debate between the government and policy makers whether to limit healthcare spending on the aged or not .
Some may argue that the measure of increasing the retirement age should be able to reduce the negative effects of the aging population .
It is true that by letting the elderly people carry on working can increase manpower in labor markets and simultaneously increase their savings to support themselves during old age .
In some cases , employers have the notion that in order to employ the aged , the setting of the workplace might have to undergo some changes to accommodate to the needs of the elderly .
In short , life today is not similar to that in the past , and challenges lies ahead waiting for us to overcome .
The effects of the aging population may be exaggerated , but we should not lack foresight and neglect them .
By 2050 , the figure will increase to 35 percent for those aged 60 years and above ( Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports 2008 , February ) . Ageing population is a challenge for Singapore for the coming years .
Money is needed in areas such as transportation , research and development , infrastructure , investment and defense .
In terms of quality of life , Singapore tops in Asia and is No . 32 in the world ( Mercer Human Resource Consulting Survey in 2008 ) .
Singapore also scored 22nd in monocle 's list of top livable cities in 2008 and ranked top 5 in city infrastructure ( Mercer 's 2009 Quality of Living survey highlights 28 April 2009 ) . Singapore 's Changi airport has accumulated 250 awards and is recognized as one of the best airports in the world .
Therefore the current problem Singapore is facing now is the aged population .
Money should be allocated for the ageing population .
Singapore is currently a developed country .
Currently the investment in the resort worlds in both the Marina Bay and Sentosa will bring in more income to Singapore .
Hence money is still needed for the country 's development in order to maintain its world class standard .
Although money is important for the growth of Singapore , the current problem of the ageing population must still be addressed .
Citizens are the most valuable asset of a country .
In order for Singapore to prosper , money is necessary to solve the problem of ageing population .
In order to encourage the elderly people 's self-reliance , the government introduced central provident fund in 1955 .
It is a compulsory saving plan for the work force .
The money can also be used to pay for medical cost incurred .
Despite the introduction of the central provident fund , the aged population feel that it is insufficient for them to retire .
In 2008 , the average life expectancy of Singaporeans has increased to 80 from 61 in 1957 ( Mon , Apr 14 2008 News Straits Times ) .
Money is needed to encourage the elderly to work longer and pursue lifelong learning .
For example incentives are given to companies like MacDonald who employ retired workers .
Trainings are given at subsidized rate for workers to upgrade themselves and to remain competitive in the workforce .
For example , housing grants are given to encourage children to stay close to their parents .
The government has increased the housing grants from $ 30000 to $ 40000 ( HDB Website ) .
Even though the government encourages children to take care of their parents , there are still cases where parents sue their children for not taking care of them .
Singapore government has passed the maintenance of parents act to make children look after their parents .
In cases where the elderly do not have any children or do not have any savings left , money is also needed to cater for their daily expenses , housing and medical expenses .
Eventually by 2050 , 35 percent of the population will have reached the age of 60 years and above .
Money is needed to spend on areas like medical centres , new infrastructure and homes for the elderly .
More medical centres are needed to cater for the ageing population which require more healthcare assistance .
For buildings like shopping malls and HDB flats , the government and developers should spend more money on building elderly friendly infrastructure and
upgrading existing HDB flats to make it more elderly friendly .
Examples include lift upgrading , slopes for wheel chairs and old folk corners .
Despite the fact that ageing population is imposing more cost on the government , their well being must still be taken care of .
If not , when elections come , the government might lose their votes as 35 percent of the population will reach the age of 60 and above by 2050 .
Over the last 50 years aging population has been considered a big problem that affects western countries economic development .
However , during the next 50 years there will be a dramatic increase in the aged and it is inevitable for Asian countries to face this challenge from now on .
To date , aging population whose age is above comprises 14 percent of the world .
According to the survey done by the United Nations , aging population in Asia is estimated to increase by 314 percent , from 207 million to 857 million in 2050 and among those sub regions East Asia will suffer most .
Japan is still the country with the largest and the most rapidly growing aging population .
Both China and Singapore are anticipated to become the second right after Japan in 30 years and those aged above 65 will make up 20 percent of the total population .
Moreover , the rate of birth has kept falling and a family will have fewer adult children than in the past , which puts more burdens on the government .
So it has been a controversial issue whether governments should cut public spending on the aged and divert it to other areas of economic development to secure stable productivity and GDP .
It seems that aging population will become a worse problem if current low-level government spending is going to be cut further .
However , taking into account all the advantages and disadvantages of the policy of cutting government spending on the elderly , there should be more effective ways to handle this challenge rather than directly or indirectly giving " fish " to the elderly , so it will be necessary for the government to limit public spending on the aged .
There is no dispute that the average age is climbing up continuously as it is impossible to prevent people from getting old . Increased life expectancy is the most outstanding but only one of the features of aging population .
It is more important to pay attention to other trends and characteristics of aging population in order to solve this problem in some other ways .
One of the biggest factors that the aged may put excessive burden on economic development is the less support to the elderly from their adult children as a consequence of lower birth rate and higher child care costs .
For example , there was a baby booming period between 1947 and 1949 in Japan but since 1949 the total fertility rate has started to fall , .
The same kind of situation also occurs in Singapore , China , Thailand , South Korea and other Asian countries .
On the other hand , the number of adult children who are willing to live with their parents has fallenl .
The proportion of Japanese elderly people living with their adult children fell from 80 percent in 1950 to 50 percent in 1990 ( Onawa and Rather 1997 ) , in South Korea from 78 percent in 1984 to 47 percent in 1994 ( Weinstein et al.1994 ) .
Thus it will be more essential for the government to emphasize the responsibility that adult children should bear to support the family rather than directly give financial support to the aged , which will in turn lay more tax burdens on the working population .
In other word , making the adult children actively support their parents will be better than asking them to passively pay higher tax .
In addition to getting support from adult children , it is equally important to provide more employment opportunities or put off the mandatory retirement age for the elderly , which is also a good method to as people tend to live longer than before .
Similar to the problem of adult children , although the number of aging population keeps rising , the number of old people who could get a chance to work either full time or part time tends to fall due to changing economic and social environments where fewer employers want to hire old labor - from 38 percent of the population 65 and above in 1950 to 25 percent in 2000 and 22 percent in 2010 according to the survey conducted by the United Nations .
This of aged and working populations affects the economic productivity to a great extent .
So the government 's task is to implement more policies concerning both the mandatory retirement age and employers ' age restriction .
For instance , hiring the elderly as part-time workers may be a good choice for both the aged and employers so as to enable the elderly to earn more as well as to enhance productivity .
This is also a good way to let the aging population by themselves .
Due to the fact that it may not be very realistic for those people who are already very old , disabled or need much medical care to be very productive , some other ways shall be combined to tackle the problem of aging population .
Both Singapore 's and Japan 's pension schemes cover all of the work force , placing great financial burden upon their governments .
Although it 's useful in the short term to the aged , with the surprising speed of growth of aging population , it will be more difficult for the governments to sustain this policy . In some other countries such as Indonesia , India , the Philippines , where the political system is not stable or in China , where the demographic structure is mainly made up of low-income working class , these policies would not be effective .
And in a country with a pay-as-you-go system like Japan there will definitely be some problems in the future if its government does not stop spending more on public pension as the number of retirees becomes larger and larger relative to the number of employees .
More taxes will also be collected from future generation .
So the best way to cope with this problem will be to encourage today 's working force to save more money for themselves instead of depending on their descendants or government .
This method is basically to set up a healthier financial saving system .
Apart from the methods mentioned above , there are more and more effective methods need to be devised to handle aging population instead of directly spending on the aged .
The elderly are a large part of the society that can not be ignored and the best way to keep a sustainable economic development and at the same time give them a beautiful autumn is to set up a system rather than focusing on any single policy .
By the year 2050 , our median age would be 54 years
( Lee , 2009 ) .The government has been taking the challenge of easing the aging process very seriously .
In the economic sector , the government has implemented the Central Provision Fund ( CPF ) to ensure that the elderly would be financially capable to support themselves when they retire .
The CPF savings are entirely invested in special government bonds which are risk free and have long term interest rate.CPF has been a major source of financial supplement for most of the retired elderly . CPF ensures that all working Singaporeans have a saving that is set aside to support their needs when they retire .
However the government also realises that the CPF savings might not be sufficient for aging needs . Hence , to help enhance the function of CPF , the government is adding an annuity scheme known as the CPF LIFE ( Lifelong Income For The Elderly ) that will provide a secure stream of income for the elderly
( Lee,2009 ) .This is done when Singaporeans reach the age of 55 , part of their CPF savings will be transferred into an annuity which will provide a steady stream of income from the age of 65 for life . CPF is a mandatory saving scheme and therefore it ensures that the elderly will have the financial means to support their aging process .
The government has also been enacting laws that require employers to offer re-employment to their workers until the age of 65.This is a flexible approach because the workers do not have to get the same job or pay .
The government has incorporated this approach from Japan because it is a pragmatic step compared to just increasing the official retirement age .
To tackle this issue the government has introduced the Workfare Income Supplement which is a negative income tax and it is weighted in favour of older workers .
In addition to that , the government has various programs to retrain older workers and improve their skills .
The healthcare sector has also contributed to helping to ease the aging process .
The national health care expenditure has been kept at 4 % of Singapore 's gross domestic profit ( GDP ) ( Lee , 2009 ) . Although healthcare expenditure will inevitably rise in the coming years , the government has introduced the 3Ms that will help the needy in their healthcare expenditure .
The 3Ms are MediSave , MediShield and MediFund.The introduction of these 3Ms has helped the elderly in financing their healthcare .
On top of the 3Ms , the government has also introduced Eldershield which is an insurance scheme that gives financial protection to those who need long-term care , especially during old age .
( Ministry of Health ) In any event where the elderly become severely disabled , they can get a monthly cash payout .
To ensure that every elderly gets medical attention , the government has built new hospitals such as Jurong National Hospital and Khoo Teck Puat Hospital to accommodate more patients .
The government is also building step-down care sectors which include more community hospitals , nursing homes and home care centres to provide better elderly care .
The government is aware of this situation and it has come up with a solution to overcome this problem by linking up acute-care hospitals with community ones .
This allows patients to recuperate at community hospitals and make room for more serious medical conditions to be treated in acute-care hospitals .
This is an effective solution because the role of caring for the elderly is divided as effectively as possible between the private and the government sectors .
To ensure better comfort for the elderly , the government has also been upgrading home care to serve the elderly better .
The government has also upgraded infrastructure to help ease the aging process .
The Housing and Development Board has been building more studio apartments to accommodate senior citizens .
The bus system is also improved by making buses wheelchair accesible.The trains in Singapore are already wheelchair accessible .
The government has also gone beyond transportation and housing to help ease the aging process by providing neighbourhoods with decent public toilets and green spaces which enable the elderly to lead an active lifestyle .
In conclusion , most of the policies and steps taken by the government have helped ease the aging process to a large extent .
In the areas of healthcare and financial security the government has been constantly upgrading and implementing new strategies to help ease the aging process .
Hence the measures taken by the government are effective ones and they have helped the elderly age comfortably .
However , with the world noticing the shift in its demographics to a more aged society , things are becoming more accommodating for the elderly .
The rising trend of companies hiring a greater number of older workers is providing older folks greater financial stability , allowing them to have the spending power to live independently .
In Singapore , seventy-five percent of unionized companies have committed to rehiring older workers , and forty percent of these unionized companies already have in place formal re-hiring procedures in addition to ad-hoc arrangements that are commonly made
( 2009 ) .
The government has also introduced better initiatives to ensure the elderly are provided for .
Often , the issue is that the elderly are neglected by their adult children and left to survive on their own .
The government thus introduced the Maintenance of Parents Act to prevent adult children from abandoning their elderly parents
( Khalik , 2009 ) .
) Furthermore , housing policies which entice married children to stay near or with their parents have been introduced as incentives
Appendices , appendix C. Retrieved from http : //www.mcys.gov.sg/successful_ageing/report/Appendices.pdf ) . These policies are targeted at curbing this social issue that has become serious enough to be highlighted in Singapore 's National Day Rally .
These two policies are some of the ways that the government is looking into to help the elderly have a better and easier life during their twilight years .
In the United States , an 80 year old retired truck driver was forced to sell his house of 33 years to pay off a $ 15 000 medical bill which was not covered by his health insurance policy
( Goldsmith , 2008 ) .
Such possible failure of medical policies has spurred efforts to better protect the old .
The scheme ensures the elderly have the money to pay should they require long-term medical care
In our society , the aged have been marginalized in the struggle of the survivor of the fittest as their contributive power to the society is reduced .
Yet , as a society matures , one can see how ingenious and novel methods have been developed and set into place to help bring the elderly from living on the margins of a society into being a part of the mainstream again .
The three developments and policies highlighted are examples of the efforts made to help ease the ageing process for the elderly by helping them keep themselves relevant to the society and their family .
It is interesting to note , also , that in helping to ease the ageing process , the society has prepared itself to adapt to the prospect of an ageing population .
Some feel that giving our full support to the elderly is of the utmost importance while others suggest limiting expenditure on the aged , being conscious of concerns from other sectors of the country such as economic growth and sustainability .
I agree with the latter ; those concerns are very real , and if left unattended , can pose a serious threat to the country 's development .
In this essay , we will be addressing these dilemmas and attempt to propose several possibilities as well as solutions that come with the various alternatives .
Limiting public expenditure is something which governments must consider seriously .
From a pragmatic standpoint , a majority of the elderly are unable to contribute to economic growth due to deteriorating health conditions which come naturally with aging .
Some common conditions such as rheumatism , failing eyesight and hearing , dementia , Parkinson 's disease , may render them unfit for work .
Not only are the elderly hindering a country 's economic growth , they are depleting it at an alarming rate as well .
Another reason why public spending on the elderly should be limited is that the funds could be diverted into other sectors of the country 's development .
Experts predict a financial toll in the near future , stating , " East Asia may experience widespread capital shortages as funds are diverted from financing productive investments in Hong Kong and Singapore to financing pension deficits in Berlin and Washington .
Even if we have enough capital for elderly spending , recent surges of new pandemics such as the H1N1 virus , call for more funding into the medical field .
Limiting public spending does not mean depriving them of support , but it means providing what 's necessary .
Certain categories fall into the gaps in the system and are left dry and powerless , even without the basic needs .
" [ 3 ] This example is one that stresses flexibility .
Spending on the aged should also be contextualized accordingly in economic situations , such as the recent economic crisis where employers are extremely selective , making jobs all the more scarce for the elderly .
Clearly , it can be seen that though limiting public spending on the elderly might produce certain immediate difficulties , it will ease the process inevitably in the long run .
However , the application of flexibility and context is most crucial as there are indeed too many factors and variables for the system to account for ; thus , it is better that humans master the system instead of the other way around .
The issues of age challenge the whole of society and put it to the test ,
" says Simone de Beauvoir in The Coming of Age ( 1970 ) , clearly reflecting the impact of the rising aging population that is happening around the world .
Governments often rack their brains to come up with the best solutions in terms of policies and research and development .
For example , some of them do not see the need of having babies and view having children as a potential source of problem to their ever-stressful life .
Thus , many are put off by the idea of having more children due to the accompanying life-time commitment of raising a child .
Thus , even if the legal retirement age was raised , it has clearly produced limited results .
As a result , employers tend to shut their doors to older workers .
In line with the above efforts to tackle the problem of the graying population , the government introduced the Parents ' Maintenance Act in 1996 to impose on filial piety .
Family ties may be further strained since the children are not taking care of their parents willingly .
Taking it from the parents ' perspective , some of them may not even consider the act of being abandoned by their children a shameful matter .
In all , moving beyond the law to enhance the perceptions of the elderly is a more practical way to increase the ability and willingness of the society to coordinate with the government in tackling the " grey tsunami " .
With the growing population and various problems that the present government face today , the governments are finding it tedious to balance the budget to ensure that all areas of development are being met .
Maintaining and sustaining a country is not just about looking after the aged , but also about developing growing sectors of our nation .
Although it is essential for the government to spend on the graying population , there are ways to minimize this spending , and this amount can then be used on other areas of the country 's growth and development , such as maintaining our country 's defense and improving the education system .
Our parents are the ones who have brought us up since young , providing us with basic necessities , educating and grooming us to be a worthy person of society , and showering us with love and concern that all individuals need .
Not only does it benefit the government as spending on the aged can be reduced , it also benefits them both economically and socially .
Furthermore , working can help to decrease boredom in retirement , as time will then be spent engaging in productive activities at work , and not be whiled away doing nothing .
Apart from defense , the government needs to invest in our country 's development as well , and this includes improvements in our education system .
However , other areas should not be neglected , as our nation 's growth and development are of vital importance as well .
Many ways are , indeed , present to help limit public spending on the aged .
The goal of limiting public spending on the aged will be made possible if the proposed measures are strongly enforced , and high cooperation among citizens of our society will help to deal with this issue too .
However , what we do not know or are still confused about is an effective way to both take care of the aged and enhance the development of other fields .
It is a matter of money usage .
There is a suggestion that governments should limit expenditures on the aged so that they will have money to spend on other areas to develop the countries .
The first point needed to be clarified is how limited government funding on the elderly should be and what will happen if the expenditures are below an acceptable level .
With fast-aging population and the restricted national budgets which do not allow spending generously on the elderly , this limit should be maintained at an acceptable level which ensures that the basic needs of the aged such as food , clothing , housing , transportation and healthcare are met .
However , in some nations , especially developing countries , in order to meet the need of investing in other areas to push the countries forward , the governments cut down the basic expenditures on the aged .
Cutting down the fiscal costs on the aging population to support other areas does not mean that those areas will receive all the benefits .
Imagine a situation in which without sufficient support from the government , the aged become a burden to their families. .
In that case , if the fiscal costs on the aged are cut down to spend more on the young generation , it can lead to the result that the money aimed to support one target in a family - the young - will be shared to partly meet the demands of both the elderly and the young .
In other words , the purposes of investing in other areas of development by using money saved from the fiscal costs on the aged can not be fully fulfilled .
In developing countries , decreasing the basic expenditures on the aged can lead to a worse situation .
The aged in these nations , especially in rural areas , do not merely need money to lead the rest of their lives , but also need money raise their children or grandchildren .
They share with their younger generations their limited monthly retirement pensions or allowances to cover all the costs of living , but usually , they would run out of money before the pensions/allowances of the next month come to their hands .
One of the productive areas to invest in is economy [ 1 ] since economic development helps to raise the national budgets and thus raise the public expenditures on the elderly .
Money earned from investments in economy should be partly used to support the aged not only to lessen the burden on the families and to alleviate poverty from generations to generations , but also to ease the elderly 's lives .
The increasing size of the economy could be relatively limited , but spending more on the aged does allow the government to have more choices to take care of the aged in a better way .
In other words , what the government should do is not merely promoting economic growth but also taking action to link each increasing level of economic growth with a correspondingly higher level of the quality of life for the elderly .
In conclusion , limiting fiscal costs on the aged without thorough considerations could lead to unexpected results which directly affect the elderly themselves and their families , as well as indirectly impact on the society and the country 's development .
In cutting down the spending on the aged , governments must ensure that the basic needs of the aged are still satisfied and the money saved from fiscal restraint should be efficiently invested to be partially plowed back into the elderly .
In 1997 , there was an estimated 217,400 elderly persons aged 65 years and above forming 7.0 % of the population ; the figure will increase to 798,700,forming 18.4 % of the population by the year 2030.Currently , comprising 7 % of the population , the elderly utilize 20 % of public sector primary care and hospital services .
It has been estimated that there will be a four-fold increase in the utilization of health resources by 2030 , based on the increasing number of the elderly and
( ) Meanwhile spending on healthcare such as is growing and it can continue indefinitely because of the continuous introduction of new technologies and treatments that are beneficial .
could be defined as scarcity , which means resources are limited in quantity and iimplies that not all of society 's goals can be pursued at the same time .
In brief the government has insufficient funds to fulfill all wants and needs of the aged population .
There are certain development areas of the country such as education , infrastructure , defense , investment and poverty that still need to be taken care of .
Government budgets should only cater to the basic needs of the elderly .
Consequently a country can not afford to spend too much on the elderly because of practical realities .
Government budgets should be diverted to other areas of a country 's development since resources are limited .
Governments and policy makers have to decide what should be supported by the public sector , and what should be left to individuals to 'buy ' for themselves , depending on their own financial capacity .
In fact , governments should only focus on those elderly whoa re poor and needy , and who have been abandoned by their .
Education , infrastructure , defense and investment are the other areas that need to be looked after by governments .
For example , more public spending on education will raise more productive children so that a more affluent future generation can be produced and the size of tomorrow 's economy can be increased .
Moreover foreign investments will be discouraged if governments over-spend on an aging population and neglect developing other areas .
Furthermore it does not help much in economic growth if governments provide too much welfare support for the elderly .
Firstly elderly people are less productive than young people and most of them are retired or unemployed .
They are unable to continue to put their effort in developing the country 's economy and infrastructure .
This/ These will also increase government spending on the elderly .
The article " Doomsday Predications about Population Aging Are Exaggerated " by Robert B.Friedland and Laura Summer points out that with little economic growth , society faces fewer choices on how to care for those who are least able to care for themselves .
On the other hand , with sufficient economic growth there would be more choices and fewer persons in need .
In addition , governments should put more effort into and invest on those areas that are productive .
This will help the country 's economic growth .
For example , Singapore 's casino-resort project will bring many employment opportunities and it is estimated that there will be very high returns in the future for both Singapore as well as the investors of this project. .
Thus the income of citizens will rise and lead to increased savings .
This will reduce their reliance on others like the government and their families .
On the part of the government , they will be able to develop medical technology and provide more medical schemes to help the aged .
Furthermore , the rate of poverty will be lower .
People would be able to afford to look after their elderly .
Governments and policy makers have to decide what is essential and should be supported by the public sector .
In brief , leaders in governments must and implement practical measures to cope with the problems of a fast aging population .
Public funds can be collected through implementing taxes on the citizens and tariffs on incoming trade items from other countries .
These funds are then used to either solve a current problem in a country , for example , an ageing population where help is needed to ensure the livelihood of the older generation in order to ease the burden the current generation has on taking care of the old .
Or these funds could be used to improve the education , communication and transportation infrastructure of a country , thereby improving the standard of living for the nation .
In this case , I would think that more funds should be allocated to a country 's development and less on the aged , as a country 's development will help solve or ease the problem of an ageing population in many other ways than directly allocating funds to address this problem. .
The government should allocate more funds to building a better education system , which will lead to more educated and productive future generations .
As the future generations will be more educated and productive , they will be able to contribute more to the economy and this , in turn , should get them a higher income .
A higher income will allow the younger generation to support themselves better and therefore provide for their own parents , so that the government can spend less on caring for the old .
Another outcome of higher education standards is that both the younger and older generations will better understand what could happen to them when they grow old .
This means both the younger and older generations will be able to better plan for their old age and the problems that come with it , for example , deteriorating health .
This makes lower health subsidies from the government possible as more people know how to stay healthy .
With an improvement in education standards , more students will pursue their studies in Singapore , creating a chance to convert these visiting students into local citizens , which will in turn increase the tax base for the future .
Both the above improvements will boost Singapore 's income , allowing the government to use more money to address various national issues , be they economic development or social problems , such as an aging society .
While the idea of improving education to ease the aging problem in the future is workable , there may still be a problem of individuals who will not be able to .
In a society , there will always be different people with different backgrounds , for example , the rich and educated versus the poor and illiterate .
But the illiterate will not stay illiterate always ; if they put an effort to improve and are given a chance for good education , they can still develop into a group of productive Singaporeans .
By allocating more funds to education and infrastructure , governments can ensure effective development in the country , thereby increasing the standard of living .
This will also lead to a society with more educated and self-sufficient families , where minimal subsidies are needed to help a minority of the population , thereby limiting spending on the problem of the aged or an aging population .
We all know that the elderly have devoted all their intelligence , knowledge and strength to our society .
Basically , it is the moral responsibility of our society to do its best to support the elderly even at the expense of other areas of the country 's development .
There is no denying the fact that each country has a limited budget , so it can not afford to spend too much on the elderly because it also has to spend on other areas of the country 's development .
For example , there are also many other needy people like orphans , the disabled or unemployed that want to be subsidized by the government .
It is very hard for them to earn enough money for themselves .
The fact is they can not compete with others .
Therefore , it would be a huge financial burden for their relatives to support them .
Unless the government spends more money to support them and create more job opportunities for them , they will be left to fend for themselves and .
However , we should consider who should be given priority and who deserves a share of the national budget the most .
The elderly usually do not have enough strength to do manual labor whereas mental work requires perspicacity and concentration , areas in which they can not compete with younger candidates .
For example , in Singapore , I have seen that almost all cleaners are the elderly .
Nevertheless , they do not look strong enough to do such manual work , but they still have to do it , to earn their own living .
Obviously , old people have fewer chances to work for their own living compared with other needy people who still have physically healthy physically bodies .
What is more , the elderly should be respected and for their contributions in the days of their youth .
The elderly were once hard working not only in raising their children but also in devoting their strength and intelligence for a better society like the one we have today .
Although there is a limit to the national budget and the government has to balance spending in different areas for the country 's development , subsidy for the elderly should not be cut .
If each person has a sense of responsibility towards increasing the size of today 's economy and tax base , then it will not be a big problem for us to spend more money on the aged .
For example , the fertility rate in the United States of America was at an all time high which was around the range of 3.0 - 3.5 ( Baby Boom Generation .
2009 ) . In fact , the name " baby boomers " was derived from an increase in fertility rates globally after World War 2 .
53 years later , the baby boomer generation is moving from the middle age to the senior years years , and issues regarding the aging process have started popping up like mushrooms after the rain .
Singapore , one of the most developed countries in the South East Asian region , has not taken this issue lightly .
According to the Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports , the elderly ( age 65 and above ) population in Singapore is at 8.6 % ( 2008 ) and it is expected to grow to 18.7 % by the year 2030
The research and development and social policies formed by the government are able to help ease the aging process of the aging population .
In the medical sector , extensive research and development has led to advancements in easing the aging process .
Through the development of new supplements , we now have a wide array of vitamins , tonics and so on for specific .
One of the common diseases that an elderly person has is osteoporosis .
This results in fragile bones which have an increased risk of incurring bone fractures .
Through research and development , the invention of bone densitometry has enabled doctors to detect osteoporosis earlier and give the right medical advice in preventing the disease from getting more serious .
This has greatly helped the aging population as
Besides that , the invention of the Magnetic Resonance Imaging ( MRI ) has also contributed to easing the aging process as cancer is able to be detected more accurately compared to when previous imaging technologies were used .
Therefore , through advancement in medical technology , the quality of life for the aged is still high thereby lengthening the life span of humans .
The main purpose of the CPF scheme is to provide financial security for the retired .
Under the CPF scheme , there are many subsidiary schemes such as Medisave , Medishield and Medifund .
These subsidiary schemes enable the aged to pay for their hospital and healthcare bills .
In addition , .
As the costs of living and healthcare have been increasing , these schemes are able to help reduce the financial burden of the aged .
Therefore , the CPF scheme created by the government has successfully ensured financial security for the aged so they would not need to search for employment to support their financial needs .
Other than the CPF scheme , a scheme for the aged named Eldershield was created to help the aged who suffer from disabilities .
The Eldershield scheme works like an insurance scheme which provides basic financial protection on a monthly basis for the aged .
The Housing Development Board has also created policies to cater to the aged such as " Granny Homes " and the Lease Buy Back Scheme .
" Granny Homes " is an economical choice for the aged when they live alone as the " Granny Homes " are small and easy to maintain compared to a normal HDB flat .
In addition to that , the aged would be living in a community of people in their age group , and this provides a good platform for the aged to socialize with their peers .
As for the Lease Buy Back Scheme , it provides an additional option for the low income elderly Singaporeans in 3 room or smaller flats to cash out part of the money locked up in their HDB flats for their daily expenses ( HDB , Electronic References , 2009 ) .
As most elderly stay alone these days and are not supported by their families , this scheme would be useful for them especially when they do not have stable financial security .
These two schemes created by the government would greatly relieve the burden of healthcare costs for the aged and so it would definitely benefit the aged .
In a nutshell , easing the aging process does n't just stop here with our current findings in the medical as well as other sectors nor with policies created by the government for the aged .
We should also play a part by taking care of our well-being in order not to be dependent on others for support .
At this moment in time , research and development still continues on to discover new findings and new medical inventions to help ease the aging process and also improve the quality of healthcare for the aged .
Governments are also looking into better ways and alternatives to provide the baby boomer generation a more secure environment with a lower financial burden , better health care and also better employability of the aged .
Nowadays , nobody can deny that an aging population is becoming one of the most serious problems to developed countries , including Singapore .
Recent research studies have shown that the proportion of the country 's residents aged 65 and above can reach the rate of 18.7 % in the next 20 years .
Population aging has become a cause of concern in the realm of finance to the government .
Should we limit public spending on the aged so that the money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development ?
However , in my opinion , public spending could be more productive if the government knows how to control the money spent on the aged and also how to invest in areas of development .
Among several areas of public spending on the aged , such as medical subsidies , public infrastructure , pension schemes , and financial aids , healthcare must be considered the most important area .
As healthcare costs are now getting more and more expensive , it becomes harder and harder for poor , old people to fulfill their payment for their medical bills .
Based on this situation , some claim that the government should automatically spend more on the aged , who deserve to be helped .
However , the national budget will come under pressure when growing numbers of elderly persons are supported by relatively fewer young persons , which leads to the question , " Can we really afford so much health care for an aging population , or are we heading toward a healthcare crisis in the near future ?
Nevertheless , the budget for healthcare is not infinite , so the government and policy makers must decide to which extent they will subsidize the healthcare cost of an individual , and this would probably depend on his own financial capacity .
The second reason is that public spending is not the only solution to the problem of population aging .
Researchers and policy makers have made a lot of suggestions and developed a lot of strategies to help buffet the negative impact of an aging population on our society .
Some of these include encouraging later retirement , , encouraging the elderly and their families to take more responsibility for their health , etc .
Therefore , instead of spending too much money on the aged , the government can think about realizing some of these policies , or or developing policies to solve the problem .
Last but not least , Singapore must spend money on a large number of other essential areas of development , such as education , infrastructure , defense , investmentsand so on
These areas of development are the key that a country needs in order to become a developed one .
Without good infrastructure , there will not be sufficient facilities for the country .
Without a good defense system , people will live in the danger of terrorism as well as of being invaded by enemy nations .
Therefore , these areas of development must be well invested in .
Moreover , when all of these areas are developed enough to fulfill , the living standard of Singaporeans will increase . Consequently , , the aged will receive more help and budget from the society , and they may even earn more money to support themselves too .
In conclusion , Singapore , as well as many European and North American countries , is facing the problem of an aging population .
If we do not put enough effort to solve the problem right now , it will be a problematic issue in the future .
As the problem is controversial and there are a lot of different opinions surrounding it , the government and the policy makers must know how to make the right decision to come up with the best solution for the country .
We need to consider many factors that affect our decision , such as whether we have enough money to afford all the healthcare cost , or whether there are any other areas of the nation 's development that really need our investment .
Among these , the increasing number of aged people as well as the decrease in fertility rate as a new way of living is a challenge that the world has to face in the next decade .
, especially in developed countries like Germany or Japan , where the aged population will make up a large proportion of the population soon .
, the elderly is receiving more and more support from the government , which is a strategy in social welfare development .
Therefore , this spending should be reconsidered carefully to avoid financial shortage in other areas of the country 's development .
As part of the effort to enhance social welfare , a lot of schemes have been adopted and operated in recent years for the sake of the elderly population .
Some intermediate and long-term care facilities like community hospitals , services like home medical and home nursing services , and aid like public subsidies in Singapore are perhaps good examples of support from the government .
In reality , the schemes below certainly accounted for not a small percentage of the increased public spending .
This growth in number of projects put heavier pressure on the government budget , which consequently created an imbalance in the expenditure for different domains .
This spending , furthermore , is likely to increase more and more in the next few .
Firstly , at the personal level , the aged have to be responsible for themselves .
When individuals are still at the working age , they should provide in advance for their life after retirement .
Saving and investing more of their income , for instance , are some ways to prepare for their old age .
Secondly , at the social level , it is the filial obligation of children to take care of their parents when they grow old .
This will obviously help to reduce the expenditure by sharing between the government and its citizens .
The most important reason why the government should limit spending on senior citizens is that it will constrain other sectors from taking advantage of the government budget .
Once the support for the elderly takes up too much of the budget , then other sectors of society can not receive adequate financial assistance .
Compared with the rise in expenditure for health , community development , youth and sports as mentioned below , government investment in strategic sectors like education in Singapore between 2005 and 2008 decreased from 994 to 856 million dollars ( nearly 14 % ) ( 2 ) .
In addition , there are other sectors such as industry , transportation and information technology which also play an important role in building a solid infrastructure for the nation 's development and which thus require proper concern from officials .
However , with a limited budget , the government is not capable of covering all expenses .
To a certain extent , restriction on is reasonable and necessary so that can be used to expand many other crucial areas .
This will contribute more to the progress of the society than .
In short , the government and policy makers should come to a reasonable decision on all projects .
In the face of a limited budget , public spending , should give priority to necessary schemes and identify which cost can be reduced in order to .
Clearly , the government can cut down on excessive support for the elderly because there are many other ways .
In this way , the money saved can be used to implement more urgent and practical policies that also contribute to the nation 's strength and potential .
According to the United Nations , 1 in every 5 persons throughout the world would be aged 60 years or older by the year 2050 .
One of problems is that the government might need to channel more revenue to meet the demands of the elderly group .
In the long run , this can lead to shrinkage in the Gross Domestic Product ( GDP ) of the country or even affect the other sectors of development .
To prevent such situations from happening , different governments of the developed nations have come up with policies to confront the challenges of an aging population .
However , this is not a fair assessment because there are elderly patients that have been abandoned by their children .
This is because some of them might find means testing humiliating as it forces people to declare themselves to be in poverty .
These examples go to show that the means-testing policy has not fully catered to the demands of its targeted group .
One of these considerations for couples is the need to strike a balance between family and work life when a new member is added to their family .
Lastly , the policy to raise the retirement age in developed nations does not serve as a long-term solution in meeting the needs of the elderly .
In Singapore , the government intends to raise the retirement age of the working group to 62 so that the elderly can continue to support themselves financially .
An employer would prefer to hire a young adult as compared to an elderly as the former can contribute to the company for a longer period of time .
Some might argue that even though the elderly can not compete with the younger generation for jobs , the government does organize job fairs to help the elderly seek jobs .
However , although these job fairs provide more working opportunities for the elderly , the success of such job fairs is largely dependent on the receptiveness of the elderly 's expectations of the scope of the new job .
All these obstacles show that raising the retirement age does not address the concerns of the elderly well .
Therefore , it is clear that social policies do not always meet the needs of the groups they seek to cater to .
No matter how well a social policy is constructed , there are still loopholes that are often overlooked by policy-makers .
Furthermore , it is important to note that social policies should be flexible so that they can make suitable changes to meet the demands of the society at different points in time .
Once the demands are met , the route to easing an aging population would be much more smooth-sailing than it is being thought .
It is common to see a society aging with the elderly population rising rapidly in recent years .
Although the society has a moral obligation to do all that it can to help the elderly , there are still limits to the budget the government can allocate to help the aged .
When there are limited resources , scarcity is unavoidable which leads to a situation where not everyone will benefit and there will be those who are in need who will be left out .
When policies are constrained by a budget .
One of the examples is the government plan to extend the working lifespan of the elderly .
With every year that by , they face the limitations of their physical and mental strength .
loss in sight , hearing and mobility as well as the development of are very common .
They also have to face the fact that they are unable to keep up with the workload they used to handle in their younger days even if they want to .
No matter how experienced or skilled an elderly person is , he or she will always be at a disadvantage compared to those who are younger , more energetic and most importantly , more productive than them .
Therefore , spending on the elderly should not be limited in order to better them .
Besides that , what the Singapore government did was introduce the Baby Bonus scheme to the public with the objective of encouraging the public to have more children .
This is important , as having more youths will increase the productivity of the country as well as spread the cost of development over a large population .
However , this scheme has not worked as well as predicted even though the government has put efforts into promoting it .
The scheme netted only a gain of 129 citizen births last year in 2008 compared to the number of births in 2003 .
Such a scheme is impractical even if it may work in the long run .
The reason is that not everyone is willing to have a baby just to get the benefit offered by the scheme .
Therefore , resources should be diverted directly to help the elderly to be able to cope with their problems immediately .
This may sound good and interesting but with the current economic status , where is less economic growth , tougher choices need to be made to cope with the demand of the society .
Even if the economy improves , the expenses of the elderly will just keep on getting higher ; it seems to only benefit the government and not the elderly .
Furthermore , will heavily burden those who have an elderly person at home and such stress leads many of them to abandon their elderly .
Besides that , there are still a segment of people that have no job , no savings nor even no family that we often .
If expenditure on the aged is cut off , how would we expect them to be able to survive and it is supposedly the obligation of the government to provide shelter to these people .
Although there are other areas such as education , infrastructure and defense that require our attention , it is also of equal importance for us to have the same concern for the elderly .
These people are the ones that have dedicated themselves to the development of the country in the past .
It is their right to enjoy the privileges provided by the government after their retirement .
If the expenditure towards the elderly is limited , many will be left in a lurch and thus among the elderly .
The tremendous improvement in nutrition and medication has led to life expectancy in the developed world increasing significantly .
Thus , many national budgets and economies will come under pressure as growing numbers of elderly people outnumber the number of younger people .
Despite all that , public spending on the elderly should not be limited as society has the moral obligation and to assist them in all aspects .
The elderly have contributed much to the country 's development so public expenditure on the elderly should not be limited .
It is undeniable that the elderly have made immense contributions to the country and their sacrifices create the relative social and economic comfort we enjoy now .
The elderly have become bright examples for the younger generation in various domains .
Many of them have made valuable contributions to the country in different fields such as politics , science and technology , economics and culture as well .
On top of that , most importantly , they have contributed to the nation by imparting their knowledge and experience to the younger generation .
For instance , over the years , the elderly have helped to build up the economy of Singapore by developing several policies and they have worked hard in securing and maintaining the stability of the country .
Although many may argue that public spending on the elderly should be limited , this will create an impact on the society and increase .
The limitation in public spending on the elderly may cause family members and individuals to shoulder a bigger responsibility in taking care of the elderly .
In addition , some of those expenses incurred to support the elderly will end up getting shifted back to the public sector through less direct and more expensive means .
For example , the rising cost of healthcare for the elderly has taken its toll on and many can not afford it .
Consequently , conflict and arguments among family members may occur in this matter .
Families and local communities will have to deal with those by restructuring welfare programmes .
Furthermore , the limitation in public expenditure on the elderly will also affect the level of physical , mental and emotional well-being of an elderly person .
With the decrease in public spending on the elderly , many elderly people will come under pressure as they will have greater financial dependency on others .
Subsidies on health care and treatment at community hospitals and nursing homes for the elderly for instance will be cut off , hence leaving the elderly to fend for themselves .
All this pressure could make them suffer from mental illness as their children may not look after them .
For most of the elderly , family members are the major source of social and financial support .
Without that support , the elderly may start to spend time reflecting on their past , remembering disappointments and that stage of life may turn into a time of despair and loneliness , with only little positive meaning in life .
All this could eventually lead to suicide and depression among the elderly .
The elderly should benefit from government , family and community care in all aspects to help them to ease their burden after what they have done for us over the years .
public spending on the elderly constitutes a safety net for them and all parties should work hand in hand to resolve .
The aging population has of late become a subject for discussion because the growth of an aging population has brought about serious health issues and social problems in the developed nations .
National budgets will also come under pressure as a growing number of elderly are supported by relatively fewer younger people .
Thus , to deal with such challenges , research has been carried out and development as well as policies have been developed to help the elderly .
The development in the field of economics has surprisingly contributed to easing the aging population problem .
Researchers believe that the critical challenge of an aging society is not only about how to accommodate the older population , but about how to ensure the productivity of future workers , regardless of age .
Thus , have been done by the government in encouraging the economic growth in our country in order to decrease the problems that may arise from the aging process .
To encourage the economic growth of our country , our government has worked hard to develop the tourism industry in our country .
Tourism in our country has successfully created a wide range of occupations for our citizens , such as tour guide , airline staff , drivers , hoteliers , caterers and interpreters .
The lower barrier to elder employment which has been set by the government has allowed employers to take in older workers to work in the jobs mentioned above .
People can work longer , accumulate more wealth and increase their savings .
At the same time , the poverty rate can be decreased .
After retirement , the elderly can also use the money that they have earned to support themselves without depending on their families .
By improving the business environment , our country has also undergone a dramatic climb in our economy .
This has created more business for our local traders .
Thus , taxes which are collected have increased and the income of our country has also risen .
These taxes have been used in the development of medical technology to help cure the incurable , such as heart attack , tuberculosis , cornea impairment and cataract .
There are also medical facilities and systems which have been lately introduced , such as laser therapy , dialysis machines and microsurgery .
With all these modern technologies , human life can be extended and people can live more healthily .
The elderly can be stronger and fewer of them will be suffering from medical conditions , such as stroke , diabetes , cancer and high blood pressure .
Employers who claim that the elderly are restricted in ability and mobility will also no longer have any excuse to reject elderly individuals who wish to work in their organization .
The government has worked hard to create opportunities for foreign investors to encourage foreign investment .
This has increased the foreign currency exchange and stopped the outflow of our local currency and hence strengthened the value of our money .
As a result , there has been a significant growth in our economy that has increased the income of our country .
The government has used the money to build more community hospitals and nursing homes which are well-equipped with elderly-friendly facilities .
They also provide a range of services to meet the needs of the elderly , such as medical care , nursing care , physiotherapy , dietary services and dental care .
The elderly can be admitted into the community hospitals or nursing homes if they need daily skilled nursing care or assistance in the activities of daily living because they have no caregiver to look after them at home .
On the other hand , there will be more choices and fewer people in need when there is sufficient economic growth .
The growth of the economy can solve many problems which arise from an aging population .
Excuses such as high cost of living making it hard for working adults to pay for their elderly 's living expenses will not exist too .
Obviously , efforts that the government put into developing the economy of our country have resulted in successful growth and inevitably , this has contributed to easing and solving the problems of an aging population .
Many developed countries are now facing the same crucial issue : an aging population .
Take Singapore as an example ; she will be witnessing a drastic demographic shift in history , with the age population ratio predicted to change drastically from one in twelve residents being over the age of 65 in 2005 to one in five residents in 2030 ( Community on Ageing Issues , 2006 ) .
Hence , there would be a need for governments to increase expenditure on the aged to accommodate this burgeoning age group .
, the crux of the issue here lies in how much this spending on the aged should be capped at .
critics argue that by limiting the amount spent on the aged and diverting the resources to other areas of the country 's development , the essential needs of the elderly would be neglected .
One such example is the healthcare needs of the elderly .
It would hardly be a surprise that healthcare costs for the elderly would continue to escalate in the decades ahead .
Furthermore limiting of public spending on the aged would shift more of these healthcare costs to the elderly themselves , causing the elderly to shoulder a heavier financial burden .
Additional profits reaped from the investment in other areas of the country 's development could in turn contribute to on the elderly significantly .
In fact , it is inevitable for the government to divert money to the other areas of development as an aging population affects these areas significantly .
One considerable implication of an aging population is its possible impact on the country 's future macro-economic performance ( Schuiz , Borowoki , & Crown , 1991 ) .
As the baby boomers , , begin to move out of the workforce , the country will face the problem of a shrinking workforce .
In Singapore , there are currently 8.5 economically active persons to support one elderly person .
By 2030 , the labour-dependency ratio will drastically drop to only 3.5 persons supporting one elderly person ( Central Provident Fund [ CPF ] Board ) .
This shrinking workforce may signal the advent of a less productive workforce and greater financial strain on the members of the workforce as they need to produce adequate amounts of output to support the burgeoning elderly population ( Schuiz et al. , 1991 ) .
sufficient economic growth would bring prosperity to the country and in turn benefit the society as a whole .
The additional profits reaped from this investment may in turn be re-channeled to the public funds to help the needy ones , including the elderly .
Hence , the investments in other areas of the country 's development would not be at the expense of the needs of the elderly ; in actual fact , they could create a win-win situation .
The government is still taking care of the aged in various aspects .
For instance , the Singapore government has passed the Maintenance of Parents Act to allow elderly parents to file lawsuits against their children for financial support ( Khalik , 2009 ) .
In addition , the government has long enforced individual savings through the mandatory CPF , compelling the population to save for their old age ( Wijaya , 2009 ) .
This approach taken by the government would enable the individuals to accumulate wealth , and hence depend less on their family and the government financially in their twilight years .
these various aspects show that governments have taken a more well-rounded approach in taking care of the needs of the elderly ; and that public spending on the aged is not and should not be used as a single depiction of how governments can express their concerns towards the elderly .
In a nutshell , limiting public spending on the aged and diverting resources to other areas of the country 's development do not necessarily mean that the government is neglecting the needs of the aged .
One should note that setting limits on public spending on the aged reduces the over-dependency of the aged on the government while diverting resources to other areas of development allows the country to prosper and subsequently benefit the whole community , which includes the aged .
It is through this approach that pressing issues such as the economic implications of an aging population can be resolved and at the same time , more revenue can be generated to help the needy that includes the elderly as well .
This essay will discuss the limit that should be imposed on the amount of funds that should be budgeted for the aged that would constitute a fair distribution of government resources .
If there is a tendency to spend more than necessary on the aged , other sectors of the economy might find that they lack finances to function adequately .
There is no doubt that some of the aged need help .
There is no doubt that we should ensure that the aged can age with dignity .
However , not only the aged , but who are dependent on the government 's help should also have the right to live with dignity .
It may be true that without help from the government , some senior citizens would struggle just to survive .
However , if the state takes care of the aged unconditionally , it would be a policy impossible to maintain in the long run .
Not having a limitation based on the results of means testing would lead to a large number of people applying for grants even when they are not in dire need of such concessions .
This is to make sure that those who eventually get the money are those who genuinely need financial assistance , not simply because they fall into the right age category
( Stolberg and Zeleny , 2009 ) President Obama aims to modify America 's health care policy to one that 'provides security and stability to those who have insurance and cover those who do not , all without adding to the federal deficit' .
This is due to the fact that the USA is a welfare state and provides pension for the retired .
This financial scheme has resulted in the USA being the country spending most on health care , leading to a great strain on the government budget ( The New York Times , 2009 , 14 September ) .
In light of this , we can be sure that this excessive amount of money is not well-spent .
Therefore , public spending on the aged should be limited to prevent misuse of funds that could be better channeled back to the economy , where more government revenue would most likely be generated .
In the society today , there are certain industries , known as public goods , which require government involvement to exist .
For example , .
Such facilities benefit everyone in the country and it is difficult to exclude anyone from enjoying them .
The wide spread of such a mentality would then result in the government having to provide these services .
Therefore , if public spending on the aged is not limited , there will be less funds channeled to projects such as the building of roads , the provision of street lights , the maintenance of the police force and cleaning of the streets .
With a restricted budget for these sectors , we may have to live with a lower quality of life and a less secured nation , which would also lower the living standards amongst the aged .
Everyone is dependent on government aid to varying degrees .
A good balance must be struck to ensure that as few people as possible are deprived of government support due to poor distribution of state monies .
This essay will discuss current political research and development that help to ease the aging process in the context of Singapore .
The aging process , which involves physical , psychological and social changes among human beings , often brings about the deterioration of physical and mental health and loneliness .
These will increase the nation 's health expenses and pension fund .
To a large extent , the aging process has been alleviated by current social policies and implementation that emphasise individual responsibility , familial commitment and residual model policies- often known as government intervention .
Government has placed policies that emphasise individual responsibility and which have been proven effective to ease the aging process .
Every working Singaporean with a minimal income of five hundred dollars will have to contribute to the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) .
These accounts are meant for medical expenses , investments , emergencies and retirement to ensure that the citizens have sufficient money when they reach old age .
However , despite having these accounts , senior citizens may still face problems with paying their medical bills and daily expenses as these accounts are subjected to withdrawal limitations and high eligibility age barriers .
Therefore , it is vital that senior citizens have a healthy lifestyle and to be active in the workforce in order for them to be in good health and have the ability to self-provide .
The Singapore government has been actively educating senior citizens about the importance of healthy living and community activities and campaigns .
For instance , the Health Promotion Board has introduced healthy aging programs and formed interest groups like Tai Chi and Karaoke Singing Clubs among the residents in the communities .
These activities promote physical and mental wellness for senior citizens as well as enlarge their social circle by making friends .
The Singapore government has devised plans and policies to develop a strong sense of familial commitment in order to ease the aging population burden of the state .
Evidently , these policies are deemed to work as statistics ( Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports [ MCYS ] , 2005 ) have shown that the majority ( 76.4 % ) of senior citizens live with their children ( p. 10 ) and 44.7 % of the senior citizens depend on their chilchildren for financial support ( p. 28 ) .
Policies include tax relief for taking care of elderly parents or grandparents taking care of grandchildren while both parents work , and public housing schemes like grants to citizens to purchase flats in areas where their parents live .
Indirectly , this will strengthen family ties and allow senior citizens to seek companionship with their children or grandchildren .
However , there are still cases whereby children refuse to support their parents though they are capable of doing so .
With the introduction of Tribunal for the Maintenance of Parents ( Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports [ MCYS ] , 2009 ) , parents who are over 60 and incapable of supporting themselves can file petitions to seek financial support from their children .
Nevertheless , the pillars of the future are further instilled with the importance of moral values such as filial piety through moral civics lessons in schools to highlight the importance of familial commitment .
Lastly , Residual Model policies are in place to ease the aging process as they act as the last straw of the social safety net when the elderly lack self-reliance or have no familial support ,
for instance , the Public Assistance Scheme whereby senior citizens are given cash grants and free treatment at polyclinics and government or restructured hospitals .
Another example is the Medical Endowment Fund ( Ministry of Health [ MOH ] , 2007 ) , which is known as Medifund and Medifund Silver , whereby the elderly are given provision for medical funds due to not having a Medisave or Medishield Account , not having accumulated enough in these accounts , or having no immediate family member to pay their hospital bills .
This enables every senior citizen to to receive medical attention when needed .
An argument against these assistance schemes is that these will increase the dependency of senior citizens on the government as they know that they will be provided if they are unable to pay for their medical bills .
However , government stresses that these policies do not entitle all citizens to share the same benefits through mean testing , whereby the individuals are assessed according to their financial situation and bill size .
Affordability is now dictated by the government and the patient who is considered not qualified for the fund will end up paying more . This will in turn highlight the importance of self-reliance .
Although there are still flaws in the current policies , shortcomings of one policy can be overcome with other policies and developments .
To a large extent , current policies have helped to ease the aging process . However , it is important that all the policies are put together to achieve the optimal result .
On the whole , the Singapore government has not overlooked the underprivileged senior citizens by providing a safety net to ensure that their basic needs are met .
Therefore , in helping the aging population age gracefully , the Singapore government has constantly emphasised the importance of self reliance and shunning away from being a welfare state without undermining the familial commitment and work ethic of senior citizens .
Aging with grace means good health and lifestyles , financial stability and being in the company of family and friends .
More countries are facing problems brought about by the aging process in the social as well as the economic aspects .
Vaccination prevented people from getting life-threatening diseases in the past , such as tuberculosis , which is no longer a big threat today .
Despite the perplexing issues arising in the process of aging , the government has put in much effort in developing policies and aiding in research to alleviate its negative impact on society .
To increase the number of people in the workforce , countries such as Singapore encourage foreign talent to contribute to her economy .
The government also implemented " baby bonus " to encourage couples to procreate which would increase labour in the long run .
Reuters ( 2007 ) reported that Singapore plans to raise the retirement age for citizens from 62 to 65 by year 2012 to account for the higher life expectancy of the population .
Hence , Japan invented robots to replace the lack of manpower due to the aging population .
These robots can also play a role in taking care of the elderly in the ; for instance , the wheelchairs that operate using buttons can replace humans pushing them .
With technological advancement , pressure on economy can be eased .
The elderly are less flexible and their movement is limited especially when they are facing a stage in life when they are more susceptible to suffer from movement-restricting diseases like osteoporosis .
Statistics show that elderly still engage in exercises and the elderly who take part in tai chi are 47 % less likely to fall down due to increased balancing ability and confidence .
Moreover , this research also shows that exercises reduced hip fracture rate by 25 % in postmenopausal women .
However , despite some elderly being more active than others , most elderly find it difficult to move about .
Therefore , the Housing Development Board ( HDB ) in Singapore has proposed to build lifts that stop at every storey in the Life Upgrading Programme .
In addition , more ramps and slopes are to be built to ensure the mobility of wheelchair-bound elderly and also the physically disabled .
The government can only implement policies or introduce incentives to encourage individuals to ease the aging process . It is up to the citizens to decide whether they want to take part in helping the economy and society in the long run .
Therefore , I strongly agree that much has been done by the government to help ease the aging process .
According to United Nations statistics , by 2050 , one of every five people will be 60 years old and above and the total number of people who are 60 years old and above is projected to be around 2 billion .
It is a cause for concern , as more elderly present in the society will affect our economic and social development significantly .
Therefore , in most parts of the world , governments are coming up with policies and sponsoring research to ease the aging process .
The aging process can be eased by increasing birth rates , increasing workforce productivity and reducing the physical and psychological aspects of aging .
Currently , governments have helped to ease the aging process in terms of economic , social technological development .
Firstly , an aging population greatly threatens a country 's economic development because with more elderly retiring , the workforce productivity falls sharply .
In Finland , which has the most rapidly aging population in Europe , has successfully raised the retirement age from 60.1 to 60.7 in 2004 , together with a pension reform introduced in 2005 to ease pressure on the state pension system
( Kunz , 2007 ) . Another method to increase workforce productivity is to invite foreign talents and immigrants to stay and work in order to counter the low birth rate of a country .
For instance , one of the main factors for Spain 's rising birth rates was due to a huge influx of immigrants from Latin America and North Africa
( Spain-Demographic Trends ) . However , these policies may not be effective because locals view foreign workers as a threat and may cause social unrest .
For instance , in Australia , there is a rise of hate crimes against immigrants .
Even so , employers should hire their employees based on their capability and not nationality in order to avoid such crimes and through this policy , it will increase a country 's competiveness , which will increase the country 's workforce productivity and boost its economy .
Therefore , by increasing the retirement age and recruiting immigrants , we have partly eased the economic aspect of aging process .
Also , their children may not be able to take care of their emotional welfare because of their busy career , hence they may be prone to depression .
In addition , the government is trying to encourage companies to hire older workers by giving incentives .
By doing so , the elderly will feel more socially accepted and there will be less cases of elderly dying alone in their house .
However , others may argue that these actions are not effective because educating the young does take a long time especially when aging is a pressing problem at the moment .
It is true that the fruits of education take years to harvest . However , according to statistics given , the national volunteerism rate in Singapore has risen from 15.2 to 15.5 in 2006 . This does show that more people are concerned about the elderly .
However , through education not only the youths will be more accepting of the elderly but also , in the future they will most likely not to practise ageism in the workplace and this thinking will be ingrained in the society thus generating positive outcomes .
Therefore , current policies and campaigns are effective in easing the social aspect of the aging process .
Moreover , with current technology advancement , we can tackle the physical barriers of aging problems such as low birth rate , increased productivity and reduced physical effects of aging , which may partly relate to elderly low self-esteem .
Others may argue that the main cause of the aging problem is actually longer life span itself .
By doing so , the aged will be more appreciated by the public ; it also does help to improve the country 's economy with an increased workforce .
Therefore , having longer life span does help to ease the aging process .
Hence , technological advancement does help to ease the economic , social and physical aspects of the aging process .
In conclusion , it seems that governments from all over the world are prepared to counter rising aging population problems .
Although certain measures are not effective immediately , we should continue to support them as it is worth the wait .
There is a saying that goes , " Give a man a fish and you feed him for a day .
" Providing the aged with health services and benefits and inviting immigrants can only ease the aging process temporarily .
However , by changing people 's mindset , people will be less discriminating against the aged and appreciate them more and are more willing to have more children .
Therefore , current research and policies have helped to ease economic development , as well as the and psychological aspects of aging process .
Eventually every one of us will grow old , therefore the effectiveness of these policies greatly concerns us . We should support them .
Thirteen developed countries have a median age higher than 40 years in 2005 . Leading these countries is Japan with a median age of 43 years ( United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs , 2007 ) .The aging population results in the increase of public spending on the aged .
Governments have adjusted national budgets to increase public spending on the aged including expenditure on healthcare , housing , pensions and transportation to cater to the needs of the aged .
The United States spent $ 2.1 trillion on health care in 2006 but increased to $ 2.26 trillion in a year after which elders have spent far more than children and adults ( The Office of the Artuary of US , n.d .
) . As the aging problem is likely to get worse in the future , public spending on the aged will constitute a large proportion of the national budget .
Therefore , limiting public spending on the aged is needed as money can be diverted to other development areas .
This limitation establishes a bottom line for public spending to control the budget but this does not necessarily mean having a cut down .
By limiting public spending on the aged and diverting money to other areas of development , government can increase economic growth .
There is a large proportion of public spending on the aged in the national budget due to a fast aging population .
Money can be diverted into other areas which require more budget such as business .
In fact , there was a significant shrinking in the economy which was 3.8 percent in 2008 compared to 4.7 percent in 2007 ( Mussa,2008 ) . By diverting more money into business domain , government gives incentives to companies in order to encourage them to explore and invest .
In the long run , it will stimulate the economy .
It will help to solve the unemployment problem . The real unemployment rate is 16 percent including persons who work less than they would like to and those who have dropped out of the labor pool instead of the official jobless rate which was 9.4 percent in July 2009 ( Channel News Asia,2009 ) .
Thus , economic growth will be increased by limiting public spending on the aged and diverting money into the business domain .
Moreover , the elderly are not the only members of society so public spending on aged should be limited so that money can be spent on children .
Children are considered as the foundation of a country as they will grow up to be leaders in the future .
Children need good education so that they can become well-versed and contribute to the country " s development .
In addition , public commitment to children has been threatened because of increased spending on the elderly .
According to an analysis done in the United States from 1980 to 2000 , the number of children living in poverty is almost three times the number of elderly over the past twenty years ( Organisation for Economic Co-operation Development , n. d .
) .Hence , diverting money to children should help to improve their quality of life .
Some critics argue that limiting public spending on the aged will become a financial burden to low-income families .
Their low wages are only sufficient for household expenses and children " s school fees .
However , low-income families can still obtain financial aid from government despite limitation to public spending on the aged .
Moreover , a tendency shows that elders themselves decide to have longer working lives .
Although they already reach the retirement age , they still decide to continue working so they will be able to support themselves in their twilight years .
For example , Japanese usually continue working until 70 years old ( OECD,n.d .
) .They will continue to be financially secure , instead of starting to depend on their family .
In conclusion , limitation to public spending on the aged and diversion of money to other areas of development should be implemented .
Money diverted into the business domain will be able to stimulate economic growth .
In addition , children are at a disadvantage if too much money is spent on the elderly .
Despite limitation to public spending on the aged , the real needy will still be able to obtain financial aid .
The consequences resulting from an unlimited increase in public spending on the elderly will become a financial burden to a country in long run .
Singapore 's life expectancy at birth for males is 78.4 ; for females it is 83.2 ( SingStats , 2009 ) .
The problems associated with the aging process can be categorized into five aspects , namely economic decline , mental agility , health , emotional and social problem .
Among all , economic and social policies are widely discussed in society .
Although it is impossible to increase the fertility rate in the short run , the problems of aging process are still alleviated by research and effective development and policies .
On the economic aspect , an aging population leads to shrinking workforce , low productivity and slow economic growth .
The annual inflation rate of Singapore has been increasing from 2.1 to 6.5 from 2007 to 2008 ( SingStat , 2009 ) .
The old age dependency ratio last year was 11.9 ( SingStats , 2009 ) which shows that 11.9 working persons would support one elderly .
Together with the problem of low fertility rate , government encourages Singaporeans to work longer to earn more for the future .
In order to encourage late retirement , the Singapore retirement age has been increased from 60 to 62 .
The CPF contribution rate for employers has been increased by 1.5 percentage points in 2007 in order for citizens to better prepare for the aging problem .
However , for older workers , the CPF contribution by both employers and employees has also been reduced in order to help the workers remain competitive and increase their take-home salary ( Channel NewsAsia , 2007 ) .
There are ramps for people using wheelchairs ; in most of the buildings , toilets and buses are specially designed to accommodate the elderly and the handicapped .
The Singapore social service sector has been taking care of the elderly with current housing , healthcare and job support policies .
HDB encourages children live in close proximity with their parents so that children can take care of parents during emergency .
Moreover , upgrading of housing lifts on every floor would make elderly life easier .
The Healthcare 3Ms , Medicare , MediShield and Medifund also provide subsidies for the elderly .
In order to benefit those who need help more , subsidy for hospitalization in public hospitals has been adjusted so that 60 percent of workers are able to enjoy full subsidy for type C and B2 wards whereas those have higher earning power will receive substantial subsidies for both C and B2 class wards ( Khalik , 2008 ) .
NTUC , WDA and employers have worked on the Job Re-creation Programme ( JRP ) to recreate and redesign jobs targeting older workers and providing training opportunities for them to take up new job openings .
Besides , SPUR focuses on retraining for older workers whereas ADVANTAGE !
Opponents of this position will argue that healthcare cost is still the main problem for the aging population .
A Medisave account may not be sufficient for many Singaporeans once they need to pay the medical bills for their parents , spouses and children .
Although most of the Singaporeans not only pay for their own medical bills , there are other subsidy schemes which may lessen their financial burden .
The elderly will receive monthly cash payout , therefore their children 's Medisave account can be used to pay for their own bill .
Other than that , the Interim Disability Assistance Programme for the Elderly ( IDAPE ) and Primary Care Partnership ( PCPS ) are other subsidy schemes available .
To summarize , government encourages later retirement in order to reduce elderly dependency and implement social policies such as subsidy on housing medical fees .
At the same time , more and more facilities are designed to meet the needs of the elderly and the disabled .
Therefore , current research and policies are able to cater to most of the needs of Singaporeans to prepare for old age .
Also , individuaindividuals have to keep fit to reduce the probability of getting ill in order to avoid expensive medical bills during older age .
However , the world must address yet another dire issue : an ageing population .
Such cost even micrifies the impact of the recent financial crisis .
However , leaders of the world have stepped up measures to combat this unforgiving phenomenon .
Ongoing research and implementation are initiated to allow the world to accept such emergence comfortably .
Reducing elderly dependency is one way in which governments can tackle the worrying phenomenon of a greying population .
In the past , the elderly were often labelled as slow and inefficient .
Therefore , the elderly should not be deprived of employment by providing more incentives for employers to attract such workers and help for those seeking employment opportunities .
Under the Main Upgrading Project ( MUP ) , grab-bars in the bathroom and non-slip floor tiles have been installed in upgraded sold flats .
However , there are many ways in which governments can compensate for the falling birth rate .
Longer paid maternity leave , more childcare leave and greater incentives for working mothers are some possible corrections to the problem .
Although this may increase the government 's expenditure , it is a necessary investment for a better future of the country .
For many decades , the world has been taking a lot of beating .
From the economic crisis in 1997 to uncontrolled viral spread such as H1N1 pandemic in 2008 , the world survived all these obstacles .
The repercussions of an ageing population are tirelessly being subdued by various helpful and effective solutions .
Nonetheless , with much support in place , the future of the world may not be as bleak as before .
Aging is a difficult process as the elderly are more inclined to get sick because of a lower immune system so having to recuperate longer would be financially draining .
Under the seniority based-wage system , it is more expensive to hire older workers ; and the perception that older workers are inefficient resulted in low employment rate among the elderly ( Lee , 2009 , para .
However , policies on the aged in Singapore have significantly heled to reduce the problems they face .
In recent years , the Ministry of Manpower has been working closely with its tripartite partners to enhance the employability of older workers ( as cited in NTUC , 2007 ) .
Coming in 2012 , the government will enact the re-employment legislation to enable the elderly to work beyond the retirement age of 62 ( as cited in Re-Employment of Older Workers Portal , 2008 ) .
This is preferred than increasing the retirement age because a higher retirement age might cause older workers to be less employable as they are no longer cost competitive which may result in them being laid off even before they are 62 ( cited in MOM , 2008 ) .
With re-employment , employers can provide jobs to their mature workers and also offer them a different job position with different salary and terms .
In terms of healthcare , the government has come out with a few financial assistance schemes to ensure that the citizens are able to afford healthcare and are prepared during their old age .
Other than the basic healthcare financing schemes like Medisave , Medishield and Medifund , the government has come out with another scheme called 'Elder Scheme' .
Other than financial schemes , the government also provides subsidies for patients who require intermediate and long term care .
The subsidies given could be as much as 75 % of the total bills depending on the family income and it is extended to community hospitals ( as cited in MOH , 2007 ) .
However , even with all of these policies and subsidies , there is no guarantee that the elderly are able to pay for all of their living expenses .
It is essential that they learn how to not only manage their wealth but also expand it so that when they choose to stop working , they would have enough money to pay for their necessities and have enough for any unexpected expenses .
To ensure that its citizen will be financially prepared when they reach their retirement age , the Central Provident Fund Board ( CPF ) has came out with a learning portal called 'Retirement Ready @ my cpf ' to help citizens to plan for their retirement ( as cited in CPF , 2009 ) .
Clearly the government and its related agencies have been working hard to help ease the aging process through many of its policies .
Through these , the elderly not only will be able to continue working ; they also need not worry much about their health expenses .
Singapore is facing a shift in the distribution of population towards older ages , where the median age of the population increase , as well as a decline in fertility rates , resulting in a rise in the number of elderly in Singapore .
Aging impacts a person 's well being in many ways , with both psychological and physical changes , including chronic diseases associated with it .
The labour age composition has thus shifted towards the older workers , where implications towards the competitiveness of Singapore 's economy will occur , especially if older workers do not make significant contributions to the productivity growth in the economy ( Thangavelu , Yong , 2006 ) .
Hence , more support and care for the aged should be provided which in turn will pose a strain to the younger generation .
This has reflected the importance for individuals to have the ability to support themselves through their golden years .
Facing high cost of living , Singapore has moved up from the 13th position in 2008 to the 10th in 2009 , in the worldwide cost of living ranking ( Mercer , 2009 ) , especially for the medical cost , where each household spends an increasing amount of expenditure in health care , with 3.3 % in 1998 to 5.1 % in 2003 ( Singstats , 2007 ) , and is expected to further increase in the future , with more aged citizens in Singapore .
Singaporeans have recognized the need to prepare for aging in terms of escalating medical costs , thus net withdrawal from Medisave scheme , including Eldershield , has dropped to 213.6 million in 2009 , and 62.5 million from the Medishield scheme ( CPF , 2009 ) .
Singapore has not only faced an aging population resulting from low fertility rates , but also longer life expectancy for individuals .
With rising life expectancy , given only a 2.5 % annual interest in the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) , and with most funds in the CPF used to fund housing or tertiary education , the CPF figure left is no longer sufficient to last through retirement ( OCBC , 2005 ) .
" The best way for people to adjust to longer life spans is to continue working for as long as they can " ( PM Lee , 2009 ) , as working provides a source of income ; more savings can thus be built up .
Increasing the retirement age is insufficient to encourage individuals to work longer , hence the Re-employment policy will be enacted in 2012 .
In order to ensure that older workers are not at a disadvantage , Singapore established schemes such as smaller CPF contributions to the aged ( CPF , 2009 ) , as well as the Advantage !
Critics of the approach on lowered CPF contribution rates for older workers have argued that it is unnecessary , as 63 % of the respondents felt that " seniors are not weak and ill " and 87 % felt that " senior citizens can play an active role in society " ( C3A , 2008 ) .
Therefore , to make the aged more employable , there is a need to move away from the seniority-wage system and reduce the CPF rates .
In conclusion , people are living longer resulting from better medical facilities . With the policies introduced to help ease the aging process , Singaporeans will be able to keep themselves occupied before formal retirement , and to be able to build up their retirement nest and retire in comfort .
Through amelioration and subsidizing of healthcare and public facilities , the problem of aging population has been eased .
Over the last 5 years , Singapore government health expenditure for citizens has increased from $ 1.53 billion in year 2002 , to $ 1.93 billion in year 2006 which is an average growth rate of 6 % per annum ( as cited in Ministry of Health , 2007 ) .
Through the increment on healthcare expenditure , we can see that the government is bringing in better technologies and focusing on Singaporeans ' health .
With advanced healthcare facilities , preventing or curing diseases has been made possible .
One of the most common diseases associated with old age is Senile Dementia , where the patient encounters mental deterioration ( loss of intellectual ability ) .
Studies show that of people over 80 , 20 % suffer from Alzheimer 's disease ( as cited in health-cares.net , 2005 ) .
For instance , researchers have invented medications such as tacrine and donepezil which are used by patients with mild to moderate Alzheimer 's disease ( as cited in health-cares.net , 2005 ) .
In Singapore , having one of the fastest aging populations in the world , with an estimated 23 % of the population to be over 65-year-old by the year 2030 , there is a need for more hospitals to be built to meet the needs of the aging population ( as cited in Singapore faces 'silver tsunami ' , 2009 ) .
Hence , Jurong General Hospital which will open in five years and Khoo Teck Puat Hospital which will open next year will be linked to a community hospital next door .
This is to ensure that older people will have the right health care treatment at the right place and in return help them to cut costs ( as cited in The Straits Times , 2009 ) .
It is understandable that older people often require more medical care , but they need not remain in the hospital for this care .
In June 2006 , Singapore Bus Services ( SBS ) Transit launched Singapore 's First Ever Wheelchair accessible buses - Service 21 ( as cited in SBS transit , 2006 ) .
Similarly , another public transport operator Singapore Mass Rapid Transit ( SMRT ) came up with its first wheelchair-friendly buses on June 2009 ( as cited in Wheelchair-friendly bus , 2009 ) .
Even with government subsidies and paying their CPF they might still find it difficult to handle hefty medical bills .
Hence , even a small family with a monthly income of $ 10,000 might also find it difficult to cope with a big hospital bill , if it has to support one or two elderly people with a chronic illness ( as cited in The Straits Times , 2004 ) .
Hence , policies such as senior citizens ' bonus where lower-income elderly aged 55 and above with an annual income of $ 100,000 or less will receive $ 200 to $ 1000 over a period of 4 years ( as cited in GST Offset Package , 2009 ) to lighten the burden of lower income families .
There is no need to worry as statistics shows that direct subsidies to patients have increased from $ 850 million in 2001 to $ 1.6 billion in 2007 and it is projected to increase to $ 2.2 billion in 2012 ( as cited in Ministry of Health , 2009 ) .
In conclusion , amelioration and subsidizing of healthcare and public facilities has eased the problem of aging population .
Therefore , maintaining a healthy lifestyle , saving up for the future and contributing monthly to their CPF account assist citizens to prepare them for better retirement and lower their economic burden .
Easing The Aging Process in Singapore
Singapore society 's aging process brings on numerous sets of challenges for the government .
The effects of the aging process in Singapore are as follows :
First , economic decline wwill occur as the size of the working force shrinks .
Second , decline in citizens ' health due to a weaker immunity system and age-related illnesses .
Third , social problems .
Therefore , the government has embarked on reforming its older policies and implementing new ones to cater to and prepare for population aging in Singapore .
For the purpose of this essay , the focus will be on Singapore 's policies economic and social problems because of the problem of aging .
When one works , it helps if one stays mentally aware , physically energetic , socially connected and financially independent .
Re-employment is one of its key goals .
Accordingly , the constitutional retirement age of 62 would be increased eventually to 67 ( Yap , 2009 ) .
Policies have not only been implemented in anticipation of the aging process but also in reaction to external factors like the global recession .
In reaction to the economic downturn , the Skills Programme for Upgrading and Resilience ( SPUR ) amounting to $ 600 million was started in November 2008 ( Yap , 2009 ) .
However , as evident from the above policies , Singapore was the only Asian country which won the AARP International Innovative Employer Award ( Yap , 2009 ) .
The award is given to companies in countries for showing innovative Human Resource practices that deal with matters related to the workforce , aged 50 and older ( Yap , 2009 ) .
Also by the end of 2008 , 700 unionised companies had already committed to re-employ close to 5,000 workers above the age of 62 ( Yap , 2009 ) .
The statistics show that reemployment is a useful tool and the government 's policies have had a positive impact on companies .
This benefit is not limited only to employed workers but unemployed workers also can turn to SPUR to sharpen their skills while they search for jobs .
Moving on , Singapore wants for its seniors , even the less mobile , to have a safe and accessible environment .
However , since July 2006 , HDB 's new public housing projects ( Yap , 2009 ) .
For example , switches and sockets low enough to be accessible from a wheelchair and toilets have been made wide enough and with hand rails .
It has also gained recognition locally and abroad .
When Singapore 's Ministry of Finance unveiled the government budget for 2009 , it was stated that an estimated total of S $ 66 million or 0.15 % of the total government expenditure will be spent on establishing various programs and upgrading facilities for the elderly ( Singapore Budget 2009 , 2009 ) .
As the problem of aging population intensifies throughout the years , there will always be a debate on how much of public spending should be allocated to the aged .
A sustained economic growth improves the level of business activities , ensures a low unemployment rate and increases government tax revenues .
More funds are thus available to finance additional projects for the needy including the aged .
This will inevitably constrict public spending on the aged due to a smaller pool of resources .
This is because the elderly have once contributed to the country 's economy and their well-being should not be overlooked when they age and are unable to work .
For example , one feasible policy is to encourage companies to provide extra training for the older workers to stay in touch with advanced technology , thus increasing their working lifespan disregarding health factors .
Also , there is ongoing medical research on senile dementia and Parkinson 's disease .
Everybody will grow old and is bound to experience the effects of it at one point in his or her life .
Only through research and development will we be able to gain knowledge on the issues circling them and come up with ways to overcome it ,
for example , the development of humanoid robots in Japan which promises to free us from physical labor and help us with our household chores such as folding laundry , doing the dishes , cooking , etc. ( Adams , 2004 ) .
Another R&D policy that has played a role in easing the aging process includes buses that are elderly- and handicapped-friendly .
These new buses are also " low floor " and for the elderly and handicapped ( SBS Transit , 2007 ) .
Apart from research and development , policies with regard to ageing population have also helped to ease the ageing process .
One such program is the Lift Upgrading Program where the lifts will now land on every floor as compared to the past where not all public housing was provided with access to lifts .
This does not only benefit the elderly , but the disabled as well as families with young children as well ( Housing and Development Board , 2001 ) .
In addition to this program , HDB has also come up with a policy which encourages children to live in close proximity to their parents .
In light of the increased awareness and growing importance of palliative care , demand for it has increased .
For example , there has been a rise in the number of patient referrals to Dover Park Hospice from 680 in 2006 to 750 in 2008 ( " Lifting Spirits " , 2009 , p. 13 ) .
By becoming more affordable , it helps to ease the financial burden of the patient and his or her family .
To conclude , research and development/policies have no doubt managed to ease the aging process but on top of that , palliative care also has a role to play in relieving suffering and improving the quality of life of people facing serious illnesses .
The current research and development as well as the policies drawn are effective in alleviating the ageing process such as decline in health , economic downturn and emotional problems of the elderly .
In this aspect , some critics argue that development in the medical field does not help address the ageing process .
The Singapore government will provide up to 75 % subsidy for the elderly provided that they are either Singapore citizens or permanent residents ; this also depends on the income of the family ( Ministry of Health : Subsidies for elderly , 2007 ) .
Hence , the policy is able to ease the ageing process through care for the deteriorating health of the elderly .
Current research in the medical field is conducted to find out the causes and cures for common illnesses among the elderly such as senile dementia and Parkinson 's disease .
When such research is successful , it will benefit humanity and better medical treatments in the world .
This will decrease the suffering of the elderly , making them less susceptible to diseases , thus helping to abate the ageing process .
