Firstly , The elderly seem to be burdensome for young generations for the young must share their budgets to take care of the elderly
Secondly , the increase in the rate of elderly people can cause trouble in health care costs which means more funds used for maintaining a healthy life for the portion of society no longer able to work .
Therefore , some solutions to solve this critical problem must be found. .
Let take a look in Singapore 's policies nowadays .
Under the , Singapore 's government has implemented some policies such as constructing new infrastructures for the elderly and for the next generations also .
Besides , policy makers also plan to extend the financial security of the elderly through either raising the working age or prolonging retirement bursaries .
Those policies are gradually easing the aging process for they create good conditions for the elderly to have more opportunities to contribute their productive labour and to have more happiness for the rest of their life .
Furthermore , the improvements in the healthcare system is also lightening the aging burden .
More and more medical innovation has applied to extend life expectancy so that the working-age has been lengthened consequently .
As a result , the productivity of citizens has also increased rapidly which leads to an increase in national revenue .
Despite the disagreement among economists about the cost of investing money in developing new technologies and drugs for maintaining good health for the elderly , the investment in health care is profitable and wise .
When elderly workers have more choices to keep their healthy lives longer , they are eager to become potential consumers for medical care ; therefore , the national budget will grow tremendously which relatively increases a big amount of GDP ( cited in the " Government will control media cost ?
So the fact that governments put efforts into developing health care systems is logical and actually they have done well .
For example , according to a study by economists Laurence Kotlikoff and Christian Hagist of the National Bureau of Economic Research : " the annualized rate of growth in government spending on health care was not only tops in the U.S. , at 6.23 percent , but that the rate of growth here was the fastest relative to increases in gross domestic product among the 10 countries studied .
Hence , the USA spent money on nursing , building hospitals and strengthening clinical care for the elderly
Likewise , in Singapore , the government spends S $ 110 million on paying basic Medishield premiums for two years for Singaporeans aged 61 to 69 so that 90 % of the elderly can have health care benefits ( cited in Asian metacare paper ) .
In short , from the economical and social point of view , it can be concluded that the elderly have been taken care of better than in the past by the improvement of technological equipment , health care systems and the serious awareness of the issue by governments .
The elderly must be respected because they are a factorr in making society better-off in economically .
As a result , governments should continue to put efforts into dealing with the aging issue .
As a result of the growing aging population , public spending on the aged has increased in an attempt to minimize the negative impacts of a fast aging population .
Such a strategy translates into increasing pressure on national budgets and economies which could be used in other areas of the country 's development .
Some have argued that public spending on the aged is redundant as the productivity and contribution of the aged to the nation is questionable .
However , the assumption that the aged are non productive is untrue due to the increasing emphasis on healthcare .
This has has allowed the aged to remain healthy , continue working and remain productive despite their age .
Therefore , public spending on the aged is crucial in ensuring the continued productivity of the aged which in turn benefits the country .
Firstly , the high medical and healthcare service fees can " substantially drain the resources of many elderly " ( Friedland , & Summer , 2005 , p.17 ) .
Despite having insurance coverage , it is still possible that medical bills are insufficiently covered .
Therefore , the government should not neglect healthcare benefits for the aged as the consequence is undesirable .
This indicates a lack of resources , whether monetary or non monetary to support the large numbers of elderly .
Besides , it brings us back to the aspect of high medical expenditures which the younger generations are probably unable to afford as well .
He is likely to face financial constraints due to high medical expenditures .
To solve this problem , public spending on the aged can provide an alternative resource to support the aged which therefore lightens the burden of the younger generations .
In addition , additional healthcare resources can improve the health of the elderly hence , enhancing the productivity of the aged .
Thirdly , the shrinking ratio of younger generations in the future indicates the importance of elderly remaining productive to the economy .
However , this scenario may change in the future due to the lack of human resources in the job market .
To prevent the disruption of the labour market , the elderly are likely to remain in the work force in the near future .
Therefore , public spending on the aged is as crucial as other areas of a country 's development .
In conclusion , the assumption that public spending should be used in other areas of a country 's development due to the lack of productivity of the aged is flawed .
One crucial problem is the increase in government expenditure for the aging population which in turn strains the future working population .
One segment of policies that the government has implemented is to increase the overall fertility rate of Singapore .
The scheme caused an adverse effect as it only focused on the explicit costs .
Some of which include giving up one 's career to take care of one'sr children .
Therefore , with the , many prefer to establish their careers before having children .
Parents in this modern society want their children to be equipped with numerous skills to prepare them for the future workforce .
However , the Medisave scheme has proven to be insufficient because medical expenses for the elderly are simply so high that people 's Medisave savings can be used up within one week ( Popatlal , 2009 ) .
This problem becomes worse if the elderly do not have any children or children who choose to neglect their responsibilities to support their elder 's healthcare finances .
On the other hand , housing policies may have the opposite effect as some couples may misuse the policy by using the grant for their own benefit .
The current development of new community hospitals which link up with the main hospitals is an example of a measure that will ease the aging process .
Easing the aging process by establishing policies that solve explicit problems has proved to be inadequate .
This may include the impact of the rise in living expenses and the influences of western culture .
Ageing Population has become an unprecedented fast developing phenomenon many countries in the 21st century , more prominently in the developed countries .
Faced with low birth rates policy makers are concerned about the social and economic impacts brought about by this phenomenon .
Despite strains experienced on public spending , to a large extent given the severity/urgency of the problem , the well being..wt the well being of the elderly should be attended to first with priority before any other aspects come into considerations during policy making .
Only then can the other problems arising from an ageing population be resolved simultaneously .
With longer average life expectancies in the ageing population , demand for a good healthcare system is critical .
With higher standards of living as compared to past conditions , people are living longer today .
Therefore governments need to channel more resources into building healthcare infrastructures and services .
A good healthcare system will be one whereby the elderly are able to access it with ease in time of need and it should be one that is made affordable to all .
Nobody should be deprived from receiving treatment on any grounds .
Investments in a good healthcare system would ensure that the ageing population is healthy and hence more government attention could then be diverted onto issues like economic development etc .
Moreover a healthy ageing population would also mean that more workers will be available for deployment and hence contributing to the nation 's productivity and development indirectly .
' This point justifies that reducing the budget in necessary public spending on the aged might in fact hinder the country 's development under certain circumstances .
Increasing investment of capital in amenities such as day care centres , elderly friendly housings and facilities , establishing more homes for the elderly etc should be carried out in response to the ageing population .
Despite the increase in capital investments on elderly friendly amenities , the allocated budget for a country 's development need not be jeopardized .
Instead governments could reallocate budgets whereby more funds initially set aside for childcare amenities be transferred to fund the development of elderly friendly amenities since the former needs fewer resources due to the low birth rate in the population .
Moreover having in place all the amenities for the elderly , it would allow the elderly to be more independent in taking care of themselves .
More policy making resources hence could be placed on other aspects of the country 's development as a result .
However welfare for the elderly should be offered on varying levels with accordance to individual needs , in order to better allocate a country 's limited resources and eliminate inefficiency and wastage ( Peterson , 2001 ) .
As shown by several welfare states such as Britain and Canada , the pension scheme might cripple peoples ' motivation to work and bring about early retirement .
This in turn would lead to lower labour deployment for the country and hence lower productivity , having an adverse effect on the country 's development .
Increased public spending in this case encourages senior citizens to stay idle , when the resources can be better diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
This reminds policymakers to adopt a more cautious mindset while allocating funds to public spending .
This essay has identified that public spending on the aged is necessary due to changing demographic patterns of today 's society and should not be disregarded .
Only when the ageing population issue is well managed can a desirable outcome on the country 's development be achieved. .
However public spending budgets should be drafted with more consideration to avoid any misuse of the country 's resources .
Undoubtedly , spending on the aged is essential as they have contributed to our society greatly , but this should only be done to an extent and should not be the full responsibility of the government .
Moreover , the advances in technology have prolonged the life expectancy of every single human , making expenditure for old age soar to a great high due to high medical costs .
According to Friedland and Summer ( 2005 ) , if a nation spends more on the aged , besides slowing down the growth of the nation , it will also create more costly problems in future .
These problems include insufficient housing for people , higher unemployment rates and insufficient budget for the future aged population .
Therefore , public spending on the aged should be limited to an acceptable level where it covers the neediest that are desperate for help , . Most of the other portions of the public fund should be invested into the expansion of the nation to generate more funds for the aged when the investments ripen .
A country that is not expanding as fast as the population grows will insufficient housing for its people .
Hence , the reduction in housing spending while spending more on the aged , may cost the government more .
This is because the government may need to build and set up temporary accommodation for the homeless , where the manpower , materials and resources will cost more than the problems associated with limited spending on the aged .
Furthermore , people will lose loyalty and a sense of belonging to the country when there is n't even shelter above their heads .
This may cause mass emigration of the working age group which will bring down the nation 's economy and further aggravate the aging population problem .
Anotherr implication of overspending on the aged will be slowing down the growth of the economy which leads to unemployment as the market is unable to support the additional people .
This again will cost the government even more as now the government will need to support the increased number of people in need .
Furthermore , the current working age group may not have anything to rely on when they grow old as the government did not invest enough in the market instead placing large amount of the funds on the current/present aged population .
This is an unfilial act .
Another social issue will be the aged taking government help for granted and depriving aged people who are really in need such as old single women and disabled people .
These two social issues will not happen if there is limitation on public spending on the aged .
In conclusion , public spending should be limited to an extent where no single needy person is deprived from assistance .
The government should also diversify funds to develop the economy , so when the economy grows , there will be more money for the government to support the aged who are unfortunate and vulnerable .
On the other hand , people will also have greater disposable income and be self-reliant , in order to support their aged parents .
As reported by SDS ( 2008b ) , we have a decreasing old age support ratio , with 17 residents aged 15 to 64 years old supporting one senior citizen aged 65 and above in 1970 , reduced to just 8.4 in 2008 .
Instead of just 'feeding ' , the government aims to get senior citizens to learn a new way of fishing emphasizing self-reliance .
If the majority of our senior citizens are able to be independent and pro-active , it helps to ease the dependency on our younger working population .
Even with the plethora of schemes , policies and aid , there will always be some who are unable to be independent .
This can be due to a range of reasons , such as disability , health , old age and even their mentality towards post-retirement work .
As expected , the percentage " increased to 77.9 % for those aged 75 and above " ( MCYS , 2006 , p.9 ) .
At the same time , it could be the mindset of some senior citizens , who feel the government should be footing their bills , as a right for the country 's elderly .
With the foresight of our country 's leaders , sociologists and policy makers , Singapore has many solutions to help alleviate the problems and hopefully , will towards sustaining the country better .
Everyone has a part to play , regardless if they are a working adult , a retiree , an elderly person or more importantly , just a citizen .
To experience a changing state of the body , generally for the worse , an individual could undergo tremendous amounts of psychological stress .
Thus , besides the critical assessment of allocating and maximising the use of the country 's resources , the government also have a part to play in ensuring that people have a smooth transition into old age .
There have been many proposed strategies , policies and research that act to target people of all ages in alleviating the effects of a greying population .
However , , because such approaches tend to operate with the concept of initial loss and future substantial gain , the majority may be unwilling to accept such propositions .
As such , critics disagree with the statement that the current policies have helped to ease the aging process to a large extent .
Although this method follows an " institutional-redistributive model " ( Metha & Wee , 2004 ) that is beneficiary to all citizens of Singapore , it involves the compulsory allocation of a portion of the salary , which in a short-term perspective is unfavourable .
Goals like car ownership may be disrupted by such interventions since the supposedly 'extra income ' is used to cover the individual for insurance and possible medical costs .
Through a holistic approach of both attitudes and actions towards such policy , .
have to align their ideology with that of the government to reap the equal benefits of such policies .
He believes that through the upgrading of the people , they can contribute more to society with their newly imparted skills .
In contrast , by creating policies to boost productivity of the workforce , the government would firstly have to set aside resources for upgrading and incentives , posing more potential of cutting welfare programs of the aged to fund the new regime .
Since the intended result is also not substantial , imposing these policies may then cause aggravation to the people as most may prefer resources to be put into more beneficial and tangible uses like funding welfare programs .
people may not work more despite the fact that they became more qualified in multiple professions .
Thus , in order for such policies to ease the issue of a greying population , the paradigm of aiding the country must be observed by society .
in the National Day 's Rally 09 ' speech made by PM Lee , he re-emphasised the significance of social responsibility .
He mentioned that though Singapore is new hospitals and strategies of saving cost in the recovery of the economical downturn , the community itself should be obliged to maintain a healthy lifestyle ( 2009 ) .
The aged have to acknowledge that community hospitals are recommended for rehabilitation while general hospitals are meant for acute problems .
Families and communities should also supervise the wellness of people through regular medical checks or even maintaining a healthy social network .
There are many existing initiatives that society can implement in the absence of such policies to ease the ageing process .
By campaigning pro-activeness as an integral part of people 's lives , it is certain that any policies implemented will be embraced by the majority 's positive perceptions .
Thus , with societal and governmental support , the process of ageing will be eased not only through the dampening of fiscal consequences but also very importantly , through the willingness of society in comprehending the greying issue .
Japan , the United Kingdom , France , Singapore , the and the United States are some countries that are facing the inevitable challenge of an aging population .
Various measures have been by the state to cope with the rising needs of the elderly .
The government has increased national expenditure to provide extra subsidies and financial aid for old age .
However , some people disagree that public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be channelled into other areas of development .
Many elderly people in society are still in need of public funds to support them financially , to subsidise their costly healthcare bills and also to enjoy more elderly services and facilities .
Public funding is necessary to support the low income group of elderly and to provide necessary social services .
For instance , in the United States , there is cash payment for the elderly under their social security system , supplemental security income program , catering meals programmes for the elderly and even subsidized housing ( Brecher , Knickman , Vogel , 1986 , Pg 366 ) .
Public spending should not be limited to helping the elderly with financial difficulties .
The state will have to pay for the workers that are running these retirement homes and rehabilitation centres .
Thus , public funding is still necessary to help the elderly who are in financial need and also to promote social welfare services for them .
Some elderly people who have retired might find themselves unable to cope with their rising medical expenses .
The government should actually help to subsidize medical bills for the elderly .
Furthermore , in the United States , there is the Medicaid programme .
They should keep themselves physically fit to prevent serious health implications at a later stage in life .
Nonetheless , public spending on healthcare subsidies should neither be reduced nor limited as the elderly still deserve care from society to lead a prolonged life .
It could jeopardize government spending on other areas of a country 's development in the long run .
Clearly , public spending on the aged should not be limited to money being diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
The aged are part of the fabric of society , and the should not be discriminated against .
After all , the elderly toiled hard when they were young and contributed significantly to the economic development of their country .
Their efforts should be compensated when they are old by providing them with a suitable assistance scheme through public spending
The rapidly aging population has caused a dilemma for the government .
The increasing dependency of the elderly is causing a burden to the national budget .
If governments neglect the importance of a country 's development and choose to spend more on the elderly instead , .
Public spending on the elderly should be limited , so money can be better spent on the country 's development , such as technological advancements for the betterment of the nation .
It is widely believed that the government should care for the elderly , in return for their valuable contributions to the country .
This is proven during a recession , where financial packages for the elderly are temporarily reduced .
The elderly usually form a minority of the population in a society .
In Singapore , the elderly comprises of only 8.7 % out of the total population .
So besides concern for the elderly , the welfare of society has to be taken care of .
Every government must fulfill their duty to build a society , where all citizens have equal rights , and not just focus on the elderly .
Education for the youth should be stressed more , school and other facilities ought to be built .
We should invest more on the young and adults instead of the elderly , as it is more promising to do so .
It is important for the government to know their role , to provide opportunity for their citizens to grow .
''Migrants should be able to migrate out of choice rather than out of necessity,' ' says the 25-member European Union .
It seems that workers tend to move out from an undeveloped country to seek better job opportunities
To the well developed countries of course .
This shows that becoming a developed country not only prevents the lost of workforce but also attracts talents to join our nation .
This in turn increases income tax and corporate tax collection which can be used for the benefit of the elderly .
Obviously , the notion of reimbursing the elderly with financial aid for their contributions to the country is naive .
There are plenty of methods that can provide aid the elderly .
This is an example of alternatives that can be used to reduce spending on the elderly .
So reducing spending on the elderly for the sake of a country 's development is a wise act .
While public spending on the aged is vital , it should not comprise other aspects of a country 's growth and development .
Despite the above , it may be argued that as the elderly contributed significantly to the country 's development in their younger days , in view of their long term hard work , they should be entitled to more benefits than the rest of the population .
For instance , as people age , there is an increased need for more healthcare resources , hence leading to inevitable spending in healthcare .
However , for the elderly with low or no income , they may face difficulties and restrictions in seeking appropriate medical treatment due to financial problems .
It is therefore crucial for governments to extend assistance to the elderly in the form of medical subsidies , allowances , rebates and other kinds of financial aid to ensure that the needs of the elderly are met and protected .
Resources of the country should be diverted into this aspect to provide scholarships and bursaries for needy children who are keen to further their studies and allow them to be exposed to better working opportunities in the future .
This further suggests that with education , older people in the future will be more affluent and will have a lesser tendency to rely on the government for their well-being .
In short , a better suggestion will be for countries to place more emphasis on its economical development , as with economic growth , people are generally more affluent and hence will possess the financial capabilities of providing for themselves in old age .
Even though there will also be a minority who are less capable of doing that , they will only comprise of the few who require assistance from the government .
Just a few decades ago , most economies were so focused in developing their country economically that they ignored the issue of an aging population .
Yet , it was only until recently that governments , especially those in developed countries , started to pay much more attention to the problem .
Undoubtedly , more public spending should be channeled to deal with the issues piggybacked along with a graying population .
As such public spending on other areas of the country 's development such as education would need to be cut to maintain a budget balance .
In today 's globalized world , where economies are growing at a tremendous rate in a diverse way , national spending has to be planned concisely and utilized fully in order to achieve optimal economic growth .
With public spending reduced in areas such as education and housing so as to fund the elderly , the country 's development would be hindered by the lack of funds .
This would greatly affect a country 's development as there are not enough people to fuel the economy .
This is especially true in countries such as Singapore , where its economic growth is largely dependent on its people .
The issue of an aging population will pose a threat to her future economic development .
Nonetheless , the government should fund the age with a perimeter in mind for such heavy subsidies comes with heavy tax levies citizens and investors .
Moreover , the aged may become over dependent on the government for subsidies .
Instead , funds should be diverted to other areas such as building more industrial infrastructures so as to attract more foreign-direct investments for the country 's development .
While it seems that it is necessary for a government to increase public spending to fund the aged so that productivity of the workers can be maintained , this can not be sustained in the long run .
Governments should not be myopic and divert most of the funds to support the aged but instead weigh the pros and cons carefully when implementing various long terms polices .
Likewise , most countries are currently tackling the main issue of an increasing ageing population .
Since today 's silver population of 65 years and above is 15 percent and is estimated to grow phenomenally to around 25 percent by the year 2030 ( Centre for Strategic and International Studies 2009 ) , governments are deeply concerned with the implementation of fiscal and welfare policies that would directly impact the aged .
A component of fiscal policy , public spending , should be limited so that self-reliance can be inculcated into the aged through forced savings and so the economy can function better by shifting monetary input to facilitate trade and investments in infrastructure .
Contrary to limiting public spending , critics of human rights have been advocating that state funding should not be minimized at the expense of growing the economy .
The mindset of respecting those who built the country from scratch resonates with feeling indebted to take care of them when they are old and providing them with the best of health-care .
Moreover , to a large extent , the government should favour funding programmes and policies for the elderly so their interests are well looked after .
Although it has always been the case that an appropriate amount of public spending is set aside for the aged , it is of the utmost importance to instill a sense of self-reliance in them , which can be effective through education about saving for retirement throughout their working life .
This plan of accumulating savings by an individual is compelled by law in some countries and at the same time , while the savings can help to enhance one 's responsibility for their own life , they can also provide people with financial security after retirement .
As such , there may be a huge concentration of growth in the area of trade because when more capital is used to invest in trade , it reaps substantial rewards in the form of revenue and higher growth and stability of the economy will ensue .
Besides state funds and capital can be used to improve the infrastructure of the country ; e.g .
public transport systems , telecommunications sector , energy and water resource divisions etc , so that the country may advance and prosper with the advent of new technologies and infrastructure .
Therefore , when economic growth is stable , this will lead to avenues of vast opportunities to further develop the country , and also result in fewer elderly in dire needs ( Friedland and Summer , 2005 ) .
As Singapore has limited land , it will have to think of ways to increase land usability and rejuvenate the old estates .
