Subsidized regular check up and medical fees must be offered to the senior citizens who are not able to pay up the amazingly high medical costs .
For instance , education is the most important part to invest in , knowing that new generations will be the future work force and take over the power and leadership position .
In Singapore , 743.4 million dollars was spent in 2007/08 to achieve a high literacy rate of 96 % ( among residents aged 15 years and over ) .
However , due to the high independence of senior citizens nowadays , it 's not necessary to provide an all-range policy to all of the aged population as there 're still many other aspects that should be taken care of .
This concludes that public spending on the aged population is fairly needed but to an extent that allows more improvement in other fields .
Old age has been always been associated with poor health and loneliness as people reach the final stage of their life .
The aging process is exacerbated when children abandon their parents as they feel that the old ones are a burden to them .
This is evident by an increasing number of old people being sent to old folks home every year .
In the past , such cases were fewer as abandoning of parents was seen as a social stigma , an unfilial act .
Unprecedented advances in technology resulted from extensive research and implementation of different creative policies have made the process of aging more pleasurable .
Firstly , in the medical arena , huge amounts of money have been poured in for research and development .
This is without waste , as many cures have been found .
Secondly government policies have impacted the lives of the aged positively .
Hence to be entitled to subsidies greatly increases their welfare .
Furthermore more and more countries are compelled by the law to set aside a certain amount of money for their old age .
In Singapore , a certain portion of working population income is set aside in their Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) in which the money can only be taken out at age 55 or later .
With more savings the old ones can provide for themselves and have more to spend for themselves instead of relying on the small sums payout by the government .
Another government policy that benefits the aged is the increment of the retirement age .
Other than the economic benefits , old people can involve themselves in their work and research has shown that working reduces the risk of getting illness associated with old age such as Alzheimer 's disease .
Thirdly , developments in infrastructure have resulted in more community centres built .
There are many activities ongoing in these community centres which are open to anyone interested .
Old people are encouraged to participate in these activites as they not only allow them to fill their time with activities they are passionate about but also expose them to opportunities to mix with a variety of people .
These activities make the aging process more fulfilling and engaging .
As countries get more developed , their citizens are more affluent and trends and cultures change .
More and more people are forsaking their parents in old folks ' homes as they could afford to .
Old people in old folks ' homes may have to deal with loneliness and the harsh fact that their own children whom they have brought up , have abandoned them .
To conclude , advancement in technology , breakthroughs in medical research and various government policies have contributed to the aging process where the aged can have better , quality and pleasurable time completing their last stage of their life .
However in certain cases development has caused a weakness in the extended family .
'Aging ' is a natural process of human life-cycle , whereby one grows older and gains his wisdom to the fullest before he departs from the Earth .
As such , this intensifying phenomenon creates a huge economic impact on numerous countries across the globe , presenting challenges on the allocation of fiscal budget to mitigate rising healthcare costs as well as costs in other related areas .
With the growth of the aging population , public spending on healthcare costs will be exorbitant .
However , the government should also ascertain the limit of healthcare finances based on an individual 's capability .
A nation 's military spending always takes up a substantial proportion of its fiscal budget due to the importance of having a strong defense force to defend itself against aggressors should diplomatic negotiations fail .
For example , the proliferation of nuclear weapons by North Korea has sparked off a regional arm 's race , causing neighboring countries like South Korea to purchase more sophisticated weaponry from America .
In addition , since the '911 ' incident , the world has come to see the threat of terrorism as very real .
Therefore , this would incur less healthcare costs as they remain fit and productive in their golden years .
People living in well-developed countries have high standards of living due to their affluence brought about by their stable economy .
This also means that less healthcare spending is required to sustain these affluent elderly people .
The lower-income group will also benefit from a well-developed economy as higher economic growth enables a government to provide more healthcare finances to support the elderly .
This would thus reduce the financial burden of this group of people based on their income ceilings .
Despite the volatility of the country 's economy due to the global market , it is imperative for a government to implement feasible economic policies to facilitate trade and growth .
Therefore , having a sturdy economy will also incur less financial costs on elderly welfare .
In retrospect , countries around the world face challenges with an increasingly aging population .
Aging is , no doubt , one of the most pressing issues that many developed countries are facing today .
Japan and Singapore have been battling an aging society for many years where the birth rates are at depressing levels and better healthcare facilities are available .
Firstly , through economical means , elderly people are becoming increasingly part of the working community , working past the retirement age .
There are subsidies from the government to employers to send workers aged 40 and above to upgrade their skills .
An example is SDF course fee subsidy of up to 90 % for workers aged above 40 with 'A ' level and below qualifications .
However , critics may argue that employers may hire younger workers due to their lower wages and higher working efficiency as compared to older workers .
As for wages , people aged above 50 will contribute less to their CPF accounts and this includes the employer 's CPF contribution .
Secondly , through social policies , there are more and more entertainment activities to keep the elderly occupied .
To cope with elderly people 's increasing loneliness , there are activities that can bond the elders together and engage them in fun-learning and enriching activities according to their interests .
For example , the Wellness Programme in Singapore provides companionship with the other seniors through activities like brisk walking , dancing , gardening or cycling .
For example , in China , it is common to see many elderly people practising Taiji in the morning in public parks and dancing along the streets at night .
Last but not least , through architectural means , there are many infrastructures and facilities put in place for the convenience of the elderly .
The flats built in the past in Singapore were not accessible at every floor as the lifts were built in a way where they stopped only at specific levels .
Nowadays , our society is highly concerned about the impact of the aging process on our lives .
In order to be a valid candidate for an explanation of the aging process , the changes proposed by the theory must meet the following criteria : ( 1 ) they will commonly occur in all or most humans ; ( 2 ) as an individual ages , these changes will become more pronounced ; and ( 3 ) the changes will lead to cellular or organ dysfunction that ultimately causes failure of the organ or system ( Steven N. Trautwein ) .
Although the aging process has raised many problems in our lives , current science research and social policies have helped to solve these problems .
As the life cycle of human beings is , human life expectancy is heavily dependent on the rate of aging .
However , a lot of money and efforts have been put in by governments , companies and scientists worldwide to do research in aging in order to slow down the aging process and also help to resolve some health problems that are caused by aging .
For example , there are scientists who have created fruit flies that are able to their normal life spans and thus have made old human cells behave like young cells again .
This research has made it possible to let us live for a longer time , leading to a healthier life in our old age .
As a result , degenerative diseases of old age such as arthritis , diabetes and hypertension can be treated and thus help to ease the aging process .
Centuries ago , human longevity was comparably shorter than human longevity today .
This is because the invention of medicine has helped human beings to sustain a longer life .
The only way to cure these diseases is to undergo transplantation .
As the growing aging population has increased the need for organs , it is hard to get enough organs needed for the transplantation .
In this case , artificial organs can help to bridge the gap in time until a donor organ is available for transplantation and thus improve the survival of patients while they are waiting for transplantation .
Therefore , we should appreciate the hard work of scientists in the lab and medical center since it has improved old age in many aspects .
Other than the medical breakthroughs , social policies for the elderly are also playing important roles in easing the aging process .
For instance , there are social policies such as introducing advanced insurance schemes that encourages young people to start saving more to be financially secure in their old age .
Many countries have made individual retirement funds mandatory and hence successfully increased the number of individuals who are able to support themselves in their old age .
In addition , some social welfare programs , especially those which help to resolve aging problems , including providing financial help to the needy elderly , are under way .
These programs protect those underprivileged elderly from starving or from being homeless .
At the same time , some charitable societies have organized many activities for the elderly to enjoy which prevent them from getting psychological illnesses such as depression that could make them feel they are worthless .
These activities have provided a place for them to socialize with others , make friends , and get exercise as well .
Hence , these social policies have brought a happy , healthy , safe and comfortable life to the elderly .
In conclusion , our society should pay much attention to the aging problems and come up with solutions .
We are unable to reverse time but on average we can live a healthier lifestyle and for a compared with our ancestors since current research and policies are practical in solving some aging problems .
Apart from that , there are also many studies in different fields such as architecture and psychology that are helpful to the elderly .
As time passes , everybody will eventually become older and so we should prepare for it now .
For the past few years , the issue of an aging population has been debated widely across the globe as it took the world world by storm .
As economy develops , the signs of an aging population worsen .
Such signs can be seen in developed countries like Germany and Japan , where the median age of citizens in the country is pushing towards 53 and 54 respectively ( Peterson 2001 ) .
As an older population will directly result in lower productivity and higher social and welfare cost in a nation , many sociologists of today are and bringing forth strategies , hoping that the issue of elder dependency will be taken care of without threatening a nation 's economy .
While the majority of the solutions revolve around increasing public spending on the aged , many think that such a proposal is not viable nor well balanced , as the economic aspect of a country has not been taken into account .
People at this opposing end , thus believe that public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development , indirectly solving the aging matter effectively .
Firstly , the root of the elder dependency problem can only be solved if the country invests in other specific areas that would indirectly relieve the situation .
On the other hand , if the country invests in other specific areas like education , the burden of taking care of the elderly will literally shift from the government to the younger generation .
This is due to the better inculcation and cultivation of moral values among the youth as a result of better education , thus increasing their responsibility in taking care of their immediate elderly family members .
A country could also focus its spending on developing its financial economy , the result of which would be that the working population would be financially better off to take care of their immediate elderly family members , thereby the burden on government spending .
Secondly , allowing massive public spending on the elderly tends to create a negative impact on the society .
Since there are no future financial worries , the working population would eventually spend all their income on personal items without saving for the future .
This would put even more pressure on the government financially in terms of funding the medical and social expenses of the elderly .
Hence , limiting public spending on the aged serves as a good warning sign to people in the working society .
It reminds people that they have to play a fair part in taking care of their own health and wealth management is necessary to ensure financial security in the long run .
Such an approach can be seen in countries like Singapore , where employees are obliged to contribute part of their monthly salary to their Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) Account .
The purpose of such an account is to ensure that Singaporeans would have sufficient funds to support themselves when they grow old .
Given my above two reasons , one may argue that the ideology of such an approach in dealing with an aging population is too long-term oriented .
As such , it is impractical and it lacks the ability to deal with the problem in the short term .
As the benefit of the approach can only be seen in the long run , reducing and limiting the public funding amount immediately would result in shortage of funds to deal with current demand .
This could then result in a precarious situation , where many elder needy may not get the medical and financial attention that they need .
By reducing public funding for the elderly , the government seeks to be more stringent in their subsidization criteria .
This will ensure that those who really need help will still get the attention needed , while those who can still afford to look after themselves will receive less in contrast .
Instead of ignoring those who demand help , this approach simply re-evaluates the subsidizing criteria , enforcing the practice of self responsibility for those who can and asking the public to take a fair share in taking care of themselves or their immediate family members .
All in all , in order to tackle the root of the elder dependency problem , nations should not focus on dealing with the current tangible problems .
This will eventually result in a smoother path in easing the aging process , and lessen the burden of the nation 's economy .
" To a large extent , current research and development or policies have helped to ease the aging process .
In recent years , many Asian countries such as Japan , South Korea , Hong Kong and Singapore have been tackling a long term issue - a burgeoning ageing population , which is a repercussion of rapid economic development , with high quality of health care but a relatively low fertility rate .
An aging population has caused an increase in public spending and decline in Gross Domestic Product ( GDP ) , owing to a decrease in the people who are highly productive .
Surveys show that many elderly individuals are prone to suicide because they can not bear the overwhelming effects of ill health and the feeling of loneliness .
Fortunately , plenty of research studies and policies have helped in easing the aging process .
Prime Minister of Singapore , Lee Hsien Loong , once said , " We are crafting new policies , improving our infrastructure and developing effective programs to enable older citizens to lead full and happy lives .
" An important policy the government has adopted is " Supporting Lifelong Employability " .
According to this strategy , legislation requires employers to offer re-employment to workers for another three years after their official retirement age , not necessarily in the same job or at the same pay .
The government is going to retrain older workers and enhance their skills so that they are ready to .
For example , in July 2007 , C3M and local university Uni SIM offered courses to senior citizens so as to enable them to earn credits through courses to pursue a degree in future .
However , critics argue that the elderly are inefficient , conservative and out-dated .
They are a burden rather than an asset in the workplace .
Nonetheless , most older workers are independent , mature and .
They possess valuable experience to impart to the younger workers and they can the younger workers that are more productive and innovative , but who lack experience .
This strategy enables senior citizens to stay engaged and contributing in the workforce , have more self-reliance in finance , boost the economic development of Singapore , , and thus slow down the aging process .
Furthermore , the introduction of the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) , a mandatory saving scheme , is also a policy carried out by the government to ease the aging process .
Under the CPF scheme , employees have to pay into their individual employee accounts during their working years and the savings can be drawn when a person retires to pay for his medical expenses or long- term care .
The policy is quite useful in grappling with the aging issue from the economic view point as it encourages financial planning by individuals during their economically active years and lowers such as their burden hindering the younger generation 's .
The government can also reduce the privileges allocated to the elderly and the public spending can be used in a more prudent way in the development of the country in other areas .
Maybe from the younger generation 's perspective , the policy does n't make sense as it not only every month , but it is .
However , it is a worthwhile practice for citizens to plan for their income and expenditure and their future .
In addition , the implementation of the " Wellness Program " and policies to create an age-friendly environment also helps in buffering the aging process .
The Wellness Program is a social program designed to encourage active and healthy lifestyles among senior citizens .
It comprises 3 parts- health screening , regular exercise programmes and social activities like brisk walking , dancing , cycling and so on .
Recently , realise that housing estates and public transport .There is also lift access to all floors of block of flats .
All these create a safe and accessible environment to the elderly .
In effect , the policies are because the welfare of the elderly is well taken care of and they will not be neglected by the community .
Despite the fact that this social policy requires a lot of money , it is crucial because senior citizens are part of our society and as responsible members of society , it is our duty to take care of their welfare when they are unable to do so themselves .
In conclusion , the aging process is complicated and multifarious , and it affects every one of us .
We may not be able to prevent the aging process from happening but we can try to slow down the process as far as we can .
Current research and development indeed helps a lot in slowing down the process .
The aging problem is serious ; it may slow down the economic growth in a country and create long-term stagnation .
Therefore , we must contribute to and support the policies available so as to achieve on a societal level in the long term .
There have recently been some issues of the ageing population that people feel strongly about .
Some think that policy makers should reduce the funds for the elderly , and spend more money on other areas of the country 's developments .
some critics would argue and object to this .
However , I agree with the first opinion .
In this way , governments can make people aware of the necessity of actively working to accumulate more money to support themselves in their retirement .
Moreover , children certainly should look after and take care of their old parents more thoughtfully than before because they would not want to see their parents affected by the decrease in funds for elderly citizens .
Besides , we can see that the elderly nowadays look healthier and than ever before .
This is due to the fact that our services for the population are now improving day by day .
For instance , the quality of life has been made better as improvements in health care and sciences now make it possible for us to .
Retirees probably do not need too much money ; the main things they want at their age are to be satisfied , to live healthily with their family and to help their offspring to be more experienced .
Therefore , the decrease in funding for the elderly should not have a bad impact on the ageing population .
It is worth remembering that policy makers should also focus on other areas to develop their countries as well as reduce the pressure of the graying population .
For example , an effective solution to the ageing population is to increase the percentage in the governments ' treasuries such as the economy , science , transportation , education and some other areas .
The reason for this is that those sectors play a significant role in the development of the nations .
Once the countries are strong enough , certainly the elderly will benefit .
To illustrate , spending money on economic research helps predict the trend of consumption and reduce the bad effects of unstable markets on the nations ' economies .
Moreover , improvements in science can not only help the people be but also decrease the size of hospitalisation and other medical bills .
Moreover , education is surely the most important area which governments must focus on as well .
The more effectively students are educated , the more productive and responsible the citizens we have .
With , there is no doubt that problems related to an no longer exists because authorities have great resources to deal with such problems .
Many critics disagree with spending less money on the elderly because it contradicts traditional morals .
They say that because the number of households with elderly members is increasing as the people born in the baby boomer generation would be nearly 65 in 2012 .
Moreover , at present , there are still many people who can not take care of their parents and have to leave them in old folks ' homes because they have their own family and they are still struggling to get by in this increasingly complex world .
However , in my view , placing a limit on public spending for the elderly does not mean that we do not care about the ageing population .
Keeping our focus on the elderly is only a temporary solution . How can we deal with this issue while we still lack support from other factors such as science and the economy ?
Governments should serve their elderly citizens over the long term instead of for the short term only .
Once they develop strong economies and improvements in science , policy makers can not only focus on the graying population but also come up with the solutions to many other problems .
Overall , governments should change their focus on other factors of the country first before they help the elderly .
Once those main sectors are strong enough , the solution for the elderly can be implemented .
The increase in aging populations around the world is being hastened due to the long life expectancy and low fertility rates in many countries .
However , if this trend of spending continues in the future , it will be destructive to a country 's financial structure .
When we flip through the newspapers nowadays , we will usually read much news about countries being battered by the prevalent recession .
According to the data calculated by the IMF ( International Monetary Fund ) to measure the impact of the financial crisis , the price of the financial crisis will indeed be high . For instance , the G20 developed countries ' GDP is expected to contract by 8 % in 2008-09 .
Nonetheless , these costs incurred during the recession will only be about 10 % of the spending related to elder care in the long-term from now to 2050.Due to the consequences brought by the financial crisis , it is critical for a country to divert more resources from elderly-related spending to pumping up the dire economy .
The substantial cost of generous elderly care will not be fully supported if the countries ' financial position is unstable .
Although many rich countries have accepted that it is time to reform their policies , the transformation is progressing very slowly due to the reluctance to introduce unpopular measures . Such reluctance is affected by political factors like election .
Secondly , it is well accepted that a country should have and appropriate development plans for gaining healthy growth .
The country should not focus too much of its effort on exploring the incentives for spending on elderly care ; instead , it should develop an adequate plan for the sectors which are equally important to the country 's development .
For example , we can not neglect the significance of education .
Education plays a critical role in helping a country grow from phase to phase .
The productivity and revenue of a country can be improved tremendously due to a well-established educational structure .
For instance , the federal government in Canada is promoting innovation where its skills and learning agenda " rests on the principle that in the knowledge economy , prosperity depends on innovation which , in turn , depends on the investments that we make in the creativity and talents of our people .
investing in innovation will brew new knowledge for the economy which will in turn then create an environment with innovation excellence to protect and improve our quality of life .
In the long run , we are still maintaining our level of elderly care a different way .
Moreover , a country which insists on providing maximum resources to the elderly care will face a dilemma when proposing a financial budget .
While elder care will inevitably account for a large portion of expenditure , the consequence of this improper budget is the financial burden of raising funds , which will result in a full load of debts and raising taxes .
The original intention of helping the elderly would then be tainted as the resulting situation would in fact cause suffering for more people .
On the contrary , the alternative to helping the elderly lead a better life is not only limited to a large spending budget , but it is also achieved while the country boosts the economy through different incentives , like supporting the entrepreneurship of people by cutting taxes and giving allowances .
It creates an environment where people will have accumulated more wealth in the early stage of their life so they can support themselves in the later stage of their life .
In reality , some elderly employees challenge the raising of the retirement age as this delays their eligibility for their pension . .
It is a challenging task for the government to persuade people to agree over such an adjustment .
In a nutshell , the solid development of a country is built on a healthy financial position and an unbiased development plan .
Having a superior elderly care system does not mean having great success in governing a country .
On top of that , spending should not be narrowly limited to elderly-related spending only , but resources should instead be evenly allocated over all the sectors instead of overlooking their importance .
Many people focused on working instead of studying , so the literacy rate was not high .
Aging problems did not arise until recently , when those who were born during the baby boom period are turning 50 to 60 years old .
It is undeniable that spending on the aged is important ; however , we should not neglect the more important areas like education and economy to make sure that the future generation does not suffer from the same problem again .
I believe that education is one of the more important areas where public money should be spent on .
In fact , a good education is the only way out of the rat race , to a better and secure future .
Although Singapore literacy rate is relatively high as compared to the rest of the world , I still believe that should be done .
For example , increasing mandatory schooling for Singaporeans until secondary school and providing more funding for students from poorer background .
Funding can be in the form of disbursing , subsidising school fees and developing more scholarship programs for the children of needy families .
These incentives will encourage children from poorer families to study further .
For instance , in the form of forced savings like the Central Provident Fund or life annuity schemes .
This will decrease the number of elderly persons that require funding from the government to get by in their old age .
More highly educated people also tend to plan ahead for their retirement .
For example , encourages retrenched or older workers to upgrade themselves to increase their employability .
Education may be one of the ways to minimize the percentage of the elderly relying on government funding .
Another area that Singapore should also spend more money on is in developing the economy .
It is when the country 's wealth can continue to grow that the economy is stable .
Coupled with better education , it will not be surprising that the disposable income of Singapore would also be increased .
This will improve the standard of living for Singaporeans and will eventually contribute to a better healthcare system in Singapore .
As Singaporeans become more well off , research for innovative products to tap on the sliver industry ( market for the old people ) will result .
Similarly , the users of the innovative products will be in a better position , financially , to afford it .
With that , the sliver industry will become a lucrative market and more companies will be willing to invest time and money into developing innovative products for the elderly .
Recently , 5 companies have received a $ 500K grant from the government to develop elderly friendly products for the silver industry .
There is an immediate problem here and we can not ignore that these 50- to 60-year-old elders as they have contributed to the success of Singapore in many ways .
Beyond that , solutions like nursing those elderly in other countries like Malaysia where expenses will be lower are not well received by the elderly themselves .
In conclusion , by spending more on both the economy and education , we will be able to decrease the effects of the aging problem .
By investing in education and the economy , Singaporeans will be able to generate more disposable income and hence , be less reliant on government funding when they grow old .
Public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of a country 's development .
Being a firm believer of the saying 'prevention is better than cure ' , I with this statement to a certain extent .
In the year 2000 , seven percent of Singapore 's total population was over the age of sixty-five , but by 2030 this will increase to nineteen percent ( Inter- Ministerial Committee on Aging Report 1999 ) .
Singapore can limit public spending on the aged , use the savings and indirectly reduce the total expenditure on the aged in terms of healthcare and accommodation .
There are three methods that can tackle the problem in the long run .
Firstly , by channeling the money saved to make a more robust educational system , the government can have better civics and moral education .
Starting from a tender age , we should no longer rely on parents to educate the youth on what they deem as unimportant issues .
The new comprehensive education system should include firm beliefs that one should take care of one 's parents when they 're old . This will help instil filial piety in the youths. .
Indeed , more often than not , education can help one out of poverty .
Thus , by having a superb educational system , the government can essentially worry less about meeting the needs of the less educated population , thereby tackling .
By spending on the development of public amenities like beaches , larger parks , family-oriented shopping malls , etc. , the government can encourage families to foster better relationships amongst family members .
I believe that with better understanding , individuals with elderly parents will feel more obliged to spend time and money to provide better care and concern for them .
Beaches and parks also provide an avenue for the aged to keep fit and stay healthy , cutting down unnecessary healthcare costs that arise from age-related problems .
Thirdly , there should be an increase in funding for the healthcare sector .
One primary concern in providing healthcare for the aged is the cost .
Although some might argue that increasing healthcare funding just targets at providing for the aged , by looking at the bigger picture , one will see that an improved healthcare system provides for all .
By treating and preventing more diseases from arising before one gets old and detecting early symptoms of diseases , a person can be healthier especially .
It is well known that depression is more destructive than any sickness the aged will have , so having a fit mind is essential for having a fit body .
As recently mentioned in the media , Singapore will get a boost in funding for palliative care .
The new initiative by the Health Ministry means that the use of Medisave for home palliative care will be liberalised .
This has been done in view that the aged actually cherish the quality rather than the quantity of life . Such care is similar to that of hospice care in providing comfort rather than cure .
The revised funding will also not only include in-patient hospice care , but also cover home hospice care .
But despite the revision of spending in this area , the government must thread the issue with care as there are doubts over the sustainability of the provision of this free service .
Interestingly , aid for the aged for their psycho-social needs is still lacking .
In conclusion , it is noted that capping of public spending for the aged will provide more cash flow to other sectors , which will in turn reduce and tackle the problems faced now .
All three areas of education , healthcare and social policy are equally important whereas unnecessary funding to other sectors , like to the military , should be avoided or reduced .
" There is only a certain extent the government can increase its public spending on the aged , in particular in the area of .
Ultimately , prevention is still better than cure , so we need to solve the problem from its root .
It is a well-known fact that the global society is growing old and old .
Because of this , it is important to make a policy that will be able to support the elderly in their late life .
It is quite a pity to limit public spending on the elderly
However , if we limit public spending on the aged , the money can be diverted and used to develop the country in other areas , such as economy and education , which will eventually lead to more advantages for the country .
Nevertheless , if we limit the public spending on the elderly , the first one to suffer is the younger generation who have to take care of their parents .
They will have to spend more money for their parents while sometimes they may not even be able to fulfil their own needs .
Just imagine if the parents have cancer and they have to go through a surgical operation which will cost the younger generation thousands of dollars .
This will bring more burden on the young .
Besides , there are also parents who have children working overseas or even have no children , which may eventually lead them to leaning on no one except the government .
Therefore , if the government limits public spending on the aged , a lot of the young and elderly will suffer .
The first one is in the area of the economy .
By diverting the money to develop the economy , the government will be able to create more jobs so that it can reduce the unemployment rate as well as increase its Gross Domestic Product , which is the indicator of the economic health and standard of living in a country .
Besides this , Friedland ( 2005 ) suggests that " with sufficient economic growth there are more choices and fewer persons in need " .
Therefore , by diverting the money into the area of economy , we can prevent the elderly from depending on government help .
Based on statistics for the year 2008 in Singapore , 68.2 % of residents who are 55 years and above have only graduated from secondary school .
It is one of the reasons why the elderly earn less money and therefore need government help .
However , by diverting the money into the area of education , we can provide the young with education that will help them in their later life .
By providing them with good education , we can also prevent the same thing happening again .
Moreover , with a higher level of education , they will be able to learn how to invest well , which may eventually lead to higher earnings and which may also result in the increase in the Gross Domestic Product , which is good for their country .
In conclusion , even if the limitation on public spending for the elderly will result in more burden for the young and elderly , because of the long-term impact that it may have , such as more jobs , better education , and increase in Gross Domestic Product .
Moreover , it is better to try preventing things from happening rather than just try covering them up all the time .
Nowadays , the has become a real concern not only for the government but also for the public .
The vast increase in the aging population has led the economy to a lack of effective workers .
Furthermore , the elderly people , who are unable to continue earning and have little support from the young , seem to have many financial difficulties and have become a burden to society .
Having said this , the aging problem is worth considering but the government should not spend too much money on it while the effectiveness of recent solutions for the problem is still uncertain and the problem can be solved indirectly by the development of other areas of the country like the economy or education .
Some of the most well-known strategies for dealing with the aging population are extending the retiring age , lengthening and encouraging financial planning during economically active year .
These strategies ' point is that if people are given more opportunities to work , they may be able to save enough money for their retirement .
However , many real problems arising from the reality that make this strategy inappropriate .
Since the retirement age comes from much careful research on human health as well as ability to work , extending it irresponsibly may be harmful for the workers .
When more elderly people are employed , there will be less workplace for younger , more effective workers ; this is really a huge waste of human resources .
The second thing is that not everyone is able to make an effective financial plan during their economically active years .
It requires some basic financial knowledge which is difficult for the normal worker to know .
In spite of focusing only on the aged , diverting money into the economy can not only bring benefits to the country but also help solve the aging problem .
If the government invests more money in the economy like reducing tax for companies , allowing more foreign investments , , the concern for lack of effective labor among the aging population may be addressed .
In addition , a growing economy provides more sufficient funds to increase the pension and improve the welfare for elderly people .
Furthermore , when the economy is developed , salaries of workers will increase such that they will have more savings when they retire .
Spending money for the economy seems to be a wise choice for the government .
Improving education is also a way to develop countries and a solution to the aging problem .
With more money invested in education , the schools and universities will have more modern educational equipment , better teachers , and most importantly , reduce tuition fees so that more people can study and have better education .
As a result , with higher education , people will have more chances of earning higher salaries , thus increasing their savings for later needs .
When people are given some basic knowledge about managing money , they will be able to do financial planning , which will help them to use their money wisely and reduce waste
Furthermore , elderly people with better education tend to have more active , healthier lives than others and are not a burden to society .
For example , since elderly people have some knowledge about nutrition , they will have the ability to choose healthy food like vegetables , beans , and fish instead of high-cholesterol food like butter , sugar , and meat .
Good education is necessary not only for society but also for people who do not want to face financial difficulties when they retire .
In general , aging population is a global problem and needs to be solved as soon as possible but we have to consider the solutions carefully .
With the uncertainty of recent strategies for this problem , we should divert our money and effort into other areas which have more potential benefits .
The word aging has always been greatly feared by most in society .
The moment we become old , it implies that we are closer to the end of our lives .
We can hardly move as freely as the young , productivity is much lower and most of the time we are bedridden because of illnesses .
Life will be sheer torture instead of enjoyment .
The aging process , to me , means progressive steps to become old , the transition to illnesses , immobility and lack of money for retirement .
To prevent such situations from happening , research and development in science and medicine , innovative infrastructure projects and social policies have been constantly crafted to reduce the effect of these problems and make life of elderly so much easier and more comfortable .
Hence , I agree to a large extent that current research and development/policies have helped to ease the aging process .
The aged are weak and vulnerable against various diseases .
As one 's age increases , the body immune system deteriorates .
The ability to fight against germs and viruses becomes much less effective .
Doctors have better knowledge of the diseases .
With much improved equipment and tools , they are able to treat illnesses with much higher efficiency .
Through research and development , more effective medicines have been invented to cater to different types of problems .
Diseases , such as tuberculosis , which were deemed incurable in the past , can now be easily treated by the level of medical procedures .
These breakthroughs thus they can enjoy the of their lives healthier , happier and with less suffering .
As medical procedures get very advanced , the cost of medical treatments is too heavy a price to bear .
However , if money is spent from illness and ease pain and suffering , the lives of the elderly are still made more comfortable than before .
Hence , research and development in medical science has helped to ease the aging process .
As mobility decreases , daily major activities are greatly reduced too .
This significantly decreases the amount of entertainment an elderly person can enjoy .
For instance , in Singapore the elevators in older HDB flats can only stop at certain levels .
Residents who live on other levels will have to climb staircases from their home to the lift .
However , under the new development , elevators in the newly built HDB flats can stop at all levels , thus making it easier for senior citizens to go up and down the flats. .
Other than making the lift accessible to all levels , conscientious efforts have been done to further simplify the lives of the elderly .
Some elderly people can hardly walk up or down any stairs , thus ramps are paved out and hand railings are erected in parks to assist them walk around .
Owing to research and development in social infrastructure , the elderly are allowed to pursue leisure and entertainment .
As an aging population can be a big problem to many countries , several social policies are put in place to ensure the old have enough money after retirement .
In Singapore , for example , all working adults have to contribute about 14.5 % of their salary into a CPF account and their employers have to contribute 20 % .
All the money deposited into the CPF account will be invested by the government and in return , offer a 3 % annual compound interest to CPF contributors .
The lifestyles of elderly people are maintained with the help of CPF schemes .
Therefore , the aging process is eased by current social policies .
The research and development of medical science , improvements in social infrastructure and social policies have helped in ensuring good health among the elderly , building facilities to create convenience for them and establishing CPF schemes to make sure the elderly have sufficient money for their retirement .
When problems related to health , mobility and finance are solved , the elderly will be able to enjoy a much better improved lifestyle .
" It is true to say that with different improvements from different fields , we can face the challenges and solve the problems arising from aging population .
If these problems are not solved , the median age in many first-world countries will reach 51 by .
During the aging process , the elderly will face financial problems and may be abandoned by their children .
Although this problem is unlikely to be solved in the short run , many ways have been carried out to ease the aging process , particularly in social policy and science research .
Some people claimclaim that it is everyone 's responsibility to plan financially for old-age to reduce dependency on children However , for those who are physically disabled and suffering from illnesses , they do not have the ability to work and look after themselves .
This policy is used to encourage them to accumulate more wealth to support themselves during old age .
Hence , the effort of the Singapore government to improve returns on CPF Savings has buffered the impact of the aging problem .
The silver jobs fair , established to find jobs for people aged 60 and over , is part of a government effort in South Korea to assist a rapidly growing population of older Koreans .
Children often expect their parents to contribute to household chores when they move in and do not expect to be made responsible for their parents ' well-being. .
Therefore , most of them need to work and master new technologies in order to earn their living after retirement .
Though some that the elderly do not perform well in their work , this group of people can actually bring improvement to the sectors they are involved in through their own experiences .
Viewing from the healthcare perspective , researchers have also taken a big step toward discovering that human hearts can grow new cells .
It was previously thought that the human heart is unable to grow new cells after birth .
However , there is a study that can disprove it .
The scientists reported the evidence that new heart cells are made through one person 's life .
Now , it is possible to say that we can regenerate heart muscles after a heart attack .
In conclusion , the aging problem is a concern all over the world .
With the current policies and development in science study , aging process will be solved in the long run .
The challenge for the future is to ensure that people with different ages can continue to participate in society as citizens with full human rights .
Hence , I hope that the relationship between the generations can be nurtured and children will take the responsibility for taking care of their parents .
To a large extent , current research , developments and policies have helped ease the aging process a
A fast increasing aged population has been occurring all over the world .
As people age , their income drops but their medical expenses are actually increasing .
Hence , every research , development and policy that will help them to reduce their burden is important to them .
To a large extent , current research , developments and policies have helped to ease the aging process .
Medical expenses are most likely to be the burden of the aged population .
As humans age , metabolism rates and immunity will start to drop , and limbs and body organs such as kidneys , livers , and hearts will start to fail due to long years of usage .
To ensure that the aged population is able to pay large amount of medical expenses which could happen due to their old age , has set up a few policies to assist them .
For example , Medisave helps when they are younger to save money for their future medical expenses . It allows more people to be able buy affordable insurance since its premium can be deducted from their Medisave accounts , while Central Provident Funds allow people to be less worried about their silver age expenses , include medical expenses .
Although some people might think that the government forces them to contribute part of their income to CPF , they fail to realize that this can be good as it prevents them from squandering it on other less important merchandise .
Therefore , when they age , they will not be very dependent on the government , which thus can divert funds into other important development plans .
Other than the expenses , science and medical discovery is one of most important factors that will help ease the aging process .
Since the increase in awareness of balanced diet , people have been consuming less salt , sugar or high fat food , thus reducing the chances suffering from chronic diseases like hypertension , diabetes , or cardiovascular diseases .
Although statistics have shown that people have become more vulnerable to these kinds of diseases , their chance of survival has been increasing as medical technology becomes more advanced .
In addition , medicines used to counter hypertension and diabetes have been popular .
Thus , these enable hypertension and diabetis patients to work and live normally after taking medicine .
What will happen if older people need these medicines but these medicines are not affordable to them ?
The medisave and medishield they bought will help them pay for their expenses ; although not fully , it would still significantly .
Architectural improvement has also linked aged people both with and without disability to be able to travel by themselves .
For instance , the SMRT company has installed lifts at every MRT station and provided bus services that are able to carry wheelchair users .
With these little extra efforts provided by the company , it would be more convenient for the aged people to ride MRT or public bus .
A decade ago , most Singapore HDB apartment lifts are not accessible on every floor , thus it was very inconvenient for older people as they still to take the stairs which might have imposed more danger to them .
Seeing this problem , the government decided to upgrade the lift systems , so most HDB apartment lifts are accessible on every floor now .
The cost of this architectural improvement required a large amount of funds , but what drove SMRT , SBS Transit and the government to spend much money on these upgrades even though these may not have affected profits ?
It was because may have seen future benefits from these upgrades as the improvements would not only benefit aged or disabled people , but they would also reduce people 's travel time thus increasing their productivity .
Hence , we find that government policies have helped people to be more able to meet their medical expenses , science discovery has helped improved aged people 's health conditions , and architectural improvement has made aged people 's life easier .
Combining all points mentioned above , we can conclude that current research , developments and policies have not only been helping ease the aging process but also have brought a lot of other benefits as well .
By the year 2030 , one in five people in Singapore will have aged 65 and above .
If there is a limit to the budget meant for the elderly , the quality of life that the government provides for the elderly will be affected .
Lack of family support , unemployment due to low education level , and social and political impact on the country are some of the factors why public spending on the aged should not be limited .
It should instead be increased gradually over the years .
Many of the young adults are leaving Singapore because of the stifling atmosphere of the country and the political and intellectual lockstep enforced by the government .
Some are also attracted by job offers overseas .
With these young adults leaving the country , the elderly are the ones who suffer because they are left alone and most of the time , their children do not have the intention of coming back .
Tribunal cases of elderly demanding financial assistance from their children in Singapore have increased over the years .
Although the government is studying the best way to use the Maintenance of Parents Act to get such children to fulfill their filial duty , they should also set aside a bigger budget each year as a cushion in case the children themselves have difficulty financing their own families .
Most of the elderly do not have proper education that is needed in today 's society in order to make ends meet .
With age catching up with time , their productivity decreases and eventually companies hire new employees to replace them .
If the government were to limit spending on them , they will face many potential problems such as unemployment or retrenchment , which will have a spillover effect on their children supporting them financially .
However , some companies do retain their older workers because of loyalty but if there is a crisis , they will still be the first ones to get laid off .
The government has done well in giving doleouts to the elderly but this could only satisfy a percentage of the elderly population .
Our population is aging and by spending more on the aged , people can be assured that when they grow old , the government will be there to support them .
On the other hand , if there is a limit on spending on the aged , people might tend towards individualism .
This will over time cause them to be more focused on their individual interests without taking the interests of society into consideration .
Moreover , besides the social impact on the country , political impact will be another factor to take into consideration .
According to Singapore statistics , the percentage of the elderly in Singapore is 8.7 % of the entire population and this number is increasing slowly every year .
Singapore has done well over the years in implementing projects helping the poor and consequently , it has gained the trust and support of the citizens .
It is therefore crucial to maintain or improve its image through .
In summary , having a limit to the budget will have long-term implications for the country 's and growth .
The government should gradually increase the budget for the elderly every year alongside its economic growth .
Instead of treating the elderly in society as a burden , the government should think of ways to harness their knowledge and experience so that they can contribute back more to society .
In the recent years , along with the decline in birth rates , the proportion of the aged in our population has also increased .
This has led to a major problem of our time , known as ageing population .
Governments around the world have been actively seeking measures to cope with the problem , one of which is to increase public spending on the aged .
Even though public spending on the elderly is essential in dealing with an ageing population , it should be limited because of underlying negative implications .
Instead , more expenditure should go towards other forms of development .
Though some may agree that public spending on the aged largely aids society in coping with the needs of an ageing population , it may also hinder the development of other sectors .
With greater expenditure on helping the aged , the country will have less funds for development in other areas such as infrastructure .
Therefore , with inadequate input into these areas , the development of the latter will be neglected .
As such areas are the key pillars of a country 's development , any slowdown in these areas will affect the country 's regional competitiveness .
EU , for instance , has been dealing with an ageing population .
It has been predicted that the region 's growth rate will be reduced by half in the near future as a result of over public spending on the aged .
[ 1 ] Hence , its impact on the economy is negative , .
Therefore , since expenditure on the aged puts the country 's growth at risk , it should be limited .
Though many may claim that the bulk of the amount needed to support the aged should come from the government which has the greatest financial power to support them , this public spending should be limited .
If large expenditures were to be dedicated to helping the elderly , the children may rely too heavily on the government to support their aged family members instead of both parties playing a part in sharing the burden of supporting them .
In Singapore , for instance , the government is not the sole party that is responsible for supporting the ageing population .
The government only contributes through distribution of subsidies to help the aged while their children carry the responsibility of supporting them .
Therefore , to prevent overdependence on the government , public spending should be limited and be diverted to other areas for better use .
Some may argue that limited public spending may not be ideal .
In the event that the government 's expenditure on the aged is restricted while the number of elderly is surging , the needs of the elderly may not be completely attended to .
This is because since the aged 's basic needs are not attended to , they have to work in order to fulfill them .
Hence , since the workforce is the main sector that drives the economy , an ageing workforce which is inefficient will slow down economic growth and hinder the country 's progress .
Currently , many governments have implemented measures which enforce compulsory savings for old age , such as the Singapore government which implementa Medisave .
Hence , even though public expenditures on the aged were to be limited , people still have savings which , when combined with government aid , are more than sufficient to meet their needs .
However , apart from coping with the latter , countries must not neglect other parts of development which are crucial to these countries as well .
Therefore , it is advisable for public expenditure on the aged to be limited so that no other sectors are sacrificed .
The number of aging people , also known as the gray population , is increasing rapidly nowadays .
A growing gray population means more things to be sacrificed sacrificed-- one of them is public money that is spent to fund the aged , usually known as public spending for the aged .
In Indonesia , the budget does not specify whether the government can spend much money on them without any limitation .
We can see it from evidence that is present , such as the currency of Indonesian rupiah which is very weak compared to other currencies .
Therefore , we can say that limitation on spending for the aged is a good idea since in Indonesia , there are still many areas that are not well developed yet , especially in the economic area .
Public spending on the aged covers many aspects of their life , starting from healthcare to their accommodation .
The fact is that according to Asian culture , they still have a family who should support them for those kinds of things and the government does not need to spend much money on them
There are also many old folks ' homes in Indonesia which have permanent benefactors
The government also should make a clear policy regarding public spending on the aged which states how much money or what is the percentage from public income that should be spent to support the aged .
It is still very sensitive to any changes , whether it is from Indonesia itself or from the world .
There are many weaknesses in Indonesia 's economy , such as the climate of investment which is still unstable .
We can infer that from big uncertainties in many obligations .
Besides that , there are many problems that make Indonesia 's economy not competitive . They are laboring problems and other structural problems such as corruption , which is still rampant .
Indonesia 's government finds it hard to fight corruption since it has been in Indonesians ' mentality from a long time ago .
Nepotism is also a big problem in Indonesia and this is also very tough to fight .
In the banking sector , we also can see many weaknesses , e.g .
the lack of manpower , in which the Bank of Indonesia keeps fixing .
From the examples I have given , we can say that there are so many areas in Indonesia 's economy that needs fixing
Thirdly , limitation on public spending for the aged is not as bad as it seems .
Then , the government uses the rest of the Nett National Product to improve Indonesia 's economy .
After one year , due to economic improvement , Indonesia 's Nett National Product rose to 20 billion per month .
This example shows that spending on the aged will be raised together with the raising of Nett National Product which is earned from the improvement of the economic sector in Indonesia .
To sum up , the government of Indonesia should limit its spending on the aged and improve other areas of the country , especially the economic area .
In fact , limitation on it does not always mean a bad effect .
We can use percentage system for the policy on it which means that the amount of spending for the aged will rise together with the improvement of the economic sector .
In the case of Australia , government spending on health rose by $ 6.1 billion or $ 267 per person from 2003 to 2004 .
Increased health care spending results in a smaller ratio of the government 's spending on other areas like infrastructure and defence leading to economic impacts .
Public spending may not be appealing because there are no advantages and immediate benefits received from spending on the aged as compared to using these resources to invest in the economy , defence or infrastructure .
Individuals do not see the benefit in investing in an aged population as they tend to associate it with having a high opportunity cost .
However , it may not be true because the repercussion of not spending on the aged will be even greater in the long run .
If we were to deprive our aged population of the basic amenities and equipment , what kind of image of the country does it portray to its foreign investors and even its own countrymen ?
Her own countrymen might feel that they are not able to depend on the government for help and support in their golden age . Hence , this may lead to the possibility of an outflow of her people .
To some individuals , the aged are outdated and relatively less productive as compared to the younger generation because they are not as well aware of the latest technological advancements nor as agile as the young .
Individuals do not see the value in retaining these older workers in the workforce .
In the case of Singapore , her government is cognizant that these elder workers are assets . With effect from 1 January 1999 , the minimum retirement age has been raised from 60 to 62 years .
In addition , the government encourages active participation of the aged in the workforce by offering free training to these workers .
This will promote active ageing .
Therefore , encouraging the older workforce to go for retraining retraining will increase the productivity of these workers and hence their employability .
For many years , opponents to such plans believed that the European style of welfare states were the perfect models , where healthcare should be accessible to everyone and that care should be delivered to the aged without them having to pay for it .
They argue that the aged needs the best possible care in their sunset years .
Stanford Center on Longevity ( 2008 ) . But , the global upward trend in growing elderly population and a shrinking younger workforce coupled with low birthrates has turned against such a model .
Furthermore , excessive spending on the aged can hinder a country 's growth , which demands equal attention .
Firstly , advocates of limiting public spending on the aged argue that optimal and prudent spending is the solution so that it is able to sustain the current and future aged .
For instance , the United States ihas currently the largest spending on healthcare as per percentage of Gross Domestic Product ( GDP ) .
California Healthcare Foundation ( 2008 ) Yet , there is little evidence that the American system is superior .
In comparison , many nations are achieving higher life expectancy rates with significantly lower public spending .
If the public spending on the aged is not brought under control , the government will have to raise taxes to sustain its coffers which can irk its citizens and result in exodus of businesses if labor costs increase .
Secondly , for a country to prosper , it has to invest on its youths through education , which will boost literacy .
Illiteracy often limits the economical growth of a nation where knowledge intensive industries are highly valued .
Thirdly , national defence is vital for a country 's security and ability to defend itself against potential aggressors .
In terms of internal threats , defence spending can boost a country 's resources in time to deal with natural disasters while external threats can be in the form of the need to protect the freedom of the country .
This makes defence spending equally important in the context of eeconomic progress .
The government 's coffer is not a ceaseless goldmine and if public spending for the aged is not brought under control , it will eventually run out , which in turn will affect future generations when they become the aged .
There has always been on-going research , development or policies to help the easing of the process of aging .
There are three reasons which will be elaborated in the following paragraphs .
Firstly , mobility for the elderly has been improved .
This code contains restrictions and regulations which engineers and architects have to comply with make the built environment accessible-friendly for the elderly .
For example , the authority ensures the installation of lifts at every storey of Housing Development Board ( HDB ) flats and Mass Rapid Transportation ( MRT ) stations , as well as ramps at all entrances of buildings .
They had commented on one shortcoming that there are still a large number of buildings which are still not fully-accessible .
With regard to this , the BCA has already stepped introduced the plan by applying another 5-year plan , known as the Barrier-Free Accessibility ( BFA ) Upgrading Program ( 2007-2011 ) to make sure that all buildings will be equipped with barrier-free improvements .
Furthermore , BCA has also set-up a $ 40 million Accessibility Fund for private buildings to be transformed into barrier-free buildings .
In addition , lifts and ramps are currently being built at older MRT stations such as Queenstown MRT station to help the elderly to travel from ground level to ticket gantries more easily .
The news articles have also been reportedly quoting that the government hopes to reduce the impacts of an aging population by extending working lives .
This program will enable the elderly to upscale their skills so that they can be retained in employment by their employers ( Singapore Workforce Development Agency , 2009 ) .
Another initiative is the Lifelong Income For the Elderly under the Central Provident Funds Scheme ( CFP LIFE ) , whereby there is a fixed amount of income for an elderly who is aged 65 years and above .
This will then ensure financial protection for the elderly when they reach the age ( Prime Minister 's Office , 2009 ) .
However , people often question the effectiveness of these initiatives .
They may have doubts whether the fund is enough to enable a high percentage of elderly to work longer or can the companies cope with re-employment of older workers ?
With regard to this , the Prime Minister of Singapore , Mr. Lee Hsien Loong , had has reassured the public that the government will continue to revise the initiatives to make sure that the elderly can work longer with ease .
With regard to the ability of the companies to cope with re-employment of older workers , the government has introduced another program know as the ADVANTAGE !
Scheme Scheme , which offers grants up to $ 400,000 to companies who are interested to re- employ older workers ( NTUC NeXus , 2006 ) .
As such , with these initiatives , the public should rest assured that the minimum of initiatives will be carried out to guarantee that the elderly can extend their working lives with least problems .
This will appeal to people who do not like the signs of aging to be displayed on their body .
Thus , there are increasing numbers of people who are resorting to these procedures as they rebut that they can age with more grace by doing so .
On the other hand , people criticized the negative impacts of such procedures and the attitude of people who engaged in such procedures .
They emphasize the side effects such as the addiction to Botox injections and they often think otherwise of the attitude of this group of elderly .
However , as a matter of fact , any medical procedures will carry a certain number of risks .
Therefore it is up to the weighing of risk the individual wants to take .
It should be left to the individuals to decide whether they want to take such risks
This is actually up to how the individual want to age and their way of dealing with the process of aging .
This is as long as they have fully considered the negative impacts of such procedures and agreed to accept them without condition .
As an outsider , we should keep an objective outlook on this issue and not impede them from what they deem is the best for themselves .
We should only focus on the stand that these medical innovations do help those who want to age in the way they define themselves .
Despite the fact that we do not know the exact measurements of how well these developments have helped the elderly , it is clear these developments are done to make sure our aging population can be well taken care of .
Furthermore , the most important thing here is that we can help everyone to age with ease , grace and happiness so that there will be less aging issues to be addressed .
Further emphasis by governments with regard to public architecture has also made aging easier .
This could not have been timelier . A study done by the United Nations in 2000 states that by 2010 , all developed countries would have an increase in percentage of senior citizens as a whole .
This can be attributed to greater awareness by technological companies of the needs of an elderly individual , thus attributing greater emphasis to this field of research .
Previously , a person in a wheelchair would require another for assistance .
However , over the past decade , improvements in the electronic wheelchair have made it significantly lighter and the battery is able to last longer .
As the field of medicine rapidly progresses , many illnesses and ailments previously difficult to treat treat have now been reduced to mere inconveniences .
On the treatment front , improvements in pin-hole surgery have greatly minimized the trauma to the patient , leading to shorted recovery time .
With such leaps in the field of medicine , health problems associated with aging no longer are such big issues as before , allowing people to have greater quality of life in their twilight years .
Social policies , especially with regard to the country 's architecture , implemented by the government will have significant effects on the respective country 's aging population .
Rather , they taper the ends of the walkways into slopes with a non-slip coating on them .
This is an example of how social policies with regard to architecture can make life easier for the elderly .
Expenditure on health , education , infrastructure , industrial and social amenities are examples of government public spending .
Today , the government emphasizes more on the aged and spends a large sum of money to assist them .
The government should increase education spending in order to nurture people to create a brighter future for the society .
Dr Bill Harrison stated that education is the key to a better future for our children .
Children who are well-educated will have more opportunity to contribute to society .
Besides that , professionals should be given more incentives to further their studies .
The government should raise the salary for professionals as a way to motivate them .
Moreover , reconsidering the education cost can initially give the poor some opportunity to have education in rural areas . Thus , this will definitely benefit society .
According to Wikipedia , statistic shows that 19.6 % from the resident non-students aged 15 years and above had no qualification in education in the year 2000 .
Furthermore , infrastructure development requires a higher percentage of spending compared to spending on the aged because infrastructure plays an important role in ameliorating the standard of living of a country .
Singapore transportation consists of Mass Rapid Transit ( MRT ) , Singapore Changi Airport and others .
The government should spend more on transportation by providing more facilities for the disabled and poor .
More recycle bins or " Saving the Earth " events should be carried out by the government .
Furthermore , renewable energy usage such as solar energy , wind energy and water energy should be used more frequently in order to reduce the usage of nonrenewable resources .
Hence , the government should pay more attention to saving natural resources .
Another significant area is industrialization .
Industrialization can be a core concern of a country as it is the second largest sector in most countries .
Wikipedia claims that intensive farming is an { agricultural } [ HYPERLINK : http : //en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agricultural ] production system characterized by the high { inputs } [ HYPERLINK : http : //en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Input ] of { capital } [ HYPERLINK : http : //en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_ ( economics ) ] ,labor , or heavy usage of technologies such as { pesticides } [ HYPERLINK : http : //en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pesticides ] and pesticides { fertilizers } [ HYPERLINK : http : //en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fertilizers ] relative to land area .
Moreover , the manufacturing industry also needs attention from the government since manufacturing is satisfying the citizens .
Manufacturing factories create many products and sells them to consumers according to their demand in the market .
In addition , the construction industry is momentous as it will determine how a country will be developed .
As we can see today , there is construction everywhere in Singapore and this proves that Singapore is advancing at a quick pace .
Singapore 's building and construction industry account for about 4 % ofgross domestic product and S $ 27 and S $ 32 billion construction demand estimated for the sector in 2008 , according to John Keung , CEO of the Building and Construction Authority ( BCA ) of Singapore .
However , each sector should have priority depending on its level of importance .
The government should think wisely and choose the sector which has more privileges .
Therefore , The government should not focus too much of their spending on the aged .
For example , in Singapore , the Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports , often works closely with voluntary welfare organisations to provide community-based programmes and residential care for the aged .
Britain introduced a compulsory pension scheme in 2006 where the employees have to contribute 4 percent of their monthly pay while their employers have to contribute 3 percent .
From a recent article from The Straits Times , some " Singaporeans were using the recession as an excuse to avoid paying their parents ' nursing home bills " , even though some looked like they could very well afford it ( Reference needed )
Governments should therefore set aside more funds to support the aged and provide more facilities for them .
This is however , only a short-term solution to the problem of an ageing population .
When talking about the most striking features of aging we can not forget the progress of science and its effects on almost every aspect of human life .
In my opinion , the contribution of current research and technology is very important in easing the aging process .
For some people , science brings more harm than good .
The rapid tempo of modern life also results in wide spread nervous disorders .
Moreover , our machine civilization is also responsible for numerous accidents and serious injuries for many people , which cause a lot of difficulties in their old age .
The human aging process has accelerated in recent years .
With advancements in healthcare service and medicine , along with a better understanding of the aging process , life expectancy for humans has kept increasing .
The unceasing experiments and research have led to numerous discoveries which explain the reasons for aging as well as the ways of slowing down this process and the key factors to keep the gray hair away .
For example , a healthy diet with enough vitamins , minerals and other necessary nutrition , together with regular exercise and a healthy lifestyle will help humans live longer and maintain their prime of youth .
Moreover , the appearance of many technology appliances like computers , machines and transportation means also increase productivity and lessen workload , which create more time to relax and enjoy life .
Old age always comes up with many unpleasant problems and diseases , both physical and mental .
In most of cases , scientists discovered medicine and the cure as soon as they discovered the causes of certain diseases .
In addition to that , the work of medical scientists also reduced pain to a great extent .
In the past , operations were performed on individuals in a very crude manner .
Today , however , many surgical operations can be done with a small incision and without any pain by application of endoscopic technology .
Furthermore , the support of many convenient devices also provides the old a better preparation to face old age .
As we can see , wheelchairs , audiphones , glasses... have contributed a lot towards assisting the old people in their life .
Together with these , the installation of lifts , user friendly machines and free barrier transportation systems everywhere are also the key for senior residents ' access to a better life .
Moreover , the electrical devices in our daily life these days such as computers , televisions , washing machines... also make life more convenient , pleasant and comfortable for the aged .
They not only save their manual labour but more importantly , make friends and are entertained
From all of these above arguments , we can conclude that government can use science and technology as an effective way to ease the aging process .
This is a good solution to cope with the increasing aging population , one of the current difficult global problems .
It not only helps slow down the aging process but also facilitates acceptance of old age .
Again , , we must thank science for giving us a better life .
Public spending on the aged is the expenditure by the government covering health , infrastructure and projects aimed at improving the lives of the elderly .
The other areas of a country 's development include investing in education , military , economy and infrastructure .
Funding for the aged is necessary as there is a growing trend in the ageing population but more importantly resources should be allocated away from just the aged itself to other aspects of the country 's development that will indirectly aid the ageing population .
