Aging population has become the topic for a lot of discussion .
This essay also wants to argue that public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development because there are strategies that government can supplement to reduce that burden , and the money invested in other areas could be a big support to society .
First of all , do the aged as a real " social problem " ?
The aged will not be viewed as a " social problem " once it is believed that most of the aged are independent .
However , as in the recession period , old people have difficulty in supporting their own living expenses , which results in social spending for the aged .
Thus , people often claim that age dependency has become an actual crisis of the society , and government has taken action to decrease their social welfare expenditure during period of fiscal constraint .
) , there are basic strategies , which policy makers and governments can consider implementing to lessen the burdens of older generations to the younger .
These strategies prove that instead of spending much money on supporting the aged , the government can seek for another alternatives to reduce the burden .
The most considerable strategy is that stressing filial obligation and increasing the willingness of tomorrow 's grown children to support their own elderly parents through informal and family channelno full-stop
full-stop after the parenthesis Originating from Asian cultures , family obligation is the most precious thing , which characterizes the parents-children relationship .
That is a good classification of labour in the society that take good advantage of the scarce labor force .
Moreover , by doing so , the elderly can earn for their living , have a savings for future need on health care , and have less dependency on their younger generation .
Although it is a controversial issue to talk about aging population and its burden to the society , this essay indicates alternatives the government can do besides spending too much on the aged to adapt to the challenge for the future , which is " to ensure that people everywhere will be enabled to age with security and dignity and continue to participate in their societies as citizens with full rights " .
Fortunately , the good news is that to a large extent , current research and development ( R&D ) , and government policies have taken action to help ease the aging process .
Opponents may say current clinical R&D causes an increase in longevity , which substantially raises the average age of the population .
Clinical R&D continuously introduce people to healthier living styles , bring in more efficacious , safer and cheaper medical treatments , which allows people to look young and stay healthy so that they are still able to work actively in middle or even old age .
To cope with it , the government has made and implemented several policies like building colleges of continuing education for the aged .
By controlling the size of population , the one-child policy indirectly shifts the governmental funds from the young to the elderly , so that the government has more flexible budget to help the elderly .
In this manner , the one-child policy helps to ease the aging process as well .
Issues such as high elderly dependency ratio , shrinking workforce and increasing healthcare problems , which resulted from an aging population , are apparent in many countries .
However , they are also aware that devising a policy to eliminate this trend is close to impossible in the short run as the two main sources of the aging problem --- higher live expectancy and lower birth rate ( United Nation , 2002 ) --- are unable to be affected by any policy .
Fortunately , much can be done as current research and development/policies have shown hope of easing the aging process by dealing with the consequences directly , instead of the sources .
The growth of the elderly dependency ratio signifies a state where an escalating numbers of beneficiaries of health and pension funds are sustained by a relatively smaller number of contributors ( United Nation , 2002 ) .
By requiring citizens to provide in advance for their own old-age dependency , policy makers were able to ease the above mentioned situation .
Some countries such as Australia , Britain , Chile and Singapore have gained much through encouraging their citizens and establishing means of law to convince citizens to save and invest a portion of their income earned , while they are still in the workforce ( Peterson , 2001 ) .
Unfortunately , a fraction of citizens still feels that the government should not intervene with the way they spend or save their income .
Furthermore , not many individuals have the discipline to maintain a healthy bank balance given the materialistic world of today .
Thus , compulsory saving can help guarantee a sizable amount of saving for their future and is a practical and effective way to ensure old age dependency is being kept to the minimum .
A shrinking workforce is another problem arising from an aging population .
The human resources of many developed countries are predicted to shrink as a hefty portion of the workforce is edging towards retirement .
The resulting situation is an increased amount of stress falling onto the shoulders of the remaining working adults as they struggled to provide for their older counterpart .
The solution inevitably invited criticism as many found themselves being victims of ageism , a situation where younger workers are preferred over retaining or hiring the older ones .
However , the situation is improving for some countries such as Singapore .
This gives much hope to the elderly as they are still employable and the problem of dependency on the shrinking workforce can be lessened .
Another major issue caused by the aging population is the increasing healthcare problem associated with the elderly .
Governments all around the world has to make provision for improved healthcare as the live expectancies of their citizens and medical technologies are improving by the years .
Adding on to the misery , the cost associated with healthcare is also growing with the combined effect of a rising standard of living and the high cost of advanced medical development .
Such a policy can give security to the elderly if they find themselves trapped in the high cost of healthcare .
It is a world-wide phenomenon that has no quick-fix solution and it is quite clear that every country will eventually reach the same stage as societies continue to develop .
Clearly , many problems associating with aging still persist and will be apparent in developing societies . But with the help of current research and developmentand policies , many socio economical problems can be avoided or minimized .
In fact , leaders and policymakers , particularly from the developed countries have proactively implemented a series of researches and policies in an effort to confront this unprecedented phenomenon .
Aging-related problem is no longer an imminent issue that concerns a particular region but is disquieted and discussed in every country all over the world .
For instance , Germany is currently facing an acute problem of aging in Europe and this prompted the government to generate flexible jobs for the elderly and discourage early retirement by cutting the pension entitlement by 3.6 percent for each year spent in retirement before the age of 65 .
In a nutshell , current development on policy reforms and researches has been carried out simultaneously over the past decades to help cope with both societal and physical impact of the aging issue .
Healthcare issue has to be taken into consideration because the elderly are prone to suffer from chronic diseases as they grow older .
For example , since the mid 90 's , the common usage of wire mesh stents for treatment of artery blockages are partly .
In addition , increased spending on new medical technologies may restrict society 's ability to expand healthcare coverage to more elderly people .
Nonetheless , if the spending on healthcare is limited , the burden will fall increasingly on low-income individuals as well as their families .
The elderly are encouraged to work longer and contribute to the growth of economy , thereby reducing elder dependency of fiscal cost .
Later retirement not only secures a better pension entitlement for the future , but also provide a direct mean of allowing people to supplement their income in later life ; and thus helping them to maintain their standard of living during retirement .
However , older workers are usually less productive than imported foreign talents , though employers may compromise on a small portion of existing aged employees .
If employers have the flexibility to hire older employees on a part-time basis , , they will be much less reluctant to hire and retain older workers .
Alternatively , the government should encourage employment of the elderly by offering privileges and incentives to private sectors .
On top of that , policies that create economic security for the elderly and remove barriers faced by them should always be a priority in .
Governments and policymakers have largely undertaken to build a basic , nationwide infrastructure which .
Current development in communities has created convenience to meet the needs of the elderly , such as barrier-free facilities , security systems , housing , transportation , and so on .
These physical community 's assets help to provide elderly a good quality of life and in the long run .
, governments aim to get all the elderly in communities fully engaged in social activities and involved in lifelong learning .
Yet , some elderly are still facing the problem of being left out or discriminated because of their old age .
Societies are responsible for upholding values such as filial piety , to encourage people to look after their elderly parents. .
In other words , it is the responsibility of the public to protect elderly rights .
.
In order to ease the current predicament , governments have to emphasize on the distribution of their budgets or reallocate funds to reduce the cost of public spending .
On the other hand , it is plausible to reward families for having children and encourage more young people to work .
The future elderly will be more professional and better educated than the current cohorts in many countries .
Thus , decision-makers must carry on fashioning programs to further ease the aging process without getting them locked into policies and approaches that may not be suitable for the changing composition of tomorrow 's elderly .
Nowadays almost every developed country is concerned about the issue of a growing aging population because this issue is a barrier for a country 's development .
Aging population is the result of an increase in the life expectancy rate over several centuries and the trend continues to increase because of advancements in medication .
According to the report of United Nations Population Division : " Worldwide , there are currently more than 600million people over age 60 .
However , from mid-1971 to mid-2006 , those aged under 16 fell from 26 % to 19 % . This is the result of effective family planning programs throughout these decades .
There is a decrease in the ratio of working people to those over age 65 . Therefore , governments are reviewing their budget plans and developing policies in order to overcome with these crucial challenges .
But this does not mean that to overcome these challenges , excessive spending should be done by the government .
As it takes years for the country to overcome this problem , spending on the aged should be limited .
So , there should be limited public spending on the aged group so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country , which will give better returns in near future .
Public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas , such as education , which is far more important than the aging issue in today 's world .
Government should be more focused on education than spending on the aged as spending more in education will probably increase the living standard and the of a country .
Indeed no country can move forward without education .
Due to the aging population , there is a shrinking workforce ; and so the government should spend more on education , so that it will increase the productivity of the workforce .
So , governments should review their budgets according to the amount spent on education .
Spending on education will give better returns to a country in near future because education is a major factor for the country 's economic growth , whereas spending on the aged is just the opposite . Spending on the aged is inversely proportional to economic growth .
For a country , spending on education is seen as injecting money into an economy , whereas spending on the aged is considered as introducing a leakage into the economy .
So for the country 's development , there should be more injections than leakages .
In a country , money should be diverted to other areas like defense and infrastructure ; and thus , public spending on the aged should be limited in order to get better returns .
A country 's opportunity cost for spending in defense and infrastructure is probably more than the spending on the aged because spending in infrastructure generates revenue for a country , such as attracting foreign investments and tourism . Spending on defense gives a sense of security to a nation , whereas spending on the aged is just an expenditure for a country ; and for a country to pay its expenditures it should have sufficient amount of revenues .
Spending on infrastructure and defense will enhance the country 's economic growth , the living standards of the people and the overall the image of a country .
Though spending on the aged could also improves the living standard and the image of a country , it would be less effective , as compared to the spending in infrastructure and defense .
It is less effective because the benefits do not exceed the cost .
Therefore spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be spend on other areas of the country 's development .
.
Since the past several decades , there has been an increase in the life expectancy rate . This has probably caused the aging problem , and so there should be sufficient increase in the spending on the aged . This will eventually improve the living standard of the aged and thus contribute to the country 's development .
There should be an increase in public spending on the aged because of consistent increase in inflation rate throughout the past several years .
should not be limited or fixed but should be proportionate to the increase in inflation and life expectancy rate .
On the other hand , the increase in public spending may cause dependency , which means that the aged will then totally rely on the workforce and the government for their needs and thus would be exploiting the economy rather than contributing to it .
Overall , it depends on the country 's situation and the budget to determine whether it should limit its spending on aged .
For a country to develop , it has to overcome with these crucial challenges of aging population , and therefore an appropriate strategy would be needed . This could be to spend more on education and infrastructure which will generate sufficient revenue in the future and then it can be spent on the aged .
There should be limited spending on the aged so by that the aged population will work to fulfill their needs . This will strengthen the workforce of the country , and so by limiting spending on the aged one will be able to contribute to the country 's development .
