In Singapore , the Central Provident Fund Board ( CPF Board ) is a saving scheme that covers working Singaporeans with a list of welfare benefits and offers a sense of security for their old age .
Also , the CPF Board reminds Singaporeans to save and stretch every dollar whenever possible so as to have comfortable lives after retirement in the future .
From the highlights of Channel NewsAsia [ 2009 ] , there are many countries with a .
In view of this demographic , countries like Japan and Singapore have been establishing ways to curb the aging population .
In Japan , the government has a policy of offering incentives to families with small children so as to increase birth rates and build up a new family .
In Singapore , there is the reemployment legislation in 2012 where employers are advised to retain the elderly as the demand for their skills are needed .
In the meantime , Singaporeans are told to save early with the easy access of financial schemes and saving programs offered .
In addition , the technological invention segment has played a part in easing the aging process .
As Schoeni , Freedman and Martin suggests , the R&D segment has been expanding rapidly .
With the the advancement of medical technologies , illnesses such as cardiovascular and cataract diseases have lesser occurrence .
Countries like the United States and Singapore are insured with Medicare and Medishield respectively .
We are insured despite the high medical expenses of new inventions in the medical fields .
, an advance health security cycle as we reach our retirement age .
Moreover , with the growing number of well-educated people around , there is a high probability that people will purchase private insurance to care for their own well-being .
