Since early days and especially in Asia , longevity has always been believed as a blessing. .
Chinese emperors even sent people , , to search for the elixir of life that was believed to make anyone who drinks it live eternally .
Fast aging population has taken the spotlight for world crisis and many governments are increasing their spending on this group as the aging population keeps increasing .
For example , in 2008 , the Singapore Government introduced a new incentive called LIFE Bonus and provided tax relief for Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) members ( Central Provident Fund Board , 2008 ) .
A greater portion of the national budget may later be allocated to the incentives for the old .
However , the increase of public spending on the elderly may not be effective as it can be diverted to other sectors that need it .
With the increase of public spending on the aged , there will be many areas that may be left out if the government focused only on the welfare of the aging population .
The economy may need immediate attention with its current situation and the education sector may need improvement .
Allocating the national budget to may result in an increase in GDP as it will benefit the nation 's economy and industry .
An increase in GDP also means that .
In the end , this strategy may improve the nation 's economy and education quality , as well as increase the amount of public spending for the aged .
It is like killing two birds with one stone because two sectors are improved by allocating funds into just one .
First , even with the rapid increase of aging population , the economy urgently needs government attention as the global economy is in recession for the past few year , many industries are closing down and companies are going into a slump .
As a result , Singapore 's GDP fell by 11.5 % due to the recession in the first quarter ( Reuters , 2009 ) .
In this perspective , developed countries that took the most blows from the recession should allocate their budget better to stabilize their economies , pull back old investors and attract new ones .
If the plan goes well , it may stabilize or even increase GDP which will in turn provide more funds for the elderly .
Secondly , the younger generation also plays an important part in the future of a country by determining its future birth rates .
Past studies ( Chan , 2001 ) showed that Singapore 's population growth is minimal and had even reached 0 % in 1986 due to past government policies on birth control and high education cost .
Now , the Singapore government is trying to raise the population growth by giving out incentives through the Children Development Account ( CDA ) and building cheap and easily accessible child care centre for working parents .
Since the cost of living in Singapore has been so high that it is called the 10th most expensive city in the world ( Hoe , 2009 ) , the government may consider increasing the number of incentives . Therefore , the government may increase the total number of people in the workforce and reduce the percentage of total aging population .
.
Education is important as it shapes future leaders for the nation .
improving the quality of education means increasing the quality of future 's work force and this should boost the nation 's growth in every sector .
Education also plays a large role in shaping the students ' characters and morals , and this may help to stop them from neglecting their elderly parents when they become adults .
Providing a and affordable education should also be in the government 's consideration when allocating budgets .
Others may argue that indirect support for the elderly is not sufficient at this time when the aging population in Singapore is predicted to increase from 235,000 in 1999 to 796,000 in 2030 ( Chan , 2001 ) .
However , it is not absolutely true as there is the CPF policy that the government has created to make the elderly support themselves .
When they are still working , some of their income will be put into savings .
The institution of which they work at will also contribute a percentage of funds to the savings .
Experts agree that the CPF is effective in providing the aging population support for their old age as the CPF has also been strategically segmented for health insurance and retirement funds . One study has even remarked that the CPF is changing the concept of social security : from providing savings for retirement to providing savings for life ( Choon and Low , 1996 ) .
Welfare cost for the aged will increase indefinitely as the aging population increases . So , if the government did not limit public spending for the aged , it may eventually take a much larger portion of the national budget .
There are also other areas that urgently need the government 's attention as well and some of these can help increase the government 's fund which will in turn also increase public spending .
Many things can be done to alleviate the problem , but the government will need to think of the next step as the aging population problem continues to grow .
D. Harman ( 1981 ) defines the aging process as progressive changes in terms of the social , psychological and physical characteristics in a person over time . These changes are linked with increasing vulnerability to death or disease. .
Today , most Asian countries like Japan and Singapore are experiencing " population aging " , as defined to be an increase in the number of oldsters in the society ( Wikipedia ) .
This essay refers " oldsters " as people who are 55 years old and above .
The aging population has many problems such as over-dependency on the younger generation , as well as the increase in national budget on health care .
Besides that , Teo et al ( 2004 ) suggested that another problem is gerontological issues , such as the responses of society towards them .
These problems are significantly critical and they attract the attention of governments and policy makers .
Therefore , current developments , researches and policies are implemented to ease the aging process , and they are highly effective .
By increasing the age , the oldsters who are below the retirement age of 62 , are able to enjoy under the retirement age act .
It is stated in the act that says " employee who is unfairly dismissed can sue the employer under the common law and write to Ministry of Manpower ( MOM ) within a month to reinstate his job .
" ( EnterpriseOne , 2006 ) Most importantly , the oldsters are able to earn their own monthly living expenses , which will reduce the burden on their children .
In addition , encourages the oldsters to be more active and to contribute to the society .
Some oldsters are experienced in their fields of work .
Thus , they contribute to society by staying at their work place to teach the younger generations their skills .
However , the jobs offered to the oldsters are very limited and they are not able to take up any jobs due to their low educational level and lack of capabilities .
Due to the government 's policy of bringing in foreign talents , the job vacancies for the elderly are limited as the foreigners may have occupied most of them .
The Singapore government has made contribution of salary to the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) as a regulation compelled by law , and this helps in easing the aging process .
The contribution rate from employee and employer reduces as the age of employee increases while the crediting to Medisave account increases
( CPF , 1955 ) . The rates are increased because the elderly are more prone to illnesses . .
This scheme allows the oldsters to be more independent as they have their own savings , particularly savings for their medical bills , and helps in reducing the national budget on healthcare .
It helps the elderly , and also encourages the youngsters to plan financially for their old age . This eases the aging process very effectively .
However , it is only effective when the individual starts working at a younger age. .
The Workfare scheme has been implemented recently to cater to the aging process , especially for the elderly who are less educated and this results in their low income status .
It is also known as the Workfare Income Suppplement Scheme
( CPF , 1955 ) . This scheme is specially implemented for middle and old age people .
In addition , it promotes the concept of active lifestyle for the elderly by involving them in the workforce .
This scheme might solve the gerontological issue . If the oldsters are working , the youngsters would not view them as useless people as they are contributing to the society as well as economically to the country .
On the other hand , this scheme is not in easing the aging process because the net payout ( cash ) is low .
Since it is a complement to the CPF contribution scheme , there is an obligation to contribute about 71 percent of the total workfare payout to CPF
( CPF , 1955 ) . Particularly , this scheme is only applicable to those who have worked for 3 months and above .
in addition , the payout is only carried out once in every 6 months .
Hence , the net payout is relatively useless due to the high living expenses in Singapore .
In conclusion , the Singapore government has implemented policies and development that are relatively effective in easing the aging process .
However , there are still some areas that required their attention such as the 2 sub-groups , namely the older single women and the elderly who have never saved during their younger days .
In terms of all the policies and developments mentioned above , especially the workfare scheme , the government should increase the net payout amount ( cash ) and reduce the percentage contributing to the CPF .
As for the increasing retirement age , the government should encourage more voluntary organizations
For the CPF contribution , the government might set up a regulation that requires individuals who reach a certain age to start working and contributing to their CPF . This policy might come in handy in future .
In many developed countries , the aging population is rising and Singapore is no exception .
The first batch of baby boomers ( babies who are born between 1947 and 1964 ) will reach the age of 65 in the year 2012 ( Committee of Aging , 2006 ) .
By 2030 , the number of elderly will reach 18.7 % , which means for every 5 residents , there will be a senior among them ( Singapore Department of Statistics , 2005 ) .
Thus , by increasing the retirement age , people are able to work longer and in return , they are able to accumulate more wealth , which will enable them to be more independent financially .
In addition , elderly people who have acquired the essential skills , knowledge and experience in their respective work fields will be able to continue working and impart their skills to the new working generation . The elderly will be able to share their valuable experience with them so that they will not follow the mistake that the seniors have made during their working lives .
This is not true as countries like Japan and the US are now encouraging elderly entrepreneurs and that will eventually create more jobs for them .
The aging of Singapore population is also due to the fertility decline in the beginning of 1970s when the government had come out with policies to discourage people from having more children .
This campaign proved to be so successful that resulted in a 0 % growth in population by 1986 .
However , the government soon realized that the Singapore population was not reproducing itself and so it reversed its population planning policy by introducing the " Baby Scheme " to encourage a higher birth rate .
Under the " Baby Scheme " , couples will be given cash gifts for their first child and up to their fourth child .
For the second till the fourth child who are born after 17 August 2008 , a Child Development Account ( CDA ) will be opened for the family to enjoy government contributions . The government will match the savings of every child dollar-for-dollar , up to the age of six years old .
This serves to help couples to lighten their financial burden for raising their children .
As the financial cost of raising children is one of the important factor for couple to decide whether they want to have children , birth rate may increase if the financial cost was reduced. .
If the fertility rate continues to drop , there will not be enough young people to replace the older generation .
This will lead to the shrinking of workforce , which will affect the economic growth of Singapore .
In the recent years , Singapore health care institutions have tried to improve their existing methods and introduce innovative applications into the healthcare system .
There are technologies to enable the elderly to look younger .
This will enhance their self esteem , and thus they will be able to participate more actively in social activities and they will not feel left out .
In addition , a better health care system will allow the people to stay healthier and prevent some major illnesses such as stroke and heart attack .
The elderly need not worry too much about their health . But , what they have to do as a personal responsibility is to go for regular check-ups and have a healthy diet .
It has to be tackled through a holistic approach which needs the involvement of the government , community agencies and private sectors .
Many policies have been implemented and research and development have been improved in the last several , though more remained to be done .
With all the efforts put in by the public , the government and the people , Singapore will continue to strive for the status of being a .
" ( Buck , 1999 ) . In Singapore , the focus on ageing issues is not new .
Since the 1980s , the government has taken an active role in caring for its helpless members
( Ministry of Communication Development , Youth and Sports [ MYCS ] , 2001 ) . Policies were introduced , implemented and refined with the goal of minimizing the impact of problems associated with an ageing population .
This essay argues that by and large , the government 's recent efforts in research and intervention have not been useful in alleviating the problems of old age in Singapore .
Firstly , current government policies are not easing the ageing process because they are limited to a specified group of the aged population .
The current policies in place are definitely planned to benefit a large portion of the target group .
However , it must be recognized that these polices have their limitations and they have left out a significant portion of the aged in the lurch .
For example , the Central Provident Fund Scheme ( CPF ) is only applicable and beneficial to the sector of people who had , or are having employment
( Ministry of Manpower [ MOM ] , 2007 ) . The CPF scheme is broken down into three portions , namely the Ordinary account , the Special account and the Medisave account
( MOM , 2007 ) . Thus , people who do not have any employment will not have any money for their retirement and healthcare .
Also , the Parents Maintenance Act is only relevant to the elderly who have children
( Attorney-General 's Chamber of Singapore [ ACG ] , 1996 ) . As a result , those without children will fall outside this umbrella .
For example , the government could topup the Medisave accounts of the less fortunate elder Singaporeans when there are budgetary surpluses to ensure that seniors have the capacity to afford healthcare services
( MYCS , 2001 ) .
In addition , the current government policies are ineffective in the ageing process .
For example , the government has increased the retirement age to 63 years old
( MOM , 2007 ) . This move is ineffective because it does not ensure that the elderly will work till they reached the retirement age .
Also , some elderly are unable to maximize their work years due to medical problems or choice .
In Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong 's speech on the 8 January 2009 , he cited that only six out of ten men are still working by the age of 62
( Prime Minister 's Office [ PMO ] , 2009 ) . Thus , the policy has minimal effect and does not address the root problem .
In addition , the Government 's plan to ensure that all public spaces in housing estates such as parks and sporting venues have facilities that cater to the whole family including seniors ( MYCS , 2001 ) , is not practical because it has not considered the fact that the average elderly in Singapore is either not interested in sports or is unable to play sports due to chronic ailments
( Suriah , Chong , Yeoh , 2008 ) . Nevertheless , opponents might argue that the plans are effective as long as the government can reach out and educate the elders on the available policies .
However , 67 % of the elderly in Singapore is illiterate and is only proficient in non-Mandarin dialects
Hence , the government must first attempt to inform the elderly in Singapore about the available avenues and encourage them to reap the benefits of the current policies , so as to maximize the effectiveness of its policies .
The government has not developed sufficient programmes to cater to the psychological needs of the aged .
In some recent efforts , the government pumped in $ 88 million to build a mentally resilient society of which its results that can only be realized in five years
( Ministry of Health [ MOH ] , 2007 ) . In comparison , the average American considers the notion of " old " to be effective only when they reach the age of 65 years old .
However , in Singapore , the word " old " is tossed around freely in conversations of people aged above 60 , who are also known as the senior citizens of Singapore .
The reason why the Americans classify " oldness " to be above 65 years old is due to the fact that they strongly believe that they still can contribute to society after retirement and thus they continue to embark on meaningful roles .
On the other side of the coin , opponents will argue that the government can not be responsible for every aspect of the issue .
Hence , the Singapore Government should invest more in programmes to cater to the mental aspect of the elderly so that the elderly can proceed to commit themselves to important and useful roles in society after retirement .
Since the problems that tagged along with an ageing population is imminent , much more should have been done by the Singapore Government to wrestle with the difficulties associated with the ageing process .
If more effective policies are formulated and implemented , they will indirectly lower the burden imposed on the younger population and society as a whole .
In 2009 , the median age of Singaporeans was 36 years .
The predicament of an aging population plagues not only Singapore , but also different countries , ranging from the richer and developed nations , such as Japan and Italy , to the relatively poorer and developing nations like China ( , 2009 ) , especially as a result of the one-child policy .
They were the ones who had toiled in the sun to build the infrastructure during Singapore 's early developing days .
They are older single women who are uneducated and were not able to save , that the government should especially provide help for .
Moreover , inadequate policies will lead to political and social instabilities for moral and ethical issues so , by not setting a limit on public spending on the aged , it indirectly helps to sustain and even improve the social cohesiveness and development in this aspect .
Otherwise , like Friedland & Summer ( 2005 ) mentioned , cutting back on public spending on welfare programmes has an impact on local families and communities .
( , 2008 ) .
In evaluating the policies to undertake , it is necessary to consider the net impact of using public funds to deal with the aging population , as well as the consequences if the issues relating to aging population are not adequately dealt with .
Nowadays aging of population has become a global problem , especially in developed countries .
To ease the aging process , many countries ' public spending will rise steadily as a share of GDP , leaving these countries in a great financial burden ( Joumard , 2004 ) .
In this case , only focusing on public spending does not seem to be the best way to solve the aging problem .
Instead , the government should limit the public spending on the aged so that more money can be invested to other areas of the country 's development .
For those countries with aging process , the biggest problem they have to face is the number of labors who ( A Touch of Gray , 2002 ) .
Consequently , the government may not be able to provide enough pension and health care to help improve the old citizens ' life as a result of lack of finance .
Now encourages the United Kingdom to simplify the pension system and they argue that nowadays the pension system in UK may have negative effects on incentives for people to work and save ( ) .
This problem not only happens in the UK . People tend to lose motivation to work or save once they have enough pension to spend .
For example , it is reported that many older workers in US withdraw from the labor market before they reach the State pension age ( ) .
Moreover , too much pension may even lead to pension abuse which will make public spending ineffective .
Despite the above two reasons , some people still argue that the public should help the elderly as much as possible since they have once contributed to the society .
But the problem is limiting the public spending does not mean cutting off the spending .
Under such circumstances , the government should make a more effective spending scheme to solve the aging problem rather than not have any plan or restriction .
To sum up , it is necessary for the government to limit the spending on the elderly so that the economy of the country can be developed more quickly and the effectiveness of the public pensions can be increased .
Limitation does not equal to cutting off but will lead to further development and better solutions for the aging problem .
The whole world is facing the aging population problem that is the result of rising in life expectancy together with decline in fertility .
Every country has its own strategies to deal with the problem but none of them has a radical solution .
Public spending on the aged should be limited and the government should use the money to invest in the young and other areas of the countries ' development .
There are many fields that need money such as education and . In the long run the young generation should support the aged instead of the government .
Moreover , the elderly usually demand higher salary in exchange for their experience but they can not work as hard as when they were young , whereas the young lack experience and find difficulty in seeking jobs .
The aged have to work and save for their lives instead of waiting for the government . This will utilize their contribution .
Most elderly face mental problems when they retire , because they receive money from their saving plan or government and simply do not know what to do , they tend to use up all the money after several years .
Another problem is that most elderly in developed countries live alone ; they do not want to ask for money from the children , which means that they will not receive sufficient financial and mental support from their children .
The Government should stress the important role of filial obligation because it not only reduces the burden of elder dependency but also gives the elderly indirectly benefit through investing in their children .
Moreover , this will create cycles . Parents support their children and vice versa , which is better than giving out money to help the aged and at the same time giving out money to develop the young .
With advanced education , we can develop new technologies for higher productivity and lower cost , which helps the young generation fill the gap of low workforce caused by the aging population and take up the burden of caring for the aged .
The government should also invest in the infrastructures , which has the long-term effect on the development of the economics ; but we should use money wisely and not bump blindly into new projects .
The young generation is the key point to stop the aging process .
Some countries such as Germany and Netherland have successfully given a rise to birth rate . They offer financial aid and tuition grant for every child , so that parents are relieved the burden of raising children .
Admitting immigrants is also a strategy that many countries such as Singapore are applying to attract talented people ; which costs far less in comparison to training high quality workers .
There are many areas in the economy that need capital other than the aged .
Public spending on the aged should be limited . The aged may suffer but we can not spend all the money on the elderly , especially when it will not bring long-term benefits .
There are many areas in the economy that need capital other than the aged such as education , infrastructure and so on .
This poses a number of serious challenges that range from the social security of the elderly to increasing needs for health care , changing consumer behavior , and possibly changes in productivity , " says Wolfgang Lutz , leader of the World Population Program of the International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis ( IIASA ) .
" ( M. Allen , 2006 . In this modern world where decisions are made based on most available technology and rational choices , the negative impact of aging process has been eased and negated .
( ) said in a rally , " We see medical science advancing ; we see new technologies , new drugs , new procedures .
Large proportions of the elderly are unemployed and they may not be able to cope with the rising medical costs .
Hence , having so many new drugs and medicine could confuse them or these drugs have not been properly tested out yet . These result in health issues for the elderly .
In a research done by the Imperial College London ( ) , " The results showed that within a year of treatment , there was a 21 % reduction in death rates and a 64 % drop in heart failure , 39 % drop in stroke deaths and 34 % reduction in cardiovascular events .
" A lead researcher C. Bulpitt ( ) said , " Our results clearly show that many patients aged 80 and over could benefit greatly from treatment .
Hence policies can bring about a lot of good or a lot of problems .
In the case of the aging population , there are many policies up to date , such as pension system in the USA , CPF schemes in Singapore , various employment schemes , medical schemes and more .
In the USA , lawmakers led by Senator { are talking about slapping a $ 495 tax on some of those covered by the medical plan to help pay for extending coverage to some of the 46 million Americans who lack it R.J .
It is often heard that some elderly abuse the pension by gambling or turn to other vices since the money is free .
As stated in an essay in honor of J.C. Weldon , " the total utility may not be maximized because the old 'spend larger and larger sums on smaller and smaller enjoyments ' or impose 'posthumous restraint on bequeathed wealth which will make it less useful to the living '
( 1990 ) .
( ) says , " Our social security system is based primarily on individual savings and self-reliance .
The elderly would hence feel more in touch with society and likewise , the younger generation would not look upon the elderly as a burden .
Such various government polices provides the aged with economic solutions , social solutions , healthcare solutions to the problems that they may face hence easing the growing problems faced by an aging population .
" ( Children are encouraged to take care of their parents when they are old through various publicity and schemes , such as the case in Singapore , whereby people are given housing grants for choosing to stay near their parents and also providing tax relief for individuals taking care of their parents .
In conclusion , through the various available health polices , government policies , social policies and technological advancements , the elderly now are able to lead a better more comfortable and fulfilling life .
Ageing process in humans refers to a multidimensional process of physical , psychological , and social change
, 2009 ) .
In the years to come , more and more countries will be facing problems from aging process .
Hence solutions are very . This essay will evaluate the current measures undertaken by various countries .
Steen Langebaek , president of AGE , an organization which aims to promote the interest of older people across Europe , believes that older people should be encouraged to study and work beyond retirement , whether through part-time work or on a voluntary basis
( , 2002 ) .
It means the elderly are welcome to continue serving in the workforce provided they are willing themselves .
In European countries , work organization and social security arrangement are flexible in providing options for combined work with retirement .
Therefore , this measure had been very successful , especially in the Netherlands with 49 % of elderly either working full or part time
( , 2008 ) .
Also , Silver job fairs , established to find jobs for people 60 and older , have mushroomed across South Korea in the past year as part of the government 's government 's effort to assist a rapidly growing population of older Koreans adrift in a changing society
( , 2009 ) .
From the above examples in different continents , it is inevitable to conclude that elderly employment is one of the policies that has been well adopted by various governments .
Japan had started to develop robots meant for the elderly .
" With Japan 's aging population , we need robots that can alleviate the burden of human tasks , " says Toshihiko Morita , director of Fujitsu 's Autonomous System Laboratory
( , 2006 ) .
Currently , the drug that helps to reduce aging is being tested and will be released into the market soon .
" It may be the ultimate free lunch on how to reap all the advantages of a calorically restricted diet , including freedom from disease and an extended healthy life span , without eating one fewer calorie .
" ( , 2009 ) .
This useful drug will ultimately increase life span , hence increasing the productivity of the workforce as people could retire at an older age because of this drug .
Singapore has implemented the retirement pension known as the Central Provident Fund that allow elderly to fund for their retirement right from the start of their working life .
This policy has been effective as the compulsory contribution to the fund will be allocated to both medical account and general account , which does not only ensure stability but also healthcare stability .
The government could also save the budget on state pension at the same time .
In addition , the Housing Development Board of Singapore has introduced studio apartments that are catered for the elderly .
The forty square meter apartments include facilities like lifts on every floor , hand railings and alarm systems that are specially designed for the elderly .
The government has also promised to build more studio apartments in the upcoming projects .
( 2006 ) .
Overall , the governments have done well to ease the aging process to a large extent with the above policies .
In conclusion , countries have used various means to ensure a better aging process for the elderly .
This will be further improved as the country is developing in other aspects like technology , education and economy .
A large portion of the public health expenditure actually goes to the aged .
Furthermore , the negative impacts of these policies will be more significant in China as its economic base is not so strong compared to developed countries such as the U.S and Japan .
Those who oppose cutting government expenditure on elderly argue that limited spending will cause social instability as many families with low income will suffer when the elderly generation needs medical support .
For instance , Japan 's economy situation shows us the consequences of abusing of the government budget on public health spending .
Japan is well known for its ageing problems with 22.1 % of the populations above 65 ( , 2008 ) .
Therefore , for China , being a country which is much less developed than Japan , to limit the spending on the aged will be a wiser decision .
The negative impacts will be even worse in China due to its one-child policy since the 1970s .
If the government raises tax to finance the expenses on the aged , the younger generation would even face difficulties making a living .
Some sociologists argue that if the expenditure on public health is to be limited , the younger generation has to pay more .
While it may sound true , someone in the society has to sacrifice in order to solve the current ageing problem .
Last but not least , China 's public spending should be limited because there are other sectors of China 's economy which need the money more imperatively .
China is still a developing country today and more of the government 's budget should go to the sectors which are able to generate more wealth .
In 2008 , the total expenditure for public wealth in China was RMB 984 billion , which is about 3.3 % of the total GDP ( 2008 ) .
A portion of the money should be diverted into the sectors which are more important in the long run such as education and
According to the National Bureau of Statistics , the expenditure of the government on education last year was RMB 901 billion and on was even lower at RMB 213 billion ( , 2008 ) .
China has to be fully industrialized first before spending its money on the old .
Previously , the aging was a tough process having to deal with the many problems faced .
By doing so , it can partially relieve the society of the increasing financial burden of an aging population .
Hence , skills upgrade and training programs like those offered by Workforce Development Agency should reach out to more elderly and make it easier for them to upgrade themselves to reduce their barriers to entry into the workforce .
When the elderly returning to the workforce they will be able to accumulate more wealth and save more so that they will be able to be self sufficient when they are older .
Therefore , it is essential to provide skills upgrading programs for the elderly and by doing so it will reduce their barriers to enter the workforce and reduce the impact of aging on the economy .
The government is aware of the challenges faced by the aging population due to inadequate facilities and living conditions and has influenced the changes in the environment so as to make life easier for the elderly .
For example , they are customized to contain various elderly friendly features such as the alarm system that automatically requests for help through a pull of a lever in case of an emergency .
Besides , features such as the building of lifts leading to every storey and the residence corners for the elderly to interact are also implemented .
The improving medical care and subsidies help the aging population cope with health problems which are inherent in old age .
With this subsidy , more elderly will be able to medical care as compared to before .
Furthermore , with the constantly improving technology in the medical field , many medical procedures have been simplified from surgery that requires hospitalisation to an outpatient procedure .
Now , the surgery can sometimes be done in less than 30 minutes as an outpatient basis .
The elderly have to be convinced to adopt a healthy and balanced lifestyle .
With the measures such as better economic situation for the elderly by encouraging later retirement , improving the housing and transport conditions and better health care for the elderly have tremendously changed the way aging takes place .
While it is inevitable to avoid the aging process , with such measures in place , it will make growing old much easier than before .
With the overly successful " Stop at Two " campaign to curb the overpopulation in the 1960 's , Singapore has since faced an ageing population as birth rate dipped tremendously .
In 2008 , Singapore was reportedly one of the Asian economies to be worst hit by an ageing population ( UBS , 2008 ) .
Our long-term economic growth is estimated to be cut by 3 percent , while support for the elderly could cost the country more than 7 percent of our gross domestic product ( GDP ) .
With such a bleak outlook of our economy , our nation should be spending more wisely .
by entrusting the responsibility of taking care of the elders to everyone in society , public spending on the elderly could and should then be limited .
With a high average inflation rate of 5.83 % globally ( Goldman Sachs , 2008 ) , it is very difficult for grown children to support both their family and their parents .
Especially in Asian societies , such as Singapore , older people are traditionally supported by their own families .
Parents above sixty , who can not support themselves , can approach the tribunal for an order to claim maintenance from their children , delegating responsibility to the children .
As the nation prospers , these homes will appreciate in value , and Singaporeans may draw on this egg nest when they are old .
With such policies , the aged are ensured that they would have enough assets to remain self reliant and not be dependent on the government .
Hence , the government will then be able to divert spending towards national growth .
Employers could also offer other kinds of employment , it does not necessarily have to be the same job or pay as of their previous employment .
As the population gets older , retired elderly will require healthcare reimbursement , building of elder friendly infrastructure and domestic helpers .
As a result , this will become very costly to the working generations , and also it will be a hindrance to economic growth .
Many elderly have deteriorating health with common illnesses like diabetes , eye cataracts , bone and joint problems , and heart problems .
There is also a need to build elderly friendly environments like railings , lifts that goes to every floor of the buildings , and ramps .
The elderly should be educated about the aging population , because the economy may be severely affected if they are no longer able to support themselves financially .
Being financially responsible , the elderly should save up as much money as possible while they are young so that they can pay for their daily expenses .
As a large working population retires , this will mean that there are less people to work and provide for the retired elderly .
Also , when foreign investors relocate their investments , jobs will also be relocated to other geographic places , this will result in fewer jobs for the population .
besides global warming , an aging population is another phenomenon that is of concern to the world today , one that has no definite solution
This aging phenomenon is most evident in developed countries like Japan , Germany and Singapore where fertility rates are low .
The growing number of the elderly around the world has certainly created a huge iimpact which in turn has caused changes to the structure of current society .
Faced with this situation , governments and policy makers around the world have been providing solutions such as the introduction of economic policies , social policies , and architectural designs which benefit both the elderly and society .
One of the main solutions to be offered is the economic policy that eases the financial situation of the elderly .
One of the evident examples would be the health care subsidy which has been carried out by many developed countries such as Singapore , Japan , and the U.S. Others may object that too much is being spent on the elderly and this will hinder the growth of the country which is fundamentally more essential .
However , this argument may not be valid because the elderly are considered as an integral part of a country and can not be totally excluded .
With the right economic plan and policies , the elderly can effectively contribute back to the growth of the country .
As mentioned by Singapore 's Prime Minister Lee , " aging should be redefined as an opportunity rather than burden to the society " .
Furthermore , other than contributing to the country , the elderly parents are also an important part of the family as they possess invaluable knowledge and experience which can guide the younger generation . ( The Journal 2009 )
As the aging population to some extent has had a negative impact on society , social policies play an important role in reducing the effect which could otherwise cause social disintegration within a country .
One important example would be the Parents Maintenance Act of Singapore , which governs specifically the social relationship between parents and children .
However , the current economic situation and the decreasing fertility rate have left young adults , who have no siblings to share costs with , no choice but to give up on their parents .
Furthermore , we should also consider the fact that society is changing over time and so does the social and cultural value of our traditions .
Thus , social policy plays an important part to maintain this relationship and also to reiterate the importance of filial piety in the minds of the young adults .
This dependency may hinder the activity of the people around them which may otherwise be productive .
With this in mind , countries have begun to provide elder friendly architectural design to assist elderly in their daily activities .
For instance , in Singapore , more housing and transportation modes are designed to provide elder friendly designs such as : rubber flooring , alarm systems and supporting hand rails .
With the implementation of elder friendly designs , the elderly will be able demonstrate some level of independence .
In conclusion , the problems of an aging population are likely to continue or even worsen over the coming years .
Including economic , social and architectural aspects of society , there are many other implementations that can be done to ease the aging issues .
With the success of these implementations , I believe the world can shift the paradigm of the aging phenomenon to have a sustainable positive impact .
In Singapore , the government and society have come up with various policies and strategies to assist the aging population .
For example , there are some organizations that help the elderly with their daily necessities ; the government is planning on making a more elder friendly environment and having an Active Aging Festival .
One might object that the government and society have not really done much for them .
For instance , there are still many who are living alone with no children to care for them .
This group of elderly usually live in small apartments with little contact with the outside world and they fall sick easily .
It is also quite inconvenient for them to move about , thus they prefer to stay at home and watch television , rest and not do anything much .
They just watch life pass by .
Many are of the view that the government is neglecting the older generation .
We can see that some buses are now made with a platform accessible for people who are on wheelchairs ; Mass Rapid Transit ( MRT ) stations with lifts and fare gates which allow them to travel just like many other commuters ; Older HDB flats being upgraded to lifts that stops at each level and car parking areas now comes with wheelchair bounded slots .
These are just examples of the many strategies that the government has come up with to ease the aging process in Singapore .
Two years ago , the Active Aging Festival was launched to encourage senior citizens to be more active in their lives
Instead of living in the past , they are encouraged to pursue their dream and work towards their future .
The festival has been initiated by Council for Third Age ( C3A ) .
Its focus is on the six dimensions of wellness which an elderly will most likely be lacking in .
It turns out to be fun and exciting for the elderly .
In having this festival , the government allows the elderly to enjoy their aging life together with their family members .
An aging population is one of the issues that faces Singapore today. .
The Singapore Department of Statistics ( Singstat ) states in its Population Trend 2008 report that senior citizens aged 65 years and above make up 8.5 % of the population and that , it will continue to rise .
Having an aging population means that there will be lesser people in the workforce and this will have an impact on the country 's economy .
Further if public spending on the aged is not limited despite the decrease in the size of the workforce , the country 's economy will be negatively affected .
In addition , the public money comes from taxing the workforce .
If public spending is not limited , this would mean that the workforce may be further taxed to provide sufficient funds for the aged .
Not only would this pressurize the workforce , it would also cause them to spend less as they have lesser discretionary income .
Thus , it is necessary to limit public spending on the aged due to the negative consequences that would arise from doing otherwise .
One may argue that the high cost of living justifies the need for public spending on the aged .
The money in the Medisave account was formed by a percentage of their income and could be used for hospitalization expenses .
An aging population should not be the only issue that is given most attention to , as there are other areas of the country 's development that would require public money .
Singstat mentions that despite the slight increase in fertility rate , the fertility rate is still considered low .
Thus , public spending on the aged should be limited as there are other areas of the country 's development that would require the national budget .
This is because of the consequences related to doing otherwise such as pressurizing the national budget as well as the workforce .
In addition , the government has already done its part in preparing its citizens for old age through the CPF Life and Medisave Account .
The aging process means that as time passes , people will undergo a process of physical , psychological and social change .
In order to help the society and its people to cope with the changes , current research and development such as new technological inventions and employment schemes are being put in place .
This is a concern for an aging population as there could be some danger posed in crossing the roads when the traffic light has turned red .
It may be objected that if an elderly person took too much time crossing the road , it may cause traffic congestion on the road .
Thus , the system is put in place for elderly to cross safely with a reasonable amount of time .
This example shows that the problems which will occur from an aging population have been well-thought through and measures have been put in place. .
Secondly , , mobile phones are used commonly and most people around the world have at least one mobile phone .
With a large demand for mobile phones , phone companies have to compete with each other by inventing fanciful mobile phones with many functions such as Internet , games , music player and more .
However , with the shift to an aging population , the purpose of possessing a mobile phone changes . The demand would be for its original functionality of maintaining contact and for emergencies .
Furthermore , as people get older , their vision will become poorer and responsiveness might be slower than before .
Thus , phone companies must take this opportunity to penetrate the market with elderly-friendly phones .
For example , Japan 's phone companies actually offer phone models which have bigger screens and larger font sizes , enhanced audibility and easier- to-operate keys to attract the elderly .
In contrast , the Japanese phone companies which offer the elderly-friendly phones also offer a free one hour session on how to use the phone .
Therefore , this shows that the phone companies are attentive to issues regarding the aging population and have taken action to help ease the problems faced by an aging population. .
However , it is not true as the government has implemented several schemes to help in the employment of the elderly .
Being one of the fastest aging populations in the Asian region , Singapore faces many challenges in trying to overcome this aging problem .
For the last 30 years , the young population in Singapore has shrunk tremendously .
Accounting for less than 4 % of the total population back in the 1960s , today the elderly , aged 65 and above constitute 7.3 % of the total population based on the Singapore Census of Population 2000 .
This projects a significant growth in the aging population over the years .
To accommodate this current changing age structure , on-going development of government policies , covering areas like economics , sociology and architectural design , have been carried out aggressively through these years .
Even though The government has implemented so many policies to help ease the aging process , some people still view this as insufficient. .
Although some of the government 's policies are initiated with the goal of encouraging the young to look after their aged parents , it does not seem to work out as planned .
Due to the changing beliefs and values of the younger generation in the 21th century , many of them hope to achieve freedom in their financial status , personal life and other aspects of their life and thus deem that staying with their aged parents would cause a burden to them .
The Government should try educating this younger generation on the correct mindset before exploiting the full potential of these implemented policies .
One of the main causes for a growing aging population is the low fertility rate in Singapore .
Due to that , Singapore is facing a serious declining fertility rate that is resulting in a huge difference between the aged and the young .
Through these implemented policies , it will help facilitate the growth of the fertility rate .
To further tackle the rising trend , the Government has implemented different housing schemes so as to better allow the families to look after their aged parents rather than putting them in old folks ' homes or leaving them to look after themselves .
Support services and subsidies are provided to families with aged dependents so as to assist them and at the same time , help the aged to remain physically and socially active .
Catering to the upward trend of the aging population , initiated programs such as free health check for the elderly are implemented to encourage the elderly to constantly conduct full body checkup to ensure that they are in good health and also to advice them on the dos and don'ts in their everyday life so as to maintain a healthy lifestyle .
Besides that , incentives are also being provided for the elderly to further motivate them in conducting health checks .
Indeed , a lot of research and development besides policies have been implemented in order to ease the aging process especially from the aspect of medicine , economics and technological inventions .
Disease like Parkinson 's disease which is known as an incurable disease is now largely controllable due to research done to discover the cause of this disorder .
Of all the neurodegenerative disorders , Parkinson 's disease is second to Alzheimer 's disease in the number of cases , with more than 1.3 million patients suffering from it in major countries .
Parkinson 's disease usually develops after the age of 65 .
Currently , research and development Solvay Pharmaceuticals Asia is progressing well on working with the newly invented therapy of SLV308 and SLV318 to improve symptomatic treatment of Parkinson 's disease .
If the medications are successfully improved , Parkinson 's disease will be highly controlled .
Research has also been done on other illnesses to find out the most efficient medications .
Compared to before , the research and newly invented medicines have helped to ease certain aging processes to a certain extent .
However , every one of us will get old and people should think twice before giving such comments .
The scheme , introduced last year , is a key piece in a comprehensive plan to tackle the problem of an aging population , as people 's retirement savings are not keeping pace with longer life spans .
Because of this , the member will not need to worry about retirement in later life
The dependency of the elderly on the young can be reduced and government 's spending on the elderly can also be minimized in the long-run .
Technological inventions should also be taken into account as they are also essential in easing the aging process .
Another device uses radio frequency identification technology to track which medications have been take and when .
Besides , a team of researchers from UGR has created a system with Artificial Intelligence techniques which notifies elderly people or people with special needs who forget everyday tasks .
Moreover , the inventions of a wheelchair controlled by a magnet on the tongue will also enable some elderly people who are unable to move freely move easily , wherever and whenever they want .
These inventions have indeed helped a lot in easing the aging process .
In a nutshell , it is undeniable that in this globalization era , research , development and policies have been doing their part in easing the aging process .
With these inventions , people nowadays are leading comfortable lives and the aging process is no longer tough for both the elderly and the young .
Globally , there is rising concern about the rapidly aging population , especially in the developed countries , for example , the U.S. Census Bureau projects the number of elderly Americans will nearly double to 71 million by 2030 .
Many countries are starting to pump money into research and to introduce policies to ease the aging process as it will lead to problems like widening of the tax base and healthcare shortages .
While current research and policies have helped to ease the aging process , there are limitations to these policies that make these policies not as effective .
The policies that the government introduced and current research have indeed helped to buffer the aging process .
This policy is effective in the sense that it not only increases the size of the working population so that the government will not have to increase the tax base , but also helps the elderly to save up more money for their future needs after they retire .
When dealing with an aging population , the government knows that healthcare is one major sector that they can not neglect .
As people have a longer life expectancy , the aging population is going to make up a quarter of the population by the year 2030 in countries like Singapore .Therefore , more people will be demanding better health care as they grow older. .
This is because as people grow older , many are bound to suffer from age-related diseases such as Alzheimer 's and Parkinson 's disease .
Thus , the government is investing large amounts of money into medical research on age-related diseases and bringing in new medical technology .
This research and technology will be used in finding new cures for certain diseases , developing of new treatments and increasing the success rate of surgery .
The research and technologies brought in are very expensive which makes it available only for the people who can afford it and the poor , who can barely make ends meet , will not be the beneficiaries .
In addition , in the case of Singapore , people can fully utilise their Medisave funds , which they have saved up from their working lives , to pay for their medical bills .
However , these are really not enough to cover the high medical bills for most people , especially those who suffer from illnesses that require long- term treatment .
For low income earners , they may have depleted their Medisave funds after one surgery , and for subsequent treatment , they will have to either fork out their own savings or , as is often the case , they will refuse to seek treatment , which thus aggravates their illness .
So , more efforts from the government is needed in this area so that affordable healthcare will be accessible to everyone who needs it .
Aging population is a problem that no country can escape , so what the government can do is to reduce this aging process with the help of research and policies .
However , there are limitations in the policies , thus the government can look into alternative methods so that people will truly benefit from these policies and research .
In recent years , the changing demographics of Singapore has caused the government and policymakers to channel more resources and to revise public policies for the elderly .
If the government still does not intervene , the working-age population will come under more pressure as elderly persons are mostly taken care of by them .
Furthermore , if it is not properly handled , more issues relating to the aging population will arise causing serious consequences to the growth of the country .
With the help from voluntary welfare organizations , there is a range of health care services available to help older people in the , .
These health care services provided are such as day care centres , senior citizens clubs and residential care .
However , at times these services are not fully utilized as they lack publicity and the location may not be accessible to some of the elderly who do not stay near the health care centres .
Therefore , these health care centres are mostly located in places where a high proportion of older people are staying .
These services are a great support and assistance to working age people who are taking care of the elderly while they are busy working .
With more of these health care services around , the elderly can remain physically and socially active , and it also helps to lighten the burden of the working age population .
Currently , the government is encouraging more healthy and able elderly people to work longer by lowering barriers for employing elderly people .
It may be argued that having older employees will also mean higher costs in term of healthcare benefits and insurance .
In such case , companies will find them a huge financial burden slowing the growth of the company .
But , on the other hand , companies do save a lot in their training costs as these employees are more experienced , and retaining them will cut down on recruitment costs .
By working longer , there is more time to ensure that valuable experience and knowledge is passed on to the younger members of the workforce .
Countries such as Japan and the United States are also encouraging more people to work longer by extending the retirement age up to sixty-five .
In addition , still having a good medical condition and good working performance , these people can be a great asset in contributing to the economy .
Hence , encouraging later retirement will benefit the economy of the country and the elderly in saving up more for their old age .
Nowadays , there is more support given by the government for families to take care of elderly people .
Schemes such as the Joint Selection Scheme that allow children to apply for flats in the same block or housing estates of their parents .
There is also more upgrading of older estates to improve accessibility such as more ramps and lifts .
In addition , beautifying older housing estates with modern design and interior improvements is a strategy to prevent the outflow of younger people .
Therefore , continual support from the government is important to promote children to stay with their elderly parents .
These issues are also faced by other developed countries such as Japan and the United States .
In order to deal with these rising issues , the government is currently taking active measures to help ease the aging process .
However , there can only be so much that the government can help in terms of health care services and policies .
If these services are not fully utilized by people and the elderly are not responding to government assistance , slowly these older people could be considered as not productive and be neglected by the society .
After World War II , there was a rapid increase in the birth rate across the globe and Singapore too , faces the same problem .
For instance , civil servants are not entitled to paid maternity leave for the third and subsequent child .
In addition , public hospitals charge increasingly higher sums for each additional birth .
With low birth rates and longer life expectancy , the aging population has become a long term problem for Singapore .
Knowing the difficulties in encouraging Singaporeans to have more children , the government and related organizations decided to carry out research studies and implement policies to ease the aging process in different areas such as the medical field .
In order to combat the shrinking workforce caused by the rapid ageing population and a declining fertility rate , the Health authorities must first gear up their medical field and prepare for an aging population .
Due to the fact that older patients are more prone to hospital admittances than other age groups , providing better medical care facilities and services not only helps to reduce the chance of re-admission , it will also facilitate better chances of making a full recovery .
With less frequent visits to hospital , the amount of money spent on medical bills would decrease .
Hence , the elderly would be able live longer with their retirement funds .
However , to develop the medical sector , huge sums of funds have to be involved which may in turn hamper the development of other sectors .
Moreover , the drugs have to be tested so as to ensure the effectiveness of the medicine and that they are safe for consumption .
On the other hand , with the rise in aging population , it is necessary to invest heavily in the medical sector as poor medical facilities will lead to more health problems within the country .
This will then result in an increase in the amount spent on medication , thus adding a greater financial burden to the shrinking workforce .
With the constant rise in the cost of living , families can no longer rely on a sole breadwinner as they need to support both their parents as well as their children in terms of food , shelter and education .
Furthermore , if either of their parents contract a long term disease which requires a significant amount of care , both adults will be in a dilemma about whether to look after their parents or to carry on with their job so as to ease the financial burden that is added because of the medical bills .
Either decision requires one party to sacrifice , thus the Singapore government decided to offer more step-down care services which provides basic medical care to the elderly after the patient has been stabilized .
To ensure that the elderly maintain a healthy lifestyle , the government has started to build elderly fitness corners around the neighborhood .
Occasionally , neighborhood polyclinics also provide free medical checkups for the elderly .
Then again , even though it is the health authorities who are responsible for providing better medical care to the citizens , senior citizens also have to play a part in ensuring their own well being .
Hence , even though the government and health authorities offer facilities to ease the aging effect , people must also take the initiative to utilize them and be more proactive in keeping a healthy lifestyle .
In a nutshell , the medical sector plays a significant role in easing the aging process by providing a high level of medical care and wellbeing to senior citizens .
Thus , if the elderly are able to take advantage of the advanced medical facilities offered to them , it will certainly play a big role in helping society to ease the aging process .
Aging is a time induced process that causes physical , psychological and social changes. .
Longer life expectancy and a continuous fall in population have caused the aging population in Singapore to increase .
In view of these strategies , it can be argued that the current research and development policies have helped to ease the aging process .
The first policy development is in the medical field .
Having quality health care services at affordable prices is viewed as one of the most important needs for the aging population .
This strategy calls for having private clinics to be within a hundred metres from the home .
The second strategy devised is the implementation of means- testing .
It is supported by reducing the subsidies of the financially well-off .
The second policy development is in the economic field .
Thirdly , more financial help is being sought from the government .
The first strategy implemented is the creation of the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) .
The purpose is to provide a compulsory and comprehensive savings plan for Singaporeans .
Some of the changes are the increase in the the CPF minimum sum and the partial withdrawal of retirement savings upon reaching retirement age .
The second strategy implemented is the raise in the retirement age to sixty two years old .
However , critics have pointed out that it is the motivation of individuals , instead of policies , that has to ease the aging process .
They also have not pointed out that Singapore has taken basic measures to ensure the general well-being of its citizens .
For example , it is compulsory for newly-born to have the BCG vaccination against Tuberculosis .
The integration of health care service providers through medical policies will result in a higher quality and more affordable health care system .
As for economic policies , having the CPF and raising the retirement age allows additional wealth accumulation .
It is norm that ageing is often associated with illnesses such as Parkinson 's and , and as a result , it is a concern of many .
Thus , medical breakthroughs by the University of Nottingham in research regarding to the slowing down and preventing of Parkinson 's and dementia has definitely relieved many .
Although , some may argue that breakthroughs in research do not severe the root of the problem as those who are ill with the diseases are still not cured .
However , one must realized that breakthroughs can help the aged to be better prepared or even prevent contracting diseases .
Additionally , since there is a breakthrough , the possibility of a cure can not be ruled out as well .
Besides , if more are able to slow down or even prevent themselves from getting the disease , the aged can lessen their medical costs which will lead to a reduced cost of living .
Therefore , medical research greatly enhances the confidence of the aged to face the eventual ageing process .
Similarly , economic policy like the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) also aid in the ageing process of Singaporeans .
CPF is a saving fund employed by the government .
It enforces working adults to save a portion of their monthly salary , so that they will have a sum of money upon retirement . Consequently , this will bring about less monetary problems when people are aged .
However , it is also not guaranteed that the saving in CPF will be sufficient , especially with the prolonged life expectancy of many .
Therefore , recently adjustments have been made to the policies to ensure that the retirees ' saving can last them through their life .
In the past , a lump sum was given to the recipients , but now the recipients will get the money in their CPF account on a monthly basis till they pass on .
Another plan in CPF known as Medisave . This helps the aged to meet health care needs and hospitalization fees , so that the aged can afford the usage of healthcare facilities .
As can be seen , the CPF policy has not only help the aged to cope with monetary issues after retirement , making sure that their savings are sufficient for their retirement but it has also made it certain that they will be able to afford healthcare facilities if required .
.
This policy not only helps to minimize the fear of not being taken care of when one is aged , it weakens the negative idea that living with parents only increases one 's expenditure . It also diminishes the worries of aged parents that their children will not have a roof over their head .
Clearly , the current research and policies have helped to ease the ageing process tremendously .
Breakthroughs in the medical research field , not only provide a cushion for the aged with regards to old age illnesses but also help to reduce their future medical expenditure .
Similarly , the CPF policy , put into operation by the government lessens the worries of ageing as medical and life expenses are already well planned for .
It is relatively hard to deny how much ageing has been made much easier .
Aging as defined by Wikipedia is the process of physical , psychological , and social change .
Physical change means that one 's health will be likely to deteriorate as one ages .
Social change in general points to the change in attitude towards life .
Fortunately , advancements in technology , economic policies and social policies implemented by the government has helped to ease this process .
Some elderly individuals may feel left behind by the pace of technological change .
Elderly individuals , who lack access and training needed to familiarize themselves with modern technology like the internet , may find themselves at a disadvantage .
This is because they will miss out on opportunities to access the large database of information , goods and services online .
In addition , there will also be concentrated efforts towards educating elderly individuals to use the internet .
This is very convenient especially for elderly individuals who have difficulty moving around .
Apart from that , advancements in technology also brings about the inventions of new gadgets that have significantly improved the lives of elderly individuals .
For example in Japan , a mobile phone manufacturer has come up with a mobile phone that has a large key pad so that the elderly can use it without straining their eyes .
As a result , elderly individuals can enjoy their retirement without having many financial worries .
Elderly individuals are generally more prone to illnesses as their immune system may have weakened due to aging .
In addition to that , they are more likely to be plagued with old age diseases like Parkinson 's or dementia .
The government foreseeing that personal medical expenses would rise as one ages , has implemented the Medisave scheme to meet elderly people 's healthcare needs .
Therefore , they do not have to worry about medical expenses when they are old .
Social policies have also been implemented to ease the process of aging .
For example in Singapore , the government has set up a $ 10million Golden Opportunities Fund to create more programmes , activities and learning opportunities for elderly individuals .
This fund will be used to construct more elderly-friendly facilities in all sports centres and within housing estates .
Therefore , through this policy , elderly people can pursue the lifestyle of their choice , be it sports , learning , or contributing through volunteering in non-profit organizations .
In conclusion , advancements in technology , economic policies and social policies implemented by the government have helped to ease the process of aging .
Currently , 7 % of Singapore 's population is over the age of 65 ; however , by 2030 , this will increase to 20 % ( Inter-Ministerial Committee on Aging Report 1999 ) . Thus ageing population is one of the challenges Singapore will face in the near future .
It is undeniable that there have been many policies implemented to ease the aging process .
However , the extent to which these policies help to ease the ageing process remains rather limited due to the limitations of the policies .
Firstly , the Parents Maintenance Act can now address the concern of the increasing number of parents who are neglected and abandoned by their children. .
It may be successful in getting the children to pay the maintenance of their parents ; but by enforcing such law , .
The act ensures that the child or children have to support their parents since they will face serious consequences if they did not . However , it is a question of whether they have done it willingly .
Filial piety is supposed to be a virtue to be upheld , a respect for parents and ancestors , and yet now we need a law to make sure everyone uphold it .
Does this imply morals are being eroded in this society ?
Furthermore , Parents Maintenance Act may not be entirely successful in getting the children to pay for their parents ' maintenance .
This is because the act is only applicable if parents made a report against their children and if the parents were aware of such an act , as well as ready to do that to their children .
And children can only abide by the obligations if they were financially stable .
Therefore this act is rather ineffective in solving the problems of unwanted parents .
Other strategies in solving the ageing problem would be to increase the birth rate .
With an increased population , there will be an increase in the workforce which would in turn lead to an increase in income tax Thus , this will solve the problems of labour shortage , as well as the heavy financial strain placed on the economically active population .
A pronatalist policy has been implemented since the early 1990s , and yet the effectiveness it has on birth remains questionable .
Despite much efforts have been put in by the government to shape a policy that aims at lessening the financial burden of having children , fertility rates continues to remain low . It could reach as low as 1,08 , which is way below replacement rate .
The pro-natalist policy focuses mainly on cash incentives such as baby bonuses of $ 3,00 for the first and second child , up to $ 6,000 for the third and fourth child ; as well as government contributions in the form of a dollar-for-dollar matching for the amount of savings the parents contribute to their child 's Children Development Account .
However , in Singapore , the financial burden is less of a concern when we are targeting at the 'productive group ' of the population .
, so when they are encouraging population growth they are targeting at the educated ones , who are also the financially stable ones .
Thus cash incentives are not a strong enough factor to encourage them to give birth , as money is of a less important issue to them .
On the other hand , it can also be argued that and the government 's help in terms of baby bonus and Children Development Account is temporary .
and it makes people think twice about giving birth , given the other considerations such as high cost of living in Singapore and the increasingly competitive society we are living in . All these make the task of raising a child well challenging .
Therefore , the pro-natalist is rather unsuccessful in easing ageing population through the encouraging of births due to other considerations people have when they decide to have a child , and these considerations may not be related to cash incentives. .
In conclusion , the two policies have shown their ineffectiveness in easing the problems of ageing population .
Rather than having one policy to cater to the whole country , there can be different policies implemented to cater to different levels of income group .
I agree to a certain extent that the current architectural development in Singapore has helped in the aging process .
Aging process causes difficulties in movement
The current scheme that the Singapore government is using is called the Barrier-Free Accessibility ( BFA )
( ) . " This BFA Code requires all new buildings , as well as the existing ones to undergo major retrofitting works , to meet certain barrier-free requirements .
'New " refers to any building that comes after BFA has been implemented .
" Certain " means that it is .
The statement highlights that to a large extent , the architectural development in Singapore was not barrier-free .
The current BFA Code focuses on the accessibility to and within a building .
.
Therefore the public owner has a part to play .
For examples , shopping malls , industrial estates , invested properties and private properties .
But that is only for buildings that do not belong to the government sector .
Buildings like the Housing development Board flats are built or upgraded to have better accessibilities .
Measures taken by the government to help ease aging process in residential areas are sheltered linkways which are upgraded to allow the elderly to access from residential blocks to markets .
Other measures include the installation of more ramps in residential areas , which are designed to have a gentle gradient so that it is user-friendly for people in wheelchairs , as well as new lifts replacements with bigger button showing larger text and better lit buttons in lifts so that the old who are visually unsound can see and press for the correct floor .
Measures are taken by the government to help ease the aging process in non-residential areas by creating better public accessibility : for example , the Land Transport Authority making plans to improve accessibility to reach public transport like MRT and bus stops .
The National Parks is also working to into its designs for parks so that even parks can be allowed better accessibility .
Private building owners need to adopt similar measures to achieve for aging population .
A large amount of development has been done by the government to help ease the process of aging but it is not enough due to the fact that the BFA Code only covers new buildings and government developments .
Existing developments by private entities still do not have desirable levels of accessibility .
Since the implementation of the Code on Barrier-Free Accessibility in Buildings ( BFA ) in the 1990s , there has been an increase of improved buildings with better accessibility .
Hence , I agree that the current architectural development in Singapore has helped in the aging process to a certain extent .
But it is only a Guide ; and its applications are not compulsory .
This means that there is no obligations to follow strictly to the guidelines ; in other words , .
In effect , UD does not help in the development of better accessibility for people who are aged .
Therefore , a revised code on Barrier-Free Accessibility In Buildings , which is a 5-year Barrier-Free Accessibility ( BFA ) Upgrading Program ( 2007-2011 ) has been added to support the upgrading of existing buildings .
The current BFA Code focuses on essential requirements confined to handicap features or facilities which are deemed to be of minimum standards essential for its intended use .
Despite this effort , private sectors are still not incorporating desirable features in their designs to help make the buildings in Singapore to be 100 % user-friendly to all intended users because they only meet the basic standards of accessibility needed by a building .
" I agree with this statement to a large extent .
The national budget has always been something that most taxpayers pay much attention to and the planning of the annual expenditure is always a big challenge to meet the ever changing needs of the country .
Public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted into more important areas of the country 's development , mainly health , education and defense .
Budget allocated to the health sector is essential in every country as reduced healthcare facilities and equipment will lead to reduced productivity as people fall sick and they are unable to receive adequate medical attention .
In the case of Singapore , a total budget of $ 3705 million has been allocated to the Ministry of Health for the financial year 2009 ( Ministry of Finance , 2009 ) .
Some might argue that more money should be allocated to taking care of the elderly as the elderly are more prone to chronic diseases and other health problems .
However , I think that this is an of the elderly issue and is not practical .
It will be much better for the money to be diverted into researching for new medicines and vaccines and improving healthcare facilities . This is more important in the current situation when viruses are getting more adapted to current medications and a pandemic is imminent .
Furthermore , it will also be better if the money is diverted into generating more subsidies for medical charges so that healthcare cost remains affordable for all citizens . This in turn will also benefit the aged as well .
Emphasis should also be placed on the education sector as it is crucial to the country 's development .
Education is fundamental for the nation as it builds the nation 's foundation .
Singapore has spent a large amount of budget on education , roughly $ 8701 million in the financial year 2009 ( Ministry of Finance , 2009 ) .Some people might think that educating the elderly is an important aspect of the nation 's development as it promotes lifelong learning .
However , educating the old will require a considerate amount of money as most of their minds are not as active as the younger ones and they will take a longer time to absorb new knowledge .
The focus should be setting a strong foundation for the young and the working population rather than spending money on the elderly .
Defence is also a major component that we have to place focus on when we talked about the country 's development .
In Singapore , defense has the highest percentage of the budget allocated in Financial Year 2009 , rounding to about $ 11.45 billion , which is about 26.4 % of the national budget ( Ministry of Finance , 2009 ) .Some people might dispute that the aged is a valuable asset as we can tap into their vast experience when it comes to defense .
However , in this fast paced and ever changing society , the experiences of the aged will get more irrelevant and money will be better used if the public spending on the aged can be diverted into defense to maintain peace so that the social and economical sectors of the nation can flourish .
In conclusion , I believe that there is indeed a need for public spending on the aged as the aged are still able to contribute much when it comes to the nation 's development such as through their experiences in life .
However , there have to be a limit as to how much we spend on them so that the money can be diverted into areas like health , education and defense , which are much more important and crucial to the country 's development .
Due to the ageing of the baby-boomers and the lower fertility rates in the first-world countries , the unprecedented problem of a fast ageing population has become the concern of governments and policy makers in the developed world .
And Singapore , as one of the developed countries with one of the fastest growing elderly populations in the world , had around 235,000 elderly aged 65 years old and above ( or7 % of the population ) in 1999 . This figure figure is going to reach 796,000 ( or19 % of the population ) by the year 2030 ( Committee on Ageing Issues , n.d. ) . Therefore , Singapore needs to face this serious challenge and ease the negative impact of an aging population on society .
The final objective of " Successful Ageing for Singapore " ( Committee on Ageing Issues , n.d. ) , which has been brought up by the Committee on Ageing Issues ( CAI ) established in Dec 2004 to represent the various sectors in Singapore , is to ensure that elderly Singaporeans should be healthy , active and secure ; as well as that all levels of society are well prepared to face an ageing Singapore .
To achieve this goal , current research and development , as well as policies have helped to ease the aging process in different fields , like psychology , medicine , etc. Nevertheless , the situation of the fast ageing population in Singapore continues to be challenging , despite the various research and development , and policies .
Although the trend of a fast ageing population is unlikely to be reversed in a short term ; much can still be done to buffer its negative impact on society .
Furthermore , in order to change the mindsets of the elderly , a systematic year-round public education ( PE ) program ( Committee on Ageing Issues , n.d. ) should be conducted , to infuse a culture of personal responsibility and lifelong planning for old age .
With the launching of this PE program , negative attitudes about ageing will be dispelled and active lifestyles and community involvement among older Singaporeans will be promoted This will strengthen intergenerational bonds , allowing the elderly to age with respect and dignity , as well as to lead independent and fulfilling lives as integral members of their families and communities . In the area of medicine , a series of efforts has been implemented .
First of all , the health-care system will be restructured to cater for an aging population in Singapore , as claimed by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong ( Channel NewsAsia , August 2009 ) .
Second , besides more new hospitals to be constructed , Singapore 's step-down care sector needs improvement too . This sector is largely supported by voluntary welfare organizations ( VWO ) , including community hospitals , nursing homes and home care .
By linking up hospitals with community ones , appropriate care can be given to the the elderly . This reduces the expenditure and releases the beds in the hospital for more acute cases .
In addition ,
Although the whole ageing issue in Singapore could be tackled by no one-off recommendation , .
With every effort put into these strategies , especially current researches and developments/ policies in various areas like psychology and medicine , the ageing process in Singapore could be eased t .
Public spending on the aged has been rising rapidly because people need more health care as they grow older .
Therefore , public spending on the aged should be limited to a certain extent , not only to avoid the high possibility of economic crisis in the near future , but also to divert the resources to other areas such as education and infrastructure development , which are essential for the economic growth of a country .
The increase of public spending on the aged is necessary because of the growing numbers among the aging population .
For example , Peterson states that " elder dependency should be reduced by encouraging later retirement , longer working lives , and lower barriers to elder employment " . ( citation )
Another strategy that he stated would be to emphasize filial obligation and encourage the willingness of tomorrow 's grown children to look after their aged parents , so as to lower government spending on the elderly .
Therefore , public spending on the aged is necessary , but we should not eliminate other possibilities that will ease the spending
In addition , education also plays a crucial role for the wealth and future development of a country .
In addition , it assists us in the development of our virtues and values , and it also cultivates us into mature individuals , who are capable of planning for our futures and taking the correct steps .
When people are well-educated , the advancement of a country 's economy will be promised ( Manali Oak , 2008 ) .
Education at the secondary and tertiary level will prepare students to be efficient when they enter the working society , by equipping them with the necessary knowledge and essential skills .
When the efficiency of the workforce is high , it will benefit the economic growth of the country .
For example , the accumulation of deficit incurred by the American public infrastructure over the past several decades has resulted in a variety of infrastructure bottlenecks-traffic congested roads , clogged ports , and an antiquated air traffic system , which undercut the economy 's efficiency .
This clearly shows that if a country were to neglect its infrastructure development , it will affect the economy greatly .
Infrastructures that are designed and built for tourists will be a significant source of revenue for the country ; hence , appropriate amount of public spending should be incorporated to develop such infrastructures .
For instance , the Infrastructure Development Finance Corporation in New Delhi said that by increasing public investment in infrastructure development , it would then attract more private investment ( PTI , 2006 ) .
This would mean more income will be generated .
The government should divert the money into education to equip the people with the right attitude and working skills , so as to ensure stable economic growth for the country .
Governments should spend sufficiently on infrastructure development because public infrastructure deficit will cause the economy to be less efficient .
On the other hand , public spending in infrastructure development attracts more private investment ; hence generating greater income .
If a country neglects other aspects such as education and infrastructure development , but over focuses on public spending on the aged , its economy will suffer drastically .
An aging process means the process of growing old and getting more matured .
As Singapore is the second fastest aging country in the world " ( Koh ) , The Singapore government has carried out many policies to ease the aging process to ensure that growing old in Singapore will be a satisfying and fulfilling experience .
The government has been focusing mainly on economic policies , which are more effective ways in easing the aging process among Singapore 's population .
One of the government economic policies which is successful is the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) scheme .
This is a " national social security fund which was established in 1955 as a form of funded retirement savings plan " ( Mehta ) .
Singaporeans are required to deposit a certain amount of their salaries into their CPF accounts .
" Employers are also required to contribute 16 % of the employee 's salary into the employee 's account " ( Mehta ) .
The contribution rates differ according to age and income of between 8 % to33 % .
Compared to other countries , Singapore has a much higher rate of contribution .
Some people might complain that the CPF is ripping away so much of their money that they do not have enough to spend .
However , this is the main purpose of CPF --- to save and reduce on spending .
The high saving rate is to enable the elderly to support themselves in old age and to provide for old-age dependency .
Some other people might say that CPF savings is not enough to provide for their retired lives .
Nonetheless , it is up to the individuals to plan their personal savings for their future as the CPF is just a way to help those who might not have planned their savings for oldage .
This is the intention of the government to protect its people .
.
It was a strategy implemented by the government in September 2002 .
It provides monthly cash out to help pay the out-of-pocket expenses for the care of a severely-disabled person " ( Healthcare Financing - ElderShield ) .
ElderShield is viewing at the increased life expectancy of Singaporeans , which translate to people living longer as compared to in the past . Therefore , one should deposit some savings during the productive years to prepare for old age disabilities .
Some people may think that this scheme is not needed and is a waste of money because they already have their account and they assumed that they will never get severe disabilities .
ElderShield will pay you monthly cash payouts if you become severely disabled for any reason , whereas MediShield helps you pay hospitalization expenses , only if you are admitted to a hospital " ( FAQs on Policies ) .
Looking at this policy , we know that the government is really trying to ease the aging process in the population .
Apart from the two policies above , the government has also implemented the Public/Society Scheme , which acts as a 'safety net ' for elderly Singaporeans .
All in all , though the government economic policies have some flaws , the policies have done much in making the lives of elderly citizens of Singapore easier and more comfortable .
Hence , the government financial policies are successful .
However , the government should limit spending on the aged .
As the country will have a smaller work force in 2030 , the government should invest more money on education to obtain a stronger work force to support the country and the large group of elderly .
" ( Krueger and Lindahl , 2001 ) With more investment in education , the standard of the work force in Singapore will increase .
And each individual worker will receive more income due to the high output and competitiveness of the Singapore work force .
At the same time , better education will not only improve the earning of the work force , but also the moral of the younger generation .
Singapore will not be able to solve the ageing issues if the younger generation of Singapore lacks morals and only puts their focus on themselves .
However , Singapore has already invested a lot of money in education , and by putting more money into education may not have a better outcome .
If Singapore stops her development in education and put her focus mainly on ageing issues , she might lose out in the future .
Thus , investing money in education is relevant and important .
In addition , Singapore needs to invest more in her defense to provide security for her population .
The recent bombings in Indonesian hotels and the escape and recapture of Mas Selamat have shown that Singapore is in danger all the time .
In addition , Singapore needs to build a stronger to prevent serious economic recessions .
Some reports suggest that investing more money on the elderly will benefit the country more , as compared to investing money on defense , which seems to be a waste of resources .
The fact is the importance of defense is hardly felt by the public because the people have been living in a safe environment for too long , and most of them think that Singapore is safe even without the defense system .
So , if the government does not invest enough in a better defense system , Singapore might have serious problems .
Limiting spending on ageing issues help to force society to take responsibility and not to totally rely on the government .
The government needs to help solve ageing issues and plan for the country so that the country will not suffer when crises arrive .
If all the problems have to be solved by the government , then the work load of the government will be extremely heavy .
And when most of the focus and attention of the government are on the ageing issues , the development of the country might be neglected , of which in the long run would ruin the country .
It is understandable that the public and the elderly are worried that if the government does not spend enough on the ageing issues , the elderly will be forgotten by the society .
If the government takes all the responsibilities , the public will take the problem for granted , just like how most of the people take the safety of Singapore as an easy thing to achieve .
Thus , the government should limit spending on aging issues and at the same time , educate the public .
The ageing issues will not be solved in a short period of time .
The ability of the government is limited .
Instead , the public itself should take a major role in ageing issues and work together with the government to solve these long term difficulties .
In Singapore , ageing population is a major issue that the nation has to deal with , considering the fact that 315,800 of the population were at the age of 65 and above in 2008 ( Annex .
A ) ; and that figure will only continue to increase , judging from the constant increment in the median age of our population since 1998
( Statistics 2009 ) . It is clear that public spending on the ageing population is essential .
By placing an unlimited amount of public spending directly targeted at the aged , the government will be neglecting economical , social and political issues which in a way , act as platforms for achieving better living conditions for the aged .
There is absolutely nothing wrong in allocating a bulk of the public funds to the aged .
The yearly Singapore Budget Speech actually recognizes the fact that someone has to make a policy to justify the amount of public spending in peace times or states of emergency
( Gerald P. O'Driscoll , 2002 ) . In addition , from the economic perspective , Singapore will never be a leading nation if there is no control over public spending .
Channeling more funds into the financial world may provide a higher possibility of a better economy , although no single entity till date can guarantee that .
Nonetheless , the government has to seriously consider the fact that a better economy will bring about higher employment rate , higher real income and lower inflation as indicated by the Consumer Price Index , and all these will enable Singaporeans in the workforce to save for the future .
In other words , financial planning , of which Peterson in " A Graying World " states to be a strategy to a new paradigm of ageing , ( Peterson 2001 ) is important . This is when more than 600 financial institutions in Singapore make the country one of the top ten most sophisticated financial markets in the world , according to the World Economic Forum .
( Kei 2009 ) For the government of Singapore to substantiate its standings in the financial markets of the world , it has to continue to provide incentives , which may come from the areas of world-class infrastructures , investment avenues , tourism and trade and those that require a sizeable amount of public spending , in order for the experts in the field to come in .
The government has to groom potential leaders and scholars to understand the importance of financial planning before they can lead and share .
Grooming then , comes in the form of a more sophisticated infrastructure for learning and monetary incentives or aids in the form of scholarships and bursaries .
One should not forget that through the functions of education , the government can increase or influence the citizens ' thoughts and awareness on being socially and morally responsible to the population which include the aged as well .
In addition , the government has to work hand-in-hand with social organizations , like the which helps ethnic groups financially , especially the aged .
In conclusion , we have to consider public spending on the other areas of concerns other than that of an ageing population
" I do not totally agree with the statement .
A country 's developments should be all-rounded but it should not be achieved at the expense of the health care for the elderly in the society .
First and foremost , the elderly are financially vulnerable in the society and need public funding for their health care .
Though Peterson ( 2001 ) maintains that the elderly could depend less on public spending by seeking employment or depending more on their families , such a method of reducing and limiting elder dependency is not feasible .
Being old does not mean the loss of health for the elderly , yet there are social prejudices against the elderly when they seek for employment at their age .
In this competitive age , employers will tend to favour the non-elderly over the elderly as the latter are nearly retired and often associated with diseases .
In addition , people are having lesser , if not , no children these days .
Such a societal trend reduces the possibility of the elderly tapping on filial obligation from their children to support them in future .
Therefore , such unfavourable trends continue to place the elderly in need of public support for their health care .
Where should the limit of public spending on the aged be drawn ?
Peterson ( 2001 ) also argues that " health " should be redefined by the government and that the government should draw a limit to its support for the health care of the aged .
A limit on spending would lead to the imposition of a limit on the range of health care for the aged that would be funded by the public .
In the context of health care , different people require different treatments .
If a certain limit were to be uniformly drawn across the public-funded health care , some elderly could be cut off from the treatment that they need .
Furthermore , the elderly may suffer from diseases which tend to be chronic in nature , like cardiac and rheumatologic diseases .
There should not be a limit on public spending for the health care of the aged . A balance should be struck in providing for the elderly and concomitantly , driving the country 's development .
However , the withdrawal of governmental support in the health care for the aged would shift the responsibilities of looking after the elderly to the families of these aged and burden the development of the country in the long run .
As argued by Friedland and Summer ( 2005 ) , the costs incurred by the families would " end up getting shifted back to the public sector through less direct and often more expensive means " .
Public support for the health of the aged is for a real cause .
Hence , public spending on the healthcare for the aged should be carried out flexibly and should not be viewed as a hindrance to the development and progress of a nation .
In a modern individualistic culture , a person should be conscious and prepared for his post-retirement .
He should strive for independence and accumulate a surplus of wealth for his old age when he is working .
Thus , the emphasis is diverted to other areas of the county 's development so that the country 's economy may grow , and the people will have a much larger income to support either themselves or their parents .
Money should be spent on education , research and growing the country 's economy so that people can have larger income to tap on .
In addition , instead of spending on the aged , policies could be made to encourage higher birth rates and stress the importance of filial piety as a value so that the aged can depend on their children .
In this way , focusing on growing the country 's economy as a mean to help support the aged seems wise .
However , regardless how much the economy is growing , not every person is going to accumulate enough wealth for their old age .
The rich is going to have a wealthy and comfortable life in their post-retirement but the poor is going to struggle with their daily lives paying for the necessary service bills , medical bills and food .
Elderly who are poor and who have no children or whose children have deserted them are only going to live on their depleting savings .
If their savings ran out , they would face difficulty acquiring income as their abated bodies may prevent them from finding a job .
They would end up living on the streets if no help were given to them .
Furthermore , these elderly can not afford expensive medical bills .
Hence , help is heavily needed from the government to keep the poor aged alive .
Everyday provision of living facilities and food is also needed for those who are poor , as we should not leave them on the streets .
Besides , long- term medical bills for chronic diseases are so expensive that they undermine an average income person 's total wealth .
Diseases that are common to old people , such as cancer , kidney failure and diabetes , require long-term medical attention and expensive treatment . As a result , an average income earner would not be able to afford payment even if his income were huge .
While it is very unfortunate to have any of these illnesses , every old person is prone to falling prey to them as their bodies weakened .
While the wealthy could struggle to fight the illness , the average man and below would not be able keep up with the medical bills if no subsidies on medical treatment from the government were given .
The aged have work very hard to develop our country in every way and they deserve a good rest for the rest of their lives .
It 's ethically not right to leave them on the streets or not to relieve them from the unaffordable medical fees , just because they have become incapable of contributing to society .
It is also against human rights to leave a helpless person to be tortured by illnesses and then leave him to die .
Selfishness and cruelly will develop in society when we decide to leave the aged to fend for themselves .
Selfishness undermines unity and cooperation which ultimately will lead to the failure of a society .
Cruelty leads to insensitivity towards death and violence , which may link to increased crime rates .
Hence , if we focused too much on pushing forward our economy and progress and neglect to take care of our aged , we might just lose our values .
By limiting public spending on the aged , there is most likely to be more old people struggling with medical fees .
It is ethically not right and impractical to limit public spending on the aged to spend on other areas of development .
As each year passes , there seems to be an increase on public spending for the aged .
This seems to be a very popular trend , as a lot of developed countries , such as Spain and the United States of America , tend to increase their public spending on the elderly .
Public spending is very essential to a country 's development , and should be utilised sensibly .
Spending on the aged should be limited so that the money can be diverted to other sectors of the country 's development , like public transportation or the army .
Public transportation is one area that could be improved if a country limited its spending on the elderly and raised its spending for the former .
" The privatization of public transport has not delivered the improved service standards nor shorter arrival times , while fares have been increasing based on the justification that being private transport operators , they are not charity and need to make profit for their shareholders .
According to a Singapore census held in 2000 , around 52 % of Singaporeans go to work using public transportation .
That is a staggering figure because over half the population uses public transportation , and yet the conditions are poor and the are high . This seems very unreasonable .
The Government can play a major role in creating a solution to this problem .
If they limited the amount being spent on the elderly , they can use their money to buy back the public transportation , and provide reasonable fares to the public .
Another thing they can do is improve the conditions of the buses .
Pollution is a growing concern to the environment , as observed by Zolla ( 1996 ) : " small land area of the central business district led to severe traffic conditions including congestion , reduced traffic speeds , and environmental problems .
"
Some of the buses used outside the city are fairly old , and unless they are disposed and substituted by newer buses , the environment is in danger .
Another way the government could use public spending more effectively is to spend more on the Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports , which is also known as the MCYS .
.
In that way the elderly have their families to look after them .
And if for some reason the younger ones in the family do not help their elders , they can be sued under the " Maintenance of Parents Act , which allows parents to sue their children for financial support .
This policy clearly shows why the government should limit its spending on the elderly , and spread it around to other more useful sectors .
" The island state 's median age will rise from 36 presently to 41 by 2030
Many people would use these figures to support their claims that public spending on the aged should not be limited .
however , it will cause major problems within the country 's health care system .
Even though the elderly continue to get money from the public , they still can not pay their medical bills , nor can their children .
The money should go instead to the country 's health care expenses .
Countries like Sweden and the United Kingdom face no problems when it comes to healthcare , as over 80 % of Health Care expenses are covered by the public funds of both nations .
To conclude , it would be very wise of the government to limit its spending on the aged , and to divert the money to other areas of the country 's development .
There are a lot of sectors more deserving of the money that could be beneficiary to both the young and old , like improving the public transportation in the country .
In the recent years , global aging issues are of significant concern .
If this trend continues , by 2030 , one out of every five Singaporeans will be 65 years old or above .
Over the years , the new researches , developments and policies in Singapore have definitely helped to ease the aging process to a large extent .
And as far as these developments and policies are concerned , ageing workforce and the cost for elderly healthcare are important factors that the government has to look into .
By looking into these factors , the country can greatly decrease the impact of the liabilities these elderly have on the country .
To prevent the older generations from being a burden to younger generations , the Singapore government has come up with several policies and acts which allow the elderly to stay in the workforce for a longer period of time .
Under this act , the minimum retirement age in Singapore is 62 years old , and thus allowing the elderly to stay longer in the workforce .
Firstly , they can accumulate more wealth through their work , of which they can then use it to support themselves in their old age .
Secondly , working provides them with a good environment to maintain and even build up their physical and mental health .
This is made possible through communication with their colleagues , which can help them to stay optimistic .
Thirdly , by working longer , they may also help to ease the financial stress of their family members .
Another worry that arises is the cost for health matters .
To help families in Singapore cope with the extensive treatment cost , the Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports ( MCYS ) has come up with services and programmes that provide affordable healthcare and eldercare services .
These facilities mostly cater to the needs of families with financial difficulties .
However , some Singaporeans have the mind set that these services and programmes are not of utmost importance to them as they have their own medisave account to pay for their hospitalization bills .
Some Singaporeans might not think that later retirement is a good idea .
For example , companies might think that it is a burden to hire an elderly worker , as he or she might not be able to cope with the stress and workload .
There are also worries about the health status of the elderly workers .
However , little did they know that the medisave account might be exhausted after a week .
Associate Professor Paulin Straughan said : " One hospitalization , for example , a stroke can set you back at tens of thousands of dollars .
Therefore , without the help and support from welfare organizations such as MCYS , majority of Singaporeans might not be able to handle the high cost incurred for taking care of the elderly .
Without the past contributions from these elderly workers , these companies might not be able to be where they are today .
Therefore , it is important that companies try to retain elderly workers , especially when the Singapore government will provide incentives for them when they do so .
These can be seen from the willingness of people to stay longer in the workforce , and to be enrolled into the services and programmes provided by MCYS .
Ageing issues can be further eased if family members took the initiative to encourage their elderly members to stay longer in the workforce , so that they can contribute more to the society , and help to ease household financial stress . The elderly could also accumulate more wealth , and also stay healthier and wiser .
In the current context , public spending on the aged has been significant , especially in developed countries such as Singapore .
With better education system , there will certainly be more literate women joining the workforce , and this may result in them having late marriages .
We will also expect the life expectancy of people to increase due to better healthcare facilities and technology .
Without any doubt , it will be common to see an increase in the aging population .
As such , governments were pushed to invest resources , especially monetary to solve problems . These may include having a barrier free and accessible environment , a scheme to take care of the elderly and subsidies on the healthcare .
This spending on the aged is necessary but should be limited in order to balance the spending between the aged and the country 's developments on infrastructure , education and skills upgrading .
Infrastructure is one of the areas that the government can develop .
More railway lines can be built to allow easy accessibility from one location to another .
Expanding the railway line will reduce the time spent on traveling .
It focuses on the general public as a whole , which rangesanging from the young to the elderly and handicapped rather than mainly on the aged .
However , as construction is in progress , it often causes high pollution level and is unsightly .
But , the ultimate aim of investing expenditure on such a large scale project is to increase the standard of living of people .
Another instance could be the upgrading of roads to cater to the increasing number of vehicles , and to reduce road congestion .
It also facilitates driving within Singapore by making it smoother and providing alternatives roads , which were lesser as compared to the past .
We may also have noticed that our buildings are often undergoing maintenance and upgrading , as it is part of the government 's scheme to maintain the condition of buildings , minimizing the wear and tear after years and most importantly to create a better environment for the public to live in .
The above mentioned could be another area to which the government can divert their expenditure .
The government can invest in additional amenities in schools , such as gymnasiums ; swimming pools ; and indoor sports halls , so as to provide a conducive environment for the students .
Besides that , expenditure can be channeled into increasing the subsidies in education to encourage people to study .
When people are educated , they will be able to contribute to the workforce in the near future .
Moreover , funds should also be diverted to provide skills upgrading for the workers . For instance , a scheme such as " Skills Programme for Upgrading and Resilience " ( SPUR ) was introduced to improve and upgrade the workers ' skills .
The aim was to increase the employment rate by encouraging retrenched people or the elderly to improve and upgrade themselves on the necessary and essential skills to continue to stay in the workforce .
However at times , people may be reluctant to take up such programmes which they perceive as useless .
It is a fact that if the elderly were employed , they would be able to support themselves with their savings .
In order to achieve that , the elderly workers must consistently upgrade themselves to keep up with the existing demands of their jobs , as employers are looking for the most cost effective resource for the organization .
Thus , this not only benefits the general public but also the aged .
In conclusion , although money spent on the elderly can ease the problem of an aging population , it is only effective for a short term and is not a feasible solution .
It will only create more reliance on the government .
Therefore , we should take into consideration the problems that we will encounter in the long run .
By investing enormously in the aged , other areas of developments for the country will be neglected , and this will result in more social problems .
Hence , spending on the aged should be restricted so that resources can be divided equally based on the needs of the various sectors .
There should be a limitation on public spending for the aged .
Over the years , the expenditure on the aged has relatively increased due to a shift towards an aging population .
This is mainly due to the increasing needs of healthcare and welfare services for the elderly .
Should more public spending be used to cater for the ageing population ?
We need to consider other sectors development for the country .
Providing better healthcare and welfare services is more important than before due to the ageing population .
Policies change over time according to the needs of the elderly .
As people are enjoying higher life expectancy today , more spending is expected to provide better healthcare facilities and other services for the aged .
It is observed that in certain countries that are faced with aging population problem , there is an significant increase in hospitalization rates as well as physician services over the years .
However , the increased health costs should not be borne solely by the government .
People are more educated and can work longer to support themselves today .
Furthermore , to stimulate economic growth , the government needs to work out carefully the national budget allocated different sectors in the country .
Therefore , we need to consider other government expenditures such as education , infrastructure as well as research and evelopment ( R&D ) .
Education spending has always been looked upon as a significant matter in the government 's agenda .
Finance Minister Tharman Shanmugaratnam said that " despite the recession , the government will upgrade both the 'hardware ' and 'software ' of the education system "
[ ( Tan , 2009 ) .
Retrieved September 15 , 2009 from http : //www.straitstimes.com/Breaking + News/Singapore/Story/STIStory_329588.html ] There should be sufficient funds set aside to provide updated facilities for schools , as well as to maintain the quality of the teaching force .
By ensuring that the younger generations are well educated , we would be assured of achieving growth and stability for the nation .
Thus , public expenditure on education should never be overlooked .
The government should also focus its spending on developing infrastructure .
The government will increase public sector construction spending to between $ 18 billion and $ 20 billion in 2009 .
As the economy thrives , infrastructure such as commercial buildings , bridges , roads and rails are developed constantly .
Infrastructure reflects how developed a country is and enables people and goods move about quickly .
For instance , the transportation network in Singapore is always developing to provide citizens with top grade transportation as far as possible .
A recent development will be the introduction of the Circle Line to the existing MRT network .
Iconic infrastructure developments are the Integrated Resort ( IR ) and casino , which aimed at attracting foreign investment and tourist attraction .
The remaking of housing estates is seen in various estate renewal programmes such as Home Improvement Programme ( HIP ) and Lift Upgrading Programme ( LUP ) .
Expanding infrastructure spending reflects a country 's economic favourably and helps in more foreign investment .
For example , the South Korean government plans to increase investment in research and development by more than 10 percent a year in 2010 .
Retrieved on September 16,2009 from http : //english.people.com.cn/90001/90778/90858/90863/6639500.html ] Many people see science and technology as a longtime investment and thus expenditure on R&D has not been affected even in the current economic crisis .
Singapore will become a biomedical hub that is globally competitive and will also turn into a trusted centre for scientific and related commercial activities .
Investment in R&D boosts economic growth , increases productivity and generates new product to improve the quality of lives .
The needs of a country will constantly change according to the fluctuation of the economy .
Even though public spending on the aged has increased due to the shift towards an increasingly population , there should be a limit on this spending so as to divert the assets for developing other areas .
The educated aged group should also be able to plan for themselves in terms of healthcare and social services .
The proportion of public spending on various sectors should be divided properly in order to promote economic growth and maintain a sustainable development for the country .
Governments have thought of many measures to help improve the aging population situation .
They have invested time and money to research on policies that can help solve the aging population crisis .
Since such a trend is likely to happen in the short run , much has been done to buffer its negative impact on society .
Therefore , I agree to a large extent , that current research developmentand policies have helped to ease the aging process .
Demographic changes such as a growing population will have serious consequences on health issues in developed countries .
To deal with such challenges , governments have only two options , and one of which is to reduce the future old-age dependency burden by increasing available resources .
By lowering the barriers and making it easier for the elderly to be employed , more elderly people would have jobs and would be able to generate income for the country .
Therefore , the government has been granting permanent residency ( PR ) status and citizenships more freely than before , as well as providing incentives such as tax rebates to attract foreign companies to invest in Singapore 's economy .
Secondly , healthcare for the society is very important .
However , some may argue that the topic on " health " is very subjective as everyone 's body condition is very different .
Therefore they argue that more and more money would be spent on researching new technologies to cure illnesses .
However , research has shown that for many diseases like diabetes , kidney failure , heart diseases and so forth , the chances of recovery are much higher if the disease were diagnosed in the early stages .
In conclusion , I feel that no matter how much research is being done , it will not completely solve the aging problem .
Only by having more children will the burden be spread over a larger and more affluent future generation .
Therefore , I conclude that although current research and development and policies have helped to ease the aging process to a large extent , they have not managed to fully solve the problem .
With the decline of fertility rate in recent years , statistics have shown that in Singapore , the ratio of younger persons aged 15-64 to every resident aged 65 and above fell from 10.4 in 1998 to 7.5 in 2009 .
As a result , Singapore will face the dangers of an aging population .
Hence , public spending on the aged will increase .
At the same time , with the rising economy , national expenditure would eventually increase .
In recent decades , academic debate has centered upon gauging the effect of modernization or industrialization on levels of familial support .
" ( Cowgill and Holmes , 1972 ) . This would indicate that the government should be prepared to meet the need of welfare services for the aged .
For instance , facilities such as Day Care Centres and Old Folks Homes will be in high demand as the ratio of the elderly to the younger generation is higher in the near future .
In the long run , if the government focused only on the development of the country and neglected the aged , it will result in economic inequality of " the poor getting poorer , the rich getting richer " concept .
This would cause the people to lose their motivation to work harder for the country , as well as their belief in filial piety which is commonly known in Asia .
In Singapore , the government has strongly upheld the belief that familial support of the elderly is ideal , but if the individual family could not handle their aged , the government would have to interfere to help .
However , focusing solely on the aged population would not be the best approach .
This is because there is still a need to contribute to the country 's economic growth to sustain the well-being of its people .
This would decrease the percentage of them being sick and also help them to build healthier and happier lifestyles .
However , too much help from the government can lead to its people being too dependent on the government .
This would result in the lack of motivation to work .
Therefore , the government can introduce policies to encourage its people to invest in their future during the early stages of their lives .
In conclusion , public spending on the aged should have a limit .
This would not only benefit the nation 's development but also improve its the well-being of its people .
Furthermore , better education for the younger generation would lead .
Due to the advancement in technologies and the implementation of efficacy policies by the Singapore government , the problems that accompanied the aging process have been alleviated to a large extent .
Take for instance , in the past , due the lack of current research and developments available , most elderly who were diagnosed with illnesses were unlikely to recover and in most cases , they would have to stay in bed for the rest of their lives .
Furthermore , in the past , elderly spinsters and bachelors of whom they have no family members to turn to in their old age , often faced financial problems after they have stopped working .
However , unlike the past , most elderly now are coping well with the aging process physically , economically and mentally .
As indicated in the statistics pertaining to the health status of the senior citizens ( National Survey of Senior Citizens , 2005 ) , it is stated that " among senior citizens aged 55 and above , only 35.8 % reported to have a clean bill of health .
" As such , it would seem that despite the great advancement in the area of medical technologies , a substantial percentage of the elderly is still suffering from medical ailments such as high blood pressure , bone or joint problems , diabetes and sight problems .
This may suggest that the current medical technologies have not helped to ease the aging process .
On a closer look , although the present medical technologies may not be able to slow down the aging process , these technologies may help to prevent medical ailments from occurring and also in some cases , alleviate the sufferings which the elderly have to go through .
For example , the invention of high blood pressure and diabetes monitors helped people , especially the elderly to be more aware of and to be more able to monitor their own health conditions .
With proper medication , the 2 medical ailments would have a lower probability to lead to kidney damage . The treatment of this illness is more difficult than the common ailments .
As such , the advancement in medical technologies have shown to ease the aging process through medical innovations that prevent common ailments from exacerbating into serious illnesses .
Although , in today 's context , around 66 % of the senior citizens aged 55 and above are provided with regular cash contributions from their children ( National Survey of Senior Citizens , 2005 ) , there is still a significant number of senior citizens who faced financial difficulties in their old age , especially if these senior citizens are retired singles .
Furthermore , besides ensuring that the elderly will have sufficient funds for their living expenses after their retirement , the Singapore government also ensures that the elderly are able to cope with the hefty and long term medical expenses in their old age through the implementation of policies such as the Eldershield ( Healthcare Financing , year ) .
" ElderShield is an affordable severe disability insurance scheme which provides basic financial protection to those who needs long-term care , especially during old age
" ( citation ) . Thus , the elderly will be able to draw on the monthly payout to aid in paying for his or her long-term care expenses .
Lastly , the grieving process ( Old Adult Mental Wellbeing , Health Promotion Board , year ) is part and parcel of the aging process whereby for the elderly , it is more common for them to lose their family members and friends in their old age and thus , this makes each single loss even more unbearable .
However , with the current developments and advanced medical help available , these sufferings would be reduced .
For instance , one such facility development of which the elderly would be able to seek help from would be the REACH Elderly Care Centre , where the elderly would be able to receive day care , supervision and supportive help .
In addition , the place also serves to offer ample opportunities for the senior citizens to mingle with other people and take on meaningful activities so that they would be healthier both mentally and physically .
Furthermore , with the advancement in medical sciences , the elderly can also seek professional help such as consulting the therapists and psychologists to assist them in getting over the grieving process , if the intensity of the grief does not fade off after a long period of time .
As such , with the different types of facilities and medical developments available , the elderly no longer have to suffer in silence .
It is ironic that how everybody wants to have longer life expectancy but yet , no one wants to grow old .
Nevertheless , the aging process is an unavoidable , undesirable , problem-ridden phrase of life that we are required to go through .
However , with the advancement of technologies and implementation of effective policies , the problems associated with the aging process are eased to a large extent. .
With the help of the technologies and various , the elderly would definitely be able to better manage their lives in old age .
The Singapore population comprises its citizens and permanent residents .
Between the year 1947 and 1964 , approximately 1 million babies were born .
.
These baby-boomers will reach 65 years old by 2012 and form the largest aged population that Singapore has ever experienced .
Singapore is a developed country where the government has already spent millions on the country 's development .
Singapore 's government has invested millions of dollars over the years to ensure that Singapore grows as a modern and sophisticated city .
The government has pumped money into various areas such as the transportation system , infrastructure , education , technology , health and welfare benefits for its people .
The government uses these developments to boost the economy .
Singapore 's transportation system is well-known to be one of the best in the world .
Almost all parts of Singapore are very accessible by road .
The government promotes tertiary education to acknowledge its importance .
As one of the developed countries in the world , Singapore has only its citizens as its resource .
Although the standard of living in Singapore has increased , Singapore citizens are able to cope with it .
This is because the government provides subsidies to the people in housing , healthcare and education .
With these developments , Singapore has produced a skilled workforce and an and efficient infrastructure . These developments attract many foreign investors to this country .
Factors which have attracted the MNCs to do business here is a corruption- free government .
Hence , MNCs feel safe and secure to trade and set up businesses in Singapore .
In fact , the strategy used by Singapore 's government has proved to be a success . For instance , The economy has shown growth that averaged at 8.0 % between 1960 and 1999 to 9.9 % in 2000 .
There is not much that the government needs to spend on developing the nation .
With a skilledworkforce , advanced facilities and infrastructure , as well as with the presence of MNCs , Singapore 's economy is expected to grow in years to come .
The issue is to maintain them .
Now the government should focus on sustaining and maintaining all these developments that are already in existent .
Furthermore , land is scarce in Singapore .
Knowing that the baby-boomers would reach 65 years old by 2012 , the government should invest on them .
This is necessary because if the baby boomers started to pull their money out of the banks and the stock market , it will affect the total government spending .
They may not be able to pay taxes if they have lost their jobs and thus , the government should consider spending its funds wisely .
It should be aware of issues that Singapore will be facing in years to come .
Thus , this would allow to remain employable .
By working longer , baby boomers could accumulate savings for retirement and share their and experience with the society .
More funds are required to encourage later retirement .
It is only through upgrading of skills and knowledge that the effectiveness of elderly employees would be increased .
Although the elderly are prone to illnesses and more funds are for them as compared to the younger employees in an organisation , they have the experience to guide the younger employees .
Due to a fast-paced and stressful working environment , the elder generations would not be motivated to extend their stay in the workforce .
Although the elderly could only do the minimum for the society and the country , they made up a higher percentage of the population and should not be ignored .
There is a need to develop a sense of urgency over the ageing population issue .
In shaping Singapore 's economy , the government should not neglect the social issues associated with an ageing population .
According to the Singapore Department of Statistics , Singapore resident population has grown older with the median age of resident population rising from 35 years old in 2003 to 36.4 years old in 2007 .
The proportion of elderly person in Singapore aged 65 years and above increased from 7.4 per cent in 2003 to 8.5 per cent in 2007 , making it the second fastest ageing population in the world after Japan .
The increase in life expectancy and decline in fertility are the two main causes of an ageing population .
Singapore is concerned with the growth of an ageing population because many older persons have minimal or no income .
Public spending on the aged should not be limited , though other aspects of public spending should not be compromised too . This is to maximize spending on the aged .
The burden on an average working class adult has increased with yearly inflation and higher standards of living .
Pressure on the working population will be exceptionally high which may in turn cause social problems .
Therefore , health care for the aged should be included as part of the public expenditure fund , to lighten the burden of the working population .This is an investment that should not be overlooked .
The elderly often find themselves abandoned by their children , and this is due to a greater emphasis on individualism among the younger generation . This has eroded traditional values such as filial piety .
Hence , the government can intervene by supporting the elderly using public spending to make sure that they are self-sufficient .
These include day care centres , wheelchair-friendly access , subsidies for medical costs and transport .
Having established that public spending on the aged should not be limited , other aspects of government spending , however , should not be neglected .
Money could be diverted to tourism and military uses , as these may be crucial areas that require public spending .
According to the Singapore Tourism Board , Singapore achieved a record of 9.7 million visitors in 2006 , from 8.9 million in 2005 , and is hoping to achieve a target of 17 million visitors by 2015 .
In order to achieve the target , Singapore has recently invested a substantial amount of money into the development of the two integrated resorts in order to remain competitive among Asian countries and other popular tourist attractions .
The Integrated Resort is one of the many strategies that Singapore adopts to generate more economic growth and boost the country 's Gross Domestic Product ( GDP ) .
Compared to the many areas of development , military defense is among one of the important because it serves as a deterrent to protect a country 's sovereignty .
Money spent on purchasing weapons and armours is necessary to ensure that the military men of the nation are well-equipped in an event when war occurs .
In addition , money could also be expended on local or overseas training to ensure that the military men are trained with relevant knowledge to defend the country .
In conclusion , public spending on the aged should not be limited .
Instead , the government should allow its public spending on the aged to hover at certain percentage .
In this materialistic world where we live in , when something loses its value , it will be forgotten .
Many elderly are neglected by their children and have become homeless .
There was case of a daughter who cheated her mother into selling her apartment and taking away the money , leaving her mother homeless on the street .
The National Welfare Association will lessen the burden of neglected elderly by providing shelters for them in Old Folks Home .
However , such approaches will not remove the root cause of the problem .
In addition , it will generate the idea that it is okay not to look after the elderly as the government will step in and provide the elderly a to stay .
This will only encourage more infilial children to neglect their elderly parents .
Hence , sustainable solutions to the aging problem start with the children who are supposed to be taking care of them .
The root cause starts with children who have no wish to take care of their parents .
Japan is known to have many homeless elderly and by analyzing the country ' performance , it is known that Japan has the highest expenses among many countries .
Besides the cultural aspect , this gives us a slight indication that the people there may have problem handling their finance .
In Singapore , this is especially true for people who fall under the sandwich generation that have to pay for the expenses of their children and parents .
Taxpayers ' money can be used to generate more jobs and higher income for the people , resulting in better economic growth .
In this way , the children will have better financial means to take care of their parents .
Educating the society on aging issue helps in the long run .
Just like isues such as smoking and yellow ribbon , the issue of aging should be highlighted in the country .
This approach not only brings awareness to the people , but also educates the people on what will happen to the elderly when they are being neglected .
Understanding the issue will change the way the society thinks about aging elderly , taking it to the level of humanity instead of practicality .
Laws should also be implemented to help control the issue of the elderly being neglected .
Fine should be made on families that neglect their parents .
Laws should not be made severe , as there are also many reasons to why one has to neglect their elders .
Issues like financial problems and time allowance may prevent one from taking care of their elderly .
.
In this way , the welfare of the elderly will be taken care of by their families and the number of homeless elderly will be lessened .
In a nutshell , public spending should be wisely used to provide aids to the elderly .
Instead of giving help directly to the elderly , the government should tackle the root of the problem by getting the people to take care of their elderly parents .
This can be done by improving on the economy , educating the young on the importance of taking care of the elderly and implementing laws .
These approaches may not produce immediate effects , but they are useful for the future generations .
I strongly agree with the sixth strategy which encourage people to provide for their own old-age dependency .
That is also why so many countries are engaged in setting up effective systems to encourage or compel people to save money for later use .
For instance , China has developed a system which requires people to turn over some money every year according to individual income and willingness .
This policy has been implemented smoothly , since both the government and citizens can benefit from it .
It not only lightens the burden of government but also gives a sense of security to the citizens .
To a certain extent , it can also inspire individual enthusiasm for work .
However , some people insist that the government should take responsibility in looking after the old people by increasing their pensions and promoting the funding of programs for the elderly , for the elderly have contributed to the development of their countries and deserved the care and respect .
From my perspective , it may not be practical , especially for developing countries with large population .
It can not solve the problem effectively , and may also lead to the economy being subjected to increasing pressure .
All in all , encouraging people to set aside some money for themselves is the wisest method .
Due to an increase in the standard of living , better medical treatment is available and this has caused the life expectancy of the people to increase .
Hence , for a small country such as Singapore of which human resource is the key factor to success , it is important that the citizens constantly upgrade themselves with the latest knowledge .
Therefore , the government should devote more capital to ensure that the education system remain relevant in today 's dynamic global economy .
This certainly seems to be more important than pouring money into public spending for the elderly .
Some may say that it is more important for a country to have an excellent research and development sector than healthy , happy senior citizens .
Research and development plays an important role in the innovation process which results in high quality products and successful businesses .
Research and development will very likely increase the levels of overseas investment as foreign multinational companies will see the country as a good place for business .
A strong education system and a strong research and development sector in a country that is not unified and chaotic will not be able to reap the benefits that they are supposed to generate .
Thus , public spending on the elderly does provide important benefits to the country and should not be limited .
Lastly , a country that does not take care of its elderly sufficiently runs the risk of having its younger population abandoning it and migrating to other countries .
Majority of them would think that their hard work have not paid off .
They have worked so hard to contribute to the economy but the government does not provide sufficient care for them when they are old .
Hence , no more future leaders will be staying back to help the country to boost the economy and run the country .
Therefore , public spending on the elderly should still be continued in the form of financial policies and benefits .
In conclusion , we should not see the elderly as a burden but an asset .
Even though other sectors such as education and research and development are important to us , we should not forget our earlier contributors .
They are the ones who build up a nation from the basic to what we have now .
Therefore , we must be grateful to those who have helped us and created a sense of belonging to everyone .
In this way , younger generation will then work harder for the nation in future .
The baby boom in the 1960s and the current low fertility rate in Singapore has made Singapore into one of the fastest aging population in the world .
Living expenditure for the elderly has increased in terms of rising medical costs and standard of living .
The people are the assets of Singapore and they have contributed to the country 's strong economic position .
The improvement in medical research has lengthened the life expectancy of the people .
However , longer life spans will inevitably incur a larger amount of long term health care expenses for the aged and the deterioration of physical mobility and communication might cause them to lose the ability to work and be self-sustained .
The situation is worse for a segment of the elderly who are unmarried and inadequately educated .
They stand in the least advantageous position should there be a limit on public spending on the aged because they do not have families to depend on and the depletion of their savings will eventually result in starvation and homelessness .
Moreover , without the government 's support for the elderly , the burden of caring for these elderly will fall solely on the " sandwich generation " of individuals who will be financially responsible for their family , children and parents .
Hence , there is a need for the government to intervene by using part of the public funds to care for the aged population and ease the burden on the working population .
Singapore has invested much of our public spending on the other areas of the country 's development , like defence and the economy .
Although these areas of development are necessary for the development of Singapore , we should not neglect the importance of public spending for the aged .
By providing more for the elderly and improvising health care polices , the government can actually improve the living conditions of the aged , which will in turn reduce possible social issues .
Furthermore , if the government can maintain social stability in its country , it may then focus on the other aspects , such as defence .
Such coordination between the working population and the government will benefit the aged who are concerned with the provision of welfare from the state and this will give them a sense of security .
An ageing population is a worldwide issue that is faced by all countries .
As a population gets older there are social , political and economical impact on everyone .
The social impact would be that people have to work harder because the younger generations have to be more productive to make up for the elderly 's low productivity .
An aging population will have a serious consequence on health issues in developed nations because more medical support will be needed by the elderly .
It will hinder the countries ' growth in the long run because more tax payers ' money will be used for public spending on the aged .
However , public spending should be diverted to other areas of the countries ' development , like the economy and the technological sector , which may help in prolonging and enhancing the quality of life for the elderly .
Investing in economic growth will reduce the stress on the younger generation as more jobs will be will be available .
More businesses will start and more jobs will be created , which means more people will be employed . Thus , there will be more income tax , which means more government funds to help support the elderly .
When more work is available , more people will be able earn and save more , and this means that the standard of living for the working people will improve and they will be able to support the elderly as they are more affluent .
An increase in economic growth will also mean that people are earning more , and thus there will be an increase in the taxes which will be used in providing better medical support to the elderly . Thus , this will provide for both the working people and the elderly .
Investing in technology in the form of research and development will allow medical advancement as well as better facilities for medical cares .
New drugs or medicine will be available for the sick elderly and more cures for diseases and sickness will be available to help the elderly This may reduce the stress on the working force in the sense that they do n't have to worry about their elderly parents .
New technology or medicine to prolong and enhance the quality of life will be available for the elderly and this will reduce the stress on the working force and in return increase its productivity as they are more focused at work and they are able to spend more time at work .
.
This will allow for better economical growth for the country , which in turn means more funds for the government to spend on the elderly .
Investing in the social welfare of working adults by providing better qualities of life and better living standards will help to reduce their stress and allow them to provide better for the elderly .
Some of the facilities provided by the Singapore government were park connectors near working industries and central business district . This allows working people to enjoy working and still have a good quality of life .
This helps to encourage working people to work and play better and gives them a better standard of living .
In conclusion , public spending on the aged should be limited and the money should be diverted to the other areas of the countries ' development , like economic growth , research and development and the welfare of the people . This will allow the people to solve their own financial problem and allow the government to invest and provide for other areas of the country 's development .
Politicians and law-makers are often debating on how much money should be spent on each sector of the country .
However , there are other areas that require cash inflow to facilitate and push the society forward .
Such areas include the military sector , the security sector , the education sector , the research and development sector , etc .
When one grows old , his body will go through many and soon , he will not be as fast or agile as he was before .
The government steps in to make the environment more user-friendly , which includes the installation of handrails along steps and stairs , the building of gentle slopes around the housing estates and the upgrading of lifts to stop at every floor in older flats .
The elderly become more vulnerable to illnesses and diseases as they age and it would take a much longer for them to recover , unlike during their younger days .
Rising medical costs and inflation would pose a problem for the aged , even for those who had prepared an amount of savings for their golden years .
The government would get involved once again to provide subsidies for the elderly in medical bills and so on .
Terrorism is a growing threat today as it is getting more complicated to understand the terrorists and fight them .
More research and studies would have to be done to learn about them , their thinking and their actions and how one should be prepared to fight against them .
As terrorism spreads , from the bombing of the Twin Towers in United States of America ( NYDailyNews , ) to the Mumbai attacks ( Mail Online , ) , one could see it is becoming much tougher to fight it in the future .
Other than relying on the police and the military forces , the government has to educate the public on the dangers of terrorism and the importance in preventing them .
Thus the need to divert reserves into this area of development is very important .
In Singapore 's context , education starts when a child enters pre-school or kindergarten l .
Government spending in the education sector has been growing each year .
This is due to increasing expenses for the needs to hire teachers and provide subsidized education for the public .
Such costs do not stop once a child leaves secondary school .
If he furthers his studies , more spending will be sustained .
Emphasizing on continual learning and skills upgrading for older workers will help them to remain competitive in the workforce .
For instance , the Skills Programme for Upgrading and Resilience ( SPUR ) ( NTUC Learning Hub , SPUR ) is introduced to employers to encourage them to send their workers to these trainings .
Such courses and workshops are relatively expensive to conduct and thus , the government 's efforts to subsidize them will encourage more workers to upgrade themselves .
This could also keep the older generation longer in the economy and provide for themselves for more years to come , instead of relying on the government , which may in turn , reduce the need to spend on the elderly .
Clearly , spending on the aged is important .
Educating the youth who are our future pillars of support , would equip them with skills so that they can handle potential problems , which in turn could support the elderly population in the future .
Education for the older generation would also help the economy as they will remain competitive and up-to-date with the relevant skills and are able to support themselves for a much longer period of time .
As shown , preventive measures against terrorism is a cost effective way to counter them instead of dealing with the aftermath of an attack .
As the saying goes : " it 's better to be safe than sorry " .
Singapore was ranked third for the highest life expectancy in the world .
Before taking any action , leaders must first realise that any further expansion of retirement benefits would only impoverish future generations and limit future public spending ( Peterson , P.G .
Therefore , I agree that public spending on the aged should be limited so that funds can be diverted to other areas like the Ministry of Finance , Education , Health and National Development .
Each area must not be neglected , as they have significant contributions in taking care of the aging population .
Firstly , for the Ministry of Finance in Singapore , funds must be pumped into the economy to ensure solvency of the country .
For instance , the Monetary Authority of Singapore ( MAS ) and the Inland Revenue Authority of Singapore ( IRAS ) are established to make sure that entities operating within Singapore are attuned to international standards and practices .
All these statutory boards and institutions require funds to run their operations to ensure Singapore 's competitiveness .
.
For example , funds are needed to build good infrastructure and facilities for academic purposes .
After all , the younger generations represent the future of Singapore and they will soon be the ones taking care of the aged .
Funds are also needed to provide effective educational programs to ensure that the young are equipped with fine skills to cope with the demands of the society .
Funds are also needed to educate the young on moral values because moral values are the corner stone of an individual 's character and personality .
Thirdly , funds are needed for the Ministry of Health to ensure that the rising demand of healthcare services for the general public is met .
For example , as mentioned by our Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong ( National Day Rally Speech , 2009 ) , hospitals like Khoo Teck Puat Hospital and Jurong General Hospital will be built to meet the rising demand of increased patients .
Funds from the government are also needed to aid voluntary welfare organizations .
More acute cases could be handled by hospitals and the patients who are less serious can recuperate at home with their families . This in turn is also a cheaper alternative for the patients to cope with the rising healthcare cost .
However , if public spending on the aged is not limited , more financial aid could be given to them , and this in turn will lessen the burden of the younger generation to provide for the elderly .
Lastly , funds are needed for the Ministry of National Development to develop housing policies and to build national parks and neighbourhood parks .
For the former , housing grants , subsidies , CPF schemes are used to ensure that the public could afford a flat .
Funds are also needed to build handicap facilities , for instance , ramps and the Lift Upgrading Program ( LUP ) .
It could be a place for all the residents in the neighbourhood to come together to interact , exercise and make friends .
This would help prevent them from experiencing loneliness and also serve as a channel for the residents to communicate and help each other in times of need .
Therefore , after considering all the factors , I agree that public spending on the aged should be limited as other factors are equally important , such as taking care of the public and ensuring international competiveness and progress of the nation .
Each factor has its own way of contributing to society as a whole and the elderly will benefit directly or indirectly from the developments as well .
Public spending must be cost effective to ensure a steady rate of returns from its investments to allow the country to develop and prosper .
Sufficient public funds are needed to develop different areas of the country which include social , economical , defence and government administration .
To ensure that there are sufficient funds for the country 's development , public spending on the aged should be limited .
In order for the country to develop , funds are needed in the retraining of the workers , expansion of the economic structure and maintenance of a high standard of education in various educational institutions .
Firstly , funds are needed in retraining the workers .
Due to globalization , the training of workers is important to develop and maintain a highly skilled workforce .
The Singapore Budget ( 2009 ) reported that the government will be spending $ 457.7 million of public fund to subsidise training programmes for working Singaporeans .
In Singapore , the Ministry of Manpower and Workforce Development Agency have developed a program called Skills Programme for Upgrading and Resilience or SPUR , to provide training courses at subsidized rate .
Apart from helping population to be re-skilled , SPUR also helps retrenched workers to learn new skills so that they can be reemployed and companies are able to send their personnel for training which helps to reduce retrenchments .
However , there are some older workers who are unable to attend any courses despite being to them at subsidized rates .
Dr Isa Hassan ( citation ) identified three factors on why older workers are not attending any courses .
Firstly , some older workers have weak command of English or are English illiterates as they are school dropouts .
This has discouraged them from attending the training course as it is conducted in English .
Some older workers are earning minimal wages , and thus they have to take a second or part time job to boost their income earning .
Lastly , the older workers are resistant toward going back to school to be re-skilled .
Some older workers may feel embarrassed or dislike going back to school at an old age .
Secondly , government expenditure is needed to expand and maintain the economic structure .
The Singapore Budget ( 2009 ) has reported that the Ministry of Transport and the Ministry of Trade and Industry will be spending a total of $ 4624.83 million on expanding the road network , railway network and developing the industrial infrastructure in Singapore .
Having an excellent infrastructure like an efficient transportation network , will attract foreign investors . This will turn the country into an industrial hub .
The World Bank reported that Singapore had earned the top position of having a top logistic hub in the world .
As a result , the country is able to maintain its economic competitive edge , as well as to create more jobs for the people and enjoy higher standard of living .
Lastly , public spending is required to maintain a high standard of education in various educational institutions .
Investing in education is like investing in the future , so that the future generations are able to meet future challenges .
In Singapore , the government invests heavily on education through subsidising school fees .
In the Singapore Budget ( 2009 ) , the Ministry of Education is investing $ 7,884 million in subsidising school fees .
This is to ensure that school fees are affordable and every citizen is allowed to receive a proper education .
In conclusion , public spending on the aged should be limited so that funds could be used in developing the country through the retraining of workers , expansion of economic structure and maintenance of a high standard of education in various educational institutions .
Funds being used for the country 's development would benefit both the young and old .
The process of gaining knowledge is of paramount importance in developing countries as it would reduce the level of poverty and increase the ability of their people to find quality jobs .
In this way , wealth would be generated and the economy would improve .
Yet , one can not deny the fact that a shortage of educated people would restrict economic expansion .
Thus , it is crucial for countries to invest in a form of education that is desirable for its people to ensure greater economic development .
Through the processes of upgrading , individuals are empowered with the relevant skills and knowledge demanded by the job market .
Nonetheless , it could be refuted that this might promote job hopping .
However , the funding of training programmes should still proceed as it would increase the productivity and capability of the working population in handling any challenges that might surface in the future .
In recent times , terrorists have access to sophisticated technologies that could create greater destruction to the surroundings and are able to instil fear in the people .
In this way , military forces would then be armed with the latest equipment to maintain their fighting capabilities .
For example , the Australian Chamber of Commerce and Industry ( 2000 ) stated that 13 million dollars are spent on national security yearly even though it places an immense pressure on the federal budget .
Therefore , continual support on national defence is important to ensure peace and harmony within the society .
In conclusion , nations should be careful in deciding the amount of money to be spent on each area of development .
Funds should not be spent solely on the elderly as it would hinder the growth of other areas like education , trainings and national security .
As the proportion of elderly persons in the world continues to increase , there is a need for the government to intervene as there will be many elderly who can not support themselves .
Through cutting spending on the aged , the funds can be used in solving problems faced by society and help to relieve the pressure faced by the current working force .
It will need to focus on areas such as education and reduce elder dependency .
The government can also lower barriers to elder employment and stress filial obligation ( Robert B. Friedland and Laura Summer , 2005 ) .
The government will need to spend some money on retraining the elderly to equip them with the necessary skills for the jobs .
Though there may be uncertainties about the results , it is still important to limit public spending on the aged so that some money can still be diverted to other important areas .
Different countries will need to have different solutions specially tailored to fit their own countries and public spending should be split evenly .
Unfortunately , these schemes have not seemed to have appealed to appeal to the vast majority as the birth rate still remains stagnant .
Therefore , having an ageing workforce might not necessarily be negative .
In an ageing society , the social aspects not only include the need for appropriate housing schemes but also health care systems for present and future generations of elderly .
An elderly-friendly built environment is a key principle to which the elderly elderly can adjust and integrate themselves into the community .
For instance , accessible infrastructure provides a safe and comfortable environment for the elderly to use in their their old age .
Hence , with these schemes , it is proven that the elderly in Singapore are given top priority in the community .
Needless to say , the nation would have problems to support the increasing spending on the elderly in a bearish economy .
Thus it is important for the nation to divert our public spending with the aim of improving the economy .
Just like the elderly are an important asset to a nation , children are an also important asset .
The nation can help the younger generation by diverting its fund on other areas .
Therefore , funds should be diverted to assist children 's development .
But there is a need to remember that not all people can fully support themselves for training programs .
The three reasons provided explain why public funds on elderly should be limited and diverted to other areas of development .
Although the elderly are an important asset , they are not the only asset a nation has .
There will be great age shift between now and 2030 as the proportion of residents aged sixty-five or older will increased gradually ( , 2009 ) .
With regard to the problems , many countries focus much attention on it by introducing policies or by giving out funds in order to reduce the problems caused by the ageing population .
Public spending should be used to provide more options and protection for the elderly .
However , it would be better if the expenses used on the aged is limited so that there will be sufficient funds available for other areas of the country 's development .
This may result in greater productivity among the workers as they tend to be more committed to their work ( , 2009 ) .
