With ageing countries directing much attention to the aged , for instance , spending large sums of money on hiring healthcare workers focusing on the latest medical technology , there will be lesser investments made in other areas like military , tourism , education and research and development .
Secondly , there is a need to limit spending on the aged due to increasing costs of basic necessities ( ,2006 ) .
People aged between 65- 69 years old still form part of the workforce and some of the aged have been providing financial support for grown up children or relatives despite their meagre income .
Furthermore , they have been providing voluntary services by actively involving themselves in community organisations ( ,2007 ) .
The increasing costs will outweigh their contributions .
The United States predicted that the demand for medical care will significantly outweigh the supply of healthcare professionals by the year 2020 ( ,2009 ) .
The Gulf Cooperation Council ( GCC ) is also facing demands for health care where it is likely to increase by 240 percent over the next couple of decades ( Walid,2008 ) .
This will mean that the countries will be diverting plenty of resources on the supply of health care and neglecting the potential of the other areas which may help to generate wealth for the country .
The government directs most of the financial incentives to primary care .
Public spending should focus on areas that play an important part in the country 's development as in the education sector .
According to the Budget Speech ( ) , the government has a budget of S $ 18.1 billion expenditure in social development which mainly comprises six Ministries : Ministry of Education ( MOE ) , Ministry of Health ( MOH ) , Ministry of National Development ( MND ) , Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports ( MCYS ) , Ministry of the Environment and Water Resources ( MEWR ) and Ministry of Information , Communications and the Arts ( MICA ) .
The government heavily subsidises the education fees in schools and tertiary institutions every year to prepare students for the future .
In addition , with the limited funding on the elderly , people would be encouraged to work harder to accumulate more wealth before they retire .
However , some may argue that the government should provide more public spending on health services instead of encouraging the elderly to retire later .
It may seem true in some way as the elderly have less ability to perform as well as the younger work force .
However , there are increasing pressures on social benefits including health services funds especially during the economic crisis .
The limited fund could only be used in those more deserving areas such as public health services . Therefore , the elderly should be encouraged to work harder to reduce the fiscal dependency .
In conclusion , there must be some limitation on the public spending in order to divert the money to other areas which will contribute to the country 's development .
Besides , considerable efforts should also be made to educate the public to lead a more healthy life .
In the developed countries , due to reasons like better healthcare and women joining the workforce , life expectancy increases significantly as the rate of reproduction decreases .
As the population ages , social problems increase .
A better solution would be to limit direct spending on the aged and redirect these resources to aid the country 's development .
This not only improves the economy ; but provides more options for the elders when they have to seek treatment .
This would in turn ease the cost of healthcare for elders and indirectly has the same effect as funding elders ' healthcare costs directly .
Furthermore , the issue is to limit spending and not totally cut it off .
Another area in which money can be directed is to provide skills upgrading training for the workers .
In order to make this an effective policy , the older workers ' skills must be upgraded and kept consistent with the existing demands .
Angelique Chan mentioned that at present , employers tend to be hesitant about hiring older workers and this has led to public debates on this issue ( This affects blue collared workers most extensively , and also happens to be the group of elders that have the highest dependency on the society due to their lower savings .
Providing training like the " Skills Programme for Upgrading and Resilience " , which the Singapore government introduced in 2008 , helps improve workers ' skills .
Those who were retrenched due to company downsizing or the likes of it can take the opportunity to improve their skills and move up the corporate ladder .
By endlessly investing in assisting the elderly , areas of the country 's developments will be overlooked , resulting in more serious social problems like unemployment .
For example , our official retirement age has been raised to 65 . This allows people to work longer to accumulate more wealth for old age .
Many programs have also been set up to retrain the elder workers and upgrade their skills in order to maintain their work productivity .
Furthermore , a mandatory saving scheme , called the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) , has also been set up to ensure people save as they work .
However , the CPF scheme may not be useful as the money that can be used for medical expenses is restricted to Medisave and Medifund .
Moreover , an elder person who is incapable of continuing to work before he meets the official retirement age , is unable to make any withdrawals from his CPF accounts to cover his daily expenses .
Secondly , healthcare system has been restructured to meet the needs of the aging population .
Hasnita ( 2009 ) reported that besides building new hospitals around the neighbourhood , Singapore also focuses on its step-down care sector which includes community hospitals and nursing homes .
Lastly , according to Mr Yap Chin Beng , Director , Estate Administration and Property , talks have been going on with the Housing Development Board ( HDB ) to initiate policies such as constant upgrading to our physical infrastructures to become more elderly-friendly .
The upgrades include lift upgrading to install new lifts which stops on every floor , shelters to the public to the nearest bus stop of the blocks and ramps for people who have difficulties in climbing stairs .
In addition , HDB is also building more studio apartments which are suitable for the elderly as it is customized with elderly-friendly fixtures and fittings .
Nowadays , many countries have to face different problems about the aging population .
It is controversial since many people are afraid that spending too much money on the elderly might decrease national budgets for other areas of development .
Therefore , it is necessary that the public finances spent on the elderly is always considered carefully by the government .
A limited amount of money given to help the aging population is a good issue for both the elderly and the rest of the population which benefits through the development of the different sectors of the country .
It is undoubtedly true that senior citizens always find it difficult to live independently in their old age .
For instance , the Singapore government spent more than 7 percent of the GDP ( gross domestic product ) on supporting the elderly with medical subsidies , public infrastructure and pension schemes ( ) , while the percentage of American GDP for public spending on the elderly rose from 8.5 percent in 1997 to 22.5 percent in 2070 ( Lee , 2008 ) .
Moreover , a significant share of the Gross National Product ( GNP ) went into pension schemes : 0.58 per cent and 1.22 per cent , respectively in Malaysia and Singapore ( Yoon and Hendricks , 2006 ) .
These show us the truth that the government spent a lot of money for the senior citizens .
We need to have the responsibility to care for the elderly .
However , we should not spend such a large amount of money on the elderly since it might cause the loss of financial supporting for other important areas of development such as education , military or infrastructure With the iincrease in the aging population and less financial support from cash-strapped young generation , the government even has a heavier burden on its shoulders to give more money to support the seniors ' lives now .
Then , they might not focus on solving other problems in other areas , which may cause many troubles for the entire development of the country .
The next point is about the consequence of having no limitation on spending money for the elderly .
A research done by the Swiss banking giant UBS reported that Singapore 's long-term economic growth would lose its 3 percentage points because of the demographic changes while Japan 's growth will drop from 9.8 to 8.3 percent and China 's growth may cut down by 1 percent .
Without the guarantee of a healthy economy , the government can not improve or develop any necessary areas in their country .
We actually have many kinds of help for the senior citizens instead of giving them money from the public budget .
In conclusion , it is essential for us to set a limitation for the money we spend on the aged .
The Singapore government provides health subsidies for the elderly to help the hefty medical bills .
On the contrary , the National Survey of Senior Citizens conducted in 2005 showed that 63 % of senior citizens had their own source of income , 66 % received cash support from their children and 62 % of elderly paid for their own healthcare expenses . The provision of health subsidies might be seen as a waste of public fundings since most seniors have the ability to pay for their own medical bills .
To apply for health subsidies , the government assess elderly patients by taking into consideration the gross income of the patient and immediate family members as well as whether patients own any private property .
Town Councils also came up with barrier-free features like ramps leading to blocks and outdoor facilities are provided to facilitate mobility of seniors from homes to public areas .
The Government believes that with later retirement , seniors will be able to support themselves independently and to allow seniors to remain physically , mentally and socially active for as long as possible .
Despite the decreasing productivity of elder workers , they possess vast experience and energy . It will be a waste not to tap their strengths and abilities so that they can contribute meaningfully to their family and the society .
Now , people who are living longer and longer lives must carefully plan their lives. .
