In the context of Singapore , given the socio-economic and political disparity between the possible usages of the fund , the funding for the elderly issues remain controversial .
The budgett Speech in 2009 reveals the measures the Government is taking to sustain the property market ( Singapore Government , 2009 ) .
A 40 % property tax rebate for industrial and commercial properties for 2009 will require about $ 800 million of the national budget ( Singapore Government , 2009 ) .
These expenditures require the Government to explore possible ways to further utilize the national budget in order to continue to develop the nation .
With the power of knowledge and advance technology , the nation can improve its economy and ensure that the well-being of current and future generations of older people is taken care of .
Public spending on the elderly in Singapore is carefully designed , so as to provide the needs of the aged in the best possible way , but the fund is insufficient to support the growing aging population .
Medifund Silver is introduced to provide means-tested socialized care for the needy elderly ( Ministry of Finance , 2008 ) .
The ministry of Finance ( 2008 ) states that the Government will be providing $ 226 million in Medisave top-ups for 734,000 elderly in the nation , this amount of assistance cost breaks down to about $ 290 per elder .
On an individual basis , the elderly are ill-equipped to withstand the possibility of contracting a terminal disease , from the calculations from the Ministry of Health ( 2009 ) , a $ 2,227 treatment bill for heart treatment is likely to devastate most retirees .
To increase the livelihood of the elderly , Dr Balakrishnan ( 2007 ) announced an increment of $ 30 .Forr the elderly living alone with no dependents will receive Public Assistance allowance of $ 290 per month .
An aging population becomes an ubiquitous trend in many developed countries such as Japan .
The idea that reserving a retirement fund in advance can help ease the aging process is regarded as an efficient and feasible method for the government ( Peterson , 2001 ) .
However , some still think that the younger generation and the government are responsible for dealing with the problem of an aging population .
For example , in a Singaporean middle class family , a young couple usually have two to four children and lives in a governmental or private house with mortgage .
In this harsh situation , the elderly parents who have no income and no savings become a big financial strain .
When the young are exposed to both financial and emotional stresses , they can not concentrate on their work .
Some people think that the government has an obligation to help the elderly by providing financial aid .
It seems that the young can shift the liability and solve the financial problem , but these excessive government subsidies will result in draining the public funds quickly .
On the contrary , the government should compel people to save a certain portion of their income into special retirement accounts before they reach retirement age and allow the owners to withdraw the money when they retire .
The Singapore government has been doing well in this respect .
All Singaporeans must save 5 percent of their total income while their employers contribute an additional 20 percent into a government retirement account .
There are two reasons for the Singaporean government to do so .
An aging population is a social problem as well as an individual problem .
The government has a responsibility to help and guide the public to plan their retirement life .
Providing a retirement fund in advance is a long term project and this can only be achieved by raising public consciousness .
Public spending should be limited to a certain degree so that the budget would be diverted to different areas such as education , research and development , tourism and the transportation system of the country .
In most countries , education is considered to be one of the fundamental sectors that the country 's government can develop and improve on .
For that reason , the process of education is considered to be essential for the development of our society such that every child has to go through a minimum of ten years of basic education .
It is crucial that the country has a good education system for future economic development .
However , on the other hand , there should be limited , but adequate percentage of public spending allocated to the aged .
So , does this means that they will die ?
This problem will continue to get worse every year if there is inadequate attention paid .
Though it is important to solve the problem of the graying society , we should limit our public spending in this sector so that we can budget for other aspects of a country 's development , such as the transportation infrastructure .
In conclusion , public spending on the aged should be limited to a certain percentage that is adequate for the welfare of the aged .
By putting a limit for the spending on the aged , we can create more budgets to spend on education , research and development , tourism industry and transportation system as they are equally important to our nation .
Current researches and development/polices have indeed eased the aging process but only to a small extent .
The aging issues that today 's elderly face include active life expectancy , diet/nutrition , disease prevention , health behaviors and beliefs , health service utilization , mental health , long term care etc .
This is necessary to help ease the aging process .
These treatments will be helpful because people get increasingly susceptible to chronic illnesses .
In the context of Singapore , to address this issue , various financial health care schemes like Medisave and Medishield are implemented to help lessen the financial burden for the elderly .
Technology and its advancements have given medical science the forefront to ease the aging process .
Research has found out that by taking nutritional supplements on a daily basis ,it can provide significant health benefits for the elderly , reducing the possibilities of them falling sick .
There are current on-going research on the different types of dietary supplements that can reverse disease , improve the overall health of the elderly and help them to live a longer , happier life .
This in turn slows down the ageing process and promotes a healthy lifestyle .
Preventive measures can be taken by referencing medical brochures/guides , or consulting the doctor on the suitable type of supplements to consume if one has a medical history .
Such well-tested medical products have helped to ease the aging process .
When people grow older , they have to cope with the physical , mental and emotional stresses of being old. .
These stresses will cause negative influences on health as it affects our bodily functions .
However , social policy can address such issues to make the aging process less painful for the elderly .
By exercising , the elderly improves their overall health and helps to prevent chronic diseases .
Social networking helps the elderly battle against loneliness and makes new friends .
However , social policy has to be revised to address the changing needs of the elderly .
However , the easing of the aging process does not only depend on the above factors .
