Furthermore , medical science is one of the effective solutions for the aging process , which helps ease the economic burden for the country by reducing the money for old people 's welfare , diverting it to other areas of the country 's development .
This is expected to reach 20 % in 2030 ( Seah , 2007 ) .
Thus , measures for aiding the increasing aging population in terms of healthcare subsidies and daily expenditures should be proactively prepared .
Firstly , greater productivity should be encouraged with the younger generation being cost-efficient and productive .
Lastly , people could be encouraged to have proactive savings when they have a job to save up for a rainy day ( Peter G. Peterson , 2001 ) .
Therefore , the aging population is not an insurmountable problem , funds could be sub-divided for expenditure in other sectors such as education , tourism and Research and Development ( R&D ) .
Firstly , education is important in Singapore as it secures the future of the younger generation .
At tertiary level , the National University of Singapore ( NUS ) , and the Nanyang Technological University ( NTU ) are leading local universities .
Funds are constantly pumped into the education system for the financing of students and also for constant improvements in the education system .
For example , the Tuition Grant Scheme is provided for the subsidising of high school fees .
Hence , funds have to be constantly injected for new tourist attractions and contingency plans in the case of an economic crisis .
For example , in February 2009 , the Singapore Tourism Board announced that an incentive of $ 90 million has been provided for the BOOST ( Building On Opportunities to Strengthen Tourism ) which is targeted at aiding the tourism sector during challenging times ( Singapore Tourism Board , 2009 ) .
Lastly , R&D is extensively utilized in major institution projects , for innovation and creativity in new developments and for environmental concerns .
For example , R&D is supported by the National Research Foundation which focuses on areas such as Environmental , Water Technologies and Interactive and Digital Media .
In addition , R&D discovered NEWater and ensured its consistent high quality for the past few years ( Channel News Asia , 2009 ) .
Due to globalization , the aged have become richer and of better health .
However , a portion of the population could still need financial help such as those with lower incomes .
Hence , funds spent on the aged should be limited in order to accommodate any high expenses in the three sectors that contribute a large proportion of revenue to the economy .
On the whole , the aging population is not an insurmountable problem .
Hence , public spending on the aged should be limited in order for funds to be sub-divided among the education , tourism and R&D sectors which are the main sources of revenue .
In turn , with more revenue being generated , more benefits and financial aid could be provided to the aged which benefits the country as a whole .
Aging population is a global issue nowadays , especially in developed countries .
This will soon affect Asian countries with serious repercussions .
Due to the size of the increasing aging population , public spending on the aged has been rising .
Hence , this has exerted more pressure on society , which could lead to problems such as low social security , economic depression and inadequate education .
Hence , it is essential to limit public spending on the elderly , so more money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
It is essential to set spending limits on healthcare .
As healthcare services gradually increase , public spending on the aged also increases .
In 2026-2027 , seniors will represent 22 percent of the population and will be responsible for close to 60 percent of total health care spending ( Population Aging,2009 .
An aging population has placed the federal budget on an " imprudent and unsustainable path " and that " passage of time only serves to worsen this situation ( Congress Daily , 2009 ) . " .
To maintain the healthcare system for the elderly , a significant amount of money will have to be spent on it , which may have serious consequences for society .
Therefore , the government should adjust spending on healthcare to an appropriate level .
Setting limits on spending on the aged would raise indignation among the elderly , especially among people without savings , poor single women , and the illiterate .
Some may say it is inhumane to limit spending on the aged .
However , policy makers should always look at the interests of the whole country rather than just focusing on one particular area .
In conclusion , .
Money saved from reduced spending on the aged can then be invested in other areas for instance education .
When education is enhanced , graduates have a higher chance of getting a job and hence contributing to the economic development of the country .
In addition , together with the development of economy , the young adults would be capable of supporting their parents .
Furthermore , they could enjoy high living standards and security in life .
Generally , the government would have enough budget to empower the stable development of the country , and to maintain the welfare and pension system at an acceptable level .
To illustrate that these are only some of the many benefits which can be achieved from reducing spending on the aged .
To conclude , it is vital for the government to limit spending on the aged to a reasonable level , so money can be invested in different aspects of the country 's development .
In the short run , the country may face difficulties , but in the long run it will be beneficial to society .
During the past decades , the lifespan of human beings has been rising rapidly .
Advanceddvanced research and developments in every aspect of life have completely re-defined the word old. .
The aging process refers to changes in the biologicall , physical and social conditions of an individual as time goes by .
People used to think that it was naturally driven and that there was no way to on it .
However , it has eventually been proven that what we used to think is not necessarily right .
Medicine nowadays gives us a strong belief that the aging process is something we can alter .
Results of different research have revealed that there are certain components which help to maintain a healthy cell like antioxidants , enzymes , hormones or " no cellular waste " ( Dr. Grey , 2005 ) . "
Together with cell collapse , diseases like heart disease or cancer , speed up the process .
Luckily , modern medicine can provide procedures to cure serious diseases and to prevent aging .
For example , doctors nowadays can build a complete plan to slow down the aging process ; such a plan includes an individualized nutritional , hormonal , dietary and exercise program .
After six months of joining the program , the biological age of a man can decrease by 20 years .
Developments in technological inventions have been having an impact on detecting and curing aging diseases .
Human beings have an increased understanding of the biological system of their own body
Once the reasons are known , researchers can come up with ideas of how to slow down or even reverse aging .
Besides , there are many other types of equipment which helps in the treatment of anti-aging .
Although almost everyone agrees that economics is a vital component in the world 's life , not many people realize that it also plays an important part in easing the aging process .
The effects caused by the global economy indirectly control the speed of aging .
In developed countries with strong economies , health issues and other social services are sure to be cared much more about than in undeveloped ones .
With a simple comparison between Western societies with those from Africa , significant differences in life expectancy and actual lifespan can be seen. .
While Western people tend to live long happy lives with a small number of serious diseases , people from African countries usually have a much shorter life expectancy .
However , economic problems may have a very bad impact on efforts to slow down the aging process .
This will be reflected in their bad habits like over-working and also harm their mental health , which will shorten their lifespan .
After much research , it is not surprising to know that , usually , the richest man is not the happiest man .
But again , these are individual lifestyles so a person should be able to change it easily by himself putting some understanding into it and by making an effort .
Human beings , with their intelligence , can find ways to ease the aging process .
The only problem left is that with a longer life , what will a person do to give back to society and the next generations ?
Aging population and longer life expectancy will inevitably lead to rapidly increasing elderly residents .
Housing , which is one of the basic needs of elderly people , is significant because the elderly need a safe , pleasing and interactive environment for their old age .
Policymakers have implemented various strategies to ensure older people own a home while enjoying sufficient retirement income for old age dependency .
The elderly will face more specific needs such as the needs for social and healthcare support .
Hence , a residential environment specially planned to meet their physical , social and recreational requirements is a must ( ( Libencore,2009 )
Nowadays , various kinds of retirement housing is being developed in many countries like the United States Japan and Singapore .
In Australia , the Granny Flats , which are integrated with elder-friendly fixtures and fittings , have been developed to facilitate independent living of the elderly .
Besides , housing developers nowadays are focusing on creating a barrier free housing estate in order to enhance the
A barrier free environment allows elderly people to have safe and easy access to the social facilities and amenities within their neighborhood .
For example , the Singapore government has committed lots of funds to improving the mobility of elderly people by retrofiting lifts to stop on every floor in public housing .
However , a safe and accessible environment for elderly people is vital .
It can lead to healthy , increased well-being and an
Therefore , it can be anticipated that more elderly-friendly features will be set up in our neighborhood in future .
Most countries have provided various housing schemes to ensure an adequate supply of affordable accommodation for the aging population .
Under these schemes , housing developers are subsidized with lower land costs to build retirement housing , while needy elderly are given priority access to public housing .
It may be argued that a number of elderly people are " asset-rich , cash-poor " .
They own a house but do not have sufficient funds to meet their basic needs in old age ( Ministry , 2006 ) .
Nevertheless , there are policies that allow the elderly to monetize their housing assets .
In Singapore , the Lease Buyback Scheme helps the elderly in smaller flats to monetize flat value whilst continuing to stay in the same flat .
Hence , it can be noticed that the housing needs as well as the financial needs of elderly have been effectively tackled by various public policies .
On the other hand , senior activity centres are also developed in housing estates to encourage the elderly to remain integrated in society .
Indeed , these strategies have effectively enabled elderly people to lead a fruitful and meaningful social life .
Clearly , the quality of life of elderly people has become more enjoyable through various housing developments , policies and improvement programmes .
These efforts have successfully eased the issues of an aging population .
A blending of housing schemes and developments that help older people to live as independently as possible can be looked forward to in the future .
One cause for this is related to the baby boomers , who are mostly now in their late fifties or early sixties .
In Singapore , this constitutes to 31 % of its population and approximately half of the workforce .
born in 1946 to 1964 , they are fast approaching the national retirement age of 63 .
In other words , in 10 years ' time , half of the citizens who are currently employed at work would have been retired .
Among some other issues that the elderly face are those of deteriorating physical condition and old-age sickness , which might cause a strain on the local healthcare system and financial system of the country .
In anticipation of this , governments have set in place policies as well as initiatives to ease the ageing process for both the individual and society .
In the context of Singapore , some of these include mandatory personal retirement funds , development of the health sector to better manage an ageing population , as well as encouraging longer working lives .
The CPF is a mandatory savings plan for workers , where a portion of their income is being set aside in this fund , and will be made available to them once they have retired .
This policy provides for financial security for the elderly as they would be financially dependent , and need not rely on public initiatives or their children for money in their golden years .
With this policy , the government is then able to redirect resources to more vital sectors .
Critics of this position point out their concerns over the misuse of the funds once it is being made available .
Participants of this new and compulsory scheme named " Lifelong Income for The Elderly " ( LIFE ) will receive lifelong monthly payouts from their CPF accounts .
Instead of being granted with a lump sum of money upon retirement , this ensures that the elderly do not exhaust their retirement funds too quickly , thereby easing reliance on public funds .
Another policy introduced by the Singaporean government is to encourage the citizens to work longer .
This may be implemented by giving tax rebates or financial incentives to companies which are proactive in the employment of older workers .
There is also evidence to show that the government is encouraging this ; such as from the proposed increase in retirement age from 63 to 65 years by 2012 .
A longer working life would alleviate the manpower shortage in the next decade , when a majority of the baby boomers are set to retire .
At the same time , with more social interaction at work , the elderly will not feel lonely .
This allows the elderly to know that they are still being appreciated , and on top of that , it is beneficial for them . A study ( Robert , 2007 ) has shown that the elderly who feel less lonely have a lower risk of getting Alzheimer 's disease .
This might reduce potential foreign investments .
However , the correct implementation of this policy will help to solve this problem .
By acknowledging that the elderly are slightly slower than their younger counterparts , companies can arrange for more suitable jobs for them .
Equipped with their valuable experience , the elderly are the best candidates to offer advices , and to groom individuals .
Therefore , they will be financially independent .
For example , advances in surgery have helped developed a non-invasive surgery technique for glaucoma , one of the main leading diseases among the elderly .
One impending problem with such rapid technological advances in medicine would be the rising cost of healthcare which is brought about by the intensive research processes to develop new cures and treatments .
With most of the elderly retired and having no source of income , they might be unable to fund their medical expenses should the need arise .
Introduced by the Ministry of Health in 1984 , Medisave would set aside a portion of an individual 's income to be made available to fund medical expenses should the need arise .
With this fund , most Singaporeans will retire with a sum of money which can be used to pay for medical expenses .
This reduces the possible reliance of public funds for funding medical expenses for the elderly .
In conclusion , this essay has illustrated that the current policies in Singapore have helped ease the ageing process to a large extent .
Policies such as implementing the CPF , raising the retirement age and developing healthcare policies have helped to ease the ageing process in the society , thereby reducing the effects of an ageing population .
The issue of an ageing population is a great challenge faced by many developed countries in the 21st century .
The great advances in medical technology over the years have resulted in improvements in the health conditions of individuals , and hence reducing the likelihood of them contracting life-threatening diseases .
The life expectancies of individuals have increased due to better accessibility to healthcare services and facilities .
As such , this has increased the need for public spending on the aged in order to fund for the needs of the elderly which include the construction of facilities for the elderly and the provision of healthcare subsidies .
It could be argued that public spending on the aged is being carried out at the expense of a country 's development in other areas . These areas include the education sector which will increase the productivity of a country , and also infrastructure and transport facilities which will serve as attractions for direct foreign investments .
However , Jenson ( 2007 ) reported that it is inevitable that individuals have a higher tendency to consume more healthcare services as they age because of their susceptibility to diseases .
Thus , it is not practical to limit public spending on the aged so that the money can be used alternatively for a country 's developments .
As such , it will be even tougher for the government to cater to the growing needs of the elderly due to a constraint budget , and this problem will affect countries facing an ageing population , such as Japan .
Opponents of this position argued that there is no need to divert too much resources to the elderly because they are no longer contributing to the society .
For instance , the investing of funds for research and development will raise the productive capacity of the country , thereby attracting more direct foreign investments .
However , it is wrong to regard the aged as a burden , because the aged is a national asset that should not be neglected by the society .
Even after they have retired , they continue to contribute to the society , but in different ways , such as taking care of their grandchildren on behalf of their children who are at work .
In this way , they help to coordinate the work life and family life of the working adults
( Conference of European Churches 2007 ) . Consequently , the aged , with their insights and experiences , is a valuable asset to the society and thus public spending on the aged should not be limited .
In addition , spending on the elderly might increase the financial burden of the future generations .
This problem is particularly pertinent in countries challenged by an ageing population and low fertility rate .
This could be due to increased women participation in the workforce , later marriages , and financial costs of having children .
In future , the ageing population might worsen if low fertility rate persisted .
The Inter-Ministerial Committee on Aging Report ( 1999 ) states that in 1999 , 7.3 % of the population comprises older Singaporeans aged 65 and above , and it is expected that they will make up 19 % of the population by 2030 .
They perceived public spending on the aged as a form of liability to a country because such spending brings no future benefits to the country , and may cause the country to neglect its development in essential areas , such as infrastructure and transport facilities , which serve as a pulling force for foreign investments .
Thus , if a limit was not imposed , the economy of a country will be adversely affected in the long run .
However , instead of limiting fiscal spending on the aged , there are alternatives that can improve the productivity of a country .
For instance , when older workers are retrained , they can be as productive as younger workers , and this will also increase their employability .
Alternatively , there should be some adjustments on fiscal spending on the aged based on their percentage in the country 's population .
This will affect the elderly who are either single or have no children , and those who have low educational level .
When they fall ill , the high costs of medical fees may discourage them from seeking medical care , and as a result , their health conditions may deteriorate over time .
As they age , they become more susceptible to diseases , such as osteoporosis .
It will come to a time when they are left with no choice but to seek medical help for their illnesses ; but since they are left with little savings , they are unlikely to be able to pay for the medical expenses .
It is one 's social responsibility to be healthy , and to be accountable for one 's medical expenses should one seek healthcare services , instead of relying on the government for subsidies to lower one 's financial burden .
However , the presence of a fiscal crisis might not necessarily be attributed to fiscal spending on the aged .
The facilities built for the elderly should not be seen negatively because these facilities provide long-term benefits to every individual in the country , since ageing is an unavoidable process .
This applies to the healthcare subsidies , as one will hope that one can be entitled to such privileges when one has limited savings , regardless of one 's age .
In conclusion , instead of placing a limit on the public spending on the aged , the government can look into the few alternatives proposed to ensure that the elderly will not be neglected and will be given sufficient attention as the country pursues its development .
With an increasing number of Singaporeans belonging to the golden age group of sixty-five years old and above , Singapore needs to deal with the financial challenges of an aging population .
An aging population , the result of a decreasing fertility rate and longer life expectancies , will certainly affect Singapore 's economy .
Although the net impact on the Singapore government 's financial position is unsure , public spending on the aged should not be limited and should vary accordingly to the needs of the country .
The population in Singapore is increasing yearly and aging rapidly ( Singapore Department of Statistics , 2008 ) .
Public spending on the aged should fluctuate according to the composition of the aged citizens within the population of Singapore .
Public spending on the aged should not be limited .
Public spending should reflect the current composition of the aged citizens within the Singapore population .
On the other hand , others might argue that by not limiting the public spending on aged means that lesser budget will be allocated to other areas of Singapore 's developments , such as education , defence and health sectors .
This would cripple the economy of Singapore , which has already been affected by the shrinking workforce .
However , by spending more on the aged does not necessarily denote that budget spent on the development of Singapore will be affected .
This is because the public spending could come from the surpluses that Singapore has accumulated over the years .
Aged citizens will require for basic healthcare and treatment .
According to the National Institute of Aging ( 2007 ) , experts predicted that there will be a huge rise in disability resulted from increases in age-related chronic disease in all regions of the world .
This implies that public spending should not be limited as it will be required to subsidise costly healthcare expenses .
This is because the aged population will not be able to afford the financial burden for the recurrent treatment of their illnesses .
Truly , aged citizens accounted for greater than 40 % of the total hospitalisation days in public sector hospitals in 2006 ( Ministry of Heath , 2007 ) .
On the other hand , it is fortunate that the Singapore Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) , which is the fundamental pillar of our social security framework for the aged , lends itself readily to provide for the needs of aging population .
Each citizen 's CPF account consists of Medisave , Medishield and Medifund , which help individuals to put aside portions of their income to meet their medical expenses when they are old .
The medisave accounts assist older Singaporeans to pay for their expensive medical bills .
Public spending will keep increasing and should not be limited as the aging population in Singapore progresses .
In addition , elderly are having higher life expectancies rate due to the advancement of medical healthcares and technologies .
This would imply that lots of public funds would be required to build an environment with suitable facilities for the elderly .
Public spending will be required and should not be limited for modifications works , such as lift upgrading projects that enable the lift to stop at every level of the flat .
Besides , public spending will be required for modifications works in neighbourhood estates , such as the building of more railings and slopes with anti-slipped layer ( Tong , 2007 ) .
In addition A neighbourhood could be specially developed with slopes , railings and lifts that cater to every floor of the flat .
This would help to limit the public spending on the elderly as the elderly can be grouped together and special needs will be provided for them in that neighbourhood .
More funds could then be spent on other areas of Singapore 's development .
However , this would create an impression that the elderly are unwanted and being left alone .
It also means that the government is encouraging the elderly not to stay with their families .
Furthermore , modifying facilities such as a lift to stop at every floor of the flat , railing and slopes with anti-slipped features , not only benefits the elderly but also the handicapped and residents living in the estates .
It allows heavy and bulky items to be unloaded from a vehicle and delivered to the flats using slopes and lift without much effort .
People should see these modifications as assets to the neighbourhood estates rather than expenses incurred on the elderly .
Therefore public spending should not be limited as the elderly . Eventually all flats will require a lift that serve every floors if not alternate floors and elderly-friendly facilities which can be beneficial to all .
In conclusion , fertility rates are declining while life expectancies are increasing around the world .
Therefore public spending on the aged should not be limited and should fluctuate according to changes such as impending demographic shift , population growth and healthcare expenses .
However , it is also important for Singaporeans to plan ahead so that they can depend on several sources of income to sustain their old-age livings and at the same time ease the burden of public spending on the aged .
Employers should also do their part in changing their traditional perceptions that aged employees are unproductive and potential burden to society ( Harper , 2001 ) .
Employers should try to retain and retrain older workers for them to be retained in the labour force ; this will extend theirorking lives and they will be in a better economic position to sustain themselves .
Public spending is the amount of money expended by a government to pay the maintenance of defence , development projects , education , social security , health , infrastructure , law and order .
It represents a large share of the Gross Domestic Product ( GDP ) and has a major impact on the productivity of the whole economy .
The elderly in a country are usually supported by public spending .
It is argued that the government should provide more public assistance to the elderly and not to limit the amount of spending on them .
However , some people may not realize that there are many countries which are already having high public spending .
Schuknecht and Tanzi ( 2005 ) stated that many countries have peaked at almost 52 % of Gross Domestic Product ( GDP ) over the past twenty years .
Most countries tend to spend more than half of the public funds on social protection , health and the aged .
Mahal and Berman ( 2006 ) mentioned that several studies have indicated that expenses of health and social protection for the elderly are usually much greater than those non-elderly .
If countries are to increase their public spending on the aged further , it may cause the proportion of public spending to be spent on other important areas , such as infrastructure and education , to be lessened .
Therefore , public spending on the elderly should be limited and controlled to prevent it from increasing further .
In view of the aging population problem , some people argued that we should not limit public and financial assistance to the elderly because of the increasing number of elderly in an aging population .
However , the increase in public spending means that working people may need to pay higher taxes , as public spending is supported mainly by taxation .
The Straits Time ( 2009 ) mentioned that the huge increases in public spending could slow down countries ' economic growth .
In an aging society , it is important to limit and control the increasing public spending on the aged .
If not , there could be a drop in the GDP and eventually the percentage of public spending on the aged could be reduced too .
It should be the responsibility of the country to ensure that all the aged , who have contributed to the society , to be properly assisted in their old age .
However , when public spending on the aged is not limited and allowed to be raised continuously , everyone in the country is going to suffer in long run .
There might be one day when the country 's work force can no longer support the extremely high amount of public spending .
It may then cause them to fail to take good care of their elderly parents and neglect their needs .
Besides that , a country should try to divert a higher percentage of public spending to other areas that might contribute to the country 's growth and development , such as infrastructure and development projects .
By investing more money in these areas , a country may generate higher return and has a higher GDP growth .
This may again increase the amount of public spending on the aged .
We have to ensure that they are efficient and effective in spending this large amount money and preventing it from rising too high .
To spend too large an amount of public funds on the elderly will definitely burden both the country and the working population .
This can definitely benefit the aged and without adding anyurden to the country 's economy and the next generation .
This alarming trend is stimulated by the decline in fertility rate , medical advances and better health care , which have resulted in longer life expectancies .
Even though this trend would most likely affect Singapore negatively , the government must concern themselves with not only the increasing expenditures on the aged , but also try to divert the budget for the aged to other areas of development .
The limited public spending will increase financial burden for the working population in Singapore .
Medical care tends to be expensive ; this will place a heavy financial burden on those who are caring for the elderly .
On top of the increasing cost of living , the younger generations have to bear the high expenses of taking care of the elderly .
This situation might result in the elderly being neglected by their children due to the excessive pressure caused by a large amount of expenditure .
Critics of this position point out that the elderly themselves impose financial hardship on the working population .
As the aging population increases , the active contributors have to bear the increase burden of paying more taxes .
Although the aging population decreases Singapore 's economic competitiveness , its large demand for health care and special elderly- related goods , such as hearing aids and walking sticks , would boost the economic sectors that produces these goods and services .
Therefore , rather than hindering the development of Singapore , the elderly provide opportunities for these sectors to develop .
In the past , the aged have been through the difficult years of struggling for Singapore 's development , such as the racial riots of the 1960s .
Thus , they are full of experience and wisdom .
As a result , the elderly are likely to be assets in our society , by providing invaluable sources of advice and knowledge .
For example , Minister Mentor Lee Kuan Yew plays an integral role in contributing to Singapore 's progress .
In addition , senior workers have immense experience that would help them serve as advisors to the companies they belong to .
At this point , one may wonder if the elderly posed a financial burden to the development of a country .
However , adjustments to the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) policies have reduced the burden of the country by providing some of the funds for the elderly in their golden years .
In addition , the increasing of retirement age of workers from 60 to 62 also reduces the burden of supporting the elderly .
In fact , some fast food restaurants have actively recruited the elderly because many are just as reliable and hardworking as their younger counter-parts .
All these show that the elderly could still contribute to the development of Singapore .
If the public spending were limited , there will be financial hardship on the elderly , especially for elderly women .
This will make older women vulnerable financially .
This situation might result in their inability to seek for medical assistance when the need arises .
However , the limited public spending also have some side effects on the country , such as the overall wealth distribution of the country will be unequal .
Thus , instead of limiting public spending on the aged , the government should look for other possible solutions .
Aging population could be a burden , but they are still a part of the country .
However , it is when people can prolong their life-span that governments need to pay attention to another difficulty --- the social influences of an aging population .
It is a controversial issue regarding how much governments should invest in this matter .
Despite the fact that many people approve the idea of unlimited budget for the old , it would be better to set a limit to the governments ' expenses for various reasons .
Investing in the aged is not as profitable as investing in some other domains .
Apparently , it is not the elderly but the younger generation that is the " future " of a country .
Generally , the elderly can not contribute to the development of their countries as much as the younger do and it is the younger generation that will assume the responsibilities of consolidating the country 's powers as well as enhancing the nation 's status in the world .
Therefore , instead of spending too much on the old , the government 's budget should focus on the people who will decide the future of its state .
The old people did contribute to the improvements of their countries in the past and consequently , they deserve the government 's care . If the government ignored this problem , the next generation may not be willing to devote itself to the country .
It should , however , be emphasized that governments do pay attention to the aged population .
The article Help the aged ( 2009 ) stresses that " the budget must not forget older people " even when governments are in difficult financial situation .
In other words , governments greatly appreciate the contributions of the elderly and try to offer them more , though they are constrained by a limited budget to do so .
From the point of view of the elderly , the more public expenses governments spend on them , the better the situation would be .
For instance , people will find that there is no need to prepare themselves for old age because the governments will ensure that they will live completely on public welfare .
As a result , the dependence on governments may lead to unexpected problems such as overspending and a lack of budget to invest in other fields .
The Strategy for Older People ( Welsh Assembly Government , 2003 ) also approved that the spending for the old should be limited so that the budget can be balanced and it is considered as a strategy for the long-term development of every country .
The expenses for old people need to expand according to the living standard as well as the increasing expenditure in modern society .
However , the problem lies with the definition of " limited " .
It is a constant proportion of the GDused to support the old people .
When governments have the budget to invest in other areas of the countries ' development , the economy will operate well and he overall income will escalate . As a result , the spending for old people will also increase .
In conclusion , there should be a reasonable limit on the spendingpending for old people so that the governments can balance their expenses .
The aged should also be aware of this situation and be sympathetic towards their governments .
With the combined efforts of governments and individuals , it is possible that countries can achieve many targets at the same time : limited budget for the old people and the development of their nations .
Korea needs to reform its national policies if it hopehoped to create a better and sustainable future society as there will be a lot of negative impacts on the country , such as the inevitable labor shortage , increase in public spending and healthcare problems if the ageing population continues to grow disproportionately with the country 's fertility rate .
This is supported by Jones ( 1995 ) , stating that the increase in population will have strong physical , psychological , social , cultural , economical and cultural implications .
Therefore , in view of this , current research and policies have been carried out by the Korean government and have helped to buffer the ageing process .
A government pension system , namely the National Pension ( NP ) , which is financed in part by employee 's contributions and employer 's liability for general workers was introduced in 1988 for retirees over 60 ( " Silver jobs in lieu of golden years , 2009 ) .
It is the main old- age pension program covering the majority of Korean workers .
Despite this progress , there are still not enough openings for the baby boomers .
So , local governments have established " silver jobs " fair like chaperons for children returning home from late- night cram schools , gas station attendants , opinion survey interviewers and wedding officiators to recruit elderly job seekers as part of the government effort to assist a rapidly growing population of older Koreans in a changing society .
It can be divided into two groups : the recreational programs and community programs .
Although many beneficial services have been provided to the elderly , this program does not seem to be so effective as volunteers may or may not render their services whenever the elderly need them .
It is not a mandatory for them to always lend a hand to the elderly .
Therefore , the government should think of a better way to tackle this problem so that the society will have a domestic routine to serve the elderly who need its assistance .
Due to the low fertility rate and the growing number of elderly in the society , there is a shortage of workforce in certain occupations .
This replacement migration has not only helped to ease the ageing process when older Koreans started to retire , which resulted in the decrease of manpower in certain specialization , it also has helped to buffer the current shortage of labor in the market .
Unfortunately , there are around 65 percent of the immigrants in 1999 who are working illegally ( Bureau of Medium- Sized Industries , 1999 ) .
The large volumes of immigrants to fill up the labor shortage due to population aging has also aroused fears of the loss of national identity ( UN , 2000 ) .
Thus , even though the adoption of the immigrant policy has helped to ease the ageing process , it might not be the best policy to conquer the problem .
Intyre ( 1977 ) once said that old age throughout this century has been seen as a 'social problem ' and this is true when the government has to adopt all kinds of policies to overcome the problem .
With the ageing population , the priority of constructing a sustainable socioeconomic system at the beginning of the twenty- first century must be given .
Peterson ( 2001 ) commented that in many developed countries , an ageing population will lead to a shrinking workforce , long- term stagnation and a decline in real GDP .
Nevertheless , we agree with Frieden ( year ) , who concluded that ageing is not lost youth but a new stage of opportunity and strength .
Therefore , leaders must design a desirable socioeconomic structure under the pressure of an ageing population and environment constraints by identifying the necessary tools to attain stable and sustainable growth before taking any effective actions .
There will be 2 billion people with more than 60 years of age in the year 2050 , according to the UN ( Nichols M. , 2007 ) .
Medical advancements allow people to live longer , and as a result , the number of elderly people has been on the increase .
Currently in many countries , the growing aging population has put a lot of pressure on the social services .
However , we ca n't simply cut public spending on the aged so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development because of 3 reasons . The elderly have contributed to the society and in the short run , old people without any means to support themselves will be struggling to live on . Furthermore , in the long run , we may have to pay twice the price for what we have done .
Firstly , the aged have contributed their youth to the advancement of the society .
More than half a century ago , they have fought to restore peace to our country .
They worked hard to rebuild and develop the war-torn country into what we are living in now .
We owe them for the peace and we have to thank them for developing the country and the safe environment that we are living in .
Public pension , healthcare and all the services for the elderly symbolise our debt of gratitude to what they have done for us .
Wo n't it make us inhumane if we made our benefactors struggle when they are near the end of their lives ?
And how do you feel if the younger generation did this to you ?
Secondly , limiting public spending on the aged means leaving out in the cold these vulnerable sub-groups of elderly people : single women , the uneducated and those who can not save during their young days .
In the report " Demography is Not Destiny , Revisited " ( 2005 ) , R. B. Friedland and L. Summer pointed out that single women have particularly low average incomes .
Furthermore , it is not assured that all are able to save up money during their younger days .
" However , what if they worked hard but still can not afford to eat ?
Let us suppose that the government uses means-testing to limit spending on the elderly . The old people outside the vulnerable sub-groups will either have to continue to work , or rely on their savings or their children to live on .
Moreover , old people are subjected to illnesses which may wipe out all their savings .
Eventually , they will have to depend on their children or ask for help from the government .
Their children who have to support themselves and their own children would have to take care of their parents ' well-being .
With all the extra expenses , the children may not be able to save enough for their own retirement .
This will result in an inescapable and cruel cycle of life which can only be resolved by reverting to the original policy and at the same time , create an abrupt change in budget distribution .
In a country with a growing aging population , the elderly make up a substantial part of the population and play a bigger role in decision-making on many issues .
The country 's social stability will inevitably be disrupted if such a policy is applied forcibly without any consent from the elderly .
Another argument advocating the limiting of budget for the old is that it is better to increase the wealth of the country by investing in the younger generation , which will be the future workforce of the country and temporarily spending lesser on the elderly , who have left , or will soon leave the workforce .
However , in times of difficulties , old people have no one but their families and relatives to rely on , and we are back in the situation that we have discussed earlier .
Furthermore , this strategy does not solve anything since the money diverted to other sectors indirectly become the money spent on the elderly .
In conclusion , we should not limit spending on the aged because it is our way to express our thanks to their contributions to the society and this allows the under-privileged old people to live on to maintain economic and social stability .
According to the United Nations report , the proportion of population aged 60 or above in developed and less developed countries is projected to reach 33 % and 25 % respectively by 2050 ( United Nations , 2002 ) .
The change in the age structure of a country 's population will have a profound impact on the political , social and economical conditions of that country .
While this may be true , such measures are ineffective in reducing old-age poverty as many elderly have little understanding of how the system works and do not possess the necessary financial knowledge to manage their savings and allowance .
As such , the government has to put more emphasis and effort in imparting financial education and providing money advice and information to help the elderly to better finance their savings and incomes .
In another separate study by Chu &Yuen ( 2008 ) , it is stated that around 67 % of the respondents think that the compulsory saving in Hong Kong can not provide them with a happy retirement life as they do not understand about the benefits of Mandatory Provident Fund ( MPF ) scheme and hence do not care about it .
Despite the changes that are being implemented , such measures are insufficient to help the aged as the root problems of rising cost and increasing inaccessibility are not addressed .
Many elderly are uninsured as they fail to realise that many of the illnesses that can be prevented or treated cheaply in the early stages very often worsen into critical conditions .
In addition , although there are health care systems in place , there are still many who do not have access to them .
This is due to the confusing systems that access the elderly base on ambiguous criteria that make it harder for them to obtain the service , as well as information and advice ( Help The aged we will , 2007 ) .
Older workers are often viewed as less dynamic and less creative as compared to the younger workers and thus they are less preferred .
There was a 46 % increase in the number of unemployed people in the UK whereas the biggest increase was those aged 60 and above with an increase of 65 % ( Wallop , 2009 ) .
A possible solution for this is to scrap the national default retirement age which often gives the power to employers to retrench those above this retirement age .
Public spending is the amount of taxation collected by the government to provide for services for its people such as education , health care and law and order maintenance .
Changes in demographic trends have led to the rapid increase in the number of seniors .
If the number of elderly continues to increase , pertinent problems will definitely escalate .
Therefore , the government should spend more on the aged not only to ease their aging process , but also to tackle problems arising from a growing population .
Despite the government 's consistent spending on the old , public spending on the aged should not be limited but should be used accordingly based on the circumstances .
They are the ones who have contributed to the development of the country .
They should at least be compensated for the efforts that they have put in for the younger generations to live more comfortably .
If the government were to place a limit on its spending for the aged , the aged will have to go through more difficult aging processes as there wo n't be sufficient provisions for the elderly to live more comfortably , especially when the country is experiencing a huge demographic change .
However , these elderly constitute only a small portion of the whole aging population .
Supported by the AARP report ( 2007 ) , most Singaporean leaders consider population aging as an opportunity to create new roles for the elderly .
The government should therefore focus more on the older people by providing them with more training .
In spite of the elderly 's willingness to work , the employers may not want to take them in , as suggested by the statistics retrieved from the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development ( 2000 ) : the forecasted number of people being employed for every person in year 2030 is 2 in Japan and 2 in Canada .
This shows that employers will have to resort to employing the aged .
Thus , it will be prudent for the government to commence its course of actions earlier before the situation become worse .
The aged are not able to depend on young adults .
Due to that , the government is advised to lend a hand in helping them and limiting its spending does not assist the aged .
In Japan ( Reuters , 2007 ) , an old man passed away in his apartment for 3 years and no one knew about it until the landlord was prompted to visit him .
In view of that , it 's known that the elderly ca n't really manage themselves , especially when they are getting older .
If nothing were to be done to protect them , the aged will continue to suffer and the situation may even worsen in the next few decades .
It will help reduce the burden of the younger generations when the government put more emphasis on the aged .
Lee ( 2009 ) has provided suggestions on helping the elders to become more self-reliant through the implementation of various policies , such as providing the elderly with better health care services and jobs .
By doing so , the younger ones will be able to concentrate on their jobs , which will in turn help develop the country and probably even increase the birth rate .
What is recommended is the government should probably help only those elderly whose children are not financially capable of supporting their parents .
The government may have to create a new policy stating that those children who have stable income of a certain amount will have to take care of their parents .
By doing so , the government is able to concentrate on those who really require the help .
In Singapore Country Report ( 2007 ) , it is shown that the most prominent economic challenge in the next 20 years is the aging of the population .
The future is dependent on how well the government incorporates policies to support the aged .
The Japanese are even resorting to the help of robots to support the aging population and cope with the declining labour force ( Reuters , 2007 ) .
The government is able to buffer the effects if it places more attention on the aged .
Hence , the government should be advised to continue providing for the aged and try to overcome the obstacles presented .
There are always some controversies over the future of aging , which is one of the most interesting subjects nowadays .
Some people think about it as a burden to the national economy which requires spending a lot on pension as well as health issues , while others argue that old people have the right to enjoy public money .
From my point of view , I strongly agree with the idea which encourages government to reduce the amount of money spent on the aged .
The very first and most striking point to note is that the world economy is suffering from many recessions and the most recent one occurred from 2008 to first 6 months of 2009 .
This means that it will be a burden for the government to keep financing the pension or taking care of all the expenditure in health and accommodation issues .
And to be specific , I think there are also many other important fields that need government aid , such as education or children 's upbringing , which will definitely have a considerable influence on the country 's future .
Secondly , the family should be responsible in taking care of the old , so that the government can have more time and money to spend on other fields .
For example , in some Asian countries such as Vietnam or Japan , their children are very willing to take care of their old parents till the end of their lives . This is a common moral obligation in Asian culture .
Nowadays , there are many blue-collar jobs which are reserved for old people to earn a living .
For instance , I can see that most blue-collar workers in Singapore are about over fifty .
Even though there are some people who argue that old people have the right to use the government financial aid because they have paid taxes , I personally think they , as well as their children , have benefited from public services such as transportation , education , etc .
In short , I think not only the government , but also the family have the responsibility to take care of the old people and so public budget could be spent on many different areas to develop country .
It is known by all that our society is aging .
Our government has played a huge role in implementing and improving our policies to maximize aid for the elderly .
However , there will always be persisting problems that the government will face , such as planning for the national budget , managing rising cost in the medical field and providing safety measures in public areas .
Thus , current research and development in these areas are required .
The national budget and the economy have come under pressure as the government provides heavy subsidies to the elderly in medical , transportation and even social activities .
Some might think that rather than having to research for and develop better economic policies , the government should allocate public funds to the .
However , we should not blindly put these money into subsidies , but instead , use it to research for better policies or systems .
With better policies , the government will be able to increase the productivity of the work force .
There will be more money generated and fewer people will be in need .
One example would the " Foreign Talent Policy " , which opened our market to foreign talents and thus increasing the productivity of the workforce .
The government introduced a scheme that allows people to provide in advance for their old age dependency .
They are encouraged to save a portion of their salaries into a special account when they are most active in the workforce .
Therefore , current research in development and policies in the economy sector have helped in easing the aging process .
In the medical aspect , no medicine in the world can cure aging illnesses such as Dementia and Arthritis .
Even though this is a fact , advancement in the medical field has proven to cure some old age diseases like Cataracts .
Thus , all these researches in medical field have aided the aging process tremendously .
At this point , one may wonder if it were a waste of resources to invest in architectural aids because these structures are costly and do not serve as much purpose as compared to the other sectors such as medical .
However , these aids have proven to be essential despite their costly structures .
In areas populated with elderly , such as Redhill or Tiong Bahru , railings have been installed not only on pavements but also in public toilets as well .
Tiles or pavements with better friction have been placed in toilets to prevent the elderly from slipping .
In addition , one of the major projects that the Singapore 's Ministry of Transport has developed is to install lifts in almost every MRT stations , which creates a barrier free route .
All these developments help the elderly , the disabled and pregnant women as well . Thus , developments in these area are definitely worthwhile .
In conclusion , all the research and developments , as well as policies that the government has invested in , have made aging a more joyous and less terrifying journey .
Thus , there is an increasing number of concerns as to how to solve the problems of an aging population .
Critics argue that by limiting the government spending on the aged , it would increase the negative impact of an aging population .
From August 2008 to July 2009 , Popatal ( 2009 ) found that there were 172 people who have filed applications at the Tribunal for Maintenance of Parents .
This is much higher than the average of 100 in previous years .
They will not form a habit of relying too much on the government .
This means that they are capable of finding a job to support themselves without having to depend on others .
There are other sectors that need the government 's help .
If government 's spending on the aged is not limited , the other sectors will be neglected .
The education sector is an example .
The government helps the young by issuing bursaries and scholarships , as well as encourages the students to study hard and helps those who are poor but are eager to go to school .
Taxes may have to increase and takes a bigger toll on the people .
Hence , it is important to limit public spending on the aged so as to divert it to other areas of the country 's development .
They should also be aware that the elderly are now healthier and are capable of supporting themselves .
A country does not consist of only the aged and spending too much government funds is unnecessary and will cause a negative impact on the economy .
The population in the world is aging rapidly and the number of persons aged 60 or over is expected almost to triple , increasing from 737 million in 2009 to 2 billion by 2050 globally .
( United Nations , 2009 ) This signals the need to deal with this pressing issue of aging Population .
In the Singapore context , there are many different approaches in place and the few main ones include the implementation of the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) , development and improvement made to the existing healthcare system and elder-friendly infrastructure and the implementation of the Tax Relief Scheme .
All these have helped to alleviate the aging process and allow the elderly to enjoy their twilight years to the fullest .
The CPF in Singapore has played a crucial role in helping to reduce the fiscal cost of elder dependency as it compels citizens to save in advance for their old age
( Central Provident Fund [ CPF ] Board , 2009 ) . Critics of this plan have debated that it is unsuitable as high costs of living makes it difficult for people to save more of their earnings for pensions .
However , this may not be true as with judicious planning of their spending , it is not impossible for them to save more while they are still active in the work force and be financially independent in old age .
Also , other social issues associated with an aging population , like declining birth rate and people living longer , have indicated that there will be fewer working adults available to contribute to the society and to support the aged .
Therefore , this has increased the significance of the CPF as it compels people to save in advance lest they are unable to support themselves during their old age .
Furthermore , the CPF has helped to rule out the possibilities of younger generations neglecting the importance of saving for their old age .
Hence , the CPF has indeed helped to ease the aging process and the financial burden of the elderly as it requires people to save in advance and also informs citizens on how much they should save in order to be self- sufficient for their old age .
This gives people a sense of security in their twilight years as they are now able to enjoy their lives without much financial worries .
Apart from the CPF , development and improvement made to the existing healthcare system and elder-friendly infrastructure have also eased the problem of disabilities and old-age illnesses .
These actions are superficial and inadequate as they do not directly deal with the problems related to old age ; and therefore are unable to ease the aging process .
However , this may not be the case as with improved healthcare system ; it helps the elderly because their healthcare needs will be better taken care of .
In addition , with the development of more elder-friendly infrastructure within the community , the community will become barrier-free , safer and more conducive for the elderly .
One of such projects is the lift upgrading programme
( Lee , 2009 ) . The improved lifts will stop at every floor and this will better cater to the needs of the elderly .
Additionally , to allow the aged to move about conveniently , many places , including public transportations have been made wheel-chair accessible .
Hence , with a safer environment and with the provision of elder-friendly infrastructure and unhindered access to the public facilities , the elderly will be allowed to move about freely and enjoy their old age .
Implementation of the Tax Relief Scheme such as The Aged Parent Relief is also an important step to improve the retirement security as it encourages children to take care of their parents , thereby easing the aging process
( CPF , 2009 ) . At this point , one may take advantage of this scheme to claim the tax reliefs for one 's use as it is nearly impossible for the government to keep track of where the money is being spent on .
For instance , the government has passed the Maintenance of Parents Act to allow elderly parents to file lawsuit against their children who have failed to carry out filial obligations
( Khalik , 2009 ) . Hence , this act has helped to deter the children from making use of the tax relief scheme inappropriately and has also sustained the main objective of the scheme to promote filial piety .
All these helped to encourage the children to look after their parents and at the same time , ensure that the elderly parents will be at the receiving end .
Hence , these approaches have increased the seniors ' confidence and security during their twilight years .
Overall , strategies such as the introduction of CPF , the development and improvement of the elder-friendly infrastructure and healthcare system and the implementation of tax relief scheme have indeed helped to ease the aging process to a large extent .
These strategies have helped to ensure that the elderly are self-sufficient during their old age and also allowed them to live in a more conducive and barrier-free environment .
Although there is still room for improvement , current strategies have already done a pretty great well in ensuring that the individuals have saved enough for their old age and increasing their sense of security .
All these have indeed made the process towards aging a more enjoyable and fulfilling one and allowed the aged to truly enjoy their well-prepared twilight years .
Expenditure on the elderly is taking up more of the government budget due to the rapidly aging population .
Money that can be otherwise spent on the country 's developments has to be used in settling the problem of the greying population .
Countries are spending more and more money on health care , infrastructure and transportation specially custom-made for the elderly .
Due to this , the country 's development in other areas has to take a step back , thus resulting in the inability to attain its potential .
In the essay , I shall discuss the problems that are brought about by the increase in public spending on the aged and the areas that could have benefited if the fund were to be used on them instead .
When a country like the United States ' ' elderly population increased eleven-fold between 1900 and 1994 , it is evident that there will be an increase in personal assistance for the aged
( Hobbs , 1993 , 25-1104 ) . This will translate into the increased funding to provide care for this group of people .
On top of the money being put aside for health care for the aged , barrier-free facilities like wheel-chair friendly roads and transportation system have to be planned to accommodate them .
To deal with these global aging problems , governments have to reserve a large proportion of the already limited public spending for the elderly .
This result in a reduction of the government budget for the country 's development in both economic and social terms .
The fund used on the elderly could otherwise be spent on allowing the country to have better economic growth by building a better infrastructure and an education system .
In this way , the general population will be able to benefit from an increase in income as a result of the economic growth .
On the other hand , it is not morally right to leave the aged to fend for themselves , especially when they had contributed in one way or another to the country 's development in their younger days .
It is true that the government should reward the aged for their contributions ; but in order for the country to continue enjoying a sustained growth , the public spending have to be diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
In addition , the responsibility of supporting the elderly does not only lie on the shoulders of the government , the elderly themselves should plan for their retirements when they are still economically active .
This is done by implementing policies like the Medisave system , where Singaporeans have to put aside a certain percentage of their income into the Medisave account
( Central Provident Fund ) . This system is to ensure that the senior citizens will be able to live on their own savings in the Medisave account .
In cases where the elderly are childless or physically ill due to aging , it will be the government 's duty to take care of them .
However , contrary to what is commonly believed , Pat Thane ( citation ) argued that , they are not inevitably unhealthy .
As living conditions improve and technology advances , people are able to lead a healthier lifestyle and live longer as compared to the past .
Thane also said that " many tasks can be performed as well by people in their seventies as by younger people , even when they involve quite heavy physical or intellectual demands
" ( Thane,1991 ) . As a result of the above mentioned arguments by Pat Thane , the Senior lecturer in Social Science and Administration at Goldsmiths College , London , being old might not be translated to being a burden to the society .
The elderly , especially the " young elderly " , would surely be able to earn a living on their own if they do not have the luxury of children supporting them .
Therefore , an aging population might not pose problems as feared .
In summary , public spending on the aged should be limited because of the fact that the elderly should have planned for their old age when they were young and they might still be able to support themselves if the need arises .
A country will be able to progress if its citizens do their part in planning for their retirement .
Many countries are facing the problems brought about by an aging population .
For instance , the workforce gets smaller as elder workers retire and the working class has to pay more taxes because of a slower economic growth and the need to provide more healthcare services for the aged .
Even though the world is facing an aging population , public spending should not be spent only on the aged as there are many other areas that need to be taken care of in a country 's development .
The aging population is already a problem in many countries such as Japan and Singapore .
Therefore , public spending had been reviewed to address this problem and to reduce the negative impact of the aging problems .
However , due to practical reasons , a country has its limitations in supporting the aged .
Hence , countries should assess the other important areas that public spending should be focused on as well .
As the aged are used to receiving allowances and subsidies , the lack of government aids might affect their lives .
They would be unable to support themselves , especially with the increasing healthcare costs .
According to the Singapore Department of Statistics , the Consumer Price Index for healthcare had increased 3.6 % from February 2008 to February 2009 .
This would mean higher costs of living for the aged .
In conservative countries such as Singapore , children are expected to take care of their parents by providing them with allowances to meet their daily needs .
Children should remember how their parents have taken care of them when they were young and hence , they should do their part in demonstrating filial piety and taking care of their aged parents , instead of relying on the country to help .
In order to ensure that the aged are properly taken care of by their children , government could introduce policies and enforce them .
This would help to enforce moral values and also directly reduce public spending that could be diverted to other areas of development .
Other areas of development include addressing social issues such as the decrease in the birthrate and the increase in child abuse cases .
In Singapore , the Marriage and Parenthood package with the extension of the Baby Bonus attained only marginal success in increasing the birthrate of Singaporeans .
The median age of citizen mothers at first birth had increased over the years from 28.6 in 1998 to 29.4 in 2008 , thus causing the fertility rate for the prime childbearing age group of 20 to 34 to decline .
Hence , public spending could be used to introduce more programs and subsidies to encourage people having larger families instead .
According to the Social Statistics 2009 conducted by the Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports , the number of child abuse cases investigated in Singapore had increased from 154 in 2007 to 176 in 2008 .
In addition , it is essential to increase public awareness through campaigns and seminars to give the public a better understanding on child abuse .
In conclusion , public spending should be used on the aged but also not neglecting other problems which hinder the country 's development .
Too much of the nation 's budget is being spent on aiding the elderly and the government should limit and channel these funds to other more important areas for the country 's development .
The elderly receive subsidies in various areas such as housing and medical benefits .
Children are obliged to take care of their parents and this will lessen the burden on society to take care of the elderly .
Excess funds should then be channeled to other areas for the country 's development .
Many may think that with the obligation to support their parents , the family members will bear a heavier burden .
However , providing for the parents is not an additional burden for the children as there are benefits when they take care of their parents .
For example , the tax relief for adults who live with their aged parents has been increased to $ 5000 and the CPF Housing Grant Scheme to encourage young couples to stay near their parents ( " Round Up Speech " , 2007 ) .
Therefore , it is not true to say that working adults bear a heavier burden from supporting their parents because government incentives are provided .
Nowadays , the elderly are able to support themselves .
Chan ( 1999 ) showed that elderly respondents with CPF accounts are significantly less likely to rely on children as their main source of financial support . Evidence suggests that as CPF coverage widens , reliance on children will probably decrease .
Policies such as compulsory CPF and Medisave savings both require citizens to set aside part of their salaries to meet their future needs .
Even if the elderly can support themselves , some may argue that since they pay taxes , they should be allowed to use the funds set aside for them .
Everyone should be responsible for themselves .
The aged should continue to work beyond their retirement age when they are still capable of supporting themselves .
In recent years , the government has been promoting elder employment and raising the eligible age for employment .
Others may think that the elderly have already contributed their share to society and should now retire .
However , instead of letting them idle at home , the retired should be allowed to return to the workforce and continue to contribute to the economy .
Not only are they able to benefit financially , they are also able to share their precious experiences with the younger generations .
With the elderly returning to the workforce , they will be less dependent on the government subsidies and thus , less funds should be set aside for the elderly .
The elderly will be supported in their retirement by their working family members , and gaining help from government policies ( CPF savings , Medisave funds and Elderly bonuses ) .
All in all , funds should be limited and directed to other more important areas for the country 's development so that the country will be able to remain competitive in the economy and achieve sustained economic growth .
Countries like Singapore and Japan have a social security system in place to help the aged , and at the same time , a substantial sum of public spending is allocated to look after their health and welfare
( Takayama , 2005 ) . However , public spending should also be allocated to other areas of the country 's development , such as education , small medium enterprises ( SMEs ) and the infrastructure . These areas would benefit the public and are effective in tackling the aging issues in the long run .
Therefore , public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development to strike a balance while tackling the aging issues .
One nation 's economy success depends on the quality of the workforce
( Edwards , 2008 ) . Highly educated future generations will tend to earn more incomes and be more health conscious , thus less reliant on government for health and welfare
( Friedland and Summer , 2005 ) . Singapore owes its economic success to the good management of the education system and meeting the demand for skills through training the workforce to meet and keep up with the economic changes
( Lee , Goh and Fredriksen , 2008 ) . Singapore 's social security system , which focuses on self-reliance and individual savings , is in line with the compulsory saving scheme , the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) .
The CPF Education Scheme allows people to use the ordinary account to pay for tertiary education in local institutions , and at the same time , encourages more people to further their education
( Mehta , and Wee , 2004 ) . Education can also be a channel for the nation to emphasize filial obligations in order to increase willingness of the future generations to take care of their parents when they are old
( Peterson , 2001 ) . As part of the Singapore 's education system , National Education aims to foster national cohesion , a sense of belonging and good moral values
( Ministry of Education , 2009 ) . Nevertheless , educating the workforce , including the aged , on the importance of planning for retirement and continuous skills upgrading are also essential .
This allows the workforce to start accumulating their wealth until the retirement age and at the same time , especially for the aged to remain productive through skill upgrading
( Peterson , 2001 ) .
The various schemes aim to help the SMEs increase their revenue and attract investors through upgrading the existing business operations and creating gateway and funding opportunities
( Spring Singapore , 2009 ) . In 2008 , the National Research Foundation ( NRF ) announced that 75 million Singapore dollars were set aside to support the Proof-of Concept grants ( POC scheme ) for the SMEs to strengthen innovation and entrepreneurship as the sector contributes over 40 % of the GDP and half of the employment workforce
( Loh , 2007 ) . At the same time , the government also provides grants to support SMEs to recruit , retrain and retain their workers , especially the older workers , to ensure productivity .
Two examples of the grants are the Human Resource Capability Package developed by SPRING Singapore and the Singapore Workforce Development Agency ( WDA ) , which improves and strengthens SMEs ' human resource management capabilities , as well as the ADVANTAGE !
Scheme , which motivates SMEs to recruit older workers
( Ministry of Manpower , 2006 ) . These will help to lower the barriers to elder employment , enabling them to work longer and accumulate more wealth for their retirement
( Peterson , 2001 ) .
Enhancing and upgrading of common places such as sport facilities , schools , public housing estates , roads and parks are to satisfy the needs of the public .
In 2009 , the Singapore Senior Minister of State for National Development announced that the government plans to spend between S $ 18 and S $ 20 billion on infrastructure projects and another S $ 15 to S $ 17 billion in 2010 and 2011 respectively .
Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong noted in the National Day Rally Speech 2009 that new general hospitals ( Khoo Teck Puat Hospital and Jurong General Hospital ) would be built in response to the healthcare needs in Singapore , and on top of that , there is also a need to build step-down care .
Twinning the current general hospitals with community hospitals , which are run by charitable organizations , will make healthcare affordable for all , especially the aged .
For example , a bridge would be built to link Tan Tock Seng General Hospital to Ren Ci Community Hospital that enables patients from Tan Tock Seng General Hospital to be moved to Ren Ci Community Hospital for rehabilitation and the patients may pay lesser for health care costs .
Singapore uses only one-fourth of its taxes , which is about only $ 381 per capita on health and individuals pay for the rest
( Callick , 2008 ) . This shows the importance of tackling the roots of the high cost of healthcare instead of using the public spending directly on the aged .
For all nations , wise planning on public spending and wise policy planning are very crucial as they influence one 's future
( Friedland and Summer , 2005 ) . Creating welfare dependency on the government only solves the issues temporarily .
Instead , it should be used on other areas of development to tackle the roots of the issues and improve the quality of life for the aged .
Public spending refers to the expenditure incurred the government , which may include expenses on military , health , education , infrastructure , development projects , and the cost of servicing ( paying off the interest on ) overseas loan .
Aging problems are likely to cause a substantial increase in public expenditure on health .
But the steady development of a society as a whole needs a balance of public spending on all aspects .
Many recent reports ( citation ) from developed countries have found that ageing will have only a small effect on the healthcare expenditure in future , thus spending on the aged can be limited within a certain small scope of the proportion of GDP .
For example , reports from the United States , the United Kingdom and Australia have reached similar conclusions .
Firstly , the older population is not spending a large proportion of the country 's GDP , and the fact is not simply that the greater the proportion of older people , the greater would be the spending .
For example , Sweden and Australia have similar , .
In 2000 , 17.3 % of the Swedish population was aged 65 years or older ; it spent only 8.6 % of its GDP on health .
Secondly , many countries have adopted effective strategies to make the expenditure on health for an aging population small and manageable , Here are some of the strategies : ( 1 ) stratify the old by age and sex ; ( 2 ) ; ( 3 ) increase transparency about self-employed income to ensure fairness in the financing of social insurance systems , including the new long-term care insurance .
.
Firstly , the factors that increase the financial expenditure have been over-emphasized .
It is true that older people use more health care services than younger people and that the proportion of older people in the population is increasing .
Secondly , some groups of people may require a significant increase in public spending on the aging population .
Compared to long-term economic development , they may be more concerned about their own welfare .
Another group is the government .
With an increasing number of elderly voters , politicians may provide excessive benefits to the elderly to win votes .
.
Thirdly , increased fiscal spending may be due to other factors instead of the aging population .
Firstly , the cost of pharmaceuticals and diagnostic tests have increased .
The report published by the Australian Federal Government found .
Thirdly , normal doctor 's prescription prefers newer drugs and the drugs are inclined to be expensive , but not necessarily more effective .
If the public spending on the issue of aging were unrestricted , the coming wave of retiring Baby Boomers may wash away projected budget surpluses and erode existing spending priorities .
For example in America , it is already estimated that over half of federal domestic spending went to people 65 and older .
The burden of the government will increase as the richer old people
For example , in Korea , there is pressure on the government for increased outlays on pensions and healthcare .
In conclusion , public spending on the aged should be limited , so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
Many countries , including Singapore , are facing the issue of aging population .
There are many implications for this issue and one of them is that the spending by the government on the aged has increased in order to deal with this issue .
This affects the amount of available funds spend on other areas of the country 's development , such as the economy , education and infrastructure .
Thus , in today 's society , much has been debated on whether public spending should be limited so that more money can be diverted to other areas for the country 's development .
Furthermore , in Singapore where it is currently experiencing a low birth rate , developing the young is crucial to ensure there will be sufficient local talents in future .
This is to ensure that Singapore will be able to stay competitive in the future .
Hence , if the government did not limit its spending on the aged , there would be a budget left for developing the education sector .
This may affect the country in the long run .
It can also be argued that there is a greater need to spend on infrastructure development as it is important .
to limit spending on the aged means that there will be a larger amount of funds available to spend on infrastructure development .
This fund allows the country to develop proper infrastructure such as roads , electricity and even water supply to attract more foreign investors to set up firms in the country .
Superior infrastructure attracts foreign investors to set up business in the country as it reduces production cost and also increases accessibility for their business .
Therefore , if government spending on the aged increases due to aging population issues , the budget on infrastructure development will be lesser and this may affect the country 's economic development .
Another reason to limit public spending on the aged is that there is a need to set aside a larger amount of money for economic development especially when there is global economic downturn .
As the economy is a key area of a country 's development , the government should spend more money on economic development in order to sustain a healthy economic growth .
In addition , a prosperous economy will lead to the increase of wealth .
This means that the burden of supporting the aged by the society will be lessened .
Thus , developing the economy will bring benefits to both the country and the aged in long run .
On the flip side , spending on the aged is equally important .
To limit spending on the aged does not mean that government should not spend on them .
Moreover , this group of elderly had worked hard for years when they were young and had contributed to the economy and society .
I conclude that there is a need to limit public spending on the aged as there are other areas that require money for the country 's development .
There is a need for the government to take a wider perspective on the different areas that need money when deciding on how much money is to be spent on each area .
Throughout the entire world , leaders of developed countries are concerned with the problems of an aging population .
A country 's budget would be spent in a few key areas such as defense , healthcare , environment , transport , research and development and education .
Public spending on the aged is necessary but should be limited in order for the money to be diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
If majority of the spending is focused on the aged , it would limit the growth of the country , which would consequently lower the standard of living for all .
Firstly , with a shrinking workforce and an increase in expenditure required in welfare , the country will need to focus on developing the further generations .
" All who have meditated on the art of governing mankind have been convinced that the fate of empires depends on the education of youth " --- this quote by Aristotle clearly states that education is the crucial factor to determine a country 's success and progress .
With proper education system , the young will be more productive when they enter the workforce .
Hence a highly skilled workforce in turn will boost the country economy and sustain the additional demands of a graying population .
Therefore a portion of public spending should be given to equip the young with the right mind set and skills which are relevant to the needs of the workforce .
Secondly , a key area which requires funding is the research and development sector .
With strong support on research , new breakthrough can be discovered to cure chronic illnesses or age related diseases .
The cost of health care could be lowered with advancement in science and medication which are more effective .
Effective medication would translate into a shorter time spent in hospitals .
Therefore it lowers the elderly 's burden on healthcare and improves or stabilizes the health of frail elderly .
It may be argued that the amount invested in research does not produce equal rewards .
However , without continuous trials and errors , new innovations could not be made .
It is due to the persistent effort of researchers that many of today 's technologies have been discovered .
A country would be considered extremely vulnerable with its graying population ( less able-bodied individual ) and outdated weaponry .
Thus with adequate funding on research and development , the country will be at a better position .
Thirdly , an emphasis should be placed on the country 's healthcare system .
With a shrinking workforce and an ever-increasing cost of living , the aged would have difficulty coping with daily expenses and medical bills .
Critical illnesses could empty the elderly of their retirement fund and thus the government should provide medical subsidies .
If the government did not provide any form of aid and shifted the responsibility to the family or society , there would be catastrophic consequences .
Society could deem the government as unsympathetic .
Those who are more affluent might migrate , which could cause a loss of investors and talents . This may affect the country 's development .
Statistics have also shown that there is an increase in spending on prescribed medicine ; from $ 535 in 1999 to $ 1410 in 2001
( Goulding , 2005 ) . Families footing the medical bills will in turn have lesser capital for the other expenses ; namely , the children 's education and daily necessities .
Needy households might encourage their children to take up part time job to supplement the family finances .
Children might grow up to be ineffective workers as their education have been disrupted .
This would negatively affect the society and the country 's economy on a whole .
A developed country with a graying population brings about a shrinking workforce . If spending were focused on the aged it could cripple the country 's economy and halt developments .
With appropriate spending on key areas such as education , research and development and healthcare , the country could progress despite the additional demand of an aging population .
Leaders of the country should balance the benefits of individual , society and country with care to maximise the country 's potential for development .
Sectors like housing and consumers'market had to be carefully taken care of .
The economy underwent a series of revolutionary changes due to the surge in population , hitting greater heights as the trend continued .
If no effort is being put to limit the increasing healthcare and social security costs , expenditures on other priorities will soon come under pressure .
Although spending on the elderly is inevitable in the face of an aging population , careful spending is necessary in diluting the effect of fiscal consequences .
Limiting elderly spending does not confine to only within the present .
It is about coming out with a permanent solution which would curb spending in the long run .
Therefore , the fiscal outcome may not turn out to be ideal because other expenses such as education and national defence will end up being squeezed .
Governments should spend more money on creating healthcare awareness .
As the average life expectancy in the world increases , people are living longer and they may become more vulnerable to contracting chronic illnesses at old age .
It is important for the elderly to know how and where to seek for help once they have contracted an illness . They can tackle the illness at its earlier stage , thus reducing the hefty healthcare costs if it were treated at a much later stage .
Eventually the economy will benefit when people become healthier and spend lesser on their healthcare .
After all , the benefits of this measure will definitely outweigh the limitations , and the measure is able to cut down the amount spent in the medical sector in future .
However , in the future , the bulk of the working population will have to come from the retiring baby boomers .
There are several limitations to the extent of how productivity can be increased among these workers .
Firstly , for the more well-off elderly , they are less willing to work as they want to enjoy their retirement .
Hence , in order to have better economic growth , the process should be viewed with a more comprehensive perspective .
Government should provide a wider protection net for the elderly , such as implementing health insurances , promoting health campaigns and better welfare programs so as to reduce the mental and financial burden on the aged .
Although economic growth is important in providing care for the elderly , the limit on the elderly spending should be set carefully , so that they would not create any adverse effects on the economy .
As the elderly will likely to form the core of the population in future , they are becoming the major source of the economic growth .
Therefore , the government has to channel more resources to look after the welfare of the elderly , especially in the healthcare sector . Additional hospitals , such as the Jurong Hospital , are being built in Singapore to meet the escalating demand for healthcare and to provide better services .
This gives rise to the problem of the aged being self-sufficient and self-supporting in old age .
Moreover , employers often hesitate to employ them as the society is technologically inclined . There are many young professionals who , although may not have work and management experience , have the much sought after skills .
In addition , the elderly might be reluctant to work due to being over reliant on the government .
Apart from providing financial support to the elderly , the government should try to help the elderly in other ways so as to reduce the dependency of the elderly on the government .
From young , the students are taught the values of filial piety .
The government came up with the Maintenance of Parents Act in 1996 and has been studying to use legal pressure to ensure that children will take care of their parents . This would reduce the reliance of the elderly on the government and subsequently , the government 's budget on the elderly need not be as huge .
The government has highlighted to the public the importance and benefits of financial planning for old age .
Financial planning allows people to provide for themselves when they have retired or are incapable of supporting themselves financially .
The CPF sets aside a sum from their monthly salary to prepare for the rainy days and their old age .
The various aspects of the benefits of CPF include retirement , healthcare , home ownership , family protection and asset enhancement .
The government has a duty to take care of the aging population .
However , they should limit public spending on the aged .
The responsibility to look after the aged should be shouldered by the children as well .
In addition , the aged could prepare themselves for their old age , and thus reduce the burden of others .
Limiting public spending on the aged reduces their dependency on the government .
However , the government not only has to deal with reducing ageing population , but also to attend to the needs of the aged .
There is a need to subsidize the aged for their healthcare , transport , facilities .
One may argue that public spending on the aged could be used on the country 's development .
Public spending on the aged should not be limited .
The aged deserves to receive the best welfare given by the country .
It is known that they had contributed to the country during the prime of their lives .
Their contributions should be recognized .
By limiting public spending on the aged , it may signify that the government perceives the country 's development to be more important than the welfare of the people .
Some people would resent the government for seeing development as more important than its people .
In extreme cases , some of them would hold protests to vent their anger towards the government .
The people may view the government as not wanting to take care of the aged , and see them as a burden .
This could cause the people to be skeptical about their welfare in future .
And the migration of the workforce would lead to a shortage of workers in the country .
Therefore , this would affect economic development of the country .
On the other hand , limiting the amount of public spending on the aged could help the country to develop more effectively during a crisis .
If the country faced an economic downturn , its revenue would be reduced .
Money should be spent more wisely in helping the country to get out of the economic downturn .
With reduced revenue , the government should be more flexible in limiting the public spending on the aged .
By limiting the spending on the aged , the government will have more funds available to get the country out of the economic downturn .
More public funds could be allocated to education , and upgrading the skills for workers and building projects .
In an economic downturn , the government could use their reserve funds instead .
This could be a morale booster for the people because spending on the aged is not reduced despite an economic downturn .
Limiting public spending on the aged is important because it indirectly controls the funds which would be channeled into other areas of a country 's development .
This accounts for the difficulty in deciding the amount of funds to be diverted to helping the ageing population as many believe that money directed to boosting a country 's economic growth is more practical than spending it on an ageing population which offers no economic returns .
Hence , a country should decide on the amount they want to commit on the ageing population as different amount would lead to different results .
For a country which places a low limit on public spending for the aged , the amount of investment being channeled into other areas of the country 's development would be lower than another with a higher limit on public spending for the aged .
For example , Britain spends more on its ageing population as compared to America and its level of investment in research and development is lower than that of America .
However , this is not to say that public spending on the aged is the sole factor for the cause of lower investments in other areas of a country 's development , though it is only one of the many factors .
Nevertheless , it still affects the level of funds being diverted to a country 's development .
A low limitation limits the funds from being diverted to other areas of the country 's development such as education and economic developments .
This would then lead to an overall fall in the revenue of a country which will translate into a drop in the public spending on the aged ( Weil : 1997 ) .
Thus , negative results are achieved , with neither the aging population nor the country 's economy benefitting from it .
However , it may be argued that countries such as Britain are still progressing well in the global economy despite a high level of spending on the aged population . This shows that a low limitation on public spending does not equate a halt in the progress of a country .
In addition , the low level of limitation would mean that quality healthcare is being catered for the elderly as sufficient money are being invested in them . This may lead to a healthier ageing population which may then contain the spread of elderly illnesses ( Dunnell : 1995 ) .
This containment could possibly lead to a fall in money being diverted to the aged population as they are healthier now ; and thus increasing the funds being diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
For instance , Singapore spend approximately 9 million on her ageing population , encouraging elderly independence instead . Thus , she has a greater amount of money to be diverted to other areas .
With lesser funds being channeled to the aged population , more of it may then be used in areas that can spur the development of a country .
This may allow improvements in fields such as infrastructures , research and development , education and technology .
Hence , it may attract more investments and that can generate more revenue for a country , which in turn may increase the funds allocated to the aged population ( Weil : 1997 ) .
This would then translate into a more serious problem as the country would then need to pump in even more money to increase the health standard of the elderly in the future ( Weil : 1997 ) .
Hence it can be seen that different levels of limitations on public spending produce different results , which can be both good and bad as shown above .
These results may not be the same for all countries because each country has its own unique way of implementing different policies to deal with its ageing population .
But there is no doubt that public spending on the aged should be limited because it affects the level of funds being diverted to areas that aid the development of a country . However , more importantly , it is the level of limitation that a country has to take note of .
Different countries will have different levels of limitation because of the differences they have within their societies .
In conclusion , each country should understand its society well and implement a limit which will best benefit its ageing population and economy .
This unprecedented demographical shift with the number of dependent adults surpassing the number of dependent children envisages serious negative impacts , from declining of work forces and real GDP to sharp increasing of elderly fiscal cost , that will impoverish and subsequently impede developmental growth .
Nonetheless , current research and development as well as policy have preeminently help to alleviate the dire consequences of the aging process .
Alzheimer 's or Alzheimer Disease is the most common form of dementia mostly diagnosed in people aged 65 and above .
For example , last year , Prana Biotechnology in Melbourne ( Reader 's Digest , Sept 2009 ) developed PBT2 that targets and reduces beta amyloid , a sticky protein hypothesized to be the cause of Alzheimer 's which form plaques that kills brain cells .
Other drugs such as Rember , are announced to delay progression of the disease up to 81 percent while Dimebon promised to power and halt the perishing of brain cells
Researchers also hope to develop early detection methods which help by prescribing preventive medication before the actual occurrence of the disease .
This implies that aging perhaps can be influenced with the manipulation of certain cells .
The breakthrough took place with the discovery of Sirtuins , a group of anti-aging genes ( Dipp , Guarente , Westphal , 2007 )
The theory by a group of researchers from Harvard Medical School ( as cited in Reader Digest , Sept 2009 ) suggests that " with more Sirtuins , DNA repair would be more efficient " , enabling the subject ( mouse ) to maintain a youthful or healthy gene pattern into old age , eliminating traits of aging and subsequently increasing lifespan by 24 to 46 percent .
Critics have argued that though these researches are seemingly impressive and hopeful , there is simply no concrete empirical evidence on their practical significance or effectiveness .
Yet , one should be constantly aware and confident of the actualization of technology 's development for a promising future on account of the past .
Also , policies are implemented in attempts to dissolve current concerns .
Countries like Singapore who have long promulgatpromulgated self-reliance do adopt certain policy framework such as the 3M 's --- Medisave , Medishield and Medifund simultaneously with Eldershield , to protect and support citizens on Healthcare cost .
Government subsidies on a wide range of intermediate and long-term care services such as community hospitals and dementia care centers are available for patients , especially elderly who require continuing care after hospitalization .
between the Oxford Institute of Ageing and the Singapore Council for Third Age ( C3A ) are launched to educate , as well as promote active aging among Singaporeans
In conclusion , society should now move toward a new paradigm : aging is not a burden on the economy or the development of a country .
Although fertility rates have fallen , longevity has increased .
Advancement in technology has certainly transformed the definition and experience of aging .
An aging population has been an issue in recent years as the increment in the social needs of the elderly and public spending , as well as the burden on the younger generations have governments probing into the issue .
Despite these significant consequences related to an aging population , " they ( Governments ) must realize that any further expansion of retirement benefits would only impoverish future generations and limit future public spending
As concerns have been raised on the effectiveness of excessive money injected into financing social welfare policies to arrest short term issues , the improper use of public spending will likely to create much burden for the next generation .
Therefore , public spending should be spent on other sectors of the economy .
There is little doubt that social welfare policies can alleviate the difficult situations that aging populations are facing today .
For example , the public assistance program can provide the elderly with a sense of security for food , shelter and daily necessities .
Some of the elderly have no dependents and they live by themselves , while others are looking at hefty medical bills and healthcare costs as their health deteriorates .
As the aging population grows , spending should increase proportionately to ensure that the elderly are taken care of .
Excessive public spending only adds to the comfort of the aging population and does not effectively benefit the economy .
As the elderly will not be encouraged to work , they will take for granted that the government is providing everything for them .
For instance , if a physically fit old man is given monetary assistance beyond the minimum amount , he will not be compelled to work , especially if the benefit made up a large part of his salary .
Another example in Singapore can be the availability of funds allocated to town councils for social welfare services .
The government has not effectively utilized tax payers ' money to the best of its ability .
As resources are being poured into different sectors in the economy , growth will increase along with public spending .
This is ensured by the motivation for personal gains in the economy as each seeks to benefit the most out of the stimulus that governments would inject into the economies .
For instance , as more money is being pumped into the infrastructural development within a country , the industries benefit , with lesser taken to set up plants , tax benefits and cheaper rental . All these will drive the costs of doing business down .
As these costs decline , businesses become more profitable when they effectively try to make use of the incentive from the government and this may translate to better salaries .
Governments should weigh the costs and benefits associated with each dollar being spent on social policies and the economy .
They must then determine where the necessary point is to effectively solve the issues an aging population is facing and then channel the remaining resources into the other sectors of the economy .
With proper policies , " public budgetary resources would be used only to secure minimum standards and basic social services
" ( Tanzi .
V. and Schuknecht , 2000 ) Till then , only can the economies as well as the aging population benefit from the effective use of tax payers ' money .
Public spending on the aged should be limited as money should be spent on other areas such as defense and public infrastructure as they play more important roles in a country 's future development .
Currently , most developed nations such as Japan , Singapore and Australia are facing problems on their societies turning grey as the numbers working to support the old are dwindling .
This causes social security problems which question the ability of the young to support a larger number of people .
An aging society means a smaller working force which would result in lesser tax payers This might cause in a decline in government fund .
It is not feasible for a country to spend more on the elderly when funds have a possibility of being decreased in future years .
Money for the aged can be saved as people should take care of their own parents when they become old .
In the Singapore 's context , each child has to take a compulsory module of moral education in their early years of schooling .
With these values in placed , responsibility in taking care of the elderly should not be pushed to the government but should be shouldered by the people themselves .
The maintenance of parents act protects the future of the elderly , allowing the elderly to sue for monetary needs if their children refused to provide .
The problem that the aging population is facing right now is the lack of human resources .
We should now invest in creating and attracting talents , both local and foreign , to reduce the impact of the dwindling working force .
Taking Japan for example , by year 2050 , one in three Japanese will be past their retirement age as the average birth rate is reported at 1.23 babies per woman .
One of the solutions is to do a " replacement migration " where foreign talents are recruited to strengthen the human resource in certain countries .
Other than talents , providing the people with a high level of security is essential .
There are currently growing fears of terrorism after the September 11 attacks .
Funds should be cast aside for security purposes , such as military technology to protect the people from external threats .
Only by living in a safe country then can one enjoy the benefits of living to a ripe old age .
Moreover , a dwindling population signifies that there are lesser people to defend the country .
Therefore , technology is highly needed to replace the loss of manpower .
During the wallstreet meltdown in 2008 , many have lost their jobs .
With huge families facing financial crises , the government will have to stand in to provide for the elderly in need .
Not only that , elderly who are being abandoned or are childless are disadvantaged as there is no one to support them in the future .
Therefore , the retirement age should be extended and people should be educated to work longer and save more for their future livelihood .
The elderlylderly should be more independent instead .
Some portion of the funds can be saved if people start to become responsible .
In an aging society with lesser tax payers , government funds will eventually drop and this will provide a huge cut in possible public expenditures needed to sustain a country .
This year , our government intends to spend $ 42.1 million on community- based and residential programmes for the elderly and the disabled
( Singapore Budget , 2009 ) . Let us just think about the money that is going to be spent on the elderly .
However , we need to realize that the older population refers to people who are not only old but are also facing certain difficulties in supporting themselves and they may help to do better .
As mentioned earlier , one reason why we should not limit the spending is that it may not be fair to the elderly when there may be those who are really in great need of support from the government .
We do know that the older population has a higher chance of facing illnesses and inconveniences in their physical movements .
Furthermore , based on the Census 2000 data , in Singapore , we have 14 percent of the elderly who only live with their spouses and 12 percent of the elderly do not live with their immediate family
( citation , 2000 ) . These elderly are facing problems in their lives .
In this case , they may not have the financial ability to take care of themselves without any help from the government .
Hence , it is the government 's duty to render the help to them instead of limiting the help they can receive .
Another reason why we should not limit public spending on the older population is because of the fact that the phenomenon of ageing population is expected to continue growing .
By limiting it , the amount may not be able to cater to all the needs in the future as the limit is set on the basis of a population at a particular time .
Yet over the years , when this group of people increases , especially at rather high rate , the amount needed will be more than the amount being put aside .
However , there is always an opposite side to the issue .
If we did not limit the amount we are spending on the elderly now , this amount would increase proportionately with the increasing number of the elderly in the future .
This will cause the proportion left for developments in other areas to be reduced in the future as well .
In an article in the Reuters , it is indeed believed that as the United States faces growing number of older people , pension and healthcare services are pushed up and thus , compelling major increases in public expenditure
( Maggie , 2009 ) .
However , I see the argument in another way .
The amount of money that the government can use for developments in other areas may not increase even after limiting the spending on elderly .
If we limit the amount the government pays , the additional cost falls on the shoulders of the family members which will then be shifted back to the government by the family in other means
( Robert and Laura , 2005 ) . Since no difference is expected , be it limiting the amount or not doing so , we should try to reduce the pressure that will be felt by the majorities in the future , such as having to pay for the high expenses for the elderly at home .
Instead , keeping it flexible , such as to have it increased in times of great need will be a better choice .
The Madrid International Plan of Action on Ageing ( 2002 ) highlighted : " since year 1950 , the average life expectancy has increased by 20 years and is expected to extend a further 10 years by 2050 " .
In fact , it calls into the question whether the elderly really benefit from the policy implemented in the aspect of financial security , employment and living arrangements .
In terms of economics , old age financial support is the government 's main concern and therefore mechanisms that provide citizens with financial security in old age have been introduced .
For instance , the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) , a comprehensive financial savings plan for the workers , has been implemented in Singapore .
Although the CPF was aimed to give security to the retired elderly by providing income to support their basic needs in old age , it has been accused for its deficiency .
Shantakumar ( 1999 ) , Asher ( 1996 and 1998 ) , Lee ( 1999 an 2001a ) , pointed out the lack of universal coverage and the lack of adequacy of funds for retirement security in the CPF scheme , especially for the low-income elderly ( as cited in David R. Phillips and Alfred C.M .
Meanwhile , in a study by Asia Times Online ( Megawati Wijaya , 2009 ) , it was shown that less than 5 % of the current elderly population rely on CPF disbursements for their livelihood .
All these prove the failure of the CPF scheme in providing a secure future life for most of the elderly .
Apart from that , the government 's initiative in raising the retirement age is also seen to be not effective .
It is undeniable that by increasing the retirement age , the elderly will be able to accumulate wealth and eventually the strain on their finances will be ease .
However , people should take note that the problem now is not about the mandatory retirement age of the elderly , but the employability problem faced by the senior citizens .
The National Survey of Senior Citizens 2005 ( Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports , 2005 ) showed that among the current generation of the elderly , only 28.2 % of them are employed .
Therefore , unless the employability problem is resolved , the increase in retirement age might worthnothing to most of the elderly that are now unemployed .
Besides that , the a ttractive financial incentives for promoting co-residence with parents which are introduced by the Singapore government have faced certain criticisms .
Inevitably , after the financial incentives such as tax reliefs and priority housing have been introduced , there are more adult children who live with , or nearby , their elderly parents .
However , the increase in co-residences with parents does not imply anncrease in the willingness of the children in taking care of their parents .
No one can guarantee that children who live nearby their parents will eventually take good care of them .
There are children who live nearby their parents just because of the attractive incentives .
As suggested in Channel NewsAsia ( Asha Popatlal , 2009 ) , there are more elderly citizens applying to the Tribunal for Maintenance of Parents over the last 12 months .
" From August 2008 to July this year , 172 people filed applications , much higher than the average of 100 in previous years " . ( citation )
This figure shows that the rate of co-residence increases with the cases of parental abuse .
Therefore , it is possible for people to remain dubious about the effectiveness of co-residence in improving the quality of care of the elderly by the adult children .
In conclusion , to a large extent , current policies implemented have not helped much to ease the aging process .
For the CPF scheme , there is lack of adequate funds to ensure retirement security . For the later retirement act , there is employability problems among the elderly that need to be resolved . For the co-residence , there is doubt on the quality of care that the older parents received from their children .
Therefore , current policies should be re-evaluated in their feasibility and should be amended in order to reach the ultimate goalof easing the aging process .
''Public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
''I fully agreed with this statement .
Nowadays , a lot of countries are having aging problem , especially advanced counties like Japan , Sweden , Germany , Singapore and the United State of America .
This global aging is also starting to affect some developing nations such as Malaysia and Thailand .
According to the journals 'A Graying World ' and 'Doomsday Predications about Population Aging Are Exaggerated ' , the population of aged 65 and older is anticipated to more than double by year 2030 and furthermore median age in many first-world countries will reach between 52 to 54 by 2050.If the fertility rates do not rise again , the problem will be worsened .
Demographic changes due to growing aging population will have serious consequences on health issues .
Governments are forced to spend more money to overcome them .
For instance , Singapore needs to restructure the whole health care system due to the aging population as mentioned by the Singapore Prime Minister .
However , the funds have to be used wisely and diverted to other fields of the country 's development .
Firstly , governments have to continue to raise the retirement age in line with rising life expectancies .
The elderly are encouraged to work longer to accumulate more wealth , which could be used to support themselves .
Moreover , a tardy fertility rate has increased the importance of having an workforce in the market .
They could help to boost economic growth by being involved in different kind of sectors .
For some countries with little economic growth , the society faces few choices on how to care for those who are least able to care for themselves .
On the other hand , with sufficient economic growth there are more choices and fewer persons in need ( Robert B. Friedland and Laura Summer,2005 ) .
Secondly , money can be diverted to the education sector .
These people are not only helping the government to cut down expenditures on health care , but also helping the country to generate more income , as well as to stabilize the economy .
That is why a lot of countries are spending a large portion in education .
To illustrate , education expenditures always occupy a larger segment in the fiscal budget in Singapore and Malaysia .
Besides , public policies that encourage and facilitate education , basic research , and the application of promising technologies can enhance the well-being of current and future generations of older people ( Robert B. Friedland and Laura Summer,2005 ) .In other words , elites are able to invent more advanced technology to accelerate nationational development .
All advanced nations are using high technology in every field .
For example , Japan is one of the countries which uses the most advanced technology in manufacturing .
Its car industry almost dominates the world market and has always produced the top-selling cars in most of the countries . For instance , Honda and Toyota are preferred by a lot of car users .
These companies are not only making cars , but are also involved in technology exploration to benefit people .
The Japanese government gives subsidies to these companies to create something more innovative in solving daily life problems .
In contrast , North Korea is still a communist country and it is conservative .
Everything is under government control and civilians are not given any chance to involve in monopoly or private business .
Moreover , most of the funds are spent on nuclear research and relatively there are less spending on people 's needs .
This causes the majority of North Koreans living in poverty .
In addition , governments could give subsidies or incentives to encourage people to increase fertility rates .
If governments provide subsidies to encourage couples to have more children , fertility rates might be changed .
For example , the Singapore government gives different types of incentives and benefits to encourage parents to have and raise children .
The increase in fertility rates is very important to every country as it could generate more manpower , as well as reinforce the country 's military strength .
Other fields of the country 's development are important too .
Therefore , governments may have to choose the most sustainable and efficient way to plan for their national budgets .
The Survey of Senior Citizens ( 1995 ) showed that although the health status among respondents aged 60 and older was generally good , more than 30 per cent have received treatments for some chronic illnesses .
About 25 per cent males and 69 per cent females were never married , widowed or divorced .
Another policy is to ensure that Singaporeans are financially secure after retirement .
Currently , Singapore 's CPF has the highest coverage of all retirement plans in Asia ( Asher , 2006 ) .
This move will increase the period of time for individual savings to last during retirement .
The Government has introduced schemes to encourage Singaporeans to maintain their parents such as the legislation on filial piety , which is as the Maintenance of Parents Act ( Vasoo , Ngiam , 2000 ) .
An aging population has been talked about much in recent years .
Hauner , Leigh , and Skaarup ( 2007 ) believed that countries with a high and rising old-age dependency ratio will expect their age-related spending to escalate by 4 percentage point of their GDP ( Gross Domestic Product ) over the next 45 years .
As a result , governments and policy makers around the world are ready to set aside a larger portion of their countries ' budget to cater for age-related spending , with healthcare for the elderly as most of their top priorities .
However , to avoid compromising the development of other sectors , it is essential for policy makers to limit spending on the elderly by looking into viable alternatives .
Majority of the elderly are not concerned with how much their children give them ; instead they are satisfied as long as their children are able to spend time with them and show their love and concern for them .
Critics of this proposal have pointed out that the money set aside for this scheme will go to waste if the elderly passed away even before they can utilize them .
However , governments of many countries have urged that such saving scheme that offers health protection can be unpredictable .
In this way , it minimizes the chances of them being unable to afford their medical bills , and at the same time reduces the heavy burden on government subsidies .
The scheme provides not only protection for its contributors .
In addition , a substantial payout from the medical insurance will be awarded if he or she is to encounter any mishap , of which death or any form of disability would render the contributor being unable to work .
Lee ( 2008 ) proposed the plan to limit social welfare spending in South Korea in order to invest in programs that will increase the country 's economic growth .
At this point , one might wonder if this move will compromise the welfare of the society and the elderly .
For example , these funds can be used in the research and development of cures for terminal illnesses like cancer .
Therefore , a boundary to the spending on the elderly should be set in order to avoid increasing the burden on future generations and upsetting of the development of other key sectors as mentioned earlier .
However , this has changed because governments and policy makers in the developed world are now confronted with the unprecedented problem of a fast aging population " ( Peterson , 2001 ) .
The aging population has become a major issue in many developed countries , including the United States , Japan and Singapore .
Increasing population of the aged created many problems on the society .
As the problem of the aging population worsens , governments have to spend increasing amount of money to counter the problem and at the expense of other areas of the country 's development .
It is important that governments take note of this and control their spending so as not to neglect other more important areas such as education and the economy .
Governments are stressing on filial obligation and hope to increase the willingness of tomorrow 's grown children to support their own elderly parents .
However , such practices are not common .
It is crucial for the government to spend money on the aged , as not doing so will lead to social problems .
The young no longer see filial piety as being important .
The elderly who are unable to support themselves and are being abandoned by their children will have nowhere to turn to if the government turned its back on them .
This will lead to increased crime rates , begging and vagrancy in the country , which are harmful for society .
As countries spend more money on the aged , other important sectors such as defense and education may get neglected and become under budgeted .
These sectors are as important as , if not more important than , spending on an aging population .
For example , in an increasingly challenging global economy , it becomes increasingly important for countries to focus on education to maintain a skilled workforce .
An educated workforce increases productivity , which drives the economy to increased wealth .
By increasing public spending on an aging population , governments risk overlooking other areas of the country 's development .
New technologies and treatments for the aged are relatively expensive .
People may take advantage of the government subsidies to pay for expensive new technologies which are not necessary .
Limiting public spending will make sure that the government does not overspend on treatment that is not essential , so that the money can be diverted to other areas .
It is hard to cure the illnesses of the aged .
Governments may be spending too much money on expensive medical infrastructure such as new facilities to suit the elderly .
Medical facilities can only prolong their lives , which do not have any significant impact on the country 's economy .
Instead , the governments can divert the money into other projects that are more beneficial to the country 's development .
For example , a new entertainment centre can attract tourists , which will increase foreign spending and benefit the tourism sector .
Governments should be cautious of their spending over expensive medical infrastructure which does not contribute to the country 's future development and should focus more on the nation 's areas of development that do .
Public spending is increasing rapidly with the growing aged population and governments are losing control of their spending .
Governments should adopt a wider perspective to ascertain whether the spending is necessary or the money should be diverted to other areas .
If the usage of public funds is not well balanced , it will not only affect the country 's development , but also put the country 's future into jeopardy .
It is undeniable that aging population is still one of the current issues that are affecting our world nowadays .
It is predicted that the problem will be worse in the future : many of the people in the first world countries will reach the median age of 53 .
Therefore , much should be done to help ease the aging process to avoid social and economical problems in the future .
Of all the different aspects of development that have been done to ease the aging process , the most significant field is medicine .
The aging population has forced a restructuring of the whole healthcare system .
In Singapore , to provide a better life for the aged , many new hospitals are built , such as the Khoo Teck Puat Hospital in Yishun and the Jurong General Hospital .
With these new hospitals , the aged patients get better treatment . They do not have to wait too long and travel too far to a particular hospital to see the doctor .
More hospitals are built to provide appropriate service to the elderly .
With this , the elderly will be able to enjoy their stays in hospitals and do their medical check ups regularly to maintain a healthy lifestyle .
Although more hospitals were being built , many aged patients with financial problems ca n't afford to go to them .
On the other hand , there are also researches done on illnesses which most commonly affect the aged .
Better solutions are hoped to be found in order to help the elderly with their health issues .
For instance , in the United Kingdom , researches on dementia are being done to find a better solution to cure the patients , who are mostly the aged .
To help ensure less elderly from suffering from dementia in the future , researches are now being done by the UK .
Much investment have been put into this research to defeat this illness which is currently and will continue to haunt the aged .
Some may argue that these researches do not help to ease the aging process because most of the time and money are wasted as the proper solutions are never to be .
But it is better to try rather than to allow the devastating disease to continue to haunt the older generations .
Besides researches and developments in the field of medicine , social policy also plays a role in helping to ease the aging process .
Many countries have taken this step to lighten the burden of the elderly .
In Japan , the government has imposed the " National Pension Scheme " on all its citizens .
In this scheme , a basic pension is provided for all citizens who are above 65 years of age and have contributed for 25 years or more to the country .
This scheme is helpful in easing the burden of the elderly as it provides financial security for them .
The aged can then be independent and they do not need to rely on their children for money .
The aged can live a comfortable life without worrying or without seeking for financial aid .
On the other hand , with these schemes , children need not do their duty to take care of their parents .
This may result in social problems in a country .
The younger generation will not be filial to their parents and will not bear the burden to take care of the older generation and will push the burden onto the government .
Although such thoughts may arise , there are no better ways to guarantee a better life for the aged .
Clearly , all these researches , developments and policies have helped the aging population to get a better life .
This effort should be continued as this would guarantee the living standard of the aged .
Thus , with the living standard of the elderly guaranteed , the social problems can also be avoided in a country .
If the country were to spend its budget entirely caring for the aged , then many citizens would shove theiresponsibilities and would not care for their own health , since the healthy , as represented by the country , would care for them .
Since birth , parents would give the best to their children , from clothing to education and this should be reciprocated .
Being able-bodied and in good health , children should not forget their parents ' kindness towards them .
They should assume this responsibility by providing for their parents .
On the other hand , a substantial amount could be saved if not spent in caring for the aged , thereby enabling more funds to be diverted for the country 's development in many other areas .
To rely on ourselves would still be the best option .
For a start , prior planning is crucial , when from young , one should be actively saving .
This would be beneficial in the short run , when facing emergencies , or in the long run , when facing retirement .
This is further enhanced by incentives being offered to companies that hire them .
Instead of grieving with regrets of having to work after reaching the retirement age , they could actually be optimistic and take this as an opportunity to be active in the society , where they could establish friendships through interactions at work .
Although it would be ideal if the government need not be 'burdened ' with expenses to care for the aged , it is not feasible .
In addition , it could also be dreadful for those who are not well equipped with education or skills to work and who really needs the country 's help .
Help given could be in many other forms instead of just monetary .
Although help is given , it is not encouraged for the aged to continuously be reliant on it .
Instead , with the skills acquired , they should 'venture ' out and earn a living of their own which would in turn reap many returns in both monetary and health .
It is also true that " work can help us stay physically active , mentally alert , socially connected and financially self-reliant " ( Yap , 2009 , p. 7 ) .
In fact , every single one of us has a responsibility and role to play in caring for them and the country .
When the country 's resources are not focused mainly in caring for the aged , it could be diverted to other areas of the country 's development , such as economic and social developments .
Limiting public spending in caring for the aged and diverting it to other areas of the country 's development would reap success in the long run . Many many would be able to enjoy the economic and social benefits then .
A country always has to be ready to with any form of challenges .
One such challenge would be the ageing population .
To find a solution to that problem , certain amount of the public spending has to be diverted to it .
According to Robert B.Friedland and Laura Summer ( 2001 ) the working population would be able to share a large proportion of the responsibility , with the government taking care of the aged primarily .
This is one of the long term efforts that the government has decided to invest in so that their public spending on the aged would be reduced in years to come , as the future working population starts to emerge .
An increase in the working population will then allow more resources to be channelled to other areas which demand such funds .
This proves to be a better solution because it allows the government to limit the public spending and fellow citizens to take responsibility .
It is necessary that the country allocates sufficient funds required for its growth and to maintain its competitive edge . Therefore it is necessary for the country to limit its public spending on the aged .
Singapore has decided to increase its public spending in the area of research and development ( R&D ) to $ 7.5 billion ( Singapore Budget highlights , 2009 ) .
Singapore sees an aging population as a potential risk and it channels sufficient funds to the aged . Nonetheless , at the same time , it focuses on other areas of development as well .
Through its R & D , Singapore aims to reach greater heights in the research fields . This would then yield substantial profits to the nation , without which the growth of the nation would be stagnant .
A government should cater to various groups of the population without any form of discrimination .
4.68 % of America 's Federal spending constitutes the assistance category in which 4 out of 5 top assistant recipients come from the health sector ( USA spending , 2009 ) .
The healthealth sector would be one of the areas where help is needed for the aged due to the rising medical expenditure and it is not fair to burden them with the entire cost .
Nonetheless they should also take into consideration the cons of not limiting public spending on the aged .
If that happens and the nation decides to be a welfare state , then it will fail like Britain .
It would no longer be able to have constant economic growths and that would be detrimental for the country .
As such public spending should be limited .
This ageing population problem can be dealt with by increasing the working population , so that it could share the burden of caring for the aged .
Public spending should also be limited because areas like R&D need more funds to ensure constant progress of the nation .
Without a on spending the country would then experience a decline in economic growth .
Therefore , public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
It is an ironic truth that Singapore is facing a demographic challenge as the population aged 65 and older is anticipated to more than double by the year 2030.There is much concern about the current development and policies , of which older people tend to be the principle beneficiaries .
Many policies such as the Maintenance of Parent Act , Baby Bonus Scheme and later retirement agreement have helped to ease the aging process significantly .
Currently , much of the public discussions about an aging society involve the responsibility of children to look after their aged parents .
As we know , Asians pay great attention to filial piety and it is their traditional practice to live together with their parents even after the children are married .
However , life today is different from that of the past . Some Singaporeans do not practise this tradition and they abandon their parents in the old folks ' home or hospitals .
Some of them even disappeared or changed their contact numbers after they have sent their parents to the homes .
This new social phenomenon could be curbed by implementing the Maintenance of Parents Act .
Some feel the state has gone too far by intruding into the delicate relationship between children and their parents .
According to statistics , over 400 parents have sought the aid of the Tribunal of the Maintenance Act since it was set up 3 years ago .
The problem of a growing aging population in Singapore could be curbed by encouraging later retirement , longer working lives , and lower barriers to elder employment , as suggested by Peterson ( year ) .
Some might argue that the seniors are old and fragile to be productive .
However , reality remains that later retirement will ensure the senior citizens a high quality of life in their twilight years .
With financial independence , the seniors would not become a burden to their families .
Not only that , longer working lives enable the elders to remain physically , mentally and socially active for a long time .
Being occupied with work , the aged could actually use their brains more frequently and this reduces the chances of developing senile dementia and Parkinson 's diseases .
As the saying goes , 'no man is an island ' and social activities are essential for the aged to stay healthy .
The seniors could build up their social circles at their work places and this reduces their dependency on their family members .
Moreover , many have expressed their desire to work longer as they want to feel valued and being able to contribute to the society .
In a nutshell,late retirement and prolonged working lives are effective solutions to ease the problems of an aging population .
Last but not least , an aging population brings about a shrinking workforce and a significant decline in real GDP .
Modern parents prefer to have fewer children , as compared to the past generation .
Therefore , the government introduces the Baby Bonus Scheme which lightens the financial cost of raising children .
Furthermore , all the children born on or after 17 August 2008 will also enjoy government contributions in the form of a dollar-for-dollar matching .
In a nutshell , it may be said without any fear of contradiction that the current policies have helped to ease the aging process to a large extent .
At present , the median age is 36.7 ( Singapore Statistics , 2008 ) and it is estimated that if current demographic trends persisted , the median age will rise to 41 years by 2030 , lagging behind only by Japan
( Wijaya , 2009 ) . The rapid growth in ageing population brings about controversial issues and one of which is related to the allocation of expenditure for the aged .
A prominent example would be public spending on healthcare , which occupies 4.5 % of Singapore 's gross national expenditure
( Wijaya , 2009 ) . Although it is one of the lowest in comparison to other countries , the rapidlyageing population makes it difficult for the Singapore government not to increase public spending on the aged and allocate more on other areas instead , such as the Research & Development industry .
The problems associated with a rapidlyageing population suggest that public spending should not be limited and allocated to other areas .
The problems are lower birth rate , rising healthcare development costs to meet growing ageing needs and economic loss incurred from a neglected welfare system .
With the implementation of the Maintenance of Parents Act in Singapore , it is arguable that the younger generations are not only morally responsible for , but also compelled to taking care of their aged parents .
However , the low fertility rate in Singapore challenges this argument because the financial burden resulting from the provision of aged parents is currently increasing on fewer offspring .
It is definitely taxing for an only child to bear the financial cost of his orher parents .
Moreover , the rising cost of healthcare adds further strains to the limited income of the younger generation , which often lead to children being unable to fend for their parents and thus abandoning them .
This is shown in year 2008 , in which approximately 172 senior citizens filed applications to the tribunal against their children
( Wijaya , 2009 , ) . Hence , this shows that even with current government assistance such as healthcare subsidies and tax reliefs , the low fertility rate in Singapore continues to urge the government to spend on the aged in order to meet the needs of an ageing society .
Singapore is a well-established country with advanced healthcare facilities .
Many perceive the current public spending on the development of healthcare facilities as being sufficient to meet the ageing demands .
However , this is often not the case .
Singapore faces a sharp shortage of medical specialists in the areas of geriatric field and palliative care and to the extent of importing foreign nurses into the medical industry .
This implies that the government has to invest more on training local medical specialists in these fields to meet the growing ageing needs and thus , more expenditure is required .
Furthermore , hospitals are constantly facing shortages of beds and long average waiting time ; the major factor of this problem is the geriatric patients .
The geriatric patients are often the ones who occupy the majority of hospital bed space and they suffered from chronic illnesses that require regular follow-up consultations .
Therefore , in the recent 2009 National Day Rally speech , Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong emphasized the need for step-down care such as more community hospitals , day-care centres as well as nursing homes .
In this way , more competent healthcare is provided satisfy the demands , since geriatric patients can receive treatment in acute hospitals and then recuperate in the community hospitals .
In addition , some will disagree that it is not feasible to expand public spending on the aged because it would neglect the development of other areas such as the Research & Development sector and the Banking & Finance sector , resulting in the loss of competitiveness and investors ' confidence on Singapore 's economy .
A neglected welfare system for the aging causes social instability to the country . For instance , citizens would feel cash-strapped with the rising healthcare costs and there would be myriad cases reporting about elderly poverty or abandonment .
All in all , it has become a fact that Singapore is currently facing a rapidly ageing population . Many problems will arise should public spending on the aged be limited and this include increased financial burden on the fewer offsprings , insufficient funds for rising healthcare development costs and weakened economic competiveness .
On November 13 , 2006 , the Prime Minister of Singapore , Lee , said in a speech : " Singapore has treated social welfare as a dirty word .
The four economies in East Asia --- Singapore , Hong Kong , Taiwan , and South Korea have taken the approach to being a 'light welfare state ' , in which they have achieved high standard of living without burdening the state with heavy social expenditures ( Midgley , 1986 ) .
In contrast , the western welfare states that fund heavily on social expenditure have hindered the functioning of the private market .
With no limits set on the expenditure of welfare for the aged , a country will face enormous financial burdens in the funding of the public pension system , expensive healthcare system and long-term dependency expenditures .
Currently Japan is facing financial difficulties in gathering funds for their National Pension and Employee 's pension insurance .
The Japanese government is now emphasizing on achieving economic growth rather than increasing welfare expenditures to support its growing aging society .
It is estimated that if the deficit budget continued , Hong Kong 's $ 369 billion fiscal reserves would be wiped out by 2008-2009 ( South China Morning Post , February 23 , 2002 ) .
There is a contradiction of a capitalistic society being a welfare state .
This means that people will not see the need to save for retirement funds or work to be financially secure , as they know they can depend on the government .
" Encouraging senior citizens to work will help them to contribute to society , and at the same time , ensure that they are financially independent .
However caring for the elderly , especially those who can not provide for themselves , is being prioritized as a national issue .
Besides having support from the government , the 'light welfare states ' rely heavily on the private sector and family to provide care for the aged .
There are also other public assistance programs for medical , housing , transportation , and even funeral preparations .
In addition , there are public and private sector mix of welfare programs and organizations .
In Singapore , there are " over 300 existing voluntary welfare organizations and service providers " and recently , the Centre for Enabled Living ( CEL ) , with some help from the government , was launched to provide a first-stop referral service to the existing welfare organisations .
Family support and close kinship , which exists strongly in an Asian society , has also helped in decreasing the state 's welfare dependency .
In conclusion , public spending on the aged should be limited to curb heavy financial expenditures , and t 'welfare diseases ' that would undermine any incentive to work .
It will not be a feasible plan to drain money from national reserves to fill up a bottomless pit .
Money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development to earn revenues in order to support the aging population .
The responsibilities of caring for the aged are divided between the private and family sector to lessen the burden on the state .
Help is readily available to those who are incapable of providing for themselves .
" Aging of population " is a term used to describe the shift in the age distribution of a population toward older ages ( Leonid A. Gavrilov and Patrick Heuevline , year ) .
Thus this refers to an increase in the population 's mean age which is generally due to a decline in birth rate and an increase in life expectancy .
Problems associated with an aging population will be the increase in social and healthcare cost and lower level of productivity .
As one ages , one 's body tends to be more vulnerable to health problems and this will add on to the medical cost which requires funding from the government . This would put greater stress on the younger generation in terms of increasing taxes .
Moreover , we will also expect a shortage of labor which would affect the level of efficiency of the country .
Hence , ongoing medical research and government 's policies can help to alleviate these problems .
Firstly , medical advancements help to lighten the burden of healthcare cost .
The mass production of medicine lowers the cost of the drugs .
Moreover , polyclinics provide highly subsidized medical care which benefits the elderly greatly .
There is also an increase in research on healthier food and supplements that helps to inform and advise the public to adopt a healthier lifestyle .
However , these benefits may only favor a small group of the elderly , probably the more educated and richer ones as they are the ones who can comprehend the latest information regarding healthcare research , as well as afford health-checks and supplements .
Long waiting queues in polyclinics due to highly subsidized medical fees may deter those elderly with real needs .
In addition , the location may not be accessible to some elderly , especially for those who are physically disabled .
From another point of view , government intervention may help to solve the problem .
In the case of Singapore , the increasing number of polyclinics that are set up throughout the island resolved the long queues and inaccessibility problem .
Besides this , polyclinics are upgraded to offer a clean and fresh environment . For example , air-conditioning are installed and Nurse Clinician Service is implemented where patients with chronic conditions can make appointments in advance to reduce their waiting time and this further ensures the comfort level of the patients ( Polyclinics Singhealth , 2009 ) .
Health screening at affordable prices organized by the government helps to identify potential health risks .
In addition , free health talks help to educate the elderly , especially the uneducated ones and advise them to lead a healthy lifestyle .
Hence , these measures enable the elderly to have a better understanding of their bodies and therefore reduce the healthcare cost .
Secondly , automation helps to reduce the social cost and reduces the need for the younger generation to take care of the aging population .
Automations such as dish-washer allow the elderly to do simple chores at home and it increases the level of independence of the elderly .
As one ages , our body tends to suffer from pains all , automation such as massage machines help to relieve pain and it might reduce the possibility for a doctor consultation .
Besides this , remote controlled lighting helps the elderly to control the house lights with a remote control and therefore , minimizes the risk of falling in the dark .
Thus , the responsibility of the younger generation can be greatly reduced , such as the need of caretakers and medical costs .
Luxurious goods such as massage machines and lighting systems are only affordable for the rich and they may not cut down the chances of getting sick .
In addition , automation only reduces the need for human labor , but there is no guarantee that it is able to drive down social costs .
When viewed from another angle , government policies help to maximize the welfare of the elderly .
The setting up of community centres which organize activities for the elderly , is beneficial for the elderly .
Hence , we can conclude that automation can be seen as a tool in relieving the aging process .
Extended lifespans have the elderly to work more and longer .
Hence , higher productivity is achieved , thus reducing the burden of the younger generation in paying taxes .
However , some may argue that the elderly may not be fit enough to work and there are doubts if the older workforce can achieve a similar level of efficiency that is expected from the younger workers . Therefore this makes it more difficult for the elderly to look for a job .
From another point of view , there is only a minority who are unable to work ; the majority should continue to work as long as they are able to and thus will not be seen as an extra burden to society .
In addition , countries like Singapore has started to tackle aging problems where the government is getting companies to rehire workers aged 62 .
Moreover , extended working years should be encouraged as a result of longer lifespan and increased literacy of future elderly .
Therefore , it is possible that productivity can still be sustain among the aging population .
In conclusion , I agree to a large extent that government policies that have been implemented helped to alleviate the aging process .
Developments in the future will be expected to be much better , and though aging process is inevitable its inconveniences can be minimized .
The average age of human has increased drastically within the last and this has led to fast aging populations that raised concerns among governments and policy makers .
According to ( 2008 ) , from 1900 to 2005 , life expectancy at birth increased from 46 to 75 years for men and from 48 to 80 years for women .
The aging process has caused unprecedented problems for society , especially for the aged , who face plenty of illnesses when they become older .
Besides that , countries face difficulties in supporting a growing number of the aged as there are many vulnerable aged who live alone and need assistance from governments .
Therefore policies have been implemented to ease the aging process and to support the aged . Undeniably , there have been significant successes in the strategies used .
To ease the aging process , governments have to put in a great effort in the research of medicine to provide the best treatment for the aged .
Since there is an obvious advancement in technology when compared to previous years , there are more inventions in medicine and equipment to treat illnesses .
However , some people may think that the aged will not be able to afford the treatment as better equipment and treatments will increase the cost .
To prevent such a situatio from happening , governments have introduced insurance schemes to reduce the cost of treatment .
For example , the Singapore government has introduced the CPF Medisave Scheme and Medishield Scheme which can cover part of the treatment fees : the patient need not pay any fees for outpatient treatments and Medishield will pay 80 % of the actual expenditure up to the claimable limit .
Through this , the government ensures that the aged get the proper treatments to reduce their sufferings .
Thus far , The government has introduced some new economic policies to ease the aging process .
This includes lengthening the age of retirement so that the aged have longer working lives ( Peterson , 2001 ) , so that they can earn more money when they are still working to support themselves .
The strategy of lowering the barriers to elder employment is effective in increasing the rate of employment among the aged .
However , some people may think that the aged is a burden to society as they believe that the physical condition of the aged can not cope with the development of the country .
While this may be true , facts have shown that the aged can still contribute to the economy as they have more experiences when compared to the others .
They share their experiences with the young and this can help to improve the economy of the country .
The government could use the money to help the aged and ease the aging process .
In addition , community centers or community clubs have their policies to ease the aging process .
It analyses the needs and existing services within the county and prepares a comprehensive plan for the delivery of services to the aged .
The community centers organize activities such as performances , games and feasts to help them feel less lonely , cheer them up and make them happy and this has eased the aging process in the society .
There are also many enthusiasts and volunteers in the society who are willing to spend their time accompanying the aged , as they know that they can give mental support to the aged .
Peterson ( 2001 ) mentions that aging process in a country will cause a shrinking workforce , long-term stagnation and decrease in real GDP .
As a result , the whole societ , including the aged , will face a lot of problems as some of them are still seeking aid from the government .
Leaders of countries must rise above ideology and engage practical realities to cope with the problem of a fast aging population .
Therefore , governments and policy makers have implemented some policies in easing the aging process .
by doing this , governments can ensure the development of their countries and provide a better living environment to all their people .
However , with the limited budget the country has , it is essential that the more important priorities are first taken care of before large scale policies are implemented to help the aged .
First of all , the country should spend the bulk of their budget on areas which are of great importance .
One of these areas would be that of the military
The significance of the military to a nation is so great that it is not possible for a country to constrict its spending in this area .
With the ever present threat of terrorism , which has the potential to cause huge destruction , there is no doubt that investing in the military is of greater importance than taking care of the welfare of the elderly .
The government should not hesitate to invest in the latest military technology and equipment .
This is to ensure that the country will be able to defend itself should any undesirable situations arise .
However , others may argue that Singapore has always enjoyed peace and that there are no signs of any conflicts with other nations arising .
With the increasing number of elderly coupled together with the issue of the low birth rate , the aging population problem has certainly become more pressing in recent years .
However , national security will always be one of the most important aspects to a country .
This dire effect is something we can not afford , thus , investing in military goods will definitely be one of the top priorities of the government .
Secondly , the government should allocate its available resources wisely so as to obtain the most effective use of them .
To achieve this , money has to be channelled into research and development instead of spending excessively on the aged .
With these , the country will be well-equipped to ensure sustained economic growth and to head towards a prosperous and progressive nation .
No doubt , some may argue that the nation should always show its gratitude to the elders of the nation by making sure that they are well taken care of .
However , if the country were to divert most of its public spending to the aged now , it is almost certain that it will face an arduous problem in the near future .
Neglecting the other areas of the country 's development will hinder its progress and lead to limited economic growth and thus a shrinking budget .
As mentioned by Friedland and Summer ( 2005 ) in " Doomsday Predictions about Population Aging Are Exaggerated " , with little economic growth , there are fewer choices about how to care for the elderly thus intensifying the problem on hand .
Therefore , it is essential to ensure healthy economic growth as it will provide many alternatives to the problems Singapore faces .
As can be seen from the above arguments , due to the limited resources available , and the ever growing number of issues that need to be tended to , it is impossible to ensure that all areas of Singapore 's development are well funded .
Thus , the government has to prioritize and allocate resources wisely so that the goals of having a stable and prosperous nation can be achieved. .
Humanity has come a long way in evolving and adapting to the changing environment .
Through the years , it has managed to overcome several limitations , which in the past were nothing more than dreams .
It succeeded in landing on the moon and communicating over long distance , yet there are still some boundaries it still has to cross despite its best effort .
While the ticking clock in our body can not be stopped advance technology and modern governance have made it possible for aging to be delayed and relieved to a great extent .
High-tech equipment and medication are available for the treatment of more illnesses as our understanding of medicine improves . Governments nowadays are also doing more for the elderly population in their society .
With more emphasis placed on healthcare by governments today and the advancement of medical technology , people get to live longer .
People , including the elderly , are made less vulnerable to diseases , and in a way , people become biologically stronger .
" One hospitalisation , for example , a stroke can set you back tens of thousands of dollars , " as stated by Associate Professor Paulin Straughan , sociologist , National University of Singapore in Channel NewsAsia ( 2009 , August 19 ) .
For this group of people , most governments intervene to help subsidise treatments they genuinely need .
In some others such as Singapore , the people are compelled to provide in advance for their old age .
For example , in Singapore , elderly parents may file in court if their children do not provide for them .
In the case of government pensions , the heavy spending of public funds on the aged may take a toll on other areas of the nation 's development .
Thus a method that works in one society may not work in another and sometimes , multiple approaches have to be taken .
However , better healthcare and protection from the government result in rising age expectancy , which is a double-edged sword because on one hand , people live longer as shown in the report ( Friedland and Summer , 2005 , Fig 1-2 ) and on the other hand , the proportion of aging population increases if the younger generation are not reproducing enough , This is the trend today in developed nations .
In today 's fast-paced society , there are several factors , such as high living costs and late marriages that discourage people from reproducing " . Peterson has claimed that , " If fertility rates do not rise again , the problem will worsen as the median age in many first-world countries will reach 51 by 2050 , " .
As the number of elderly increases , with a great , there might not be enough young people in the workforce to support the economy and generate enough money for healthcare subsidies and government pensions as mentioned previously .
However , this revolution has generated a rising aging population which may be a problem to all levels of the society .
Governments in developed countries should look beyond temporary solutions to the rising aging population and focus on getting people to reproduce .
While there are initiatives like maternity welfare and the baby bonus to encourage reproduction , more can be done for the better .
Many people have argued that public spending on the aged is a must for countries facing the problem of an aging population as an ageing population has dire social , economical and cultural consequences on the country .
True as it seems , the question posed here is how should the government allocate its resources to cope with this problem .
As the saying goes , 'Give the man a fish and feed him for a day , teach the man to fish and feed him for a lifetime' .
Therefore , the use of the country 's resources should be well diversified to different areas of the country 's development so that no one area is compromised on .
With elderly care hugely subsidized by the government , the aged will tend to be reliant on the government providing for their old age .
This has caused the aged to be heavily dependent on the government and thus has developed a negative practice of the aged not saving for their own retirement .
It may be argued that the money which is not saved for retirement can be better spent elsewhere .
Although it is argued that the 'extra money ' that the elderly possess will be better spent elsewhere , it may not be spent in the most efficient way possible .
Adam Smith also points out that individuals will act in their own advantage , not that of the society .
With more money from public spending spent on the aged , this also means that there is less money for the other areas of development in the country .
Other areas of development that will increase the economic growth of the country will then be compromised .
Critics of this position point out that when more money is spent on the aged , it generates economic growth .
With better and more affordable healthcare services provided for , the elderly can be healthier and more economically productive .
This will allow the elderly to be able to work for longer and delay their retirement .
This will then increase the labour force of the country and result in economic growth .
By designating the role of the caregiver of the elderly to the government , " Asian values " such as filial piety will be eroded as children may shed the responsibility of taking care of their parents to the government .
It may be objected that these values are innate to one 's identity and are not easily influenced or changed by other factors .
In Singapore , one is compelled to undertake the role of the caregiver and this is backed up with law of maintenance of parent 's act to ensure one fulfills one 's filial obligations .
But in view of the many problems that a country would face if large amount of public spending are spent on the aged , it is only wise that the government diversifies its public spending to other areas of development and strikes a balance among the other priorities .
Technological advancement enables humans to live longer .
On the other hand , the younger generation are chasing after 'an individualistic and 'live life to the fullest ' lifestyle. .
In the long run , this will translate into a low fertility rate in the country .
In the case of Singapore , the growing elderly population should not be accompanied by restrictions in public spending on the aged , which may come in the form of pension schemes , medical insurance , healthcare benefits and disability allowance .
This is because the current benefits that are provided for the elderly are still inadequate .
In terms of welfare and poverty , less than 5 % of households in the low income group are beneficiaries of the state-funded system .
Only 0.07 % received public assistance in 2004 ( Asher & Nandy , 2008 ) .
If public spending on low income groups is limited , there would be fewer elderly who could benefit from government aid .
Therefore , an increase in social disparity and healthcare problems would be an issue for the country .
Although public spending on the elderly is an endless process as they do n't generate much productivity to the country , social responsibility as a nation needs to be promoted. .
There are many elderly people who are unable to support themselves and have to take up jobs like road sweeping and toilet cleaning .
Besides that , the elderly were once the people who contributed to the growth of the nation and economy .
Therefore , there should not be a need to divert public spending on the elderly to other areas of the country 's development .
The nation 's infrastructure , development and trade are in a desirable condition and the current spending on them is adequate to sustain economic growth .
Hence , the government should not focus on limiting public spending but on ways to spend it wisely .
One example is means-testing .
In addition to that , the money that is spent on helping the elderly is partially their money which was deducted through tax payment .
Thus , policy makers have the responsibility to provide the elderly with .
The aged should be able to enjoy social security during their later years .
We have to be conscious that even though they are deemed as a liability , they are also part of the nation and should not be neglected .
However , there are certain groups of elderly who are single , child-less , not on good terms with their children or who still need to support their 'parasitic ' adult children .
On top of that , the elderly who are disabled and suffering from chronic illnesses need a large sum of money to deal with their condition .
Even with the assistance of MediSave and MediShield , elderly people suffering from terminal illnesses will not be able to pay for their high healthcare costs when their bank accounts are exhausted ( Channel NewsAsia , 2009 ) .
Although this will create a sense of dependency on the government , it is an unavoidable situation where the government needs to care for its citizens .
In summary the government should not limit public spending on the elderly and divert it to other areas of the country 's development .
This is due to the ascending numbers of elderly in the coming years that need to be dealt with ( Friedland & Summer , 2005 ) .
These elderly were once the people who helped in building up the nation and the government should show their compassion and care for this vulnerable group by not restricting public spending on them .
It is vital that the expenditure on the elderly is delegated according to their needs so that wastage can be avoided .
Hence , more elderly people can benefit through this act and it would not be seen as wastage of the country 's funds .
The aging processes in Singapore with its ensuing serious impacts , has caught people 's attention. .
The aging process requires special attention because due to the low birth rate , Singapore has became an aging country with a large fraction of its population being aged .
The government is currently carrying out research and implementing policies to help to ease the aging process for both the elderly and the country .
The latter involves developing public facilities that cater to the needs of the elderly who are physically weak .
Research on healthcare and infrastructure has been constantly improving to ease the aging process .
Firstly , the government is currently researching the possible type of chronic illnesses that are likely to surface at a certain age of life , at the same time as implementing control measures to prevent the occurring of the illness .
As the saying goes , prevention is better than cure , thus the government sector such as the health promotion board and the Singapore eye care centre is constantly organizing campaigns to raise the awareness of the elderly regarding the serious consequences associated with the illnesses .
They also provide free medical checkups for the elderly usually aged 50 and above for early detection illness .
This is because for the elderly , who are illiterate and living alone , may not know that there are such campaigns going on as they are unable to read campaigns published in newspapers , or understand advertisements telecasted over the television as they are mostly in English or Chinese .
Thus the elderly that only understand dialect will not get the message thereby defeating the purpose of the campaign .
Next , improvisation of infrastructure on public transportation and housing estates is another area of research that is being focused on .
For public transport , a portion of seats have been removed leaving a spacious area to suit the needs of the elderly that are wheelchair bound .
In housing estates , the government has upgraded flats that are relatively old and inconvenient for the elderly .
Examples of upgrading is lifts that are now able to stop at every storey of the flat and within the lift there are handles for the elderly to hold on to for support while taking the lift .
Also all the squat toilets have been converted to seat toilets to avoid accidents of people slipping and falling when squatting and standing up .
This improved infrastructure kills two birds with one stone as it not only provides for the elderly , it also benefits the handicapped . Thus this research does not only serve the elderly , it also serves other purposes as well .
Policies complement the research .
Given the high cost of living in Singapore , the government has provided benefits for the elderly by granting subsidizes on healthcare .
This policy works well because the aged would have their savings used for daily expenses such as food and necessities .
Apart from subsidies , the government have reorganized the healthcare system to cater to the needs of the elderly .
For example , the government have taken a step-down approach by including more community hospitals and nursing homes in the health care sector that are more affordable than staying in the hospital .
This policy is workable as the elderly can recuperate better in a community hospital as they do not have to worry much about the medical fees .
Also , community hospitals provide convenience as they are near the neighborhood thus enabling them to get medical aid soon after they fall sick . It also helps to assure their children that there 's someone to attend to their sick parents when they are at work .
However , although the cost of healthcare is greatly reduced , there are cases whereby the elderly who are childless and do not have any savings or income , do not have any medisave to pay for the large amount of medical fee incurred .
Even though there are subsidies , the elderly will still not be able to afford medical expenses .
The next policy that is suggested is to give rebates to those who purchase a house that is close to their parents .
This is to encourage children to visit their parents often thus giving them a sense of warmth and security .
Some children will only make use of the reason to get as much subsidy as possible and they might not visit their parents even though they are living very near .
Therefore , although all these approaches have only provided limited ways of easing the aging process , they still offer a feasible and practical approach .
Only a small group of the aging population faces these limitations and the government may also come out with other policies to solve these problems so that the approach implemented can be workable without any flaws and limitations .
Besides relying on the government , Singaporeans must also pay attention to the aging issue and help to play a part in reducing elderly dependence on the government .
For instance , they can help to take care of their aged parents ,or be a volunteer to contribute to a society that is gradually aging .
People must put themselves in elderly people 's shoes and realize that one day they will also be aged and need the support of their children and others .
Likewise , , if people do not treat others well , one day they may receive the same treatment .
In Singapore , increasing life expectancy together with high-quality healthcare and declining fertility rates are the causes of the graying population .
Besides slow economic growth , one result of the ageing population in Singapore is the rising pension and healthcare costs , which forces a major increase in public spending .
Hence , governments and policy- makers face great challenges towards the ageing population .
Nevertheless , despite the fact that the ageing population is likely to hurt public finances , it is crucial to recognize the well-being and livelihood of the aged can not be compromised by investing in other developments for economic gains .
This is because the elderly have not only contributed significantly to the society , but in fact have many important roles to play .
For instance , they represent the link with our history and tradition which is a crucial source of cultural identity and social stability ( Rasheed , 2010 )
While Singapore strives to develop itself to become a " world-class " and self-sufficient country , it is equally important for its society to be socially stable and secure .
Singapore was lauded by economists " for avoiding the pitfalls of erecting an expensive welfare state that diverts government funds from economic development ( Burton , 2007 ) . "
This is because over the years , Singaporeans have been encouraged and educated to be financially independent , self-reliant and to plan for their old-age ,so as not to be overly dependent on the government .
For instance , Singapore established its social security through the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) in 1955 , which is a mandatory savings programme that funds pensions and healthcare for citizens ( Burton , 2007 ) .
One example is the passing of the Maintenance of Parents Act that allows parents to sue their children for financial support ( Wijaya , 2009 ) .
In other words , public spending on the aged should be limited so that the government can pour in more state funding into other areas of the country 's development such as education , research and development ( R&D ) , urban development and upgrading public transport and housing. .
As a result , these efforts to invest and develop the nation benefits future generations of all ages .
Firstly , despite the fact that the CPF is a flexible scheme to enforce savings for individuals , it has shown signs of weakness and has been seen as being insufficient to last for one 's retirement years ( Tsao , 2008 ) .
One of the fundamental reasons for insufficient funds in one 's CPF is the need of the population to finance their public housing .
Additionally , it is especially hard for elderly people ,whose wages were low during the early 60s and 70s , to keep up with the rising cost of living ( Burton , 2007 ) .
Furthermore , the CPF does not protect certain segments of the population who were not able to work and save during their younger days .
For instance , housewives were not able to contribute to their Medisave because they had to raise their family and chose not to work as a result .
Eventually , this does not only burden the aged with insufficient funds to support their medical expenditures but it also strains the relationship with their children as they need to provide more monetary contributions to their parents .
These reasons continue to urge the government to expand public spending on the aged so as to sustain the needs and livelihood of the aged within the population .
In a survey , it was reported that 66.0 % of senior citizens aged 55 and above were provided with a regular cash contribution from their children .
Additionally , it has been shown that dependence on children to finance their healthcare expenditure increased with age and only 35.8 % of senior citizens aged 55 and above have a clean bill of health ( Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports [ MCYS ] , 2005 ) .
In other words , most elderly people are rather dependent on their children to support them , particularly those who suffer from chronic illnesses .
This dependence is coupled with rising health care costs that is taking a toll on their children 's finances .
Besides , the decline in the number of children supporting elderly parents due to smaller family sizes , puts further strain on the children ( Wijaya , 2009 ) .
Therefore , the government ought to increase its public spending to assist and ease the strain of children supporting their aged parents .
On the whole , as Singapore 's population ages rapidly , it accentuates the need to increase public spending on the aged in order to meet greater healthcare demands and the rising cost of living .
As discussed earlier , rising healthcare costs coupled with longer living parents puts pressure on cash-strapped children to provide for their elderly parents .
Apart from that , the aged are also burdened by inadequate funds in their CPF accounts due to various reasons. .
In short , the aged need more financial help from the government so as to ease the strain on the elderly as well as their children .
Nowadays , the aging population is increasing and the problem is more serious .
In 2008 , the proportion of the elderly in Singapore was 8.6 % and it is estimated that the proportion of the elderly in 2003 will increase to 18.7 % .
From another perspective , an increase in the aging population will lead to an increase in government spending on the elderly .
According to statistics , the elderly dependency ratio in Singapore is 11.9 per 100 in 2008 .
However , public spending on senior citizens should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development such as taking care of the needy , the unfortunate , the young and infrastructure .
Public money that is saved can be diverted to building infrastructure because it benefits all social classes such as the elderly , the needy , the unfortunate and the young by increasing their social welfare .
In addition , an increase in infrastructure can attract investment from abroad because facilities are fully equipped .
Furthermore , an increase in infrastructure can attract more tourists to travel to Singapore
The building of infrastructure makes tourists feel comfortable and it is convenientt because tourists can travel around the country without barriers .
For instance , , Mass Rapid Transit ( MRT ) , roads , buildings , and resorts are some of the facilities that can be provided to increase social welfare .
Public funds that are saved can be used to develop the economy because economic growth will increase the standard of living .
The government can not choose to develop everything because of the scarcity of resources , such as land , funds and workers .
Therefore , the government has to choose the most beneficial areas to invest in .
In addition , the government can also invest in areas where profit and social welfare can be improved so that the standard of living will be increased .
Therefore , citizens have more job options and find it easier to be hired .
Moreover , citizens can request higher salaries as the economy has improved .
Therefore , the standard of living will be much better compared to the past .
New products and technology will benefit citizens by giving them satisfaction and convenience .
For example , new medicines for the elderly to improve health , electronic wheelchairs for handicapped people and robots to take care of the children and elderly .
Moreover , some of the research and development is not only beneficial to the economy , but is also environmentally friendly .
Therefore , environmental pollution can be lessened by reduced fuel usage. .
In conclusion , public spending should not be mainly on the elderly as the money should be used for other areas of the country 's development .
Public money that is saved can be diverted to increase social welfare and the reputation of the country. .
Moreover , the development of the country is a long-term investment and it must be planned properly because it will affect the future of the next generation .
Senior citizens can contribute to the nation by imparting their knowledge and sharing their experience with the younger generations .
Have you ever asked yourself , How will we live in the old age ?
Who will take care of us ? Our descendants , ourselves or the government
Nowadays , more and more people have to concern themselves with these questions as the fast aging population is becoming a serious problem which many countries are confronted with .
In my opinion , because there are a lot of effective methods to solve the aging problem , except for medical and welfare programs , the government should limit spending on the aging population in order to develop other areas .
When the economy grows , fewer old persons need to be helped because of the following reasons .
The first point that should be taken into consideration is that the more economic growth there is , the more chances the elderly have to find jobs .
For example , people can invite nurses to their homes to look after their old parents everyday , or the elderly can live in rest homes with creature comforts and a lot of care .
It is said that the government should spend a lot of money on the aging population in order to reduce the burden on young people .
This argument goes on to assert that because the expenditure of time and money on caring as well as buying medicine for the elderly is enormous , public spending on the aged will help young people concentrate more on their work and improve their quality of life .
However , increasing public spending on the aged is not a sustainable long term strategy .
If other areas of the country 's development such as education and the economy are not invested in adequately , future generations of older people are likely to be even worse off .
The first reason is that if people are not educated well in their young days , their lives in old age will be very vulnerable as people with more education tend to have higher incomes and better health .
Therefore , concentrating on prior areas of the country 's development instead of investing significant amounts of money on the aged is likely to ensure better lives for future groups of older people .
Because few medical and welfare programs are launched when government expenditure on the aging population decreases , many people may have not enough money to send their old parents to rest homes .
They have to spend more time taking care of their parents by themselves .
As a result , family sentiment is enhanced significantly within societyin society
In conclusion , because of enhanced economic growth , ensuring better lives for future generations of older people and stressing filial obligation , limiting public spending on the aged in order to invest in other areas of the country 's development is a good approach to solve the global aging problem .
In order to make the most of the limited budget for the aging population , the government should concentrate on supporting people who really need aid such as older single women .
An aging population is a common situation in many developed countries .
With the number of elderly increasing rapidly there are numerous problems like deterioration of health .
There is a need for governments to focus on these problems , in order to improve the welfare of the aged .
However , this may lead to an issue of whether the governments should limit their public fund on the aged .
One argument is that , instead of limiting spending , it is morally right to spend money on the aged who contributed most of their life to nation building .
Critics may argue that public funding should be used for cultivating the younger generations , who will be the future pillar of the countr , instead of spending public funds on the elderly who no longer capable of contributing to society .
The elderly have contributed a lot to society
It is because of the elderly who participated in many aspects of nation building such as education .
Therefore , we are able to enjoy comfortable lives today .
There is an ancient Chinese proverb " remember the source while drinking the water " which can be applied to this case .
The contributions of the elderly should not be forgotten , the need to reward them for their efforts is crucial .
Therefore , the government should not reduce public funding on the elderly .
Instead , the government needs to recognize the efforts contributed by the elderly in nation building .
The public funding spent on the construction of medical infrastructure as well as the building of elderly friendly houses are beneficial to all human beings .
Since there is no way to escape aging , the government needs to pay a lot of pay a lot of attention to the issues relating to aging .
Therefore , the government has implemented the three M policies -Medifund , MediShield and Medicsave .
In addition , the government is focusing on care too .
For example , the co-operation between the Changi general hospital and St Andrew 's community health care .
These measures help to reduce expensive medical fees for the aged as well as catering to the needs of the elderly .
These measures will benefit the younger citizens in times to come .
In the above paragraph , it was mentioned that if the government does not target the health issue of the aged seriously , it may eventually backfire. .
The unhappiness and anger towards the government 's willingness to deal with the issue may increase among the aged .
An atmosphere of anger may slowly result in strikes .
Hong Kong is one example .
Additionally , the uncaring image of the government will slowly encourage the migration of citizens
Therefore , the government needs to pay extra attention to taking care of the aged .
On the other side of the coin , if the needs of the elderly are well taken care off , they will still be capable of contributing to society .
For example , Lee Kuan Yew , Minister Mentor of Singapore , is still active in politics by advising young politicians .
The requirement for Mr. Lee to remain active in politics is good health .
Thus , it is crucial for the government to spend more public funds in dealing with medical problems of the aged .
In conclusion , public spending on the aged should not be limited .
I agree that other areas do need public funding , and indeed money has to be spent on it .
This positive impression will in turns attract foreigners to choose the country as a destination for pleasure .
An aging population is a problem affecting many global countries .
With an increasing aging population , countries will face lower productivity and increased social and health care costs .
Therefore , part of public spending should be placed on the interest of the elderly and the rest should be diverted to other areas of the country 's development to help boost economic growth .
Though it is a long term investment which takes many years to help generate income for the country , it is definitely worth the investment .
When the government steps in to provide subsidies for eligible students to further their education , the country has a population with higher qualifications as it covers more of those less fortunate families who could not afford the huge amount of school fees .
For example , the European Commission has contributed 2 billion to ICT research projects as ICT is one of the areas that underpin Europe 's economic performance and it is pivotal to its economic growth ( Europe 's Information Society , 2008 ) .
It is stated in the article that " it is essential to have continuous investment in research and development when difficult policy decisions to support the real economy worldwide " ( Europe 's Information Society , 2008 ) .
Another example , 2.4 % of Singapore 's GDP ; amounting to 3 billion euros , is spent on research and development ( Gafoor , 2008 ) .
Nevertheless , Singapore is planning to increase its spending to 6.8 billion euros by 2010 and targets to spend 3 % of their GDP ( Gafoor , 2008 ) .
The main objective of the investment is to build knowledge in three areas ; bio-technology , environmental technology , and digital media and information technology , for the rapid growth in Asia .
Last but not least , business opportunities can be created with government effort .
A well constructed environment where visitors enjoy good Internet connectivity and teleconferencing facilities in most hotels , convention halls and exhibition venues , opens up the opportunity to attract local and foreign corporations .
For example , Singapore put a lot of effort inton constructing a place for business travellers One of their notable examples is the Novotel Clarke Quay Singapore , which is an ideal venue to hold MICE events that had just recently renovated its facilities ( Uniquely Singapore , 2006 ) .
Thus , in 2006 , Singapore won the award of 'The Corporate Meeting of The Year ' ( Uniquely Singapore , 2006 ) .
This Award helped to enhance Singapore hotel positioning as a venue for business travellers and MICE events ( Uniquely Singapore , 2006 ) .
Coupled with a good education system and powerful research and development , creating business opportunities is part of the key to attracting more businesses and foreign talents into a country , as people are always interested in working in a vibrant country .
On the other hand , if most public spending is used on easing the aging process , it will slow down economic growth because it 's more of a cost than income for the country .
The cost of more suitable healthcare , infrastructure , transportation , housing , pensions and financial aid for the elderly is necessary to help ease the aging process However , spending should be limited as the health and economic value of the elderly decline , and emotional and social problems increase .
This is because in the long run , if most money is spent on accommodating the older population , there will be little economic growth , and society will face fewer choices on how to care for those in need ( Robert & Summer , 2005 ) .
In conclusion , public spending is for the good of the country 's population and the portion spent on the various areas
However , leaders must realize that as more money is spent on easing the aging process , future public spending will be limited and this could have a negative impact on future generations .
Therefore , improving the economy in different areas , such as education , rbusiness opportunities , and research and development opportunities as mentioned earlier , is more important than just focusing on solving one area of the problem .
Where is all the money invested ?
It has always been for the development of Singapore and its people .
The elderly have been perceived as the nation 's burden .
Hence , it can be argued that the government should limit their expenditure on the elderly so that money can be directed to other aspects of the country 's development .
The cost of living in Singapore is high such that children have resorted to abandoning their parents .
It is the responsibility of the government to take care of and ensure that their citizens are not suffering and to ease their plight , especially in times of recession .
The elderly have played their part in their younger days by paying for taxes and it is only reasonable for the government to repay them .
With the inflating cost of health care in Singapore , the government can not avoid implementing schemes such as Medisave and Medishield .
In the context of the elderly , the reason why the government has to spend a lot of money on them is due to the fact that children nowadays are abandoning their parents either in hospitals or old folk homes .
Looking back and considering living conditions in the past , the sacrifices they made then are no match for anything we would ever do in the present .
However , the children have to realise that not assuming their responsibilities to care for their parents , affects the whole society .
The elderly should also consider ageing actively and with dignity .
This will help increase psychological and emotional well being .
In conclusion , public spending on the elderly is necessar . however to a certain extent .
the government can not be relied on as they too have other areas of development to look out for .
The fact remains that education helps individuals gain knowledge and insights into life , which is the basis of civilisation and is vital for a nation 's political stability in the long run .
For instance , the government should adopt a more holistic approach so that the skills learned in classrooms can be adapted to the globalising world .
With its well-reputed education system , the focal point of public spending should instead be placed on the elderly .
Prime Minister Lee pointed out in a newspaper report ( Mathavan , 2009 ) that the country should not overlook the issue of caring for the elderly and provide health care subsidies .
However , this may be insufficient due to the stringent criteria placed on the Per Capita Income Rate of Subsidy .
The income assessment overlooks details such as a family having more than one elderly person that requires medical attention .
In this case , they might encounter difficulties in paying for the medical fees as they have more than one elderly person to look after .
This programme comprises of health checks , talks on how to engage the elderly socially , as well as activities that help them adopt healthier lifestyles .
To maintain elderly people 's interest , public spending should ideally be spent on building more facilities island wide so that the elderly need not travel long distances .
The efforts made by our leaders though commendable , are not sufficient to ensure the elderly remain interested
They are reluctant to start a family and even though they are married , they do not wish to have any children .
On the other hand , life expectancy has increased because people have become more affluent .
Thus , the aging population is now an increasing problem globally .
A very good example is Japan .
A case study in 2008 has shown that 20 % of the population now in Japan is sixty-five years old and above .
By 2030 , the percentage of the population who is sixty-five years old and above will rise to 38.1 % .
An aging population will be a never ending problem in this modern society .
Increasing public spending on the aged will not be able to solve this problem .
Firstly , increasing public spending on the aged will only make the aged dependent on the government .
People may think that it is time for the aged to enjoy their life because they have slogged for many decades , but they do not know that most of the aged are still fit and healthy .
If a person is employed , it is beneficial for their physical well being .
This proves that it is not necessary for the government to increase their budget on the aged if their aged population are able to cope financially .
The money on the other hand can be put to good use by improving on their research and development .
One good example of a country benefitting from research and development would be Japan .
Statistics have shown that in 1987 , around 33 percent of computer related patents in the United States were Japanese , as were 30 percent of aviation related patents and 26 percent of communication patents .
Not only does the country economy benefit , it helps the country to keep on developing and moving forward so as to catch up with
Therefore , public spending on the aged should be limited so as to let the other areas of the country 's development advance which will result in an improved economy .
Lastly , policies have been implemented by countries to help the aged .
However , people might argue that the aged have their children to depend on , but this dependence is straining on family ties as average health care costs rise .
Having a saving fund for them would be a better choice .
Hence , by having this CPF scheme , the government is able to cut down on spending on the aged and put it to better use by diverting it to other areas of the country 's development , thus improving the country 's economyeconomy of the country
In conclusion , public spending should be limited and money diverted to other areas of a country 's development. .
This will not only help the current aged , it will also enable the present generation to be able to enjoy healthy and fulfilling lives into their sunset years without putting a heavy burden on their children and grandchildren .
To a large extent , current policies have helped to ease the aging process .
Being one of the top aging populations in Asia , Singapore has to be prepared for the challenges to be faced currently ,or in the future , when Singapore turns into a prominent ageing society .
In order to take care of the challenges , the Singapore government has implemented several policies ,such as housing , health and employment policies , to overcome the obstacles of the aging phenomenon as well as to provide .
One of the policies is the housing policy , which strongly encourages extended families by providing incentives and elderly-friendly housing for senior citizens .
A report by the Government of Singapore 2000 , shows that in the year 2000 , around 9 out of 10 senior citizens who were above sixty-five years old were living together with their children ( Government of Singapore 2000 ) .
This may due to the various housing schemes which resulted in a high rate of elderly staying with their children .
Some of the housing schemes implemented by the Housing Development Board ( HDB ) include the Multi-Tier Housing Scheme , the Joint Selection Scheme , and the CPF Housing Grant Scheme ( Kalyani K. Mehta , 2002 ) .
The Multi-Tier Housing Scheme iwas introduced to encourage married children to live together under one roof with their parents or vice versa .
This scheme allows extended-family applicants to be given priority allocation on the flats they want to live in .
The Joint Selection Scheme allows families to choose the flats in priority order so that married children and parents can stay in separate HDB flats but close together , in the same neighboring town or estate ( Kalyani K. Mehta , 2002 ) .
Finally , the CFP Grant Scheme was also introduced to encourage married children to live near their parents by offering a higher grant if their flat is near their parents ' home compared to those who are either staying alone , or not staying close to their parents .
Apart from these schemes , Singapore is also trying hard to create an elderly-friendly environment by : modifying lifts to stop on every floor ; using non-slip floor tiles to minimize the danger of elderly people slipping and falling ; having support hand bars in toilets ; installing alert alarm systems ; and building ramps and link ways to facilitate wheelchair access .
Housing schemes and building an elderly-friendly environment would definitely allow the elderly to live more comfortably
Health care policies for the aged have been getting noticed in recent years .
For instance , old people who do not have any health care indemnity have been advised to have Medishield accounts with support given from the government ( Chan , Angelique 2002 ) .
This account permits individuals to pay for their medical bills .
Besides , the government helps in subsidizing health screening programs for senior citizens .
Despite having various schemes for health care , there are still numerous underprivileged senior citizens who can not afford their medical expenses especially for prolonged illnesses such as strokes and rheumatism .
Thus the Medifund was established to provide aid for those who are unable to pay for healthcare services ( Ministry of Health,2010 ) .
Needy patients are hence , able to apply and use this fund to pay for their healthcare services .
Last but not least , it is important to make the elderly an asset to Singapore 's society by giving senior citizens who are physically capable the opportunity to work .
The government has started to put emphasis on the re- training of the older workers to work more efficiently and productively ( Chan , Angelique 2002 ) .
Not only that , the government has also extended the retirement age of individuals .
This permits the aged population to continue serving society and also in certain ways helps to build confidence in the elderly .
In conclusion , the Singapore government has seriously looked into the needs of its senior citizens and the challenges faced in terms of aging population by implementing policies to ease the aging process .
Public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
There are many aspects in society that require the country 's resources. .
Spending on Education , Healthcare , Research and Development and the aged
It has been acknowledged that the aging population will require a large portion of a country 's budget to support various welfare programmes .
Thus spending on the aged is necessary yet it should be carefully limited so as not to compromise other sectors and overall national interest in the long run .
If the budget over emphasizes on the aged , this will result in insufficient funding for Education , greatly compromising the academic intelligence of the younger generation .
When the population is less educated , the country 's general growth declines , , especially in the area of Research and Development that requires highly educated personnel to function .
The correlation between economic growth and spending on the aged must be understood .
With economic growth , the budget available will increase and the government can afford to spend the same portion of the budget yet providing a larger real sum .
Robert B. Friedland and Laura Summer ( 2005 ) mentioned that with economic growth , there will be a lower demand for government handouts and there will be more funds made available for elderly welfare programmes .
Thus education , which helps to sustain future economic growth , is an aspect where spending on the aged must be carefully limited in order to prevent any compromise .
Secondly , Research and Development engages in tertiary scientific and technical studies and in turn will bring about new discoveries or innovations to current technology .
This will cause the growth of new industries and constantly keep the country 's technological level at the cutting edge of innovation .
In Singapore 's case it heavily depends on the ever advancing technology to create new industries and job opportunities . Therefore , , Research and Development spending must be guaranteed so as to ensure the country 's economic growth in the future .
Certain objections must of course be considered
However , Robert B. Friedland and Laura Summer ( 2005 ) mentioned that with economic growth , the aged population has more ability to fend for themselves either by getting employment or through children 's support .
This information should be treated as a means of relief to the government 's handouts .
To conclude , the role of government in providing assistance to the elderly , either to show its appreciation or simply to those who are in need , can not be denied .
Robert B. Friedland and Laura Summer ( 2005 ) , point out that a group of uneducated or single elderly remains vulnerable as they did not have the means to save up for a decent retirement when they were working .
But it should be remembered that while sympathy and appreciation for the aged must remain , it must not be overdone because there are more than just the aged to look after .
Thus spending on the aged is necessary , however , it should be carefully limited so as not to compromise other sectors and overall national interest in the long run .
In this modern era , ageing populations have become a phenomenon in many countries , especially those which hold records of past baby boom and present low fertility rates , like Singapore and Japan .
While liberals view social welfare as a legitimate function of government and provision of welfare as citizens ' rights , it can be argued that the welfare state may end up heading towards a 'bottomless pit'- one which requires relentless public spending , in this case , on the aged and is indifferent to a person 's capability in attaining self-sufficiency .
Also , to ensure a nation 's continual economic growth and social development , much of the fiscal earnings should be utilized on other areas like investments and education .
Therefore to maintain a healthy balance between various demands and to reduce dependency , , there should be a boundary set on the public expenditure for care for the elderly .
To begin with , the fact that public funding is not infinite must be recognized .
In fact , an ageing population itself will make the matter worse , as there is a " growing number of elderly persons ( being ) supported by relatively fewer younger persons " ( Peterson , 2001 ) .
As such should the government be spending more or even lavishly on building care for the elderly ? This could be significantly depriving other areas for development , for example , the economic sector due to the shortage of funds for investments , and the social environment due to the limited resources for enhancing the quality of living , to name a few .
Critics may point out that higher taxation rates will be able to increase fiscal earnings .
Nevertheless , such measures would fend off new immigrants ( who are needed to make up the shrinking population ) , and may even propel citizens away from their homeland
Restrictions should therefore be imposed on public expenditure on the aged due to competition for funds by other sectors .
Moreover in today 's context , many nations are advocating early preparation for retirement .
In the case of Singapore , the government implements a compulsory savings scheme , the Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) to help its citizens start accumulating assets and savings upon entering the workforce .
Pro-family policies and regulations , like the Maintenance of Parents Act , also help to reinforce social obligations in children to take care of their aged parents ( Peterson , 2001 ) .
This ensures that the majority , if not all of the aged would be financially independent
Therefore the area that the public sector should take care of is the psychological needs of the elderly upon entering their twilight years .
Facing loneliness and empty-nest syndrome , the elderly require social support .
Also , financial aid would only be given to those without family support , through the Public Assistance Scheme .
As compared to a welfare-state that provides pensions indiscriminately to all , such as comprehensive approach would demand less public expenditure on the aged and thus funds allocated should be limited accordingly .
Nevertheless , some may argue that it one 's " entitlement " to receive a pension and other forms of material benefits upon retirement ( Fernandez , 1994 ) .
However , this may create an impression that one can rely on the state during old-age , and result in the sapping of incentives to work and save for retirement .
Since an ageing population would translate into a growing number of 'beneficiaries ' , the figures of public expenditure would thus be expected to multiply and eventually become such a vast amount that it could go beyond the financial capability of the welfare state societies .
To avoid such social repercussions , free-flow expenditure on eldercare that can draw individual dependency on the nation should be prohibited. .
On the whole , public spending on the aged should not be made at the expense of the progress of other sectors .
Also , restrictive expenditure will avert the formation of " welfare dependency " but promote the building of a " compassionate society " through family-centred policies ( Chua , 1993 ) .
The concept of a welfare-state should be especially avoided in countries with scarce resources like Singapore , because in times of financial difficulties , they will have no resources to tap on but have to rely solely on themselves ( Clasen , 2001 ) .To be on the safe side , policy-makers should allocate fiscal earnings in a diverse manner , and not solely on maintaining the aged .
It is undeniable that the world population is ageing regardless of how obsessed humans are about the .
Hence , an ageing population is
In fact , it is a real world phenomenon faced prominently in the twenty-first century by many developed as well as developing countries , with some exceptions in only a few under-developed countries like the Middle East and North Africa where the youth population is bulging ( Dhillon , 2008 ) .
The main reason lies in the advancement of research and technology , which conveys the message of the importance of living a healthier lifestyle by avoiding excess food consumption , smoking , liberal sex .
Therefore , humans tend to live longer and the ageing population is rising at an increasing rate regardless of how developed their nation is .
In the World Population Ageing report 1950-2050 ,prepared by Population Division of the United Nations , it is stated that Europe , a region which comprises mainly of first world countries , has the highest proportion of the aged in the world .
This is certainly a very large demographic number for the governing states to deny support because public spending , on the aged , if limited , will incur more disadvantages than advantages , not only to the aged who will be directly affected , but also to the overall society as a whole due to the fact that members in society interact with one another .
As more people live longer , it is necessary for proper public spending to enhance various social security systems as tthe aged are more vulnerable to be discriminated against in a capital-driven society nowadays .
Some forms of discrimination occur when current policies that are supposed to protect the ageing population are inefficient , as they do not seem to eradicate the problems of poverty among the aged .
Society is still witnessing a considerable number of older people abandoned in the streets and alleys begging for money from the public .
The aged living in poverty is only one group needing help , the others consist of the handicapped , mentally-disabled , single and unmarried , the illiterate , and so on who should not be denied of receiving public fund from the government .
This is because neglecting them will create a 'paralysed ' society - a society of social problems with discrimination and marginalisation of certain groups of people that impair the progression of the groups ( TheFreeDictionary , 2009 for the definition of 'paralysed ' ) .
In a society accompanied by materialism and ageism , the needy aged will be pushed to their limits as many of them are vulnerable .
In addition , many employers are reluctant to hire older labours either as skilled or unskilled workers. .
As a result , without the appropriate approach from the government to assist them financially , the aged are 'paralysed ' by cut backs on levels of public spending and likely to lose most means of life without jobs , shelters , and money to purchase their basic means of surviving like food and medicine .
Such distortion in society is a form of violation of basic human rights .
Diversion of public spending to other areas of the country 's development , instead of on the aged is a doubtful policy to maintain regional political stability .
Firstly , limiting public spending on the aged will definitely cause disparity on the principle of democracy itself , where the aged are denied their freedoms and rights to be supported by the government although they are the rightful citizens who play the role of voting in the government .
because the aged are provoked and to vote for a ruling government who marginalize them .
Research has shown that young people in India are less likely to vote and the elderly are most likely to vote ( Joshi , 2009 ) .
Additionally , Japan , where 20 percent of its population is 65 years or older ( Reuters , 2007 )
Political parties are less likely to ignore this essential category of voters in order for them to succeed in the elections .
Secondly , Mark L. Haas of Duquesne University argues that a disproportionately high number of young people in a society along with high rates of unemployment creates strong grievances against current political conditions .
He cited research showing that population ageing has been a source of political stability and economic development in many regions .
In other words , the world 's ageing population has the potential to defuse the war on terrorism .
Diverting funds from the aged to other forms of development will allow growing levels of poverty within the rising ageing population , thus creating shaky grounds for the country 's political stability , and also
Moreover , it is unclear who will truly take care of the aged after the government retreats from providing
There should be some organizations which hold as much capital as the government and willingly play a larger role than the government .
However , it is a form of investment that portrays forms of risk .
The aged are vulnerable failed investments and the poorer elderly may not be well protected as they do not possess much capital .
The opportunity to obtain aged care support and services will be limited if they are provided by the private for profit sectors rather than the private not-for-profit sectors ( McIntosh , 2003 ) .
Apart from this , non-profit organizations like social workers , have lesser incentives to provide sustainable and constant assistance to the aged , since their duties diverge to other social groups as well , such as the orphans , homeless teenagers , single mothers and others .
Therefore , the adult children of the aged seem like the most plausible individuals to provide for their parents .
The act of depending on a child 's filial obligation will instill greater social and financial pressures on them when
Besides , there will also be psychological effects of limiting public spending on the aged too .
Public spending on the aged should not be limited and c .
For example , public spending should be spent on the aged under a better mechanism through more practical efforts like encouraging the aged to be productive if they are still capable of providing their knowledge and wisdom .
Some jobs that the government can monitor to protect our senior citizens from being discriminated against are in agriculture , working from home , consultancy , teaching , making handicrafts , and gardening , .
This helps to increase the country 's productivity among the aged and the aged are still able to sustain their basic means of living .
The combination of these forces can yield economic growth and not the stagnation that some predict ( Novelli , 2003 ) .
Denying support for them on the other hand , will further result in a nation with social , political and economic disparities .
The aging problem is an important issue that governments are worrying about .
Peterson ( 2001 ) even claims that the aging problem will worsen as the median age of the elderly will reach around 50 by 2050 in many first world countries .
This prediction is further supported by a survey conducted by the World Bank , .
With the growing population of the elderly , governments have put in a lot of effort , by providing financial assistance and grants for example , in order to ease the issue effectively .
However , some people disagree with the government 's policy and claim that there is a need to limit public spending on the aged so thatt the money is diverted to other areas to attain a balanced economic and social development .
Moreover , it can also be argued that the government 's approach is not a good remedy to cope with the aging problem permanently .
Some people may argue that limited public spending on the elderly .
The aged have contributed a lot to form and shape society .
Limiting public spending has a deeper meaning , that the government does n't acknowledge their contributions to the country .
Education is a good example that helps to solve this issue more effectively .
This may indirectly help them to think and spend wisely in their future so that they are less dependent on the government as their future is financially secured .
Besides , instilled moral values remind them of the importance of taking up the filial obligation with their parents .
Hence , public spending on the education should be stressed as well since it helps to solve the aging issue more effectively , rather than keeping on spending money on the elderly
Social work aims at restructuring society , such that a more balanced society is attained , where no single citizen becomes the victim of economic development .
It also helps to solve existing social problems and provides support to the needy .
Without the Singaporean government ( Ministry of Community Development and Sport ) providing funds and subsidies to these organizations , some of them might not be able to survive and continue operating , especially during the economic downturn which has has badly hit Singapore recently .
Besides , it helps to solve other social issues than just the aging problem .
Hence , public spending on this sector should be increased so that a balanced and more structured society is formed and a more rigid social safety net is provided .
With the economic downturn , job opportunities have decreased
This is shown in statistics from the Ministry of Trade and Industry of Singapore , which state that the unemployment rate has risen by 1.2 % , which was from 3.6 % in December of 2008 to 4.8 % in March 2009 .
Therefore , public spending on industrial and related sectors which provide more job opportunities for people who have been affected during this harsh period should be stressed equally .
Besides , some elderly still wish to continue working as a result of insufficient savings and the increasing cost of living .
Besides , increased unemployment rates contribute to a lot of social problems which may threaten the social security of the country .
However , from another perspective , the money diverted to other areas or sectors such as industry , tourism , social work professional associations and education , help to form a more rigid and structured society .
The aging issue worldwide was not pressing until the large population of the Baby Boomers generation began to welcome their golden years .
As medical facilities and technologies have continued to evolve , so have the lifespan of modern mortals prolonged .
In recognition of this problem , current policies as well as research and development that have been implemented has yielded to ease the aging process .
An aging population is often associated with a decline in the workforce and the productivity of the country .
For example , Denton and Spencer ( 1998 ) noted that the rate of growth per capita GDP is certain to fall significantly over the coming decades unless either the immigration rate or the productivity growth rate increases dramatically .
It is the ageing of the population that lies behind this concern ( as cited in Scarth , 2002 ) .
Therefore , policies such as Angel Policy 1989 , New Angel Policy 1999 and the " Angel Plan , Plus-One " 2003 , have been introduced and implemented in Japan to increase the birthrate and expand the workforce of the future as to maintain productivity of the country ( Cardiosk , 2008 ) ( Devasahayam , Yeoh , 2007 ) .
The size of tomorrow 's economy and tax base should be increased by raising more productive children so that the cost burden is spread over a larger and more affluent future generation ( Peterson , 2001 ) .
Another alternative carried out by Japan is to use their advancement in science and technology to curb the aging issues by using robots in their workforce .
Japan has innovatively modified robots to put them in production lines and the service industry as substitutes for their aging workforce .
These two measures have attempted to reduce the reliance of the workforce on the aging population and to soothe the pressing matter of the aging population .
The health care system has also been given high priority to cater to the needs of the aging population .
For instance in Singapore , besides building new hospitals such as the Khoo Teck Puat Hospital in Yishun and the Jurong General Hospital , the authorities have taken a big stride by building a link between hospitals and community hospitals where patients can receive treatment at the and then recuperate at the community hospital .
In this way , the elderly obtain appropriate care aat the same time as lowering health care and freeing up beds in hospitals for more critical cases which need to be treated ( " Healthcare system to be reconstructed " , 2009 ) .
This scenario maximizes efficiency as government hospitals will be able to deliver high quality medical skills and the community hospitals will be able to tend to patients ' psychology and social needs better .
Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong noted in the National Rally Day speech 2009 , that the best way to keep health care costs down is by maintaining a healthy lifestyle .
In the agenda to help the elderly maintain a healthy lifestyle , Wellness Programme was launched in 12 constituencies in 2008 with the aim of allowing senior citizens to undergo health screening , fitness assessments and to participate in physical activities ( " Wellness Programme popular " , 2009 ) .
Wellness Centres organize various activities for their elderly members , such as intellectual pursuit , physical activities and also activities to expand their social networking .
Cheerful and happy elderly people , who are satisfied and contented mentally and physically from the activities designed for them , are less susceptible to illnesses , preventing the need for long term care , keeping the cost of healthcare maintenance low and resulting in a happier aging process .
The implementation of the Maintenance of Parents Act in 1995 was said to be against Singapore 's Confucianism idealistic norm and controversial in a filial piety orientated society .
Also , the Central Provident Fund of Singapore ( CPF ) ,that was first introduced in 1955 , is actually a social security savings plan where the overall scope and benefits of CPF revolve around retirement , healthcare , home ownership , family protection and asset enhancement ( " Singapore Central Provident Fund - CPF " ) .
In the early days , employees could only withdraw money from the Central Provident Fund when they retire however , in 1984 , a new scheme known as the Medisave was introduced , so .
In addition to Medisave , MediShield which is a medical insurance scheme was introduced in 1990 in order to help members to sustain and pay for long term medical expenses which arise from serious illness .
A new strategy , Eldershield , implemented in September 2002 , is a special insurance scheme that provides coverage for disability , especially in old age due to the lengthening of the life span of Singaporeans ( Kalyani K. Mehta ) .
All these policies aim to lessen the financial burden on the elderly to provide them with security in their sunset years .
Although given the support and coordination between the government , Voluntary Welfare Organizations ( VWO ) , the community and individuals , the aging process in various countries is believed to be able to be eased , if not overcome .
When life expectancy increases , the the aging population also increases as people live longer .
According to the Top Ten list ( Compare Infobase Limited , 2006 ) on the countries which have the highest life expectancy at Birth Year 2004 , Australia falls in 5th position at 80.2 % , while Singapore moves up to the 4th position at 80.5 % .
Therefore , current research and development/policies have helped to ease the with people living longer as compared to the past .
The government has taken some measures to deal with the reality of the aging society
For example , more , like the Khoo Teck Puat Hospital in the North and the Jurong General Hospital in the West , have been built to cater to more elderly patients .
Building more community hospitals is also vitall to the elderly as community hospitals can provide lower costs and special care for elderly patients to recuperate after being discharged from General Hospitals .
The hospital also provides many activities like Karaoke sessions and performances by volunteers to cheer up the elderly patients to help them in their early recovery .
Other charity organisations like the NKF , TOUCH Community Services , and The Salvation Army are help the elderly by having different types of programmes or services ranging from rehabilitation to counselling .
A special trained pool of doctors , nurses , social workers and caregivers are employed to cater to patients special needs
Although hospitals are built to cater for the elderly and medical science is advancing , the most critical issue is still the high medical cost that patients and families have to worry about .
To tackle this issue , the government has introduced policies like the CPF which consists of the Ordinary Account , Special Account and the 3Ms , which include Medisave , MediShield and Medifund Account , to prepare the citizens for their retirement .
When the citizens of Singapore turn 55 , they can withdraw their savings from their CPF .
Besides that , the CPF can also be used to buy a house , cover hospital expenses or for education fees .
As a result , the government sees fewer cases of residents unable to afford healthcare and social medical workers have reported that Medifund is enough to cover hospital bills .
Community Centres and Resident Committee Centres have also been built in different areas of Singapore to provide recreational activities and programmes for the elderly to participate in .
Infrastructures such as elderly friendly facilities outside HDB flats or in the parks have also been specially built for the elderly to encourage them to exercise and keep fit .
Although not all elderly people would be willing to use the facilities or take part in activities , the centres advertise the activities through banners and flyers or even the mass media to encourage the elderly to be active and healthy .
For example , Paro , a cooing baby harp seal robot fitted with sensors beneath its fur and whiskers , has been developed by Japan 's Intelligent System Co , to soothe patients in hospitals and nursing homes ( Alan Taylor , 4 March 2009 ) .
Even though new products like robots have been invented families with lower incomes may not be able to afford these extra luxuries .
It encourages adult married children to live near their parents so that they can take care of them and attend to their parents ' needs conveniently .
The government also encourages adult children to take care of their own parents by pushing filial piety values on them , as there is a limit to how much the government can help the elderly because resources like land and workforce are very limited in Singapore .
However in some cases where children are unfilial , the government has introduced the " Parents Maintenance Act Law " , to help solve the problem of unfilial children by making them support their elderly parents in a form of paying them a monthly allowance .
In addition to the fear of the government also introduced different policies to help in other areas like ensuring work security in women who are on maternity leave , baby bonuses and children 's Edusave education funds .
However , there is still the problem of a growing aging population due to low birth rates .
In order to deal with this problem , the government has opened up doors to foreign workers to work in Singapore so that they can help increase the workforce productivity Companies can also employ more care-givers to help the elderly .
From birth to the death , man has experienced huge change continuously which is called the aging process and as a result , our society has became older and older .
Not only man , the world has been changing continuously especially in the economic sector which is the most important part of making a living .
Thanks to economic growth , people may escape from worries about hunger and poverty but do they feel insecure about their future when they imagine that they are in their 70 's or 80 's ?
Though the world economy has prospered dramatically for about a century , it does n't seem to have a place for the old the focus is on achieving hasty economic growth .
Firstly , the fundamental flow of a modern economy is market capitalism in which most of the economic assets and system are owned by the private sector , not the public sector and government .
The owner of a property always tries to seek profit from that so their basic needs to live are considered as means of making money .
The problem starts from here .
For instance , if health insurance belongs to an individual for people should pay a lot more to see a doctor and get a prescription This causes problems for old people as they do not earn after retirement but have to visit hospital more frequently than before ( Peterson,2001 ) .
As the market economy brings about the private ownership of basic elements for living , the faces distress .
Secondly , the silver labor market should be considered because OECD ( 2005 ) reported that around 2050 , the old will consist of one sixth of the total population .
.
Take Korea as an example , its government is trying to create employment for the old .
Although the Korean government is making new jobs for elderly people they tend to be low status jobs like security guards or delivery men . and the salary for silver labor is too small .
This is because the current economic system looks for a more efficient and competitive work force and the companies that hire the old do n't consider the elderly and try to avoid engaging them .
As a result , the existing alternative plan for increasing aging population employment is not effective
Thirdly , it can be argued that people have achieved huge economic growth and the product of that accomplishment results in an upgrading of living standards without uncertainty for the future .
Needless to say , Singapore 's GDP shows economic improvement every year .
Despite this progress , .
Because the economy always encourages people to spend all of their money on new products and services and not on saving , people are not used to saving something for the future .
A concrete example is credit cards .
To get a drastic expansion of the consumption for economic growth , the market created the credit card which can distribute current consumption to the future to reduce the present burden .
The aim of this may be good , but this has led to the credit crisis where people suffer from financial difficulties .
In a nut shell , the economy only cares about profit , people can not prepare for the future by saving and finally , the old may experience financial hardship .
Definitely , the economy becomes bigger every moment and it offers a lot of advantages , for example , people do n't have to worry about starving or a lack of food .
However for some people , this benefit is just
The marginal protection for the old is now
For these reasons , from the aging population point of view , economic improvement has n't eased the aging process .
To ease this process , the economy should consider excluding people , the old of the society and let them know how to prepare for a stable and comfortable future .
An Ageing population is a problem encountered by many countries today .
To date , elderly aged over 65 constitutes 8.6 % of the total population in Singapore , which will see an expected rise to 18.7 % in 2030 .
Such a significant trend has led many to worry about the problems associated with this phenomenon , hence the government has initiated certain policies and developments aimed at helping the elderly .
Although these initiatives are beneficial for the aged , the government should consider limiting public spending on them to divert money to other areas such as education and development in Singapore .
Spending on the aged should be kept to a smaller proportion as compared to areas such as education .
Prime Minister Lee ( 2009 ) at a dialogue with Nanyang Technological University students took the stand that local students should build networks with the rest of the world and integrate in new environment in order to " push the boundaries " and break new grounds for Singapore .
Money should be given to aid needy students who will then not be deprived of a chance to participate in Exchange programs administered by the institution .
Singapore , having one of the top education systems , should continue it 's reputation , and the government should divert money spent on the aged to refining students who are the future leaders of Singapore .
Singapore 's tourism sector is a lucrative field which has contributed greatly to the country 's economic success .Therefore , the the government should divert money on the aged to this thriving industry .
Since 1996 , the number of tourists coming to Singapore has been increasing steadily with an estimated $ 14.8 billion tourist received in 2008 .
Tourism has made a significant contribution in creating more jobs for locals and with the upcoming Marina Sands project , thousands of jobs for Singaporeans are expected to be created in this period of economic downturn .
Also , the tourism sector has made huge contributions to Singapore 's economy , with an estimated $ 230 billion in 2007 .
Thus , the government has to continue improving on its infrastructure and developments for tourism and tourists so as to remain on a competitive edge with other Asian countries .
Hence , funds spent on the aged should be limited in lieu of spending it on more beneficial areas for the country .
Critics have validated the spending on aged by arguing for the role which the elderly hold in building and molding Singapore to where it is now .
'Hardware ' has been constructed to facilitate the aged in their daily lives ; 'heart-ware ' should be proliferated instead .
" heart-ware " means giving emotional support to the aged and providing unconditional love and respect for them .
Teo ( 2009 ) believes that people should treat the elderly they way that they want to be treated when they are old .
the government can not coerce 'heart- ware ' on the young ; instead they can be influenced and taught in school when they are young .
.
The aged still remain as a figure of respect .
The government should reduce the proportion of funds spent on aged facilities and divert it to education and tourism development as these two fields will enable the continual growth for this small nation dependent on it 's labor force .
In fact , nowadays Singapore 's population is aging too and it is one of the fastest aging populations in Asia .
There are several developed countries such as Japan , the US and Singapore predicting that educated aging boomers will have longer life expectancies than the generations that preceded them .
It is estimated that by 2050 , Singapore 's median age will move from 36 to 54 , similar to Japan and Italy .
In addition , an aging population causes a decrease in the workforce .
Notwithstanding a viable policy , Singapore citizens feel that these new immigrants and foreigners might not benefit them because they will face even more intense competition in the workforce .
However , if Singapore does not adopt immigration , it will face manpower shortfalls .
As more elderly people retire from the work field , this causes a lack of productivity in the workforce as well as a labour shortage .
Subsequently , a labour shortage will have a negative impact on the economy as it slows the country 's economic growth .
Nevertheless , these problems could be eliminated as the influx of foreigners through immigration will satisfy the needs of the labour market and boost the economy with improved labour productivity .
Admitting more immigrants will help to replenish the country 's aging population in the years ahead .
For example , the government of Singapore has introduced several measures to boost the fertility rate .
One of which is immigration , which has attracted many immigrants mainly from China , India , and Malaysia to integrate into society and has helped to raise the fertility rate .
Moreover , since there are more young people engaged in the workforce , the elderly in later life will as they will be supported by the younger generations .
Immigration is a practical solution adopted by developed countries with aging societies , namely , Singapore , the USA and China .
For instance , Japan is facing a population crisis as they have the lowest birth rate in the world .
The shrinking of the labour force and the lack of vitality for the workforce will happen in the near future .
Therefore , Japan needs to ease up on its immigration laws by allowing more foreigners to immigrate in order to solve the problems .
In conclusion , coping with an aging population will require a long term effort and it is a challenge to a country .
However , this challenge could help to ease the aging process in the long run by adopting immigration .
There are others policies that should be taken into consideration , including ; family policy , later retirement for the elderly , and promoting healthy life styles for resolving problems posed by aging process .
, the government should encourage older population to live an active aging life .
The elderly , who prepare well and early for old age will be more ready for retirement , then the present generations of people will be able to enjoy meaningful and happy lives without relying or putting a burden on their children .
The Ministry of Community Development , Youth and Sports ( 2009 ) showed that at least 1 out of the 5 people will be 65 or older in 2030 .
As for Japan , at least 1 out of 4 people will be 65 and above by 2055 .
This alarming statistic has rang a bell about the importance of the public to spend their wealth on the needs of the aged .
This essay will address the scope of which is the appropriate amount of resources that public should spend on the vulnerable group .
Not all the aged need financial help as these people may well be taken care of by their children .
The developing countries , on the other hand , should invest their public spending on areas such as education and law and order before they can address the issue of the aging population .
Thus , public spending on the aged should be maximized in developed countries , while public spending in the developing countries should be utilized to help to reduce societal problems .
The aged need money to cover their extensive bills , that range from medical purposes to other basic necessities .
In Singapore , it is not uncommon to see the aged working in sectors that are shunned by the young .
It is true that the aged are able to support themselves by being financially independent .
However , they receive low salaries , which can hardly cover the increasing cost of their medical bills .
Thus , the cost of medical treatment is considered as expensive by the aged especially those who hold low-income jobs or who live alone without the support of the family .
Their target is always this vulnerable group as they believe that it is relatively easy to manipulate them in order to gain sympathy from the public .
Aging populations are becoming a very serious and significant problem especially in developed country where the educated and professional continue .
Public spending should not be limited as the money can be utilized to promote campaigns that encourage the vulnerable to stay employed .
Although the vulnerable may be perceived as the ones with vast knowledge and experience , the young is likely not to overlook this matter .
, which is able to work quickly and productively .
It believes that the vulnerable should be given the right to work and that companies should abolish the concept of age restriction .
This is the human right that individuals should be entitled to as long .
Thus , campaigns will raise the awareness of the public to help the aged to face the discrimination that still prevails within society .
In Thailand , for instance , social problems need to be addressed as children are involved .
Berger and Glind ( 1999 ) from the Thailand Office of the National Commission on Women 's Affairs reported that an estimated 40 000 children are involved in the country 's lucrative sex industry .
This is an alarming issue as the vicious circle may worsen .
Besides , the children believe that this lifestyle is one of the easiest ways to earn an astronomical amount of money .
Public spending is thus needed to rectify the perception shaped by the children , or else the problem will remain unsolved .
The spending should be used in campaigns in order to raise awareness about the importance of basic education for children .
Thus , it is indeed clear that developed and developing countries have different issues to address .
The prevailing issue needs to be resolved before the issue gets worse .
Although it is true that the ageing population is less severe in developing countries at present , it may not stay true for the future .
It is because globalization h
The children in the developing countries who have received a quality education , may want to pursue their career in other countries with a stable and high income .
The majority of the people in these countries , live in villages .
The children , who have been socially ingrained with moral values , are obligated to look after the parents .
Hence , in future , when migration issues becomes a global pandemic , the public should give a helping hand to the aged since the children will no longer take care of their needs .
The public will then need to assist them in order to reduce the burden .
In conclusion , the amount of money utilized to help to ease the burden of the aged should not be limited .
The financial burden and discrimination faced at the workforce are among the problems that the aged are going through .
There should be a level of awareness to help the aged so that they will age with dignity and pride .
This is because everyone , sooner or later will reach the ageing stage and will want their needs to be taken care of as well .
Hence , this is where the role of public spending should come iin to play to address the needs of the aged .
Decisions on the allocation of government funds can impact different aspects of society differently .
So how would spending money on the elderly affect society ?
Some believe that government spending on the elderly should be controlled and that the money should be used in other aspects of the society such as education , economic growth and public health care .
However , the community and not only the government can help the weak elderly in society
Thus , the government should use the money to handle more pressing issue such as the health of the general public in this period whereby there are outbreaks of a lot of diseases such as avian flu and swine flu , that have taken the lives of many .
Some politicians may argue that although the proportion of elderly people is still small now , it will grow larger if the problem of aging population is not dealt with now .
Since there are definitely other ways to cope with aging populations governments should allocate its funds to other areas that are more urgent .
Furthermore , Governments should focus on other areas such as education and economic growth , as tackling such areas will solve the problem of an aging population in the long run , killing two birds with one stone .
Increase in economic growth will also lead to an increase in employment .
In this scheme , a portion of a person 's monthly salary will be deposited into the CPF account on a monthly basis and it can only be withdrawn at the age of 55 , thereby assuring financial independence of the elderly .
Therefore , governments should reduce their spending on the elderly and more of the budget should be used on education and for boosting economic growth .
In conclusion , public funding should be limited as it may cause the elderly to be over reliant on it . The money should then be used elsewhere in areas such as public health that are more pressing as well as on education and economic growth as that will also help to solve the aging population crisis .
By carefully allocating government funds , society will benefit as a whole .
The reason for this is because their aging population problem is much more serious as compared to developing countries .
There is a need to understand that the amount of reliance the aged have on the public is quite significant . It is also necessary to take into account the contributions that the aged have made , as well as to recognize the more substantial advancement in .
Critics have commented that other areas of the country 's development such as education need the money to substantiate the advancement of these particular developments so as to bring them to greater heights .Therefore , limitations on public spending on the aged should be enforced .
However , there is the recognition of the fact that governments in developed countries have already pumped in a huge amount of money to develop the main areas of development like education and national defence .
In addition , an aging population has not been an area of concern in the past and only recently have the aged formed a significant population in developed countries .
It is well known that Singapore has a world class education system .
The efforts can be seen clearly as Singapore is now an advanced developing country . However the most predominant problem arising now is the aging population .
Thus public spending on the aged must not be limited as it is problem .
Cynics have mentioned that in developed countries , quite a number of the aged are still working and receiving wages , so they will have the means to pay for their living expenses and healthcare costs .
However even though a significant number of the aged are still in the workforce , most of them are taking up menial jobs like cleaning which only gives them a meagre pay .
In addition , the aged are still quite vulnerable to diseases and are weak , thus public spending on the aged should not be limited so as to assist them with their healthcare costs .
