By continuous self learning , the elderly are able to refresh their minds and keep up with the pace of .
If a grandfather knows how to surf the Internet , his life will be more colourful and meaningful because he has more opportunities for recreation and more access to information .
On the other hand , with life-long learning , the old are more competitive in the work force because they possess new knowledge needed in a new age and have profound working experience , which is an advantage over the young .
Once the elderly become more competitive in employment , it is easier for them to choose late retirement .
However , one might propose that psychology development has brought about ageism , which involves prejudicial attitudes to the
On the contrary , psychological development has helped to eliminate ageism ,
It is the old who have contributed to our society a lot .
Psychological development has provided the right view of aging , helping to eliminate ageism and ease the aging process .
In conclusion , elderly depression problems are becoming less severe with the help of psychological consultation and treatment , life-long learning has been promoted by psychological development to equip the elderly better for employment , and ageism has been somewhat eliminated by
With the population of aged getting larger in society a big sum of money is involved in helping the aged .
If this huge amount of spending is reduced , but in turn , spent on other areas of the country 's development , the wealth of the country can reach a .
To many people , limiting the amount of money to be spent on the elderly can be perceived as being cruel to them .
However , it is necessary to be realistic and pragmatic .
With sufficient funds , the country can spend on manpower , education , investment , construction and other aspects to aid in its development .
Nevertheless , a government can still provide funds for the aged .
In this survey , the elderly can state down whether they receive any forms of subsidy from their families , where they stay , who they stay with , and whether they are interested in applying for financial assistance .
On top of that , it ensures that their contributions to the country 's economy still exist .
By doing so , the country could differentiate them from the rest of the elderly that do not need any form of financial aid because they already have enough to finance themselves .
On the other hand , for those who are really in need , they can apply for subsidies to receive a certain amount of funding every month .
Under this financial plan , they will benefit from the country 's welfare and at the same time be able to satisfy their basic needs .
A well-developed country can bring wealth and boost the economy of the country .
With that , the citizens can get to improve their living standards and quality of life .
Imagine a country that has slower development in education .
In the near future , children in the country would have a lower chance to be educated .
People need to be more practical and far-sighted to consider the next generation in the country .
This can be done by building up funds for the country 's development , while not overdoing funding for the aged .
Some countries are experiencing an aging population , for example Japan , which is facing rapid change , had a 5.1 % 1 increase in aging population over the last 30 years .
This figure is expected to increase as more elderly reach 65 years old .
Countries such as Singapore are also facing rapid aging population growth with a decreasing fertility rate of 0.31 % 1 over the past 7 years .
If this trend continues , Singapore will be second after Japan .
An aging population affects the country 's economy because of the high retirement rate and the increased need for providing healthcare for the elderly .
therefore public spending should not be limited because it is still part of the country 's responsibility to take care of the aged population .
Firstly , Singapore is one of the many countries experiencing an aging population , where the median age has increased from 16.9 years since 1970 to 19.51 years now with a decreasing fertility rate [ 1 ] .
Large number of retirees are expected in the future .
Other policies the government have implemented is creating more job opportunities for the aged including , providing part time jobs , allowing flexible working hours and giving an option for them to work at home .
Secondly , as the country 's aging population increases , health problems become one of the concerns for the elderly .
For most developed and developing countries , healthcare will become an issue .
As the cost of living increases , the cost of healthcare also increases .
For instance , healthcare is an issue in the United States .
Any healthcare cost will become a burden to the elderly as well as to their family members .
On the other hand , countries such as Singapore have policies which help the elderly to cover their medical expenses .
This will not be possible if a limitation on public spending on the aged is imposed .
For instance , during the current economic downturn , public funding should be diverted to developing more facilities , which will in turn improve ththe economy .
One example is the recent government project of the integrated resort , which will create job opportunities and attract people to spend money when it is completed .
If the economy of the country is not growing , it may affect businesses within the country , which in turn affects the employment rate .
Therefore , public spending on the aged should not be limited as they are still part of the country 's development and social well being .
As a Chinese saying goes , the aged population is actually a treasure to the country .
However a significant amount of funding should also be diverted to other to stimulate the economy and help the country and its people to survive the economic downturn .
It has been argued that " To a large extent , current research and development/policies have helped to ease the aging process .
" Elders experience capabilities in body functions , like standing for extended duration , lifting , diminishing eyesight and slower reaction time among others .
Technologies have been deployed to assist elderly people in day to day activities to counter or decrease disadvantages they face due to their less athletic bodies .
Elderly people are eased in the aging process by technologies that retain
Compared to the past where there was less advanced deployment of machineries and technologies , there are four areas that technologies help the elderly in , work , communication , healthcare and transportation .
Firstly , mechanization and automation have taken away the physical component of many jobs
This allows the elderly to have less physical capabilities in their work .
The elderlys are as capable of operating and monitoring equipment as the younger , stronger workers are. .
Working at the port or the warehouse would be impossible for elderly people in the past , where cargo is uploaded by man .
Dockside cranes and forklifts , , allow elderly people to handle the job even though they are not as fit as the younger workers .
Thus , due to mechanization and automation , workers have a smaller decrease in productivity due to age , allowing elderly people to work at an older age than could be done in the past .
The elderly can have a longer time to save up for retirement , decreasing potential financial problems .
The elderly can be at ease knowing that they are able to be more financially capable at an older age .
Secondly , elders can access communication networks through specific communication devices designed for usage by the elderly .
While most products are still at the prototype stage , the demand in the market warrants such products to be available in the near future .
These devices take into account the tendency of the elderly to fail to recall operation methods , contacts , schedules , locations , etc. Much emphasis has been placed on shadow learning curves and user- friendliness to non-technically inclined users
User interface and controls can be self-descriptive and intuitive by using extensive use of icons , grouping of related tasks and automatic hiding and showing of controls by intelligently determining the likely intention of users .
A phone by Doro with big buttons and limited functions is a good example .
The simplicity of this device made it more adoptable for elderly people .
Elderly people can now communicate with each other , their children and relatives regardless of geographical distance .
In the past , they would have had to visit physically at another geographical location or employ the help of their children to make a phone call or chat on the Internet. .
For , technologies can assist in their healthcare
There are products in the market where the elderly at home can wear a device like a necklace on which there is a big red emergency button .
A modem installed at home will wirelessly detect the pressing of the emergency button and automatically dial for the emergency services with the location , medical information and family members of the elderly person as long as they press it within the detection range of the device .
This greatly increases the chances of help arriving in a timely manner .
Emergency respond units are able to have detailed medical records of the patients before arrival and apply the appropriate pre-treatment before sending the patient to hospital .
In the past , elderly people would need someone else to look after them and respond to emergency situations .
The elderly might also be unaware or can not remember their own medical records .
Technologies thus make aging much safer for the elderly .
To help elderly people travel around , the public transportation system underwent changes catering towards them .
In Singapore , MRT stations are retrofitted with lifts so that elderly people do not need to climb the staircase or take the the escalator
Many bus service providers around the world are acquiring low- floor buses , which has increased accessibility for elderly people .
Combined with a policy that encourages priority seating for senior citizens , taking public transport has become a much more comfortable experience compared to the past .
In conclusion , many technologies have helped to ease the aging process by a large extent .
Aging would become much more difficult and uncomfortable without these technologies .
One of the most challenging issues in the world now is the ability to meet the increase in energy demand .
Current resources like fossil fuel , which is used to generate electricity , will eventually be depleted in a few centuries ' time ( Mitenkov , Kodochigov , Vasyaev , Golovko , Ponomarev-Stepnoi , Kukharkin & Stolyarevskii , 2004 ) .
Although there are public opponents who do not wish for the nuclear reactors to be built due to potential threats , past incidences and cost , the Generation IV VHTR aims to overcome these negative aspects with funding for its research and development .
This is one of the reasons why opponents among the public do not wish for nuclear reactors to be built .
Therefore , the likelihood of reactors melting down because of terrorists shutting off the coolant to the VHTR is minimised .
Furthermore , terrorist attacks could also come in many other forms ; one well-known example is the terrorist attack upon the United States on 11 September 2001 which did not involve nuclear reactors .
Therefore , it can be concluded that if terrorists are determined to destroy a country , they could still use different methods even if nuclear reactors are present in the country .
In addition , since terrorists know that there will be extra precautions taken to safeguard the nuclear reactors , it will be more difficult for them to sabotage the country by means of the nuclear reactors .
In order to make the VHTR much less attractive as a target to terrorists , funding for research and development is necessary to develop simpler safety interlock systems and materials which can withstand very high temperatures to build the reactor .
The public being nuclear-averse is also the result of the past accidents at Three Mile Island and Chernobyl in Pennsylvania and Ukraine respectively .
Moreover , the cooling system of the reactor was not properly set up ; hence , overheating caused the reactors ' core to melt and become severely damaged ( World Nuclear Association , 2009 ) .
The VHTR can reduce the occurrence of this incident by incorporating a simple cooling system which does not need skilled operators ( Butler , 2004 ) .
Thus , with careful , well trained operators and better cooling systems , the probability of accidents happening will be reduced .
As for the other accident which happened in Chernobyl , it was a result of operators , who were not well trained in operation and safety , operating on a reactor which was inadequately designed ( World Nuclear Association , 2009 ) .
These factors led to 56 deaths by 2004 as a result of the reactors ' explosion and the release of radioactive materials into the surroundings ( World Nuclear Association , 2009 ) .
It was noted that the explosion was due to the coolant used , which was water , turning to steam and thus suddenly increased the power produced and set off a nuclear reaction ( World Nuclear Association , 2009 ) .
In the case of the VHTR , the coolant will be helium .
Being chemically inert , helium does not influence the nuclear reactions with a temperature change or .
Hence , power surges of the reactor will be minimized , resulting in a decrease in the probability of reactor explosion .
There is no doubt that opponents would not want history to repeat itself , so they would not want nuclear reactors to be built .
However , there are important lessons to be learnt from this accident which can be used to improve the design of nuclear reactors .
Research and development of the VHTR can help to ensure safer operation of a nuclear reactor where safety aspects of the reactor will be better than before .
Besides that , adequate operator training will be planned and carried out faithfully to bring accident rates to a minimum .
With safer nuclear reactors , opponents should feel more at ease with them in their country , and hence , more can be built to help in sustaining the energy supply for the future .
Although the cost of hydrogen replacing gasoline is huge , there will surely be more benefits to mankind due to high efficiency .
According to Butler ( 2004 ) , approximately 400 nuclear power plants , each requiring about US $ 1 billion , need to be built in order to fully be dependent on hydrogen instead of gasoline .
In addition , research and testing work is required to look for materials which are able to resist the high temperature of the VHTR and the rapid impact of high energy neutrons in the reaction ( Butler , 2004 ) .
This could help to meet the rising energy demand .
Although there might be future technologies which will be better than the VHTR , this is not definite as yet .
Therefore , rather than wait for a new technology to fully emerge , we should continue to carry out research work on enhancing feasible technology present now , which is the nuclear reactor .
Opponents may think that nuclear reactors are potential terrorist targets , but precautions have already taken to minimize the impact .
Moreover , nuclear reactors are not the only targets of the terrorist ; there are other ways terrorists can think of to destroy a country .
Certain major accidents in the past which resulted in deaths involved nuclear reactors , so the public are against nuclear reactors .
However , it is because of these past experiences that there can be improvements to the design of the Generation IV VHTR .
Therefore , the VHTR can be said to be much safer than nuclear reactors of the past .
Lastly , the cost to build and experiment on newly designed nuclear reactors may be high , but the advantage that they can produce more energy with the same amount of resources far surpasses the cost involved as the important issue now is to solve the problem of constantly increasing energy demand .
It is mentioned in Butler 's article ( 2004 ) that building the VHTR can involve many obstacles , but if engineers are able to overcome them , then energy production will be " safe , abundant , reliable , inexpensive and proliferation resistant " .
Hence , I strongly recommend further funding for research and development for engineers to overcome the challenges involved in constructing the VHTR .
When talking about the most serious accident ever in nuclear power history , the 1986 Chernobyl Accident will come to everyone 's mind ( UNSCEAR , 2009 ) .
According to an authoritative report ( WNA , 2009 ) , 56 deaths were confirmed to have been directly related to the Chernobyl Accident by 2004.It is officially suggested that the Chernobyl Accident was the result of inadequately trained operators , a flawed design , as well as the lack of proper regard for safety ( WNA , 2009 ) .
As researchers have been paying more and more attention to applied psychology in the recent decades , people have been wondering whether the use of psychology during the design process would have prevented some major engineering accidents like the Chernobyl Accident .
Evidence shows the use of psychology during the design process would have largely reduced the chance of the Chernobyl Accident by raising the awareness of safety among the crew .
In this essay , two aspects where psychology could have been applied to prevent the accident will be talked about ; they are : calling attention to the importance of safety and making people consider the safety of the complex high hazard system from a macro view .
Above all , applying psychology during the design process could make people pay more attention to the importance of safety .
It is identified by the International Atomic Energy Agency ( IAEA ) in the post-accident report that the deficient knowledge and awareness of safety of the crews was one of the main causes that led to the Chernobyl Accident ( IAEA , 1992 ) .
Here are some examples that reflect the deficient safety knowledge of the crews .
For the design team , a few fatal design errors of the nuclear system and their possible consequences had been known long before the Chernobyl Accident , but no action was taken to correct these errors in the design .
For the operating team , insufficient training of the operating staff caused a serious problem with the man-machine interaction .
Finally , the regulatory team underestimated the potential danger in the nuclear test and therefore did not provide the necessary supervision for the test .
( James , 2009 ) All these contributed to the painful consequence of the Chernobyl Accident , which could have been prevented if psychology had been applied to make the crew more responsible and pay more attention to nuclear safety .
Furthermore , paying more attention to the importance of safety is not enough ; psychology should be applied to guide the engineers to consider the safety of the nuclear plant at the system level .
However , like all the other accidents of the same nature , namely accidents of the complex high hazard systems , the Chernobyl Accident was not the consequence of a single error , but of a combination of the failure of various factors ( Wilpert , 2007 ) .
When the Chernobyl Accident occurred , the poor communication and interaction between different departments of the nuclear plant made it even worse than it might otherwise have been .
To have prevented the accident , it would have been important to consider the safety of the system from a macro view by analyzing the whole nuclear system , including the interaction among humans , as well as organizational and technological factors ( Meshkati , 1996 ) .
On the other hand , not everyone agrees that applying psychology during the engineering design process would have prevented the Chernobyl Accident .
First , due to the wrong social perception of psychology and the social sciences , many people think psychology only come under the field of human arts and social science , which is totally unrelated to engineering ; therefore , they doubt that applying psychology during the designing process will help to prevent engineering accidents like the Chernobyl Accident .
Nevertheless , these people do not realize that those who design , construct , maintain , and run the systems are all humans ( Wilpert , 2007 ) .
Therefore , a large part of the safety of the engineering systems lies in human activities .
Applying psychology in engineering can help to make people more mature , responsible , and careful while dealing with complex high hazard systems like nuclear reactors , which will definitely reduce the chances of an accident .
Another rebuttal against applying psychology is that some people argue that design errors are the main cause of major engineering accidents , and applying psychology can not correct these design errors nor prevent the accidents .
It is true that a lot of accidents are due to design errors , but it is also true that humans are the factor that gives rise to the accidents in many cases .
If we can not improve the safety awareness among the crew , there is no point in merely solving the technical problem .
For instance , about a decade before the Chernobyl Accident , a nuclear accident occurred on Three Mile Island , in which the technical cause was also the water cooling system ( WNA , 2001 ) .
The reason why , ten years later , a similar technical defect also caused the Chernobyl Accident is because people did not pay enough attention to nuclear safety and therefore did not learn a lesson from the prior accidents , which were not purely due to a technical problem and which could have been solved by applying psychology .
Humans are therefore of vital importance to the safety of engineering design processes .
Thus , instead of solely focusing on the technical problems , applying psychology would be another thing we need to give equal priority to in order to accidents .
In conclusion , there is adequate evidence showing that the use of psychology during the design process would have largely reduced the chance of the Chernobyl Accident , considering psychology could help to make people pay more attention to the importance of safety and consider the safety of the whole nuclear system in the design process .
Nevertheless , solely applying psychology during the design process would not have totally prevented the Chernobyl Accident , because there are other factors , such as , the cultural factor , that lead to the accident
It is confirmed by the UN ( WNA , 2009 ) that was one of the direct causes of the Chernobyl Accident .
Nowadays , the scarcity of energy has increasingly become a severe problem .
Compared with other kinds of power generation , nuclear energy is relatively cost competitive and eco-friendly .
among all the generation reactors , I believe the supercritical water reactor should be the most applicable for most countries , especially those developing countries without advanced technology and tremendous capital .
Firstly , the supercritical water reactor is not only very highly thermal efficient but also quite economical .
The construction cost of the supercritical water reactor is rather low .
Due to the simpler structure , many of the traditional Light Water Reactor components such as the coolant recirculation pumps , pressurizers , steam generators , and steam separators and dryers can be eliminated in the supercritical water reactors .
( Buongiorno & MacDonald , 2003 , p. 3 ) And as for material engineering , according to the corrosion and stress-corrosion cracking ( SCC ) susceptibility tests in supercritical water by scientists from MIT ( Massachusetts Institute of Technology ) and the University of Michigan ( McKinley , Teysseyre , Was , Mitton , Ki & Latanision , 2003 ) , two traditional austenitic steels ( 304L and 316L ) can be used as high temperature components in the SCWR .
On the other hand , as for the Very High Temperature reactor , big safety provisions have to be considered to ensure its stability under high temperatures and a multitude of coolants are needed .
Since the coolant for the VHTR is an inert gas such as Helium which is not recyclable , a lot of energy and money will be required to separate it from air .
Moreover , a large amount of money needs to be spent to design and develop new related materials which can bear high temperatures , high { neutron } [ HYPERLINK : http : //en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neutron ] doses , and { corrosive } [ HYPERLINK : http : //en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corrosion ] operating conditionsinside the VHT reactor ( IAEA 2004 ) .
In addition , it is very costly to build the VHTR because of its excessively complicated inner structure .
However , the SCWR can be installed not only within a shorter period but also by fewer workers , which will dramatically save the fixed costs of plant construction .
In the meantime , the supercritical water reactor also enjoys high thermal efficiency and a high energy conversion rate .
According to the SCWR annual report published by Jacopo Buongiorno and Philip E. MacDonald ( 2003 ) , about 45 % to 55 % of the heat generated by nuclear reactions can be transformed into electricity against 35 % efficiency for advanced LWRs .
Since the coolant is just supercritical water , at extreme pressure , above the critical point , steam and liquid into a single phase , which will convert more fission energy into electricity .
Moreover , compared with the VHTR , the SCWR is a one . Thus , it can produce more potentially usable fuel , which means less core material such as uranium would be consumed to produce the same quantities of electricity .
Lastly , compared with the VHTR , owing to its lower temperature , the SCWR needs less heat to trigger the reactions and keep the thermal inertia , which saves more energy but also .
Since the SCWR is a combination and expansion of the old Light Water Reactor and the fossil fuel fired boiler , which are commonly deployed and widely used around the world .
Thus the basic theories and technologies for the SCWR have been proven to be reliable for many years ( Yang & Zavaljevski , 2003 ) .
In contrast for VHTRs , not a similar plant has been built yet ( the first VHTR will be completed in 2020 ) , a lot of new and untested concepts still need be verified , which may cause reactors with more nondeterminacies to produce more unexpected problems .
Moreover , for the VHTR , a lot of technical challenges also remain to be settled .
However , since the SCWR 's simple and user-friendly design incorporates mostly mature technologies of the LWR it is more likely to be adapted soon by many countries , especially those developing countries without strong capital and mature technologies .
Moreover , by processing electricity , hydrogen can also be generated with electrolysis by the SCWR , which will support the development of the hydrogen industry in the following decades and make additional profits .
Different from Light Water Reactors used around the world today , the Super Critical Water Reactor is more likely to slow down and catch 'fast neutrons ' , which means it would burn less nuclear fuels in a more thorough way .
Thus , the time for breaking down nuclear wastes will be decades instead of millenniums after the SCWR is applied .
Further , compared with the VHTR , the primary and secondary coolant of the SCWR is the same supercritical water which can be relatively easy to get and recycle .
In addition , because of the super enthalpy of supercritical water , more energy will be transplanted but less unexpected by-products will be produced , which will certainly decrease the risk of contamination to the environment and enhance the integral efficiency of transplanting , which will effectually reduce carbon emissions by burning less fossil fuels .
The safety of the SCWR has been proven and can be bettered in the future .
Thanks to the improvement of the core design , less average core density will be required so that the possibility of devastating accidents such as the core melting down will become extremely slim . Moreover , because of the dedicated moderator of the SCWR , the boiling crisis of coolants under normal operating conditions can also be eliminated .
Since the SCWR safety system is comparable with that of the ABWR , scientists are now trying to combine the SCWR with ESBWR-type passive safety systems .
If they can be integrated together , the safety of the SCWR will be dramatically enhanced .
To conclude , although some technical issues of the Super Critical Water reactor are still being researched , I reckon that the SCWR would be the most promising reactor against other generation IV ones , in terms of performance , cost , feasibility , and impact on the environment .
With the development of science and technology , the SWCR will not only be able to efficiently produce clean energy but also significantly address the severe global warming challenge today .
( Butler , D 239 ) GIF 's criteria for including a nuclear reactor design for consideration include : sustainable energy , competitive energy , safe and reliable systems and proliferation resistance .
( " Very High Temperature Reactors " , section 5 ) The Very-High-Temperature Reactor ( VHTR ) is one of the six generation IV reactor concepts proposed by the GIF .
The VHTR requires an operating temperature of 1000oC and high pressure with helium being the coolant used .
( Butler , D 239 ) Critics have argued that the current nuclear plants in operation are susceptible to terrorist attacks and doubt that the plant is worth the high cost of funding .
All these critics are against the funding and development of nuclear power plants .
However , I strongly support further research and development funding of nuclear reactor plants .
This is because nuclear reactor plants have many advantages such as being able to produce both hydrogen fuel and a large amount of electricity from a small amount of fuel at the same time .
Ever since the 9/11 incident , protection of nuclear plants has been a heightened national priority.Yet , some anti-terror experts have commented that the current criteria do not protect the plant from a threat equal to the one posed by the 9/11 hijackers .
A report released by the Government Accountability Office even mentioned that it is critical of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission ( NRC ) , finding that the latter has not increased standards enough to ensure plants are genuinely secure , but only as much as industry officials believe is necessary .
One solution is the " Design Basis Threat " ( DBT ) which specifies the severity of the attacks that has to be prepared for .
The NRC requires each nuclear plant to periodically conduct security exercises to test its ability to fight against the DBT .
" par.9 ) In conclusion , the security of the plant is now sufficient to repel terrorists and therefore the funding of nuclear power plants should be supported .
The high cost of the funding for the development of nuclear plants has also met with much public discontentment .
In the USA , since its beginning , nuclear power has cost the country over $ 492 , 000 , 000 , 000 , which is nearly twice the cost of the Vietnam War and the Apollo Moon Missions combined .
No other industry has enjoyed such a privilege .
" par.3 ) The high cost of nuclear plants is transferred to the citizens so they have to pay more on utilities .
Hence , they reject the idea of funding nuclear plants .
On the other hand , many differ in opinion .
Therefore , nuclear power actually costs about the same as power generated from coal .
" ) This means that nuclear energy can be charged at an affordable price that is competitive to coal and gas .
In addition , nuclear energy , though expensive , can be produced in abundance to meet the ever increasing demand for energy .
In short , nuclear power plants should be funded as their benefits outweigh the shortcomings such as the high cost .
After the Chernobyl and Three Mile Island nuclear accidents , which took away many innocent lives due to the explosions as well as exposure to excessive radiation , people are now very concerned about the safety of nuclear plants .
In Texas , the citizens have again succeeded in opposing the development of two proposed nuclear reactors at the South Texas Project .
The opposition came about as the citizens are fearful that the environmental effects of radioactive compounds may lead to health problems if contamination or leakage was to occur .
( " Citizens Gain Ground in STP Intervention over Water Concerns Atomic Safety and Licensing Board Panel Admits Four Additional Water Related Contentions for a Hearing " ) However , there is evidence to support the claim that the safety aspect of nuclear plants are up to mark .
According to the World Association of Nuclear Operators ( WANO ) , performance indicators show that the U.S. nuclear plants have managed to sustain high levels of achievement in safety performance , industrial safety , unplanned automatic reactor shutdowns and programs to protect workers from radioactive exposure .
In conclusion , I support the notion of research and development of nuclear power plants .
Even though there may be problems and public opposition along the way , by bearing in mind three main factors , namely , the benefits of nuclear energy , the importance of a strong defence and most importantly , the importance of having a set of safety protocols , we are able to push the development of nuclear power to greater heights .
The world can expect the number of nuclear power plants to double by 2050 , spreading across the Middle East and Southeast Asia , particularly in China , India , South Korea , and Japan ( Butler , 2004 ) .
In 2008 , Kaplan ( 2008 ) reported that more than 40 developing countries have expressed their interest in launching nuclear power programs to United Nations officials .
Some argue that a nuclear reactor is too costly to build and that they should adopt other renewable energies instead of nuclear power ( Totty , 2008 ) , while others argue that developing countries do not have enough skilled labour to cope with the needs of building and operating nuclear reactors ( Squassoni , 2009 ) .
Although there is much opposition to the idea of building nuclear reactors in developing countries , there is some evidence that building nuclear reactors , such as the Generation IV reactors , yields positive outcomes for these countries .
Although proponents of nuclear reactors agree with the fact that the reactors are expensive to construct , they argue that it is comparatively inexpensive to operate because nuclear fuel accounts for only 27 % of the variable cost of a kilowatt-hour as compared to alternatives like natural gas which accounts for 85 % .
The Nobel Peace Prize laureate , Mohamed ElBaradei , proposed that these countries could alternatively construct hundreds of small-scale plants for a single town , each one built using a fraction of the cost used for a large-scale plant and without using expensive power grids ( Bullis , 2005 ) .
However , despite the fact that studies show that the use of solar and wind energy is more economical than nuclear energy , opponents completely ignore the limitations of these energies in producing electricity for the decades ahead ( Healthy Environment Alliance [ HEAL ] , n.d. ) .
Moreover , solar power is limited to daylight hours and there is no continuous supply of wind .
The International Energy Agency ( IEA ) forecasts that , even with continued subsidy and research , and a landscape full of solar panels and windmills , these renewable energies can generate only about 6 % of the world 's electricity by 2030 ( Silverio , 2008 ) .
As a result , opponents maintain that building nuclear reactors would not address the problem of unemployment ( Squassoni , 2009 ) .
In summary , developing countries should develop nuclear reactors for several reasons .
In addition , a new nuclear reactor design will only be approved if it presents a relatively lower construction cost .
Moreover , if developing countries have insufficient funds , they can approach AEHI for financial and labour support but an alternative way would be building smaller-scale plants without the need to use costly power grids and thus incur lower costs .
Besides that , developing countries like China and India have sufficient highly-skilled workers to contribute to the nuclear industry and the unemployment rate can also be reduced , as approximately 2400 jobs are made available in each new plant .
Therefore , in my opinion , developing countries should first provide huge funding to build generation IV reactors in order to combat unemployment and poverty in rural areas .
According to Butler ( 2009 ) , researchers have been pondering on whether to use nuclear funding for the development of generation ( IV ) reactors , which are projected to be better than the current generation ( II ) and ( III ) reactors , or to retain the nuclear funding for existing generation ( II ) and ( III ) reactors .
Moreover , for the generation ( IV ) reactors , there is a debate on whether to channel the funds for the research of SuperCritical water reactors ( SCWRs ) , which scientists have claimed would benefit mankind more in most aspects like cost and efficiency compared to the other five generation ( IV ) reactors .
Although there are reasons that seem to support the funding of the SCWR , the development of the SCWR should not be funded as there are other factors like economic and social feasibility to consider before we can conclude that the funding for the development of the SCWR should be approved .
One of the many reasons given to support the claim for SCWR funding is that the SCWR is a combination of two proven technologies , which are Light water moderated reactors ( LWRs ) and supercritical-water fossil plants ( Buoniorno , 2002 ) .
Supporters of the SCWR claim that the SCWR would have a reduced capital cost as a result of plant simplification and high thermal efficiency .
Although I concur with their view to a certain extent , they have overlooked the problem of the SCWR being capable of reaching the commercialization stage of an innovation ( Rogers , 2003 ) .
The likelihood of the SCWR reaching the commercialization stage is low because even though the SCWR is the combination of two proven technologies , research is still required to merge the two technologies together .
Furthermore , the simplification of the SCWR involves the usage of materials that are either expensive , rare , or do not exist ( Absolute astronomy , 2009 ) .
This reinforces the possibility that the SCWR can not enter the commercialization stage of innovation , proving that there should not be funding for the development of the SCWR .
Another reason proponents give is that the SCWR uses water which is cheap and easily obtainable as a coolant ( Butler , 2009 ) .
In addition , supporters of the SCWR also state that the SCWR takes up less space than current Generation ( II ) and ( III ) Reactors ( MacDonald , 2003 ) .
I have to acquiesce to the two points raised by the supporters of the SCWR .
However , these two arguments do not consider that both water and space are vital to mankind .
Although water is easily obtained and affordable , only 1 % out of the 97 % water available is usable ( West , 2007 ) .
This implies that funding should not be channeled for the development of the SCWR .
Instead , funds could be directed to the development of the Very High Temperature Reactor ( VHTR ) which utilizes helium which is not important for human survival as helium is not found in the human body ( The Encyclopedia of Earth , 2008 ) .
In addition , although the land required to build the SCWR is less than for the existing reactors , the area needed to build a new SCWR would be better utilized as area for agriculture instead , especially in the future .
It is projected that in the year 2050 , there could be 9.2 billion people in the world ( BBC , 2009 ) .
Therefore , there should not be funding for the development of the SCWR as the SCWR utilizes two key ingredients for human survival .
The last reason that advocates funding for the development of the SCWR is that the building of the SCWR could generate desirable jobs for the society ( Nuclear Energy Institute , 2009 ) .
According to the Nuclear Energy Institute , the operation of a nuclear plant generates 400 to 700 permanent jobs and these jobs offer a salary that is 36 percent higher than average jobs .
Although this may be beneficial to society , after the completion of the construction of a nuclear plant , there would be job losses involved .
During the construction of a new nuclear plant , around 1400 to as high as 2400 jobs are created .
This indicates that a job loss of around 1500 will be incurred .
Furthermore , the 400 to 700 jobs require personnel that are highly skilled which developing countries are unlikely to supply .
Therefore , the validity of generating desirable jobs needs to be redefined .
After considering both sides of the arguments , it is evident that there should not be funding for the development of the SCWR as there are more shortcomings than benefits .
The first consideration is that the funding for the development of the SCWR should be channeled to more pressing needs like eliminating poverty and food shortage .
Next , the possibility of the SCWR surviving the commercialization stage is low .
Lastly , the benefits that the researchers had predicted are not totally beneficial to humans ,
thereby indicating that there should not be funding for the SCWR .
Thirdly , most people 's impression of nuclear energy is that it is too expensive and inefficient .
Even a small amount of uranium ( the main source of nuclear energy ) will generate a large mass of energy to run nuclear power plants .
Achieving an all-time high rate of efficiency will greatly reduce cost and time while satisfying the demands of the people .
Currently , there are around 440 nuclear power reactors generating one-sixth of the electricity of the world
They are a proven success in generating energy so it is worthwhile investing in such a technology for the sake of meeting future energy demand .
Subsequently , various groups of experts from the nuclear and chemical industries investigated the the case , and some of them came to the conclusion that the most effective way to prevent such a catastrophe from happening again lay in the enhancement of the psychological education of people , whereas others insisted that the main problem was actually failures in the design of the plant , and the accident could hardly be simply regarded as a psychological issue .
Those against the psychological point of view further claimed that even if the human factors had all been removed through psychological approaches , accidents still stood a chance of happening .
They concluded that the actual primary causes of the 1986 accident was nothing but engineering factors , and permanent avoidance of such accidents could only be achieved through more advanced technological development .
According to the author of 'Psychology and design process ' ( Wilpert , 2007 ) , the human mind 's deficiency is the basic reason behind an accident .
He thinks that disastrous consequences can be avoided or at least minimized with the help of psychological education , and if psychological aids are provided throughout the whole engineering progress , during item processing , structure designing , team managing , and even decision making , the Chernobyl disaster could be essentially avoided .
In my point of view , I am supportive of the idea that human factors ' impacts overwhelmed all other factors in the Chernobyl accident .
The report by the International Nuclear Safety Advisory Group ( INSAG ) ( 1992 ) states that the three components of reactor protection , which referred to the Emergency Core Cooling System ( ECCS ) , the trip on steam drum water level , and the 'two turbine ' trips , had been disabled .
The disabling was not prohibited under normal conditions , but a test was being carried out that day , and thus special approval should have been obtained for the disabling of the three components .
In addition , the required test power level had not been achieved , and the reactor was operating only at half power then .
Moreover , whenever a problem in the engineering process occurs , such as in the case when the engineering process was unable to perform according to the plan , the whole system should have been ceased immediately for a thorough re-evaluation .
However , in the 1986 Chernobyl incident , the operators did not stop but tried to modify the condition on the spot ( the International Nuclear Safety Advisory Group , 1992 ) .
In sum , psychological aids are urgently required to educate high-risk-system operational teams on a large scale , to call their attention to operational safety .
The disaster could have been totally avoided if at least one of the operators had had a sense of operational safety .
Secondly , the design faults of the reactor account for a considerable proportion of the causes of the accident .
For example , the void coefficient of reactivity was positive , while the value should be negative in the document to ensure the system 's stability .
In addition , the speed of activation of emergency protection was too slow ; to be specific , it was ten times slower than the normal configuration .
Some people argue that those design errors reveal immature techniques , and thus there is no way to have avoided such mistakes by means of psychological education .
Therefore , they believe that even though could probably have removed human factors psychologically , the hardware technical problems would still have triggered similar accidents by themselves .
Granted technical faults sometimes and constrain the effectiveness of psychological education , however , the engineering deficiencies in this case were actually design errors ; in other words , they were probably manual errors due to carelessness or misses of considerations .
The use of psychology provides an approach , or at least fraction of the box , so that we can see what goes on in designers ' heads , and thus prevent or at least minimize the design errors ( Wilpert , 2007 ) .
Last but not least , the political factor is another primary factor we can not ignore .
The political conflict , military tension , and economic competition with the United States urged the Soviet Union to produce as much weapons-grade plutonium as possible and also as soon as possible ( FROT , 2000 ) .
In that political environment , the safety issues tended to be ignored ; to make it worse , rigorous demands such as having to fulfil large orders with limited time for production and a low budget was given priority .
Such political circumstances changed the nature of the design process , and consequently , loosened the safety regulations .
In this case , to be concerned about safety first instead of pursuing political advantages .
Based on my analysis of the Chernobyl accident , it is evident that the disaster was totally the result of a series of human factors instead of purely hardware fault .
In recognizing the three main problems as the operators ' unawareness , designers ' misses of considerations and politicians ' arbitrariness , psychological aid should be highly appreciated as an efficient way to minimize human errors , and thus to prevent such an accident from happening again .
With the increasing demand for energy and the rapid depletion of currently available energy resources , nations are now trying to look for new , alternative ways of energy generation .
Presently , thirteen countries have come together to set goals on nuclear energy generation research on six reactor designs , namely the gas-cooled fast reactor , the lead-cooled fast reactor , the sodium-cooled reactor , the molten salt reactor , the supercritical-water-cooled reactor and the very-high-temperature reactor .
The conceptual design of the VHTR will be the first to be defined and optimized by the year 2015 ( OECD Nuclear Energy Agency , 2009 ) , although the LFR is , judging from the existing schemes , more feasible because of its low costs and good security features .
In comparison with the VHTR , I feel the LFR has more advantages and is a better reactor design and thus deserves more research .
Both the LFR and the VHTR have their advantages and disadvantages over the other in terms of performance .
The VHTR will be operating at temperatures of 900 to 1000 degrees Celsius .
This high outlet temperature allows it to be highly efficient ( > 50 % ) in energy generation and also gives it the ability to produce hydrogen ( OECD Nuclear Energy Agency , 2009 ) .
Even though the LFR is estimated to have a comparatively lower efficiency in energy generation than the VHTR ( Chapin et al. , 2004 ) , it is more suitable in certain countries due to its flexibility in its scale of operation .
Currently , the reactor is envisioned to have 2 sizes : a small transportable system of 50 to 150 MWe and a medium system of 300 to 600 MWe
( OECD Nuclear Energy Agency , 2009 ) . The small system design will be useful for providing energy for developing countries and remote communities due to its size
( Idaho National Laboratory , 2007 ) . Moreover , research studies have shown that the LFR will also be able to generate hydrogen ( Bouchard et al , 2008 ) .
Hence , it is evident that though the LFR is predicted to be poorer in terms of efficiency as compared to the VHTR , the LFR seems more useful and suitable for many countries due to its other features .
the projected cost of building a prototype of the VHTR reactor is around $ 1.1 billion ( Butler , 2004 ) .
In addition , the reactor will be using helium as a coolant , which is costly as helium is a rare gas in the atmosphere .
On the other hand , it is roughly estimated that the smaller plant of the LFR can be designed , constructed and operated for 15 years for less than $ 700 million .
In addition , the development of the small LFR will incur smaller research and demonstration costs , since the technology base can be applied to later LFR concepts when building larger reactors
( Idaho National Laboratory , 2007 ) . Thus , on the whole , it seems that lead-cooled fast reactors are much cheaper to build than VHTRs .
Lastly , the LFR 's operation methods seem safer and more secure than those of the VHTR .
At such high temperatures , there is a higher possibility of a dangerous melt-down of the reactor .
Furthermore , the amount of nuclear waste that will be generated is greater than that generated by the LFR ( OECD Nuclear Energy Agency , 2009 ) .
the chance of a melt-down of an LFR reactor will be far lower as the operating temperature is only around 550 degrees Celsius ( OECD Nuclear Energy Agency , 2009 ) .
Moreover , as its fuel cycle is closed , there is no need for an offsite emergency response system - the system will shut down without spreading radioactive materials .
Therefore , the LFR seems a safer reactor as compared to the VHTR .
Hence , there are still uncertainties in the features of the reactors ; it is not certain that the LFR will still have these advantages over the VHTR after the completion of the designs of the plants .
However , after looking at the advantages the LFR has over the VHTR in theory , I believe that the LFR will be a better reactor than the VHTR with its predicted flexibility in its scale of operation , low cost and better security .
Hence , more funds should be allocated towards the research of the LFR .
Within the past half century , two major accidents at the Chernobyl and the Three Mile Island nuclear power plants have caused the public to have a negative view of the operation of nuclear reactors and also , the future of nuclear energy generation .
Presently , the most common energy source , which is coal-fired power generator , has been causing detrimental effects on the environment by releasing tremendous amounts of greenhouse gases and subsequently causing a rise in global warming .
In 2001 , the Generation IV International Forum introduced six different generation IV nuclear reactor concepts which had been designed in such a way that when accidents occur , the damage will be contained ( Butler , 2004 ) .
This accident , especially , had caused many to oppose the nuclear power system as they feel that the extent of damage incurred by such systems would be massive and unacceptable .
For example , the accident which occurred on the Three Mile Island did not involve any deaths or injuries as the radioactive particles were successfully contained within the reactor itself ( Yousefzadeh , 2007 ) .
This simply shows that with advanced technology , even if an accident-free nuclear plant may never be achieved , at least the technology incorporated into the reactor system would be able to ensure that radiation is contained in times of accidents .
Hence , with more funding directed towards the research and development of the LFR , it may one day become one of the safest forms of energy generator .
Critics also claim that nuclear power plants and nuclear waste can be potential terrorist targets as a great extent of damage can be done when the plants are attacked or exploited .
Another factor to be considered is the sustainability of the LFR .
Critics of nuclear energy claim that nuclear energy generation produces a large amount of radioactive waste products and eventually , storage spaces will run out , making nuclear energy unsustainable .
With this reprocessing feature in LFRs , uranium and plutonium , which make up 96 % of the nuclear waste , can be extricated and reused in the reactor ( Butler , 2004 ) .
In addition , nuclear reprocessing also increases the efficiency of the usage of uranium and hence makes nuclear power a sustainable source of energy .
Moreover , lead is abundant ( The Lead-cooled Fast Reactor , n.d. ) , and uranium resources can last us for the next 250 years or so ( Wider et al. , 2005 ) , making the LFR an excellent reactor in terms of sustainability .
In conclusion , the LFR has much to offer to mankind especially in terms of safety , security , sustainability as well as environmental effects .
The LFR is a nuclear energy reactor that is environmentally friendly with zero greenhouse gas emission .
The public has been concerned about the danger of radiation leaks from nuclear plants , especially after the Chernobyl incident in 1986 when the massive radiation exposure directly caused approximately 250 deaths ( WHO , 2005 ) .
The US administration , though , has recognized the potential of nuclear energy and has committed US $ 40 million to support research and development ( R&D ) for Next Generation Nuclear Plants ( NGNPs ) ( DOE , 2009 ) .
The very-high-temperature-reactor ( VHTR ) , with and the extensive R&D conducted on it , has been selected over other reactor concepts such as the supercritical-water-cooled-reactor ( SCWR ) as the reactor choice for the US ' next generation nuclear power plants ( DOE , 2008 ) .
Federal funding should be channeled for the R & D of the VHTR concept as it promises enhanced safety and inherent security designs , in addition to a highly efficient production process .
The slow but fatal effects of radiation have made radiation leaks from nuclear reactors a major safety concern among the public .
The inert nature of helium means it will not react with the radioactive materials of the VHTR to become radioactive , eliminating a source of radiation in the event of a coolant leak ( CHM333 , 2007 ) .
Another safety feature of the VHTR is the use of uranium fuel pellets multi-coated with graphite .
These reinforced pellets are extremely heat resistant and do not crack easily , so even in the case of a meltdown , the uranium pellets will be able to retain the radiation and fission products within its core with minimal release to the surroundings ( CHM333 , 2007 ) .
In addition , unlike traditional reactors , the VHTR is designed to minimize fissionable material in its spent fuel by running the fuel pellets through the reactors for consecutive cycles until its fissionable material is exhausted .
However , NGNPs are not only capable of generating electricity like coal and gas power plants , they can also simultaneously produce hydrogen ( GIF , 2008 ) .
Hydrogen fuel cells have been identified as the energy source of the future , so the capability to produce hydrogen gives NGNPs an edge over existing coal and gas plants .
Moreover , the high operating temperature of the VHTR also results in higher fuel burn-up ratio of the fissionable materials in the uranium pellets ( DOE , 2008 ) .
With its highly efficient fuel burn-up , NGNPs will have a lower carbon footprint than coal and gas technology and at the same time , having less radioactive material remaining in the spent pellets reduces the amount of radioactive waste to be treated , improving the overall process economy .
However , additional funding for the VHTR will only be available if both the US government and the public can be convinced about the viability of NGNPs replacing coal and gas power plants as the main supplier of US electricity .
To achieve this , the VHTR has to stay on track through sustained R&D work in the coming years so that it can meet its expected delivery deadline in 2020 ( Butler , 2004 ) .
The world is encountering an unprecedented challenge which requires urgent global action to prevent the risks of climate change ( Stern , 2008 ) .
To do so , the global greenhouse gas emissions have to be reduced by half relative to 1990 by 2050 , which means to reduce to less than 10 Gigatonnes of emissions ( Stern , 2008 ) .
Many countries rely on fossil fuels as their source of energy and fossil fuel is known to be the major contributor of greenhouse gases .
In the United States alone , greenhouse gas emissions mainly come from the burning of fossil fuels for energy use .
Energy- related carbon dioxide emissions from the combustion of petroleum , coal , and natural gas contributed to eighty-two percent of total U.S. anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions in 2006 ( Energy Information Administration , 2008 ) .
By using the very high temperature reactor ( VHTR ) , hydrogen can be used as the fuel of the future to replace fossil fuels .
In addition , more electricity will be produced with the help of the VHTR .
Therefore , for a better environment to live in , countries should support further research and provide large funding for the development of the VHTR even though the public is concerned with the cost and security of the VHTR .
VHTR plants are able to produce hydrogen for fuel using high-temperature steam electrolysis , which breaks apart the bonds of water molecules ; this process is 50 percent more energy-efficient as compared to existing hydrogen production methods ( Svoboda , 2009 ) .
However , until now , there is still no material that can withstand the high temperatures and pressures required for the VHTR to operate , and even if such materials are found , they might add millions of dollars to the still- unknown cost of constructing a VHTR power plant ( Svoboda , 2009 ) .
and so they need to be involved in achieving global emission reductions .
1.6 billion people in the developing countries do not have excess to electricity so they have to end their day earlier than those in richer countries due to lack of proper lighting ( Bradley , 2009 ) .
With the VHTR , developing countries will be able to meet their energy demand and will thus lift millions of people out of poverty .
Therefore , similar to those rich countries , developing countries should also provide funding for the development of the VHTR .
In addition , INL researchers also believe that nuclear energy will be important in maintaining the nation 's electricity supply as ( Svoboda , 2009 ) .
However , given memories of the partial reactor meltdown in 1979 at Three Mile Island , Pennsylvania and of the 1986 accident at Chernobyl in Ukraine , during which the reactor core exploded , killing some 31 people instantly and spreading radioactive debris across Europe ( Butler , 2004 ) , the public is concerned about the safety of the VHTR .
However , in actual fact , the VHTR is able to function without having to rely on the reprocessing of plutonium waste ( Butler , 2004 ) .
Nuclear reactors would then become less of a terrorist target .
The VHTR also has safety features to prevent core overheating and the release of radioactive material , in hope that these new approaches will eventually erase the memory of Three Mile Island and Chernobyl ( Svoboda , 2009 ) .
Therefore , countries should provide funding for research and development of the VHTR .
Building of the VHTR means that countries will no longer need to depend on fossil fuels as a source of energy and the emission of greenhouse gases will also be greatly reduced .
Generating sufficient hydrogen to totally replace gasoline for transport purposes would mean building more than four hundred nuclear power plants , ( Butler , 2004 ) .
It is evident that countries should proceed with the research and development of the VHTR .
Developing countries should also invest in the development of the VHTR as satisfying their energy demand is essential for their economic growth .
Nevertheless , the world has always been concerned about the safety and security issues of nuclear reactors .
Thus , researchers have come up with generation four reactor concepts , hoping to ease the public 's worries .
I personally support the molten salt reactor concept for further research and development based on the following factors : safe operation of the plant , global security and cost efficiency .
Radioactive emissions can come from nuclear explosions or nuclear wastes .
An explosion of the nuclear reactor not only affects the people on site but also millions of others kilometres away .
An explosion of a nuclear reactor occurs due to either excessively high temperature or excessively high pressure .
Nevertheless , Forsberg ( 2006 ) states that the MSR has a strong negative temperature coefficient .
Thus , when there is an increase in temperature , the fuel-salt density will reduce and push fuel out of the reactor core into critically safe , passively cooled tanks .
This will prevent overheating which leads to explosions .
According to Forsberg ( 2006 ) , the final nuclear waste from the molten salt reactor can be solidified to a stable form , thus ensuring that it does not emit radioactivity .
He also added that MSRs operate at a steady-state condition , with minimum excess nuclear reactivity .
Besides safety issues , the security of the nuclear reactors is another point brought up by critics .
The location of a nuclear reactor is to terrorists an ideal bombing target .
In addition , in molten salt reactors , plutonium , a key ingredient of advanced nuclear weapons , is actually created during the process before it is reprocessed .
Critics fear that the plutonium might be stolen by terrorists to make nuclear weapons .
However , Idaho National Laboratory ( 2005 ) claims that the plutonium remains in the salt and has high critical mass that makes it less desirable for use in weapons .
According to Butler ( 2004 ) , supporters are also positive that the plutonium obtained can be spiked with other chemicals or elements to make it to steal .
This further supports the need for research and development on molten salt reactors .
As for , the World Nuclear Association ( 2008 ) states that the basis of the design of the reactors assumes these threats .
Having to incorporate all the safety and security measures makes the cost efficiency of the nuclear power plant another concern .
The World Nuclear Association ( 2009 ) states that the cost of nuclear power generation has declined since the 1990s .
They also show statistics proving that although the construction cost of nuclear reactors is significantly higher , once the reactors are built , the nuclear generation cost is comparable to other energy sources .
In addition , Thornley ( 2009 ) claims that as compared to other energy sources , nuclear energy has the highest average capacity factor .
Taking the MSR as an example , previous designs for the MSR used steam cycles for electrical production .
The current proposal uses the Brayton cycle which has advantages such as lower cost and improved efficiency .
However , the MSR uses fluoride salt , which is more corrosive at high temperatures .
Thus , there are doubts about whether the MSR is a good choice .
Nevertheless , there is currently the carbon-based material which , according to Forsberg ( 2006 ) , is compatible with molten salt at high temperatures .
In conclusion , I have to agree that the molten salt reactor is not perfect , but the benefits of the molten salt reactor outweigh the cons and supporters are optimistic about finding solutions to the problems , showing their potential .
Thus , I support the further research and development of the molten salt reactor .
A serious train calamity took place in Eschede on 3 June 1998 and claimed the lives of 101 innocent people while 88 were left severely injured ( Sckhman , 1998 ) .
At hindsight , it seems that this whole accident could have been prevented if more precautionary measures had been taken into consideration .
The numerous controversies over the actual cause of this accident revolve around the unsuitable design of the wheel , the inability and misconception of the conductor , the inadequate train repairs and the company guidelines for investigating the accident before addressing an issue .
After reviewing this accident , some experts have felt that incorporating a psychologist into the developmental process could have aided in preventing it .
Nevertheless , the psychologist could have contributed to the design process by reducing the rate of accidents .
A point to argue about is regarding the wheel design .
The train company , InterCity Expss ( ICE ) , had received complaints regarding the original train wheels causing serious resonance and tremors whilst travelling at high velocity .
It is evident that had the engineers waited for the approval of the new wheels before , this accident might not have happened .
Company policy stated that thorough examinations had to be done before taking any necessary action .
This led to the conductor refusing to stop the train even after a passenger raised concern regarding a damaged coach .
In addition , even after the conductor had verified the problem , he still refused to stop the train and insisted on adhering to company regulations .
It is shocking to realize that this unique policy that ICE complies with differs from the traditional 'stop and examine ' one .
This accident could perhaps have been averted if the conductor had used his personal judgment and halted the train when an unexpected problem was discovered .
It must have been pressure from the organizational management that made the conductor follow ICE orders and refuse to do what was right i.e .
In part , it can be said that the cause of the accident was ICE for forming this rule and the conductor 's erroneous judgment .
After conducting a root cause analysis on the accident , a psychologist could perhaps have aided the company by vetting the flawed regulations to grant train conductors the power to make an assessment to stop the train should they receive any complaints from passengers .
Yet another point is a simple fault found in the train 's wheel .
This proves that checks were only conducted on the external structure of the train and not on the internal hardware and sustainability of the wheels to support the train 's weight .
The aid from a psychologist in this aspect would have been limited as it deals with technical equipment and the views of psychological design would not have been implemented in this field .
Instead , it was various factors working together to create a chain reaction which led to the dire consequences .
In this train accident , the problems began from the preliminary wheel design that design engineers came up with , to the insufficient maintenance of trains and the operation mode ICE used .
The aid from a psychologist would have been inadequate in preventing the accident as the majority of the causes for this accident dealt with technical aspects that psychologists do not have experience in .
However , the psychologist could have contributed to the intangible aspects of the company 's routine like spotting the mistakes engineers sometimes overlook .
Hence , with the help of psychology design , the rates of accidents may reduce drastically .
Public opposition regarding the issue of nuclear technology has been evident ever since the Chernobyl and Three Mile accidents .
People are mostly concerned about public health and safety caused by radioactive exposures .
Unfortunately , .
In addition , nuclear waste repositories require geological isolation .
On the other hand , the concept of fourth generation nuclear power addresses the issue of .
They are capable of combusting nuclear waste and leaving a minimal volume of waste with insignificant half-lives , thus addressing the nuclear waste problem .
The coolant comprises a molten salt .
The concept of the MSR involves nuclear fuel dissolved in the molten fluoride salt as uranium tetra fluoride .
Thus , the MSR has the ability to work at high temperatures , at low pressures and at high power densities .
At higher temperatures , most of the reactor heat can then be transformed into electricity which ensures complete combustion of the uranium fuel .
Operating at lower pressures reduces accident risk and in the event of an accident .
The MSR can be air-cooled , making it capable of using waste heat for water desalination .
The turbines have also excellent thermodynamic efficiency due to the relatively high temperature it functions at .
Fission products are removed and new fuel is added to portions of the fuel at a time , drastically reducing the cost operating the MSR .
The Obama administration was initially opposed to the idea of the Yucca Mountain nuclear repository .
The amount of money needed to build a nuclear repository isolated away from civilization cost up to $ 25billion .
There are better methods of using this sum of money collected from taxes from its people to solve the waste disposal problem .
Accelerated development of MSRs will result in the US successfully managing the nuclear waste problem and revolutionizing an entire new level of carbon-free energy that can last longer than just centuries .
Furthermore , MSRs are up to 300 times more fuel-efficient compared to LWRs .
They actually provide a bit more than what most scientists expect from fusion as an MSR can be built in small 1.2MW electric units .
A 7.4 MW thermal reactor was built in the 1960s and operated for years , .
MSRs are also much more efficient than helium-cooled Very High Temperature Reactors ( VHTRs ) operating at similar conditions , in terms of electricity conversion .
Materials used for these reactors require high dimensional stability and most importantly corrosion-resistance , due to the molten salt of MSRs being corrosive itself .
Some materials that are suitable include nickel-base super alloys , silicon carbide , specific grades of graphite and refractory alloys , which are expensive in nature .
Hence , the cost of operation will not be as price-friendly as claimed .
Nevertheless , the introduction of MSRs still deserves strong support as they are likely to prove to be the best solution for improving energy efficiency and developing renewable energies .
Prompt development of MSRs is especially required for countries such as China and India .
These countries are unable to satisfy their energy needs solely based on the current available avenues for energy sources .
In conclusion , nuclear energy from fourth generation nuclear reactors is the best substitution for coal and natural gas .
We have already crossed the threshold of acceptable greenhouse gas emission levels .
Thus , preventing accelerated climate change beyond human control is of the greatest priority .
According to a study done by the Sunssex Energy Group based in the University of Sussex , the world 's fossil fuel supply is currently dwindling and will be running out within the next 20 years ( Walker , 2009 ) .
Moreover , the increasing emission of carbon dioxide from the burning of fossil fuel has been proven to be one of the factors causing climate change ( Jager , n.d. ) .
However , there remains doubt of the safety of nuclear reactors ' operation and hence , the public might not fully .
In order to make the nuclear reactor safer , cleaner and cheaper , the Generation IV International Forum ( GIF ) was established in mid 2001 to further research the III generation nuclear reactors .
In late 2002 the GIF announced the six best reactor technologies which they believe will become the future nuclear reactors .
The six technologies are the Very High Temperature Reactor ( VTHR ) , the Super-Critical Water-Cooled Reactor ( SCWR ) , the Molten Salt Reactor ( MSR ) , the Gas-Cooled Fast Reactor ( GFR ) , the Sodium-Cooled Fast Reactor ( SFR ) , and the Lead-Cooled Fast Reactor ( LFR ) .
The few paragraphs below explain why you should support further research and development on the super-critical water-cooled reactor ( SCRW ) in terms of safety , security and performance .
The first reason is the safety of the super-critical water-cooled reactor ( SCWR ) .
The working temperature is about 510-550K and the pressure is 25MPa ( Butler , 2004 ) . many people may feel shocked at the high operating temperature and pressure of this reactor .
They will argue that the pressure vessel wall can not withstand such a high pressure and the high working temperature will melt the core .
They worry that the will replay the accidents on the Three Mile Island on March 28 , 1979 and at Chernobyl on April 26 , 1986 ( " Nuclear Disasters and Accidents " ) .
However , with the growth of modern technology , the SCWR has been designed with the pressure-tube design .
The success of this design eliminates the need for a thick wall vessel and minimizes the risks of explosion of nuclear reactors .
Furthermore , in this design the separation of coolant and moderator is introduced as part of a passive heat-removal system to minimize the consequences of accident scenarios where active cooling may not be available .
Decay heat will be removed through radiation and convection from distributed channels during accidents , and consequently fuel melting in the core will be prevented .
As a result , this design improves the safety of the SCWR .
The second reason are security issues such as nuclear proliferation .
Nuclear power leads to potential security risks , as plutonium has to be separated out during the reprocessing of nuclear energy production .
Although the U.S.A. has decided to dump all the plutonium waste at Yucca Mountain , the government never mentioned the level of safety that can be achieved .
Consequently , the public claims that nuclear power wastes create a high degree of proliferation risks and until today there is no solution for it .
Among the six generation IV nuclear technologies , only the SCWR and the VHTR do not require waste recycling .
In the super-critical water-cooled reactor ( SCWR ) system the waste recycling is optional , which means that the SCWR can operate without having to depend on the contentious reprocessing of plutonium waste ( Butler , 2004 ) .
In conclusion , this technology is free of proliferation risks .
The SCWR is considered one of the most promising future nuclear reactors because of its high thermal efficiency .
The use of the multi-pass flows system in the SCWR allows the production of process heat on demand and improves the thermal efficiency .
Moreover , the distributed fuel channels in the SCWR allow the system to optimize fuel bundles into each channel .
Thus , an appropriate fuel cycle , flow , cladding temperature and independent power distribution can be achieved , which ensures the stable and predictable performance of the reactors .
In conclusion , the super-critical water-cooled reactor ( SCWR ) has been proven to be cleaner , safer and better performing as compared with the generation III nuclear reactors .
In addition , to reduce the emission of carbon dioxide from burning fossil fuel , we should now support further research and development for the super-critical water reactor ( SCWR ) .
The super-critical water-cooled reactor is the best future reactor to generate sufficient energy to fulfill the energy needs of the public .
Commercial plants in use today use nuclear fission reactions , which is a result of a large molecule breaking into smaller fragments .
Nuclear fusion reactions are believed to be much safer than fission reactions and appear potentially viable , though technically it is difficult for them to take place .
The atomic bombs dropped on the island of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in Japan during the Second World War and the Chernobyl nuclear plant that caused two explosions in 1986 have raised eyebrows about the devastating effects of nuclear energy .
The Chernobyl disaster , especially , exposed millions of people to radioactive chemicals and has been linked to many forms of cancer in Eastern Europe and Russia , as well as destroyed animals and plants .
These two incidents have highlighted the power of nuclear energy , which has caused so much controversy as to whether it is a liability or a source of energy to the world .
In this way , nuclear power has become an independent source of energy to meet the rising energy demand of a country and an increasingly growing global population .
These new plants will operate at high temperatures to improve their efficiency and they will include simplified safety features that rely on non sophisticated back up systems to eradicate any problems .
As much as there are many positive reasons to use nuclear power , many people still have their doubts about this source of energy , mainly due to the fact that they remember the infamous Chernobyl incident and the atomic bombs of World War Two .
The consequences of an accident would be absolutely devastating for both humans and nature , have been the case in the past .
No atomic energy plant in the world could withstand an attack similar to the infamous 9/11 incident .
Nuclear energy uses uranium , which is a scarce resource , as a form of energy .
Theoretically , the supply of uranium is expected to last for about 50-60 years .
It is a unique blend of technical , economic , political and military interests .
Nowadays , the issue of nuclear power is being discussed frequently .
Nuclear power is a new energy source and has a lot of potential to be discovered and explored .
According to Declan Butler ( 2004 ) , nuclear power will not release the greenhouse gas carbon dioxide , and global energy demands are predicted to double by 2050 . Therefore , the nuclear option has now become a viable alternative to be considered .
However , there are many uncertainties regarding safety in the processes found in nuclear power plants .
Many accidents and tragedies have happened .
Studies ( Recently in Nuclear Accidents Category , n.d. ) state that in 2008 , there was a plutonium leak at the Austrian IAEA Facility and a uranium leak at France 's Tricastin Nuclear Facility .
In 2009 , a fire broke out in Unit 1 of Ukraine 's Rivne Nuclear Power Plant .
Although these accidents did not cause any people to die , it reminded people that nuclear power is not as safe as people think .
One system-the Emergency Response Information System ( ERIS ) - has hence been developed to enhance the safety .
When something happens , the system will function immediately to respond to the incident and therefore adequately save the nuclear workers and the general public .
However , in some aspects , this system still has many defects in terms of its feasibility and performance .
In carrying out the ERIS , many training courses and regular exercises are essential in order to make the nuclear worker able to deal with radiation leaks or other accidents .
These essential courses and exercises will cost a lot of money to carry out .
Besides the cost of training , money is also needed for introducing advanced technology skills as well as modern facilities and equipment into the nuclear power plants .
This is a big amount and thus needs a consortium to raise .
However , there are many obstacles and contradictions in finding a big consortium to raise these funds .
Hence , the ERIS is not feasible enough to be carried out .
In order to provide quick and effective response to any nuclear emergency , this system requires a complete round-the-clock operation centre ( E.Asculai and H.E .
There must be a very close connection between each stage of the system 's operations in order for the system to perform well when incidents happen .
Even at midnight , there must still be workers to monitor the system to ensure that the system is functional for 24 hours .
Furthermore , most of the public are ignorant and do not have much knowledge regarding this system .
In addition , the government should also have good coordination with the nuclear power plants regarding safety issues and be very clear of what they should do with this system when an accident happens .
Although this system is efficient to protect people when incidents suddenly happen , nobody can give a 100 % guarantee that this system will perform well as this system consists of many operation stages and requires a wide range of people to monitor it .
Thus , what is the most efficient design to enhance the safety of nuclear power plants ?
No one can design the most efficient system to enhance such safety .
They claim that other than the problems of cost and performance , this system is still very important and functional when nuclear accidents happen .
This system is believed to be the best system so far to protect nuclear workers and the public rather than other methods such as probabilistic safety assessment because the ERIS is more practical protecting people directly after an incident happens .
To sum up , the Emergency Response Information System is a effective system that protects the public if an incident happens .
However , it has to be improved on and developed more in-depth to ensure its safety and enhance its feasibility .
The countries that are developing this nuclear power ( only five countries-China , France , Russia , the United Kingdom and the United States ) must make good use of the nuclear power as the energy source for people 's daily use .
Therefore , developing a design to enhance the safety of nuclear power plants becomes a long-term project of the world .
Consequently , the nuclear power source will be extensively used by the public .
Mankind has been exploring various methods of obtaining high energy output to sustain the usage of energy supply for our daily lives , resulting in the expansion of the energy supply industry .
However , this promise is notably associated with the technologies , the costs and the precise features , which were not yet known with high precision then .
There are various reasons leading to why expansion of nuclear power has faced problems through the years , such as the public 's objection ( Butler , 2004 ) .
For instance , the Very-high- temperature reactors in the generation IV reactor concept ( Butler , 2004 ) , which still requires further development in the aspect of safety at this stage , is rather .
For instance , the Chernobyl accident is still causing deaths years after the accident , with victims mainly dying from cancer caused by exposure to radiation from the highly radioactive waste products released after the massive steam explosion , which occurred due to system flaws , and a second non-nuclear explosion ( International Atomic Energy Agency , 2006 ) .
A 2005 report entitled The Chernobyl Forum , prepared by the International Atomic Energy Agency and World Health Organization , attributed 56 direct deaths and estimated over thousands more deaths among the most highly exposed people .
Another example is the Three Mile Island accident , which occurred due to a partial core meltdown in one of its units ( Corey , n.d. ) .
The above examples illustrate the potential dangers of nuclear power due to its explosive and radioactive characteristics .
The radiation coming from the nuclear wastes will not only produce instant harm , but also a long-term effect on residents in affected areas , spreading across generations .
Keeping that in mind , the gas-cooled fast reactor , one of the generation IV reactor concepts , which requires research on irradiation- resistance material , .
Furthermore , the need for research on heat resistance material and security in the various generation IV reactor concepts is also worrying in terms of the possibilities of nuclear accidents in the future .
Secondly , arguments are that nuclear power is the best alternative because of the characteristic of not producing combustion-related air- pollutants that will lead to global warming , and because of the huge power supply it provides .
In addition , nuclear power uses uranium , which is a scarce resource that is only expected to last for another 30 to 60 years , as fuel .
Therefore , uranium will soon deplete and we will need to search for a new form of energy supply .
Thus , the huge amount of funds pumped into research and development on nuclear power , which will not support us for the long run , is not cost-effective .
Moreover , renewable energy technologies are now expanding faster than nuclear power technologies ( Natural Resources Defense Council , 2007 ) .
They are equally environmentally-friendly and the depleting of resources for renewable energy is of no worry since the reactants are renewable .
Last of all , one of the most promising and nerve-racking reasons is the risk of development of nuclear weapons in an era of transnational terrorism ( Gaukler , Barnett , & Rosinski , 2002 ) .
Terrorism is one of the most troubling global issues in recent years .
The improvement in technologies of the nuclear power would also provide in handling nuclear weapons , so any leakage of details could result in development of nuclear weapons , which in the time of translational terrorism is almost inevitable .
It is also worrying that nuclear power plants may be the target of attack for terrorists due to their destructive nature .
Therefore , there will be a higher risk of nuclear warfare .
The result will be disastrous .
In addition , the need for research on security in various reactor concepts of generation IV is also disturbing .
To summarize , nuclear power has various that could affect the well-being of our environment and health that can not be neglected despite its numerous benefits .
In addition , there are better alternatives such as renewable energy that will be able to support our energy needs in the long run .
Hence , the funds pumped into the development of nuclear power should instead be used in the development of renewable resources that are more cost- effective .
In Singapore , according to the Ministry of Manpower ( 2009 ) , about a total of 11000 cases of fatal and non fatal occupational accidents occur in Singapore and 60 people die in these accidents per annum .
The accident of the Nicoll Highway Collapse in 2004 , which is one of the most catastrophic accidents in the construction sector of Singapore , took away 4 lives .
According to the accident investigation report ( Ministry of Manpower , 2005 ) , it was found that the main cause of the collapse was due to under-designing of the retaining wall which could not handle the stress of holding up the tunnel .
Although some people might think that the effectiveness of psychology in preventing accidents from occurring is controversial , I believe that the use of psychology during the design process could have prevented this accident from occurring .
Many people think that not only the Nicoll Highway Collapse incident , but also most of the major occupational accidents were unexpected and mainly caused by errors in human judgment .
They believe that psychology could have done nothing to prevent the accident from occurring ( International Labour Organisation , 2000 ) .
However , in certain aspects , accidents can be prevented if psychology is introduced to during the design stage .
According to the Heinrich Domino theory , an accident is caused by the chain reaction of a series of factors .
Moreover , " Heinrich proposes that the removal of unsafe acts and unsafe conditions will prevent accidents , as his research found that these were the direct or immediate causes of most accidents " ( Singapore Polytechnic , 2008 ) .
This made significant enhancement in the steel- making , chemical manufacture and construction industry in preventing accidents at work .
Besides that , with this Human Factors Analysis Tools ( HFAT ) , the originators also won the Occupational Psychology Practitioner of the Year award in 2006 ( Division of Occupational Psychology , United Kingdom , n.d. ) .
Most people claim that accidents are unpreventable because a malfunction in a product is due to inadequate design that might cause accidents to occur , which is beyond the control of human capability ( Wilpert , 2007 ) .
( Association of Independent Consultants , Inc , n.d. ) .
These could assist the engineer to experience and discover the limitations and weaknesses of the design and improve on it .
They may take into consideration of the Fixed Guard design ( Singapore Polytechnic , 2008 ) . This design has no moving parts and prevents access to dangerous parts at all times by enclosing the hazardous operation completely .
The safety level is 100 % even when there is a malfunction of the system during its operations , so no one will get injured .
Moreover , many people in the construction industry think that accidents caused by natural disasters and unfavorable working environments is something beyond the human limit and are unavoidable ( Julian , 2007 ) .
For example , a landslide occurs on a work site due to soil erosion after a heavy downpour .
This may be out of our control , yet it is not 100 % inevitable that accidents can not be prevented from occurring in this kind of situation if approached with psychology during the design stage .
It is used to identify the cause of the accident so that corrective measures can be taken to prevent such similar cases from occurring .
Carrying out research studies on related issues or consultation of expertise would help the engineers to understand and envisage the possible accidents that may occur due to the surrounding environment ( Association of Independent Consultants , Inc , n.d. ) .
Therefore , they may apply appropriate measures to eliminate or minimize the potential risk with respect to the unfavorable working environment , such as strengthening the slope with grout anchor tie back , and using an inclinometer to monitor the slope condition .
To summarize , the approach of applying psychology throughout the design process of a project such as understanding human behavior and knowledge on how accidents occur may help to prevent them from occurring .
Studies on related industrial accidents and accident investigations , the ability to envisage possible accidents that may occur , and working with a psychology practitioner could eventually help to minimize and prevent the occurrence of accidents due to errors in human judgment , malfunctioning of products , and working environment factors .
In conclusion , although accidents are unexpected , it is possible to minimize and prevent them from occurring by using the psychology approach in design processes .
It has also been proven to be effective in accident prevention as the MOM has made an obligatory requirement that all work sites must employ a Work Site Safety and Health Officer before the commencement of a project ( Singapore Polytechnic , 2008 ) .
However , the general public is still cautious about accepting nuclear power as a viable energy source .
Although we should never forget the painful lessons of Chernobyl and Three Mile Island , we should also be open-minded about the possibilities that generation IV nuclear reactors bring .
Of the 6 generation IV reactors earmarked for further development , the gas cooled fast reactor design is both innovative and slated to become an efficient and sustainable nuclear energy option .
According to a recent US poll , a significant 44.7 % of the respondents think that nuclear energy production is somewhat dangerous or very dangerous .
To address the safety concerns of the public , the design gas cooled fast reactor includes many safeguard systems .
An NEA report stated that a 'three barrier principle ' will be implemented , and there will be 'cladding at fuel levels ; vessels and primary circuit' .
Hence , the treatment of nuclear waste is a major public concern .
According to the article , 'Nuclear Power 's New Dawn ' , published in Nature , '96 % of spent fuels consist of uranium and plutonium ' ; in other words , more fuels can be generated if the wastes are reprocessed .
In addition , as the design is a fast neutron reactor , it produces excess neutrons which can be used to transmute the nuclear waste into isotopes of shorter half-lives , reducing the toxicity of the waste .
This design also addresses the security concern surrounding nuclear waste reprocessing .
Currently , in the logistics of reprocessing , nuclear wastes are transported to reprocessing facilities which recover the uranium and plutonium before sending them to another mixed oxide fuel ( MOX ) reactor to be burnt as fuels .
However , a report by Hussein Khalil from the Argonne National Laboratories in the USA envisions 'an integrated , onsite spent fuel treatment and refabrication plant' .
This essentially obliterates the security risks involved in transporting radioactive wastes and allows security efforts to be focused on the plant itself .
Lastly , the gas cooled fast reactor is committed to becoming a sustainable form of nuclear power .
Contrary to popular belief that nuclear energy is renewable , uranium is actually a rare element that can be depleted .
The higher efficiency if this reactor design together with the recycling of wastes , means that the same amount of fuel will produce many times more the electricity than that produced by the conventional reactor .
In conclusion , the many advantages of the gas cooled fast reactor make it look extremely promising .
Although nuclear waste remains problematic , it is reduced to a minimum .
Above all , the reactor shows the potential to be sustainable , an advantage that can allow it to be built on a large enough scale to shoulder a significant portion of the world 's energy needs .
Therefore , its research and development should be supported and properly funded so that one day it can reach its full potential and alleviate some of the world 's energy problems .
Global warming has become a concern to people due to its high emission of greenhouse gases from energy usage .
To reduce the carbon dioxide emission , a new energy source which can provide sufficient energy with the least emission of greenhouse gases should be considered since the energy needs of every country is rising .
Nowadays , engineers and industries are very interested in nuclear energy , which can provide up to 80 % of the electricity in France ( Butler , 2004 ) in a cost effective way via mass production .
However , there is always a great concern held by the public regarding the safe operation of nuclear reactors and radioactive waste management .
According to a research study , accidents involving nuclear plants are much fewer than those involving traffic , suicides and fire
The Generation IV International Forum ( GIF ) , a research and development group organized by ten nations to carry out research on the next generation of nuclear concepts , is identifying and selecting six nuclear energy systems with a variety of reactors , energy conversion systems , and fuel cycle technologies .
With GIF 's nuclear technology , the concerns of the public mentioned above would be addressed .
Among the six generation IV reactor concepts , the most advanced concept is the VHTR ( very high temperature reactor ) which is a more efficient way of converting heat energy to electricity and which can provide 50 % more energy from the same amount of fuel compared with other conventional nuclear plants .
Regarding nuclear power plants , the safety features of the plant is the greatest concern of the public .
There were nuclear accident hazards all over the world a few decades ago ; for example , the reactor core explosion at Chernobyl in Ukraine killed many people , with two people dying in the initial explosion and other deaths resulting from radiation poisoning ( Gramling , 2009 ) .
The VHTR system has its own safety features such as a very high system temperature , enhanced goals for safety and reliability , low decay heat load , low power density with and so on ( Idaho National Laboratory ) .
The core is composed of non-combustible nuclear grade graphite which has a very stable structure even at high temperatures and high heat capacity .
Thus , the possibility of explosion due to the very high temperature becomes extremely low .
Moreover , additional safety features such as how to minimize damage and protect lives if an accident occurs will also be developed further ( Lee , 2005 ) .
Another concern regarding nuclear power plants is how to dispose of the nuclear wastes which are long lasting , radioactive and toxic .
As the VHTR operates at a very high temperature , there are fewer wastes to reprocess than those of other systems .
Moreover , the reprocessing will 96 % of the nuclear waste produced , which consists of plutonium and uranium , and only about 1 % of long lasting elements are left as residue .
There are also additional steps of processing to convert those long lasting wastes into elements with shorter half- lives , i.e .
Hence , nuclear waste disposal will not be a great concern in the future .
Nuclear terrorism has always been a threat to the world since the sudden attack on Hiroshima in 1945 .
The VHTR is carefully designed to discourage weapon proliferation and to increase assurance that are very unattractive and are the least desirable route for , .
Hence , it would be harder for terrorists to steal or use the material .
Since the VHTR is still undergoing research , the earliest delivery will be in 2020 ( Butler , 2004 ) .
With the security system developed , nuclear terrorism can be prevented .
In conclusion , in view of the increasing global need for more energy globally , nuclear energy will become essential in the future once issues such as safety , waste management and potential exploitation of plutonium proliferation by terrorists are addressed .
This , in fact , has become possible after the development of the VHTR which incorporates features that minimize the risks of accidents and enable safer disposal of nuclear waste .
Therefore , research for VHTR technology should be funded for further development to reach its optimal potential .
In the United States alone , people use close to 4 million kwh of electricity daily .
In addition , as society grows , the demand for such energy grows as well .
The usage of fossil fuel as a fuel at power plants is projected to increase by 44 percent from 2006 to .
With promises of lower cost , less waste and a safer alternative , it may seem that nuclear power with the introduction of generation IV reactors such as the super-critical-water- cooled reactors is the next generation of power plants .
However , these promises are revealed to be empty promises if one looks deeper into the issue of nuclear Power .
Therefore , support of further research and development funding for nuclear power should not be continued .
The cost of a nuclear plant can be divided into 3 main parts : capital cost , operating cost and fuel cost .
It is claimed that the capital cost of a nuclear power plant is $ 9 / MWh , which is the same for a coal plant , and the fuel cost is very low at $ 5 / MWh as compared to $ 11 / MWh for the coal powered one .
Therefore , it may seem that nuclear power is a cheaper alternative .
However , what they fail to realise is that these costs are only present prices .
They will increase as time goes by .
For example , the construction cost of the nuclear power plant does not just stop there .
All these would incur more costs .
The operating cost of the plant includes its daily operations and also the disposal of the waste .
These wastes are radioactive with a very long half life .
Full disposal of it will incur very high costs in the long run which are often not factored into the operation cost of a plant .
Hence , the nuclear power-plant is not as cost efficient as it may seem .
With regard to safety , it has been reported that there are more cases of fatalities for coal powered plants than their nuclear counterparts .
In the last 40 years , 6400 individuals have died due to coal power plant related accidents while only 31 have died in nuclear powered ones .
Therefore , it is claimed that nuclear plants are a much safer choice .
There will be a point in time when there will be an error which could result in an accident in a nuclear power plant one day .
This single incident will have catastrophic effects and the fatality rate will be substantial .
In the Chernobyl disaster alone which happened on 28 April 1986 , 47 people died on the spot with 4000 more who subsequently died from cancer .
The effects of the incident are still greatly felt today with the radio activeness of the area still at a record high despite three decades of clearing up .
Hence , we only need one nuclear accident to cause the kind of damage a coal plant would take more than 50 years to cause .
Further to what has been pointed out , nuclear power will also evoke security issues in the region .
This will lead to an arms race which might inevitably cause some conflicts in the region .
An example is the nuclear program of Iran .
Iran has developed its nuclear program as a form of deterrence and to build up national pride .
However , many neighbouring countries see these reasons as an excuse for the building of nuclear weapons so they feel threatened .
Hence , many conflicts have resulted .
From this , we can see that nuclear power brings issues to not only the country which is developing it but other neighbouring countries in the region as well .
The price for a small mistake in the pursuit of nuclear energy is too much for mankind to pay .
However , since a large amount of electricity is needed , commercial power generators have been built to convert fuel into electricity .
Another option , which is nuclear energy , had been explored with moderate success but currently only holds a 17 % share as a global energy supply ( Butler , 2004 ) .
However , development of the technology used by nuclear reactors are still on-going with the recent introduction of Generation-IV nuclear reactor concepts , one of them being the molten salt reactor .
The major draw in continuing the research of molten salt reactor is its potential to make converting electricity from nuclear energy much safer , more environmentally friendly and more economically viable as compared to current reactors .
A key step in current nuclear power generation , which is separation of the by-products in the nuclear reactor wastes , would yield materials usable in the creation of highly destructive weapons .
This will ensure that the majority of the fuel is burnt in the process , leaving very low levels of remaining enriched fuel that can be extracted for use for the manufacture of nuclear weapons .
The alternative to replacing coal is arguably the use of solar or wind energy .
The hydrogen produced by the reactor will have further uses as fuel for other systems where its combustion will not produce any greenhouse gases .
For example , the amount of uranium currently mined from the earth 's surfaces have been approximated to last for another 100-200 years as fuel for the reactors ( Lightfoot , Manheimer , Meneley , Pendergast , and Stanford , 2006 ) .
Molten salt reactors can also use thorium as fuel , reserves of which are estimated to be four times larger than that of uranium ( Duffery , 2005 ) .
However , since the fuel is expected to be close to , or completely , burnt up in the molten salt reactor as opposed to the case for current reactors , this higher level of fuel efficiency can drive the duration for which the uranium reserves can sustain the global energy comsumption longer than estimated .
The increase in fuel efficiency will reduce operational cost since there will be less need for storage of long life radioactive waste products .
In addition , considering the development of advanced materials in the further research of molten salt reactor , the actual amount of materials needed in the building can be reduced , thus reducing overall cost .
For example , by replacing the stainless steel commonly found in reactors with other alloys that are equally strong or alloys that are stronger and more durable , and that do not use nickle , the cost of building the reactor can be reduced since the price of nickle has been increasing in recent times ( Busby , 2009 ) .
While the use of nuclear energy raises some concern in terms of security and cost , the continuous research of molten salt reactors can address these concerns through the recycling of fuel and the use of a different variant of fuel .
However , while the research cost of a reactor is very high , this can be solved through the cooperation of more countries , especially the larger countries like China .
In the long run , one of the benefits of using molten salt reactors would be that it can meet energy demands while maintaining a clean environment .
In the recent two decades , whether to adopt nuclear energy as a sustainable source of energy has become one of the heated arguments in the world .
scientists state that coal and fossil fuels on earth are depleting at an alarming rate and would be running out in the next century .
Nuclear energy has thus emerged as one of the most viable solutions .
However , due to the strong oppositions from the public about the safety of nuclear power plants , many countries are caught in the dilemma of whether they should build a nuclear plant or not .
However , in the current situation where there are no better alternatives , nuclear energy seems to be the most suitable energy for the future and therefore one of the generation IV reactors , the lead-coaled fast reactor , should be adopted as the solution .
Firstly , the argument raised by most opponents is the safety issue .
They declare that the nuclear reactions which may be termed as nuclear fission and nuclear fusion are extremely dangerous and even fatal to human beings .
The Chernobyl accident in 1986 was a reminder of the importance of safety .
30 people were killed ( mostly by high levels of radiation ) during the accident and many more were injured or adversely affected .
It was indeed a disastrous accident which subsequently made nuclear plants appear to be scientific devils .
However , the reactor used in fact lacked some basic engineering provisions for safety , probably due to technological constraints at that time .
However , with advancements in science and technology nowadays , the level of danger of the nuclear reactors would be minimised to the lowest degree .
The generation IV reactor , the lead-coaled fast reactor , is the safest one among the four being proposed .
In addition , the operating temperature allows a range of 550 to 800 degrees .
This medium range of temperature increases the functional capacity of the reactor as compared to those which only operate at a fixed temperature .
On top of that , lead which is used as the main source is a less reactive metal compared to sodium for sodium-coaled fast reactors .
another opposing view is that the cost of building a nuclear plant is rather high .
Gas-fired power plants are very cheap and quick to build , but very expensive to operate due to the cost of their fuel .
Furthermore , the cost for mining out and transporting coal and fuel is also very expensive due to their scarcity whereas the sources for nuclear power plants are much cheaper since plenty of uranium can be extracted from the earth 's crust .
Most importantly , the waste generated by the lead-coaled fast reactor can also be recycled and thus there is virtually no pollution to the environment .
Hence , in the long run , it is more economical to adopt the lead-coaled fast reactor which is also an environmentally friendly source of energy .
The final argument advanced by opponents is that there are other sources of safer energy such as solar energy and wind turbines , so there is no need to adopt the nuclear power reactors which are still untested .
However , can we really solely rely on ?
We would still have to rely on other sources when solar energy runs low at times .
As long as the nuclear sources such as lead and uranium are provided , energy will be generated .
Therefore , the lead-coaled fast reactor is a more efficient and reliable energy source .
All in all , with the depleting sources of coal and fuel , lead-coaled fast reactors will be the most likely alternative energy source in the future .
With advanced technology and engineering designs , the safety of nuclear reactors will be ensured .
Therefore , such nuclear power reactors should be adopted in the future as a promising source of energy .
The world depends largely on external energy to operate all activities in the society .
The world 's main energy resource , which is fossil fuel , is slowly depleting .
As a result , there is a need to depend on alternative energy resources to satisfy our high energy demands .
Nuclear power has proven to be an effective energy source as it can generate electricity efficiently to satisfy the world 's energy needs .
However , there are many controversies over the use of nuclear power , and many critics criticize its use .
Some of the gravest concerns that are widely mentioned are safety , costs and performance .
Safety issues raised by past nuclear accidents still strike fear in the public 's heart .
An example of such an accident is the " the 1986 accident at Chernobyl in Ukraine , during which the reactor core exploded , ( killed ) some 31 people immediately and ( spew ) radioactive debris across Europe .
Articles have shown that many experts agree that nuclear power costs significantly higher relative to the other major energy sources .
[ 5 ] Moreover , there are still many doubts about whether nuclear power has a competitive edge over other energy providers in terms of performance .
With all these concerns on the use of nuclear power , it seems that nuclear power poses more of a problem than a solution as a beneficial energy source .
However , with the building of generation IV reactors such as the VHTR , problems that the old generation reactors faced will be greatly reduced , making nuclear power a viable energy source .
Regarding safety concerns , opponents of nuclear power might argue that nuclear reactors are potentially dangerous as the effects from any nuclear accident would be disastrous to both the environment and the people .
However , Generation IV reactors such as the VHTR have advanced safety mechanisms which will minimize the probability of accidents occurring .
The VHTR is capable of dissipating heat even under severe accident conditions and its graphite structure is able to withstand high temperatures to prevent itself from self-sustained combustion .
[ 2 ] According to the " Four levels of Safety " ( by ( By Professor Lawrence Lidsky , MIT ) , the VHTR is the only reactor that meets the level 1 safety criterion , which means that it is immune to major structural failure and operator error .
[ 2 ] Therefore , the VHTR will be a safe nuclear reactor , liable only to minor accidents .
Regarding cost , critics might debate that the high financial costs in building nuclear plants worldwide will create a negative impact on the worldwide economy .
However , although the cost of building nuclear plants is high , future benefits from nuclear power will be able to boost the economy greatly .
In comparison to other hydrogen producing methods , the VHTR produces hydrogen at a lower cost .
[ 4 ] Statistics show that " the VHTR produces hydrogen at $ 1.40/kg , steam reformation of hydrogen costs $ 6.30/MBtu while MHR produced hydrogen costs $ 1.52/kg .
" [ 4 ] In addition , using the VHTR to produce energy would reduce the economic costs spent on controlling carbon dioxide emissions from the burning of fossil fuels .
Regarding performance , critics might strongly argue that the frequent unplanned nuclear shutdowns [ 6 ] would make nuclear power the most inefficient energy among all energy sources .
Sun , wind , tides and waves can not be controlled to directly provide either continuous base-load power or peak-load power when it is needed .
In addition , the VHTR gas turbine system can generate electricity at an efficiency of 50 % whereas existing nuclear power plants generate at only 33 % efficiency
[ 3 ] , making it one of the best performance nuclear reactors .
In comparison to older generation reactors , Generation IV reactors will have better safety and cost effective features .
The VHTR is one of the best generation IV reactors , making it one of the most reliable energy providers in the future .
Hence , further research and funding for the VHTR will definitely benefit the future generations .
According to Marshall & Robert ( 2000 ) , the rising costs and rapid depletion of natural fuel has led to the search for a more sustainable energy source .
Thus , countries are focusing on the development of nuclear reactors , the most viable energy source that seemingly appears to be endless .
However , in terms of safety , costs and overall performance , the VHTR would be the best nuclear reactor to be implemented
( Marshall & Robert , 2000 ) .
According to Butler , safety is a main priority in the designs of new nuclear reactors due to the previous nuclear disasters of Three Mile Island and Chernobyl .
There is a large margin between the operational temperature and the coolant boiling temperature .
This would mean a relatively safer work environment in addition to the low operating pressure conditions .
However , the passive cooling system of the SFR has major flaws .
In comparison , the VHTR model uses helium , which is an inert gas , as its coolant and thus would be much safer than sodium .
The cooling system of the VHTR is a helium turbine system , operating separately under stringent human control and thus allowing for quicker actions to be taken in the event of overheating
DOE Nuclear Energy Research Advisory Committee , 2002 ) . Cost factors are also taken into consideration given the scale of the nuclear reactors .
The Sodium-Cooled Reactor is claimed to be cheaper in terms of research costs .
Given that the technology base exists for the SFR , it is said that not much additional extensive research has to done .
However , this is not the case .
In actual fact , many technical viability issues are waiting to be resolved .
According to the US DOE Nuclear Research Advisory Committee , due to the instability and radio-active state of sodium , more research has to be done to find suitable materials for its reactor 's primary core
DOE Nuclear Energy Research Advisory Committee , 2002 ) .
The Very High Temperature Reactor would be a much cheaper option as the core for its plant has been confirmed to be graphite .
As Sterbentz brought up in his report on the VHTR , graphite is a much more stable and cheaper material in comparison to the suggested cores for the SFR .
In addition , with low reactions to heat and chemical irradiation , replacement of the graphite cores only need to be done around once in five years .
According to the Austrian Institute of Ecology ,the performance for the SFR was rated highly for its closed fuel system which recycles 99.9 % of the actinides produced in its process .
There is close to no nuclear waste produced by the once through system .
The energy output is much less than the VHTR models which will exceed 50 % .
Furthermore , the VHTR produces hydrogen in addition to electricity .
This additional fuel production would mean a larger net output by the VHTR in comparison to the SFR
In conclusion , the Very High Temperature Reactor would be the best nuclear reactor concept to implement .
Whether it is about safety , cost or performance level , the VHTR is a notch above its peers such as the SFR .
The VHTR 's potential as the best nuclear reactor is recognized by many countries like France , Japan and the United States of America .
Globalization has caused the demand of oil to surge to the extent that the supply of crude oil can not match the demand for it , hence leading to a shortage of oil .
The Generation IV International Forum ( GIF ) , an organization formed to further develop nuclear energy has come up with six generation IV reactor concepts
Since there are a lot of benefits in using nuclear energy , especially energy from the very high-temperature reactor ( VHTR ) , further research and development on nuclear energy sources should be encouraged .
Firstly , a nuclear power plant is more cost effective to operate as compared to other energy sources .
For example , although the start-up cost of building the VHTR plant is very high , which is up to US $ 10 billion , it is cheaper as compared to other fuel , such as bio fuel , in the long run .
Consequently , many countries have regarded VHTR as the energy source of the future , because it produces hydrogen gas as a complimentary energy source that is reusable .
the reactor can separate hydrogen gas from water thermodynamically during the nuclear reaction at an extremely high temperature of about 700-900 degrees celcius .
( Burthler , 2004 ) Additionally , according to the economics concept , there is less third party cost incurred by others if nuclear power is used instead of other fuels .
It is also relatively cleaner to the environment as compared to other sources of fuels .
Thus , the sum of all the various costs of producing nuclear power is relatively lower than other sources of energy .
Secondly , a nuclear reactor , especially the VHTR , produces less waste as compared to other energy sources .
It is known that a large percentage of the greenhouse gases present today is due to the use of petroleum and combustion of fossil fuels .
The burning of fossil fuels also produces other waste products that are harmful to the environment .
On the other hand , even though the VHTR produces nuclear waste which will emit harmful radioactivity , the industry has come up with effective ways to dispose of the nuclear waste .
One such method is to bury the nuclear waste in the ground .
Research has shown that the radioactivity that is produced by the nuclear waste under the ground is equivalent to the radioactivity emitted by cosmic rays .
Thus , humans are safe from the radioactivity produced by the nuclear waste .
That is , nuclear power , especially that produced by the VHTR , is a much cleaner source of energy for the environment , so further research and development should be done on it .
Critics may argue that the security measures used in the nuclear power plants are inadequate , and this will endanger the safety of the people living close to the nuclear power plants .
Indeed , the aftermath of an explosion of a nuclear power plant would be harmful .
For instance , it was shown from the Chernobyl incident that an explosion in a nuclear plant would cause cancerous effects on human beings , and this effect would last for a few centuries
However , according to the GIF , the six nuclear reactor concepts being researched by them , including the VHTR , incorporate a high security-proof mechanism .
Thus , they are 'meltdown proof ' , which means that they can reduce their temperature to the accepted temperature range in the event of an accident , with little human intervention .
Hence , the safety aspect of the people is well taken care of even if there is any terrorist attack on the nuclear power plants .
Therefore , more research should be carried out on the nuclear power plants .
In essence , nuclear reactors , especially the VHTR , are more cost effective in the long run as compared to other energy sources .
In addition , nuclear energy is less harmful to the environment and it is safe to humans .
Moreover , it has been shown that the VHTR is 40 % more effective in producing energy as compared to other sources of energy .
Thus , in my opinion , more funding should be provided for research and development to further improve the production of nuclear power , and the research should focus more on the VHTR .
The usage of nuclear plants to generate electricity has been a controversial issue since decades ago , due to the disastrous incidents on Three Miles Island and at Chernobyl , which have resulted in major health issues caused by radiation exposure .
The public has been rejecting the construction of nuclear plants due to safety concerns .
However , as technology has evolved with time , the Generation IV power plants are better in terms of security , cost and performance .
One of the main reasons stated by the opposition is that nuclear plants consume uranium and produce nuclear waste , which could be used to manufacture nuclear weapons .
The molten salt reactors are capable of recycling the nuclear waste to produce more electrical energy , so the waste created from the recycling process will not be available for creating nuclear weapons .
This process also helps to prevent the existing practice of spending large amounts of money to store the nuclear waste .
In addition , the International Atomic Energy Agency ( IAEA ) has set up necessary guidelines for governments to ensure the highest level of security for their nuclear facilities .
The Generation IV plants are built to shut down automatically in the event of a meltdown or terrorist attack ( Butler , 2004 ) .
To prevent the escape of radiation which resulted in the Chernobyl incident , the new plants are built with shielding that can prevent radiation from escaping into the surroundings in case of a meltdown .
Opponents have also argued that renewable energy sources are better sources of energy as they produced cleaner energy when compared to nuclear reactors , which produce radiation and nuclear waste .
In addition , renewable sources are also unlimited , whereas uranium will last another two centuries at most ( Fetter , 2009 ) .
Thus , they believe that governments should spend the money on research for renewable energy instead of nuclear energy .
Furthermore , the electricity produced from renewable sources like solar energy is measured in Mega watts per hour , while the electricity produced from nuclear plant is measured in Giga watts per hour , so one thousand times more energy is produced .
In comparison , the biggest solar power generator located in California is able to support half a million users , less than two percent of the city population ( Wolff , 2007 ) , while a single nuclear plant is able to provide electricity for a few cities .
Another issue is that uranium is finite like fossil fuels .
Every year , governments that are supportive of nuclear energy have spent billions of dollars on it .
In 2008 , the United States Government increased their budget allocation for nuclear energy and the research and development for Generation IV power plants to twenty-five billion dollars ( Barnett , 2008 ) .
The opposition has stated that the power generated is not worth the cost , as the cost is accumulated from .
It is definitely worthwhile spending more to protect the environment .
In conclusion , governments should support further research and development on nuclear energy as the security concern regarding nuclear waste can be eliminated ; moreover , nuclear plants are the most efficient energy source and the cost of nuclear energy is the cheapest in the long term .
With further funding on the research , humans will be able to produce energy in the long run without damaging the environment .
robotic surgical technology is a prototype and a new breakthrough in the field of engineering and medicine .
The robotic system uses fine , precise robotic arms and its three dimensional high resolution computed image guides the surgeon during an operation .
According to a report ( Guru , 2007 ) the rate of survival of every fifty patients of mean age 68 years old undergoing Robotic Radical Cystectomy is 98 % .
Whereas according to Kyung Hee University , Seoul , Korea Cancer Research and Treatment ( 2005 ) , for the traditional Radical Cystectomy surgery , the survival rates are 62 % for males and 39.4 % for females , with mean patient age of 62.8 years old .
Thus , it has been proven that the robotic surgical system has a significantly more positive clinical result as compared to the conventional surgery method .
However , although the initial clinical outcomes are positive , safety is a major factor why the robotic surgical system still remains fearful to the public .
Safety concerns involve technical credibility , surgical liability and operation performance .
Even though there is no guarantee that the robotic surgical system can absolutely ensure the safety of patients , the design of the robotic system can nevvertheless improved to enhance safety .
During an operation , the condition of the patient is unpredictable ; many tasks and decisions need to be made involving the surgeon , the nurses and the robotic system .
For example , when tools are changed , the robotic system needs to be paused in order to replace a surgical tool .
During this process , the surgeon has no direct access to the situation ; the system relies largely on verbal exchanges between the nurses and the surgeon to coordinate the surgical procedures .
The differences in perspective with respect to the patient 's condition and the robotic system create safety issues , mainly due to the potential of miscommunication .
In order to enhance safety , a common ground needs to be built through ensuring similar speech patterns .
Therefore , communication between surgeons and nurses can be improved by the sharing of a common set of statements and ideology .
Although the robotic system has improved greatly in its dexterity , its full potential in terms of instrumental design and sensory sensitivity has yet to be developed .
This poses uncertain dangers during an operation .
According to Zorn ( 2009 ) , no credible system is currently available to assess the capability of a surgeon while operating the robotic surgical system .
In order to improve the system 's safety , the future of the robotic system can be expanded using ultrasound and infrared .
In addition , the surgical equipment occupies a large space which may restrict the movement of nurses and cause delays during an operation .
miniaturizing the equipment will help address the problem and also save cost in making room for the accommodation of this expensive equipment .
In the end , however , , despite all the development of ideas to improve on safety , cost is the major concern as to whether these ideas can be implemented .
The surgical system is an expensive technology whose initial cost is 1.5 million dollars each with maintenance costs of hundreds of thousands each year .
This high equipment cost induces an increase in surgical costs of over thousands of dollars .
Moreover , laboratories are currently working on the development of new devices to enhance safety during operations .
Subsequently , this development will induce a higher capital cost of equipment .
However , if we compare the cost of conventional surgery with the cost of the robotic surgery , knowing that most cases of robotic surgery optimize chances of quicker recovery which implies shorter hospital stays .
The difference in cost imposed by the use of the robotic equipment will be balanced off in comparison to the cost of hospital stay for the conventional surgery , so cost will not be a constraint in the enhancement of safety .
During the past few years , there have been discussions on whether nuclear power plants should be built or not .
For the past few centuries , most of our electricity has been generated from coal , fuel or oil refineries .
However , as the population increases , there is a higher demand for electricity , so more raw resources such as fossil fuel have to be used .
Recently , the rate of depletion of fossil fuel has been increasing , leading to a higher electricity cost .
As a result , more people are turning to nuclear power as a solution to the high electricity cost .
However , before we change to nuclear power , there are some factors we need to consider .
The factors which would be discussed are cost , security and performance .
Some of the reasons why people are opposed to the idea are the high construction cost and level of danger of nuclear power plants .
However , because of the lower electricity cost and the ability to meet the world 's demand in the future .
Despite opposing views , further research and development funding for the Very-High-Temperature-Reactor ( VHTR ) should be encouraged .
Firstly , in terms of the cost factor , according to Michael ( 2009 ) , uranium , being the raw resource of nuclear power , has been proved to be able to meet the need of world demand for hundreds of centuries .
Due to its abundance , the cost price of uranium would be cheaper when compared to that of fossil fuel .
Besides this , the mining cost of uranium Is also very cheap .
these factors result in low operation costs for nuclear power plants .
The Economics of Power ( 2007 ) , shows the of US electricity production costs from 1995 to 2008 .
The book compared the cost of electricity generated among oil , gas , coal and nuclear plant .
However , by the year 2008 , the cost of electricity generated from oil plant had increased to 18 cents per kilowatt-hour , whereas for nuclear , the cost had remained constant over the years .
However , people are claiming that the construction cost of a nuclear power plant is too high .
Although in the long term , the low production cost would have an edge over the construction cost .
Since the cost of fossil fuel is soaring high now , if we still continue to use it , we would have to pay a very high electricity cost compared to the cost we would have to pay for electricity generated by nuclear energy .
Once the construction cost has been recovered , .
Thus , in terms of the cost factor , it is still an advantage to the public if we use nuclear energy in the long run .
The second factor is security. .
According to Bulter ( 2004 ) , the public has highlighted the accidents which occurred in 1979 at Three Mile Island and in 1986 at Chernobyl .
However , in the case of the generation IV reactor , it has been claimed that there would be a security feature called the " Meltdown " Proof which would reduce the temperature to a minimum in the event of an accident .
As technology advances over the years , we can foresee that the chances of accidents occurring will be reduced .
Thirdly , in terms of the performance factor , Bulter ( 2004 ) claims that the VHTR could squeeze 50 % more electricity from the same amount of fuel compared with conventional plants .
Engineers have agreed that in order to reach such efficiency , higher temperatures would need to be generated , thus causing a higher chance of accident .
In conclusion , we can see that even though there are some disadvantages of the nuclear power plant , it is still beneficial to the public if we operate it in the long run .
The advantages of the nuclear power plant outweigh its disadvantages .
The Very High Temperature Reactor ( VHTR ) is one of the six generation IV reactors which need to be developed .
The six generation IV reactors are the vision of the future of the Generation IV International Forum ( GIF ) .
GIF looks at the future with nuclear reactors in its mind , because it believes the current coal-burning source of energy would not be sufficient for the world 's need by 2050 ( Butler , 2004 ) .
In addition , GIF believes the coal- burning is contributing to global warming by carbon dioxide ( CO2 ) into the air .
The six generation IV reactors are believed to be able to replace coal mines .
These six generation IV reactors are still in the testing and research phase .
GIF is researching them in terms of their safety , their cost effectiveness and their effect on the environment because these are the public 's concerns about them .
This is due to memories of past accidents involving the partial meltdown of nuclear nuclear reactors .
Looking back at a few decades ago , there were two accidents which brought the world 's attention to the importance of safety in nuclear reactors .
In 1979 , on Three Mile Island , Pennsylvania , there was a malfunction in a cooling system which caused part of the reactor core to melt and some radioactive gas to be released into the air was , fortunately , not enough to cause any radiation dose .
In 1986 , at Chernobyl , Ukraine , a flawed reactor design that was operated by untrained personnel and without proper regard for safety , exploded and released at least five percent of the radioactive reactor core into the atmosphere and the surrounding area .
The two accidents caused people who lived nearby the nuclear reactors to suffer from the radiation .
The nuclear-averse public oppose the development of generation IV reactors because they are afraid such accidents will happen again and cause more damage to the people who live nearby nuclear reactor plants .
This feature would simplify safety features ; hence we would not need to rely on sophisticated backup systems or experienced operators .
This is because generation IV reactors can cool themselves down in the event of an accident with minimal human intervention ( Butler , 2004 ) , thus preventing the meltdown accident from happening again .
The second factor is the cost of building the nuclear reactor plant .
The nuclear-averse public oppose the development of generation IV reactors because they are too costly to build .
It is true that a country needs to put billions of dollars into the research and development of nuclear reactor plants .
This is because it is beneficial for the country in the long run .
With the increasing population , the demand on energy sources will increase .
One alternate energy source which has been suggested by many scientists is nuclear energy .
This is because with the same amount of raw materials , a nuclear reactor plant can produce up to ten times more of the energy produced by a the fossil energy plant .
Lastly , the third factor is the effect of nuclear reactors on the environment .
The nuclear-averse public oppose the development of generation IV reactors because they are worried that its waste will pollute the environment .
The waste of the nuclear reactors will last for a few years on earth before it starts to deplete .
When GIF have found out the proper method of recycling , the public can live with ease nearby nuclear reactor plants .
To conclude , the nuclear-averse public oppose the development of generation IV reactors because they do not fully understand the concept of generation IV reactors .
Hence , the very high temperature reactor should be further researched and developed .
In the 21st century , the energy issue has become a serious problem that human beings are facing .
It is predicted by experts that fossil fuels will run out in 250-300 years with oil disappearing in less than 100 years
Thus , it has become really urgent to find a substitutable energy source to meet the increasing demand of human beings .
As a result , many scientists have turned to nuclear energy and are doing research on future Generation IV reactors which are safer and have higher productivity .
Although some people are against these nuclear reactors , one particular generation IV reactor called the molten salt reactor is really worth researching on .
Some opponents argue that the safety of the nuclear reactor can not be guaranteed , and such dangerous power plants should never be built .
They think that nuclear waste is radioactive and may cause health problems to the people around the reactor .
However , the real situation is not as bad as they think .
In addition , the molten salt reactor can solve these problems completely .
It is written in Generation VI Reactors ( 2009 ) that the molten salt reactor uses liquid sodium fluoride as the coolant , which dissolves the uranium and circulates through the graphite core .
This means that there is no radioactive waste in the whole process .
Therefore , the concern about radioactive waste is not founded .
Some opponents argue that even though there is no radioactive waste , the reactor itself is a big safety problem ; the reactor may explode and cause disasters .
However , according to Power Uprate Safety & Containment Overpressure ( 2005 ) , the major safety problem for the reactor is that the balance of energy generated and energy removed may be affected due to some reason .
As a result , the reactor may explode because of excessive pressure and release large amounts of radioactivity .
However , according to Dr. Paul Pickard ( 2002 ) , there is lower pressure in the molten salt reactor as the boiling point for molten salt is 1400 degrees celcius .
In addition , which may cause an accident is low due to the continuous removal of mobile fission products .
In addition , the molten salt can absorb a lot of heat with little change in temperature .
All these guarantee that the balance will not be easily broken .
Furthermore , it is mentioned in Power Uprate Safety & Containment Overpressure ( 2005 ) that an entire system , which is designed to match the energy produced by the reactor and the energy removed and can thus effectively prevent accidents from happening , is now used in each reactor in America .
In the molten salt reactor , a better or at least the same system will be used to ensure the safety of the reactor .
opponents also argue that the cost of the nuclear reactor is so high that it is not worth being built .
It can not be denied that the cost of nuclear reactor construction is very high , but according to The Economics Of Nuclear Power ( 2008 ) , in 2008 in America , the electricity cost for nuclear energy per kwh was 8.34 cents while the cost of coal energy was 8.51cents .
Moreover , the external cost , including the pollution to the environment , of nuclear energy was 0.4eruo cents/kwh while for coal energy , it was 4.0 euro cents .
Hence , the cost of nuclear energy is actually less than coal energy and it is much more environmentally friendly .
Moreover , according to Generation VI Reactors ( 2009 ) , all the generation IV reactors will reduce the cost of electricity and produce higher levels of electricity with lower use of fuels compared to previous reactors .
Such evidence shows us that the molten salt reactor will cost little .
One major problem is to find a material material which has a high resistance to the corrosion of the molten salt .
Further research and development is needed to overcome this challenge and to turn this reactor into a reality .
Many inventions have improved our quality of life and made each human being a large consumer of electricity and fossil fuels .
With the development of technology and the increase in populations , energy demand has exploded .
Contrarily , the main source of energy , which is a non-renewable energy resource , is disappearing from the earth .
To solve this problem , one way is to gather energy from nature .
However , .
Nuclear reactions were found generating significant amounts of energy rapidly .
Unfortunately , chemical species used in nuclear reactions have incredible destructive power so people are fearful of their leakage .
In history , the leakage that happened in Bhopal , India in 1984 was a " terrible tragedy " ( " The incident " , n.d. ) during which " approximately 3,800 people died and several thousand other individuals experienced permanent or partial disabilities " ( " The incident " , n.d. ) .
The fear of leakage has result in a small number of nuclear plants being built on earth .
Nowadays , the generation IV reactors are in development and one of them called the Very High Temperature Reactor ( referred to as the VHTR below ) is worth developing .
The VHTR has a high safety level , a high efficiency level and an ultra-long lifetime which make it the best of the six generation IV reactors .
Safety is ensured in the design of the VHTR .
According to Teri Ehresman , the VHTR is able to retain " the desirable safety characteristics offered by modular high-temperature gas-cooled reactors " ( Ehresman , 2009 ) .
Furthermore , it is shown in the report of James W. Sterbentz that it is possible to " increase the thermal safety margin under transient conditions " ( Sterbentz , n.d. ) for the VHTR .
Thus , it is reasonable to assert that safety in the design of the VHTR is ensured .
Some may argue that nuclear reactors are not safe at all since accidents have happened in history and caused huge disasters .
However , they fail to consider that the broken reactors were the first generation reactors and technology then was not mature nor well developed .
After decades of development , nuclear technology is now more advanced and most importantly , safety in design has been largely enhanced .
It is not right to deny the future of the nuclear industry simply because of the accidents in the past .
Indeed , safety is ensured in the design of the VHTR and it should be further researched and developed .
The VHTR has high working efficiency .
The VHTR operates at about 1000 Celsius degrees which is enough to produce hydrogen .
Thus , the VHTR produces electricity , hydrogen and a large amount of concurrently in .
As an energy supplier , the VHTR is able to work more efficiently than that produce only electricity .
Some may say that the temperature needed for the VHTR to operate is high and it is not easy to provide the operating temperature for it .
It is true that VHTR needs more energy to start operating but once it is started , it produces energy more efficiently than other reactors .
It is reasonable to say that in the long run , .
Thus , the VHTR is promising in providing energy and solving the energy shortage problem .
Last but not least , the VHTR can have an ultra-long lifetime with minor actinides .
Moreover , it maximizes the usage of a reactor to a great extent .
With the cost lowered , reactors can be massively built and commercialized .
Only if reactors are .
As some may argue , maintenance also needs money and may lead to an increase in .
However , it is common sense that maintenance fees should be much lower than the cost of building a new reactor .
Besides , building fewer reactors and lengthening their lifetime save money as well as natural resources such as land .
Hence , the VHTR is worth researching and developing on .
To summarize , the VHTR is well worth developing mainly because safety is ensured in its design process .
In addition , the VHTR tends to have higher working efficiency and an ultra-long lifetime which makes it more favourable than other generation IV reactors .
Hopefully , it will not be long before the nuclear power 's new dawn and the VHTR is on its way , leading generation IV reactors to serve human beings and finally solving the energy shortage problem .
Nuclear power is electrical power which is produced from controlled nuclear reactions ( France , 2005 ) .
Although nuclear power can produce a much more significant amount of electrical power compared to other forms of electrical energy , its safety makes the public concerned about nuclear power production .
Among many nuclear reactors built all over the world , one type of reactor is the " Sodium-cooled fast reactor " which is operated at a temperature of 550 degree Celsius under low pressure .
The power output of this reactor is electricity .
However , nuclear power is not an efficient way if we consider the storage and safety issues of nuclear materials as well as the huge cost of nuclear power plant construction ( Hannity , 2009 ) .
On the other hand , many countries , such as Pakistan , Japan , China , India as well as the United States are active in nuclear power production regardless of the concern of the public over the safety issue .
The World Nuclear Association has stated that on average in every 17 days , one new nuclear reactor was set up during the 1980s and this rate may increase to one nuclear reactor per every five days in 2015 .
Although nuclear power plants ' construction cost is much higher compared to the cost of other alternative sources , for example , solar panels and wind turbines , nuclear power has efficiency output and sustainable energy .
The lower initial cost of alternative sources but nuclear power should be considered ( Gonyeau , 2009 ) .
Supporters claim that third generation power plants would be cheaper as well as faster to construct than second generation power plants , based on previous experience of constructing nuclear power plants .
However , there is also proof that some of the new generation reactors can not fulfill their promise .
For example , Westinghouse claimed that its advanced AP1000 would cost $ 1000 per KW construction cost , be completed within 3 years and would provide cheaper electricity than fossil fuel generated electricity , including Australian Coal power , with no sequestration charges .
But the promise was fulfilled ; the construction cost was over $ 3500 per KW which was even higher than the cost of the previous generator
( Group of Physicists School of Physics at the University of Melbourne in Australia , 2009 ) .
Since nuclear power plants do not release any harmful materials , nuclear energy is ideal .
A nuclear power plant emits significantly low carbon while fossil fuel pollution kills around ten thousand people per year in the United States due to respiratory problems .
However , some opponents also claim that an average nuclear power plant creates twenty to thirty tonnes of high level waste per year and that waste has to cool on site for at least five years before they are moved .
According to one environmental group , Yucca currently fills up 2495 tons of nuclear waste ( The Charlotte Observer , Hauter , 2004 ) .
Some people claim that the chances of accidents at nuclear reactor plants are very low because of advanced technology.However , the accident at the Three Mile Island Unit2 nuclear power plant which has been the most serious in the US , as well as the explosion at the Chernobyl power station , prove that nuclear reactors are still dangerous and not 100 percent secure .
The number of deaths by cancer also increased because of these incidents .
Not just health and environmental facts , but psychological factors should also be considered .
The worst situation is using nuclear power as a weapon ( Walker , 2004 ) .
In conclusion , nuclear power should not be widely produced because of security as well as environmental issues .
Alternative energy sources such as wind , solar , hydrogen as well as water should be used instead for a more secure future for the next generation .
Evidence also shows that very few new reactors have been built since serious accidents took place due to explosions or meltdowns of nuclear reactors in the 1980s ( Butler , 2004 ) .
To date , people are still suffering a lot of the repercussions from these past incidents .
However , with the expected increase in energy demand worldwide and the growing awareness of global warming , climate change and sustainable development , the new Generation IV ( Gen IV ) nuclear reactors seem to be the ultimate solution to these problems .
According to Gerstner , the Gen IV nuclear reactors will promise safe , economically competitive , proliferation-resistant nuclear power without the danger of increasing greenhouse gas emissions .
Many developed countries are starting to express interest in this new nuclear technology and some have even formed a consortium to pool their expertise and funding to carry out research on the six most promising prospects for the future Gen IV reactors .
Thus , I agree that there should be research and development ( R&D ) funding for the Gen IV nuclear reactors .
According to Reuters ( 2008 ) , the Electric Power Research Council in the United States has said that there will be a need for some 35 more { nuclear power } [ ] plants by the year 2030 .
The existing technology is to store the waste on site , but it can be politically sensitive - Yucca Mountain in Nevada is .
Reprocessing the spent fuel is another alternative to reducing the waste volume by a factor of two or three .
However , this is expensive and inefficient and poses a nuclear proliferation threat .
The Gen IV reactors aim to develop waste-free nuclear energy by burning up fission waste , leaving a residue greatly reduced in both volume and radioactivity ( Gerstner , 2009 ) .
However , the challenges lie in the complication of building a nuclear fission reactor and the lack of funding to carry out research in this area .
Although it would take years to develop such advanced technology and probably cost quite a large sum of money , research studies have to be done to tackle the faster mounting nuclear waste problem .
Opponents of nuclear energy claim that before the first of the Gen IV reactors will be built , optimistically in 2030 and possibly 2040 to 2050 , solar power systems would already be highly mature and widely developed .
However , a report ( { McLaughlin } [ HYPERLINK : http : //www.associatedcontent.com/user/1887/brant_mclaughlin.html ] , 2007 ) pointed out that most solar power plants can only generate power at 20 % of their average efficiency .
They are more efficient and require less resource to operate , compared to fossil fuels and solar energy .
Thus , it is important to channel funding to the R&D for Gen IV reactors as they provide the energy that will meet our future energy needs .
There is a profound need for a new generation of nuclear reactors as they not only bring cleaner energy for our future generations but they are also a waste-free , terrorism-proof and affordable source of energy .
As countries such as China and the U.S. are showing interest in constructing new nuclear power plants , large amounts of nuclear waste is expected in the next 20 to 30 years .
Hence , channeling funds to the R&D of Gen IV reactors is necessary as it helps to solve the waste problem .
The Very-High-Temperature Reactor Versus the Sodium-Cooled Fast Reactor
In addition , burning fossil fuel emits greenhouse gases , a main cause of global warming .
Therefore , scientists and engineers are placing high hopes on the new generation of nuclear reactors which are seen as a clean source of energy without emission of green-house gases .
However , base on past nuclear accidents and technical hurdles , some people argue that nuclear power is unstable , extremely dangerous and expensive .
Fortunately , generation IV nuclear reactors are on the horizon , promising " safe , abundant , reliable , inexpensive and proliferation resistant " nuclear power plants ( " Nuclear Power 's New Dawn " , 2004 ) .
In this essay , I will compare two outstanding generation IV models : the very-high-temperature reactor ( VHTR ) and the sodium-cooled fast reactor ( SFR ) , and argue that the VHTR is safer , more economical and more proliferation-resistant than SFR .
It is said that the VHTR has not achieved the goals of simple operation and transparent safety concepts because it does not have a passive heat removal system ( Generation IV International Forum , 2008 ) .
However , this is not true as the VHTR is developing a passive heat removal system that can achieve a higher level of safety which is not dependent on human intervention .
the VHTR was initially designed to use helium as its coolant which is not the most suitable for an instant passive heat removal system .
In order to achieve a more effective heat removal system , salts or mixed gas could be used because of their superior heat transport characteristics .
According to " GIF R&D outlook for Generation IV Nuclear Energy Systems 2009 " , molten salts can enable 4 to 6 times higher .
As a matter of fact , the overall cost of building , operating and maintaining the VHTR is more cost-effective than for the SFR .
Outdoing the SFR , the VHTR has lower fuel cost and higher hydrogen production due to its high operation temperature , which allows a high burn-up rate of the fuels .
Furthermore , in contrast to the SFR , the VHTR is resistant to nuclear weapon proliferation as it abandons the reprocessing process .
The reprocessing process incorporated in the SFR extracts plutonium , which is an indispensable part of nuclear weapons .
Because VHTR is operated at an extremely high temperature and within a closed cycle system , high utilization of uranium can be achieved even without reprocessing .
Thus , the VHTR prevents potential nuclear wars that the SFR may lead to .
To conclude , simple operational and transparent safety concepts are inherently embedded in the VHTR , ensuring a high level of safety .
The VHTR is more economically competitive than the SFR as its overall cost of building , operations and maintenance is lower
The VHTR also has the unique feature of proliferation resistance which would prevent potential nuclear wars .
Engineers will have to take into consideration future needs while being creative and also without jeopardizing the functionality and the usability of the product .
As psychology studies human mental functions and human behavior , we are able to pin point human errors and thus minimize design mistakes and prevent accidents from happening .
In my opinion , as the human factor always plays a part in major industrial accidents .
The use of psychology during the design process stage can help reduce these accidents .
One major engineering accident was the Eschede train accident which happened in Germany ( Wilpert , 2007 ) .
The accident , which happened in June 1998 , caused a total of 101 deaths and 88 injured .
This incident was not caused by failure of only one component .
Rather it was caused by the interaction of multiple factors like human error and design mistakes .
In this case , we are able to relate psychology into the factors and examine how pscyhology could have prevented it from happening .
The original set of wheels used by the train were monobloc wheels .
However , the wheels appeared to be too noisy and vibration could be felt in the train cabin .
Therefore , the engineers came up with a similar design to what the trams were using to solve the vibration issue .
The new wheel was wrapped with a thick layer of rubber .
The layer of rubber helped reduce the vibration .
The design was not tested but it proved to be reliable because over the years it did not have any major problems .
However , according to Khandani ( 2005 ) the final phase of a proper engineering design process is testing .
In this process , engineers might discover design flaws and make the necessary changes to the design .
The engineers of the Eschede train made a mistake in neglecting this important step in the design process .
If prototyping had been done the accident might not have happened .
Before the derailment of the train , .
The train conductor or a passenger may have prevented the train accident if they had pulled the emergency brake .
The subsequent accident would not have happened if a passenger or the conductor had possessed adequate problem solving skills .
The passenger could have pulled the emergency brake himself instead of notifying the conductor .
The train conductor would have been able to stop the accident from happening if he had not followed the company 's policy for stopping the train .
It separates the high speed trains from the slower trains .
The railway track used by the Eschede train involved in the accident was not dedicated for high speed trains .
However , it had been upgraded so that it could be shared between high speed trains and slower trains .
In addition , rail switches were used to maximize the usage of the tracks .
The rail switches transferred the trains from a slow track to a fast track and vice versa .
However , seconds before the accident happened , the wheel rim which pierced through the cabin floor slammed against the rail switch , forcing some of the train cabins to disconnect from the first cabin and switch to another track .
The entire disconnected cabin was thereby thrown off the bridge .
In conclusion , is undeniably desirable as it makes our life better .
However , besides focusing on the improvements offered by a new design , one should also pay attention to the possible tradeoffs .
When the improvements in a new design are unable to compensate for limitations , designers should abandon the design .
If we put much consideration of the psychological approach into the design process , many accidents can be avoided .
The use of psychology would assist engineers and designers to think creatively and better and therefore they will come up with safe and good inventions .
In addition , by exploring further the psychological aspect and applying it in our daily routines , many of such major accidents can be prevented or minimized .
21 million square meters of land was polluted and could n't be used for living .
Chernobyl was not the only serious nuclear plant accident in the past .
There was another nuclear plant accident in Three Mile Island in the US .
As these disasters happen over and over again , the problem of how to improve the design process should be examined from a different perspective .
One such perspective is to take psychology into account .
What is the role of psychology in engineering ?
Engineering pscyhology is concerned with adapting the equipment and the environment to people , based upon their psychological capacities and limitations ( Blum , 1952 ) with the objective of improving overall system performance ( involving human and machine elements ) .
From this statement , we know that psychology aims to improve systems by helping people in a psychological way .
Some may wonder if it is really helpful to apply psychology .
We consider the Chernobyl incident as an example .
As mentioned in the preceding paragraph , Chernobyl was considered as a technological catastrophe .
However,was it just caused by technological errors ?
Let 's take a quick look at the accident .
The first thing working against them was that another power plant on the circuit was down , so Chernobyl was producing more power than usual to compensate for it .
Thus , the day staff did not run the test .
However , nobody ever told the night staff not to do it , so they tried to perform the test as planned .
Consequently , the reactor started getting out of control .
Thus , they had an uncontrolled nuclear reaction .
Because they did n't have the right Geiger counters , they did n't know what a serious danger they were in because they did not know the actual radiation levels .
They were at the plant for about 3 days until the explosion , trying to pump water into the reactor to control it .
It is obvious that human factors played an important role in this accident .
Though the original cause was technical , if anyone discovered the mistake and corrected it , it would n't have happened .
What 's more , regardless of what extent automation is achieved , the role of man can never be underestimated in production .
Furthermore , since nobody can avoid mistakes , applying psychology in design processes could reduce the probability of human errors , thus increasing the safety coefficient of a system .
Nevertheless , some hold the opinion that if technology improves enough , we could eliminate accidents without applying psychology in design processes .
As technology improves , it is true that the probability of accidents can be significantly reduced .
Considering nuclear technology , the methods used to control the reactors have been significantly improved .
However , all these improvements only reduce the severity of the consequences of the accident , and it does n't mean the probability of such accidents is reduced .
A study found that 92 % of all significant events in nuclear utilities in 1983-1984 were caused by people and of these only 8 % had been initiated by the control room operator ( Stanton , 1996 ) .
Hence the most efficient way to reinforce safety is by applying psychology to design processes .
Will psychology prevent accidents completely ?
Of course , this would not be possible .
The objective of applying engineering psychology is to adapt the equipment and the environment to people , based upon their psychological capacities and limitations .
And the result is making the production process safer but not necessarily totally prevent accidents .
As engineering psychology is applied more and more deeply in design processes , it will make the production , especially the highly complex socio-technical systems with hazardous characteristics , safer than before .
Could the use of psychology have prevented Chernobyl ?
On 26 April 1986 , a catastrophic disaster , which destroyed the city and killed 30 people in a few seconds , fell on Chernobyl .
Massive amounts of radioactive substances spread , and eventually caused approximately 270000 cancer cases and 93000 fatal cancers ( Greenpeace , 2006 ) .
Ever since the disaster occurred , the cause of the accident has been extensively looked into .
Most of the studies have shown that it was the carelessness of the operator and a large number of design errors which led to the disastrous explosion .
Therefore , a wide range of approaches has arisen to enhance safety in the engineering process , and psychology is among one of these approaches .
While opponents deny the capability of psychology to prevent accidents , proponents insist that psychology is applicable to enhancing the safety of a system .
Although some people perceive that psychology would not influence the engineering process much , I do believe that the use of psychology during the design process could have effectively prevented the accident .
Nuclear plants are complex systems , which involve the simultaneous operation of many systems .
Therefore , opponents claimed that psychology might not have been able to detect each of the errors from the complicated design process and the use of psychology would not have prevent the accident .
However , although engineering psychology may not have been able to detect all the errors , the methodology used throughout the process would definitely have pointed out some of the erroneous parts .
According to Noyes ( 1997 ) , the accident mostly occurred due to numerous errors , and elimination of each of the errors could effectively have prevented the accident .
For instance , the control rods used in the exploded Unit 4 reactor , which served to slow down the reactions , were made of boron carbide with graphite tips .
A study in 1983 , three years before this accident , had shown that graphite tips can increase the rate of reaction ( Jacques , 2000 ) .
Clearly , if engineering psychology had been applied , further research would have been carried out during the preparatory phase and the error could have been detected , and this accident may have been prevented .
Opponents perceived that the Chernobyl accident was mainly due to the insufficient knowledge of the designers and operators , and advanced technical knowledge could have been able to prevent the accident instead of the use of psychology .
However , the study of Jacques ( 2000 ) stated that it was the dictatorship of the Soviet Union , rather than technical incompetence , which brought about the Chernobyl accident .
In fact , the scientists in the Soviet Union were equipped with deep technical knowledge , but they were more motivated to produce nuclear weapons out of self interest .
Therefore , the neglect of safety eventually led to bad decisions during the design process .
On the other hand , engineering psychology , which comprises a 'decision gate ' in each design phase , would effectively have enhanced safety from the human point of view .
In fact , the Chernobyl accident arose from a chain of human errors .
Other than the political factor and the use of inappropriate rod materials , the incompetence of the operator , the unwise decision making during the test plan , and the deliberate violation against the procedure for safe operation account for this disaster ( Denton , 1997 ) .
In my opinion , the input of psychology at each stage would have been able to change the erroneous part of the design process and effectively enhanced the safety of the system .
To sum up , engineering psychology provides the means to detect human errors in each phase of the design process and even in the implementation phase .
These preventive acts can prevent the occurrence of a disaster .
Therefore , psychology in engineering is definitely required to promote safety throughout the design process , especially for hazardous systems such as nuclear plants .
With the modernization of the world , the consumption of energy has drastically increased .
There has been opposition which has been further research and development of the VHTR due to high costs , unsafe conditions and low efficiency of the VHTR .
However , I feel that despite these , we should still continue with the further development of the VHTR .
There are fears that the reactor may get overheated as it operates at very high temperatures .
However , with improvements in the machine design and materials used , the VHTR is now cooled by helium which is an inert gas .
The helium gas does not react readily with other gases , which makes it safe to use .
In addition , the material used to build the reactor is graphite which has a high melting point .
Graphite also has high heat capacity and thermal inertia , thus allowing it to withstand high temperatures .
There are skeptics who argue that the high start up cost , due to the materials of the reactor , make it not worthwhile to further research and develop the VHTR .
The aim of the government should be revised and other important needs such as the healthcare of citizens should be considered before building these reactors .
I agree that the start-up cost of VHTR is high as it costs about 114.9 billion US dollars to build .
However , the operating and maintenance costs are much lower as compared to the start up cost .
The fuel used in the VHTR produces a large amount of energy when burnt , thus reducing the amount of fuel burnt .
As the VHTR is able to produce two products , hydrogen and electricity , concurrently , it helps to reduce the cost of producing both products separately .
Critics also highlight the efficiency problems of the VHTR .
If the helium is insufficient , it will not be not possible for the VHTR to operate at its optimum temperature .
However , the VHTR still has a high efficiency rate .
It uses plutonium waste to run the reactor and thus helps to recycle waste products .
The high temperature produced by the reactor can also be used to split water up thermodynamically and thus help to save energy to produce additional energy .
Although helium is seen to be both a good and bad cooling agent .
Moreover , it has high efficiency and the reactor is safe to use .
Cost should not be an issue as it will eventually be reduced with the overhead costs .
Therefore , research and development on the VTHR should continue .
These technologies have many advantages , such as enhancing nuclear safety , minimizing the generation of nuclear waste and decreasing the risk of nuclear weapons proliferation ( Gen IV International Forum,2007 ) .
Although Generation IV nuclear energy systems have so many advantages and plans for four systems have been finalized ( Gen IV International Forum,2007 ) , public opposition questions whether further research and development are still needed for them .
However , and the Gen IV systems will definitely benefit most nations .
Firstly , opponents question the safe operation of the VHTR at over 1000 Celsius degrees under transient conditions .
However , they have failed to consider the inherent characteristic of a helium-cooled , graphite-moderated core which is designed for the VHTR .
The VHTR system takes advantage of the thermal inertia of the graphite and a special property of the helium coolant which is that helium has a single phase .
Because of the effect of graphite , it manages to maintain a high heat capacity and stability at the same time even at extremely high temperatures .
When it is used as the coolant , it hardly interacts with other materials ( { High temperature gas cool reactor technology development } [ HYPERLINK : http : //www.iaea.org/inisnkm/nkm/aws/htgr/fulltext/29026666.pdf ] , 1996 ) .
Therefore , the helium-cooled , graphite-moderated core is on the whole the best design and in this way the safety of the system is almost guaranteed .
Secondly , critics argue that the VHTR is too costly and it will ultimately be eliminated in the future due to economic factors , just like what happened to the HTGR or High-Temperature-Gas-Reactor in 1989 ( International Atomic Energy Agency , n.d ) .
However , even though the one-time capital input is high , the VHTR has low operating and maintenance cost ( Gen IV International Forum , 2007 ) .
From the economic perspective , low variable cost will finally lead to low average cost despite the fact that the fixed cost is quite high .
Moreover , the electricity generation of the VHTR system has an efficiency ratio of higher than 50 percent and it is much more efficient than the Generation III systems .
Such efficient electricity generation will outweigh the high cost of the engineering design and production of the system ( Jaeri , 2002 ) .
In addition , the abundant heat produced in the VHTR system raises the efficiency of hydrogen gas production to a significant level .
Hence , the high one-time economic investment does not seem to be a problem compared with the high efficiency and the significant side product of the VHTR system .
Thirdly , some people are concerned about whether the Generational IV Nuclear Energy System will become a privilege of the wealthy or technologically developed countries and enlarge the gap between the developed countries and the developing countries .
this concern is actually unfounded since most countries have reached the consensus that the development of Generation IV systems would be an international initiative rather than an independent investigation .
According to estimations , these systems will be available by 2030 in both developed countries and developing countries ( Argonne National Laboratory ) .
To sum up , even though there are concerns about the Generation IV VHTR system , such as the potential danger of the system , the high cost of the system and possible negative effects of the system , the advantages of the Generation IV VHTR system surpass its disadvantages .
The Generation IV VHTR system should be fully developed since the VHTR system intends to increase safety , efficiency and reliability as well as provide other benefits such as hydrogen production .
However , most people have never considered the question of how many years the current supplies of petroleum and coal can last .
Scientists have said that human beings can only use petroleum and coal for no more than one or two hundred years more .
Based on that condition , new energy , especially nuclear power , , for which we must change our attitude towards nuclear power .
Nowadays , many people still resist nuclear power because of its so-called danger , its waste and the fear of terrorists .
I can not deny that some tragedies have occurred during the exploration and development of nuclear power .
However I want to emphasize that nuclear power will still be our first choice and many people resist it only because of some misunderstanding about its history .
I suggest that we can use Supercritical-water-cooled reactors , which are efficient , safe and environmentally-friendly .
From the angle of safety , many people are afraid of the hypothesis that terrorists may attack the reactors because they are the best targets to create chaos and cause mass destruction .
Actually , the issue is being considered in the countries where these nuclear reactors are being built .
As the Pittsburgh Tribune Review January 18 , 2007 reported , the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission said that in the future , the design of nuclear power reactors , such as SWCR , will take into consideration avoiding to prevent attacks by terrorists .
In addition , according to a research group , concrete structure used in such reactors can withstand a deliberate crash by a military jet .
Furthermore , most countries in the world have regarded fighting terrorism as one of their main tasks in the future .
They will try their best to prevent terrorism and spare no effect to protect their nation from being attacked .
Therefore , terrorism should not become an obstacle in the development of nuclear reactors .
However , many people fear nuclear reactors because they are not assured of their safety .
People may be afraid that some accident may happen in such a tough environment .
However , nowadays , a nuclear reactor contains many safety features , such as automatic shutdown of the fission process by insertion of control rods , emergency water-cooling for the core in case of pipeline breakage , and a concrete containment shell which can help prevent accidents .
Last but not least , some people say that the heavy metals in nuclear wastes may cause a lot of environmental problems .
However , this new kind of reactor is quite environmentally-friendly .
What 's more , it also has a waste recycling system , which is a combination of two parts .
This recycling system makes it more environmentally-friendly than other reactors .
Thus , we need not worry about how to deal with the waste because of these two significant steps .
Nowadays , with the development of nuclear power , more and more problems have been solved by nuclear scientists and engineers .
, we can build solid reactors as well as emphasise anti-terrorism at the global level .
and drying the waste to reduce the emitting of waste from a reactor .
I think we already have enough reasons to make full use of nuclear power to benefit the whole world as well as our future generations .
People have been putting efforts to improve engineering designs to eliminate unexpected accidents .
Not surprisingly , psychology plays a crucial role in engineering design processes .
Engineering psychology can be understood as the study of human behaviors , as well as designing and building mechanical devices or artificial environments to improve human interaction with a system , and to satisfy anthropometric or psychological requirements so that people will use the devices ( Wickens & Kramer , 1985 ) .
Up till now , the most deadly aircraft accident in aviation history has been the Tenerife accident on March 27 , 1977 , with a death toll of 583 .
Basically , both human errors and system failure led to this tragedy .
Although there is not one definite cause for such accidents , the correct use of psychology in certain areas , including the design of the airport , the communication procedure and the training of manpower , may help to prevent similar disasters in the future .
Designers failed to consider that the airport needed to accommodate a large number of planes , resulting in parking congestion which was one of the reasons for the accident .
Otherwise , the Pan Am plane could have entered the first or the second taxi way .
Therefore , it would have never collided with the KLM plane .
Furthermore , located just close to cloud level , the airport area had a very special fog pattern .
However , designers actually did not install radars .
However , claimed that it was not economic to build a large airport in such a small place with such few people .
As Tenerife had been seeing more and more visitors , people should anticipate some contingencies , and a safe airport with the necessary facilities should have been ensured to anticipate such unscheduled landings .
Secondly , communication was also a serious problem in this accident .
Actually , the Air Traffic Controller ( ATC ) was using only one channel to communicate with two approaching airplanes at the same time .
The controllers did not consider that the same frequency made them unable to hear each other clearly , so that the ATC failed to get the information that the Pan Am was still on the run way .
To make things worse , as professional controllers , they should have used standardized terminologies for communication , but they actually did not .
Words such as " take off " should never have been used in an ATC clearance but they did .
The ambiguous language caused confusion such that the Pan Am pilots , the KLM pilots , and the ground controllers did not get the proper information .
Some people may argue that during those early years , having lowly educated air controllers was inevitable .
It was hard to find a Spaniard speaking English fluently .
However , people still need to consider communication as an important issue and try to find a precise and standard language for aviation communication .
Last but not least , the training of the captains and the crews also contributed to the accident in a sense .
The captain of the KLM was used to being a training captain , which means he conducted training flights more than regular line flights .
However , many operational problems only emerge during the actual flight .
Hence , when the captain encountered problems , he may not have kept calm and made the correct decision .
Though the accident can not be entirely attributed to the captain , he had the highest power and should have been experienced enough to seek safety for all the passengers .
Hence , both theoretical and operational training should be reinforced for all training captains and crews. .
On the other hand , there are also countries that are against this idea , such as Germany , which is withdrawing its nuclear programme ( BBC , 2009 ) .
The reason for opposing nuclear programmes is that nuclear accidents release harmful radiation that has adverse effects on humans and the environment .
This is seen in the nuclear accident at Three Mile Island in 1979 followed by the Chernobyl accident in 1986 , which have reinforced fears of nuclear power in the people .
In addition , many are concerned that nuclear reactors are prone to being used as weapons of mass destruction by terrorists and hostile countries .
Firstly , in terms of safety , the VHTR is said to be a relatively safe nuclear reactor because it includes a back-up emergency core cooling system .
However , the MSR operates under an even safer condition .
The method of cooling in the MSR is more efficient than the VHTR because if the MSR coolant salt overheats and overflows , the coolant salt will be transported to various storage tanks which are installed with passive decay heat cooling systems , so they are verified to be critically-safe .
Besides the storage tanks , freeze valves that will automatically open whenever they detect overheating of the salt are also installed .
Secondly , the overall performance of the MSR also surpasses the VHTR , making the MSR a better nuclear reactor .
Besides the varying sizes that an MSR could work in , it is also able to operate at two varying temperatures of 705 and 1000 ( Butler , 2004 ) .
This shows that at the same temperature , the MSR is at least 10 % more efficient than the VHTR .
Therefore , countries should invest in the MSR which is more efficient than the VHTR in terms of overall plant efficiency .
Last but not least , waste recycling in the MSR allows better usage of materials as well as ensures a lower cost of operation .
The system collects and processes the wastes according to their physical and chemical properties , and separates the residual fuel from the wastes .
This in turn reduces the volume of material disposed of since plutonium and uranium make up almost 97 % of the entire mass of fuel used in generating nuclear energy .
This will also lead to reduction in costs since capital spent on reactants are significantly reduced ( The National Academies Press , 1984 ) .
Scientists and engineers are now thinking of developing a new generation of nuclear reactors that can solve many problems such as green-house effects , the rising prices of energy and the safety of nuclear reactors .
In " Nuclear Power 's New Dawn " , Butler ( 2004 ) mentions six concepts of Generation IV ( GenIV ) reactors .
While some proponents totally support further research and development funding for this concept , others still doubt the benefits of the SCWR since there are many challenging problems in the R&D process .
It is often argued that the SCWR is rather safe in comparison with other generation IV reactor concepts because it operates at rather low temperatures , ranging from 510 to 550 Â° C ( Butler , 2004 ) .
Although this argument is true , high operating temperatures is not the only source of accidents in a reactor .
At such a level of pressure , the steel used in nuclear reactors is easily corroded by high temperature water .
Another safety problem comes from the very fast turbine speed of the SWCR ( about 3600 rpm , twice as fast as the existing Light Water Reactor ( LWR ) ) .
Therefore , we must stress the importance of finding suitable materials that are stress-resistant and anti-corrosive and develop a reliable auxiliary feed water system .
However , one disadvantage of the SWCR is that it , in fact , is the only concept among the GenIV reactors that does not produce hydrogen fuel .
The temperature needed to split hydrogen from water in a reactor is from 700 to 900 Â° C and even if the SCWR could produce hydrogen , separating it with liquid water would become a big problem .
Hydrogen fuel is considered the energy for the future since it is carbon-free , non-toxic , less of a fire risk and more highly efficient than petrol .
Furthermore , it should be noted that if most car owners switched to fully electric cars , many countries would need to double their electricity production ( Louis , 2009 ) .
Therefore , it would be better if we develop reactors that can generate hydrogen fuel rather than ones that can only generate electricity .
The SWCR is preferred to other GenIV concepts because of its simple design , which indicates that it will be cheaper and easier to develop and operate .
One example is the very-high-temperature reactor ( VHTR ) which can produce hydrogen fuel and which can be completed by 2020 ( the earliest delivery for the SCWR is 2025 ) .
Moreover , the estimated amount of money needed for R&D activities for the VHTR is about $ 670 m ( versus $ 870m for the SCWR ) .
Although the VHTR also has its own challenges in R&D , it is , besides the SCWR , highly interesting to the experts .
Although it can not be denied that SCWR is the most practical one among the six concepts of GenIV reactors , it is not the only choice .
Developing a new generation of nuclear reactor costs us not only a huge amount of money , but also a lot of time and manpower .
Therefore , we must consider carefully when choosing whether to develop the SCWR or other concepts .
The public is very concerned about the safe operation of nuclear reactors and there have been debates on whether the Generation IV nuclear reactor should be built or not .
Issues being discussed are the safety of operating the nuclear reactor as there have been catastrophic events in the past like the Three Mile Island and Chernobyl disasters ( Butler , 2004 ) .
The cost of building a nuclear reactor as it involves billions of dollars of taxpayers ' money .
These are the main factors why few nuclear reactors have been built in the past few decades in many countries and I agree that the Generation IV nuclear reactor should not be built .
Over the years , nuclear technology has improved and in principle , created the term 'meltdown proof ' reactors whereby the nuclear reactor can cool themselves down in the event of an accident with minimal impact or minimal,if any , human intervention ( Butler , 2004 ) .
Hence , the safety of the nuclear reactors has always been the main issue surrounding the building of nuclear power plants .
However , human error is a factor that decides whether the safety system in place works in the event of a failure ( Greenpeace ) .
Events that clearly show the effects of a nuclear meltdown are the Chernobyl disaster that resulted in 336,000 people being exposed to radioactive chemicals and being relocated .
The result of the explosion has been linked to many forms of cancer in Eastern Europe and Russia , as well as to the destruction of animals and plants .
Waste from the nuclear facility is another major issue .
Although the development and research of Generation IV reactors produces less nuclear waste , the main problem lies in getting rid of it rather than in storing it .
According to Andrew Blowers , a former member of the Committee for Radioactive Waste Management ( CoRWM ) , which advised the government , the nuclear waste does not decompose easily and will last for thousands if not millions of years ; thus , it will impose a burden on future generations .
cost has always been one of the biggest issues of building a nuclear reactor .
Unfortunately , no more than three of the six designs are likely to survive the feasibility testing phase and go on to become research prototypes , each costing at least US $ 1 billion or more to build and test ( Butler , 2004 ) , thus wasting taxpayers ' money .
To summarize why nuclear reactors should not be built , no nuclear reactor in the world is inherently safe as all operational reactors have inherent safety flaws which can not be eliminated by safety upgrading .
For example , highly radioactive spent fuel requires constant cooling .
There will always be nuclear waste regardless of the amount the development and research of Generation IV nuclear reactors can reduce .
Billions of dollars are being spent on building a nuclear reactor and not just a few million .
Furthermore , there is no guaranteed of building a successful nuclear reactor .
With emission of green house gases now soaring , nuclear energy , as a non-carbon dioxide source , is finding its way back on the table .
However , the huge cost and the potential danger prevent nuclear plants from being widely accepted .
Actually , GIF ( the Generation IV International Forum , a consortium of ten nations that is planning the nuclear reactors of tomorrow ) has already budgeted for R&D funding for the new generation of the Generation IV reactors ( Butler , 2004 ) .
Although there are some opposing voices against this funding , it is a wise decision to provide R&D funding for Generation IV reactors .
Opponents of R&D funding for generation IV reactors claim that nuclear plants are very dangerous ( Ashcroft , 2008 ) because of the radioactive wastes and the radioactive materials that escape from the reactors ( Ashcroft , 2008 ) .
However , these two disadvantages are not problems for the Generation IV reactors .
This is because all the six concepts of Generation IV reactors operate at a very high temperature ranging from 510 degrees C to 1000 degrees C and have a highly automatic circular system , so the radioactive waste can be minimized to a very safe level ( Butler , 2004 ) .
In addition , unlike what the public thinks , there are almost no radioactive materials escaping from the reactors except in an unexpected accident .
This is true for previous generations of reactors .
However , if the Generation IV reactors really work , ( Butler , 2004 ) .
As mentioned above , the new reactors operate at very high temperatures and have highly automatic cycle systems , so they are more efficient .
For instance , the VHTR ( very-high-temperature reactor , one of the six concepts of Generation IV reactors ) can produce fifty percent more electricity with the same amount of resources ( Butler , 2004 ) .
Therefore , the cost of the resources can be significantly reduced .
Furthermore , due to the highly automatic system , the capital spent on hiring experienced operators and building offsite monitoring systems can be reduced .
The final argument advanced by opponents is that this new generation of reactors will be more of a terrorist target , because they are more powerful ( Ashcroft , 2008 ) .
The reason is that all the six concepts of Generation IV reactors contain simplified safety features that no longer depend on sophisticated operators , which means that they can cool themselves if anything goes wrong in the whole process .
Therefore , any attempt to deliberately trigger an accident will be in vain .
It should be evident that arguments against providing R&D funding for Generation IV reactors are not valid .
Moreover , the simplified safety feature makes those new reactors less of a terrorist target .
Global warming and rising energy demands are redefining the concept of nuclear power .
The Generation IV International Forum ( GIF ) is a consortium of countries planning future nuclear reactors .
Very High Temperature Reactor ( VHTR ) , one of the Gen IV reactors , holds much potential .
To date , the nuclear industry has created a lot of problems ( safety of nuclear installations , nuclear waste , radioactive emissions and so on ) without a solution , and with the current growth rate , nuclear power would not be able to play an important role in future world energy production CITATION But04 \ l 1033 ( Butler , 2004 ) .Research and development funding for developing VHTR must thus be increased while addressing public concerns about safety and improving design to reduce costs and improve performance .
means that VHTR can produce 50 % more electricity from the same amount of fuel compared to existing reactors . In addition , it can be used to produce hydrogen which holds much potential as a fuel of the future .
However , reactors will need new coolants as ordinary water can not be used under typical pressurized conditions CITATION But04 \ l 1033 ( Butler , 2004 ) .
A large capital is required for the building of Generation IV nuclear reactors .
The Greenpeace report of 2005 says that the estimated costs for the development of the six Gen IV concepts are about US $ 6 billion CITATION Aus07 \ l 1033 ( Austrian Institute of Ecology , 2007 ) .
France intends to replace its ageing plants using a US $ 3.5 billion Generation Three reactors ( Butler , 2004 ) .
Better performance has to be weighed against high building and maintenance costs .
VHTR systems do not use waste recycling , thus reducing the risk of proliferation .
Public opinion is against the construction of nuclear reactors due to the partial reactor meltdown accident in 1979 at Three Mile Island , Pennsylvania and the 1986 accident at Chernobyl in Ukraine ( Butler , 2004 ) .
It is generally recognized that it is a practical impossibility to render civilian nuclear energy systems proliferation-proof CITATION Hir05 \ l 1033 ( Hirsch , Becker , Schneider & Froggatt , 2005 ) .
The development of Gen IV nuclear reactors is necessary to respond to the upcoming scarcity of fissile material , the issue of proliferation and the requirement for safe repositories for nuclear waste .
Research still has to be done to work on a better cooling system and material that can withstand very high temperatures ( Butler , 2004 ) .
Shortages in energy supply and insecurities caused due to rising oil prices and the threat of climate change clearly show the need for the development of nuclear power .
Nowadays , as the population of the world is increasing rapidly , humans are facing a severe food crisis .
One good way to solve this problem is to develop Genetically Modified Food .
Currently , because of the uncertain effects of Genetically Modified Food ( GMF ) , it has not been widely accepted .
However , I believe that GMF has a very bright future .
According to Whitman ( 2000 ) , the term GM foods is commonly used to refer to crop plants created for human or animal consumption using the latest molecular biology techniques , and such food has been modified in the laboratory to meet people 's demands .
GM foods have advantages over food from traditional plants .
So the amount of chemical substances used will be largely reduced .
In addition , we can increase crop yield by cultivating GM plants .
However , although GM food is not a new term to us , many people are still concerned about the consumption of GM food .
One major concern is whether GM food will do harm to human bodies .
As a result , the effects of GM food in human consumption are still relatively unknown .
Toxins and proteins produced by GM food may have unknown side effects if consumed over long periods of time ( Cardiosk 2008 ) .
People are afraid that GM plants may break the balance in nature .
They may transmit their special genes to other species or restrain other plants ' growth thereby causing disasters .
We need to solve these problems by enhancing the assessment of GM food .
most people are only worry about the uncertain effects of GM food .
GM foods are not like common drugs or chemicals ; they are more complex .
But if we can precisely evaluate the impacts of the GM foods on the human body and verify that they are healthy , people would accept them .
One of these assessment methods is to compare the GM foods and their original natural species .
Moreover , scientists have come up with a new method , in which they insert a special kind of gene into the plant cell to prevent the plant from breeding .
In conclusion , GM foods have not been fully developed , even until now .
Their impacts on human bodies and environments are not clear .
But in my point of view , it is just a matter of time .
Scientists will enhance the safety of GM food with new genetic and assessment technologies in the near future .
