Some people may question whether SWCR is good enough to be applied widely , especially in developing countries .
In the history , there have been cases such as the Chernobyl nuclear reactor explosion and the Three Mile Island accident , which were catastrophes caused by the misuse of nuclear power .
Furthermore , plants can not grow there in tens of years , and milk is not allowed to be produced there in over a hundred years .
With present science and technology level , nuclear power can be used by human beings for approximately 20 years .
To further broaden the use of nuclear power , the next generation of nucleargeneration IV is under discussion .
The concerns from the public have been a main obstacle for further advancement in nuclear research .
With the advent of the new generation of nuclear energy , people will make a difference in the utilization of energy .
That figure stands at 85 % in Sweden and the United Kingdom and 81 % in Japan .
However , in the United States the figure stands at 45 % , and it is now grappling with a controversial reform plan to provide universal healthcare coverage .
The benefits of economic growth would help to ensure the continuity of social benefits for the elderly , and by increasing the national income , there will be surplus to spend more money on the social needs of the nation .
For example , Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong has stated that businesses will get help with rental and wage bills .
There are differing views about health insurance to be subsidised from current budgetary surpluses , and about the Government financing more of its longer-term development expenditure by borrowing from its reserves so as to free up current revenues for social spending .
Social subsidies should not be expanded simply because there is currently a budget surplus .
Spending needs are growing in many areas , not forgetting social spending ,but the government budget is expected to be tight , therefore our challenge will be to manage the increase in social spending as our population ages , and to focus subsidies on those most in need .
At the same time , Government subsidies help to keep basic health care affordable MOH ( 2009 ) . As such , the government plays a significant role in providing health care services for public , but the government can only do this much .
Policies that favor income distribution towards capital will also raise the return on capital , which will enhance capital formation , and in turn raise labor productivity and the national income .
( author,year ) . As opposed to an ageing population , Singapore will have a sector of un-employed people without families ,who are either single or divorced , with perfectly unsound financial management and diagnosed with chronic illness .
When they reach a tenable age for retirement , they will be unable to pay for their medical bills since they do not have adequate savings .
As the population ages , the importance of public spending on the aged with regards to healthcare should be managed effectively without having to over spend or iinadequately provide .
Social subsidiaries should be evaluated thus reducing unnecessary spending by allowing the Government to finance more of its longer-term development expenditure which in turn brings about greater economic growth .
With economic growth , the financial burden will be lessened allowing more money for spending on social areas .
One of the challenges that needs to be addressed will be the aging population on the economy .
As reported , " Singapore has one of the fastest aging populations in the world , with over 65-year-olds ,estimated by 2030 , to represent 23 % of the population , the second highest percentage in Asia lagging behind only Japan .
" ( Wijaya , 2009 ) With the aging population occupying one quarter of the population , public spending should not be limited on the aged .
Higher life expectancy of the population is foreseen with the literate population getting healthier together current advancements in medical technology .
Long-term care and health costs are examples of welfare expenditure .
" ( Fernandez , 1994 ) More funding will be essential as the demand for health care increases .
This means that the older population should continue to work if they are willing .
Extending the retirement age reduces expenditure to provide for the aged .
Unsound financial management and little education are also some aspects that may result in elderly people depending on the government .
From research , it is reflected that 9 % of the population in Singapore are not living with children or a spouse .
Public assistance is needed especially for families who rely on voluntary organizations and self -help groups .
In Singapore , large subsidies are given in three core areas .
These are mainly health , education , and housing .
Taking care of the population 's needs brings about the country 's development .
" ( Fernandez , 1994 ) With a rapidly aging workforce , it is not feasible to reduce spending on the aged and divert it to other areas of the country 's development .
From a financial point of view , the government still makes it a point to promote self-reliance and individual savings within the nation .
This is to ensure that the elderly will have enough money and be ready for old age .
An example is the mandatory saving scheme : Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) .
With this practice , public spending on the aged .
In conclusion , it is not wise to limit public spending on the age given the fact that reliance on government support is necessary to certain groups of the elderly .
With longer life expectancy and declining birth rates , elderly dependency on the young should be shared with the government .
As a result this may affect the country 's development when the welfare of the young working population is taken into consideration .
Singapore in this aspect has done a good job by providing minimal ,yet sufficient , welfare benefits to the population .
In any part of a nation 's economy , well balanced expenditure and earnings is sought .
Hence limitation on public spending on the aged should not be implemented given the fact that the aged makes up a quarter of the population .
The Singapore government has been aware of the potential problems with regards to its ageing society since the 1980s ( Mehta ) .
Various committees , like the Committee on the Problems of the Aged and the National Council on Family and Aged ( NACFA ) , were formed over the years to address the challenges of an ageing population .
In recent years two more high-level committees , the Committee on Ageing Issues ( CAI ) and the Ministerial Committee on Aging ( MCA ) , were formed to spearhead the vision of successful ageing in Singapore ( MCYS , 2008 ) .
Therefore in terms of , this essay will focus on the public policies aspect of the ageing population .
The committees built on the the works of previous committees , with the belief that policies should allow the elderly to benefit in terms of housing , employability , financial security , healthcare , eldercare and active aging ( MCYS , 2006 ) .
In terms of housing , studio apartments ( SA ) have been built with elderly friendly features like non-slip tiles , smoke detectors and emergency alarms .
These housings cater for the elderly , especially for old people living alone or on low incomes , , providing them with a range of housing options depending on their ideal living arrangement .
Furthermore , buyers are allowed to utilize their Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) to purchase a home at an affordable , subsidised price ( MCYS , 2006 ) . Moreover , family members of the elderly benefit from schemes like Married Child Priority , when they choose accommodation with , or near their parents .
This will help to boost the economy and .
Policies for employability and financial security , like the Workfare Income Supplement ( WIS ) scheme for older low-wage workers , were introduced in 2007 .
Under the WIS scheme , the elderly are given supplements apart from the CPF contributions made in their by employer .
These policies will increase the older workers chances of continuing their employability and building up their retirement savings ( MCYS , 2008 ) .
The Eldershield scheme was improved in 2007 to make step-down care services affordable to the elderly , in particular the low wage elders ( MCYS , 2008 ) .
With this scheme , the elderly are able to afford the services which are specially created for them .
Furthermore the elderlyelderly people can interact with other people at these centres , thus they will not feel lonely .
A new scheme , Wellness Programme was created recently to promote healthy lifestyles and social networking for citizens , especially the elderly ( PMO , 2009 ) .
Thus , with a healthy body and mind , the elderlyelderly people are able to continue to contribute to society which in return will benefit the nation .
The Council for Third Age ( C3A ) was formed under MCA , to further promote active ageing through community-based projects ( MCYS , 2006 ) .
Their major events to create public awareness are the Senior Citizens ' Week and Active Ageing Festival .
In conjunction with the annual event , C3A created a Senior Citizens award to honour role models and active senior citizens in the community ( MCYS , 2006 ) .
Judging by the policies made for the elderly it is clear that the government has invested a large sum of money in them .
On the other hand , instead of trying to change what can not be changed like personal health and family upbringing , there should be alternative ways to solve this problem .
The Education System can be an area worth investing in .
Children should be taught the importance of filial piety and a healthy lifestyle .
If these moral values are cultivated in the system from young , there will not be a need to create schemes like the Maintenance of Parents Act .
However , there are bound to be minorities who will think otherwise .
The government has been trying to ease the process through implementing policies .
Citizens should do their part too .
Singapore 's only resource is its people , thus a collective effort from each and every citizen will make a vast difference .
To prepare for the growing demand of the ageing population , more government funding is required for providing better infrastructure and amenities for the elderly .
Thus , public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development , which in turn can help to solve the problems of the aging population .
Economic growth is seen as the key to resolving issues relating to an aging population .
With economic growth , the average income will increase , and thus ,
Furthermore , with the increased income , the government can impose more tax and use it to introduce more or to continue existing welfare programs for the elderly .
The Lewin Group and The Nelson A. Rockefeller Institute of Government ( July , 2004 ) found that states of less fiscal capacity on average , spent less on social welfare programs than states with higher per capita incomes .
Thus , public spending should be channelled to promoting economic growth which can help to continue or enhance welfare programs .
Next , public spending should be channelled to the education sector , to allow more people to get the chance to go to school , to improve the standard of education , and to encourage research and development at tertiary levels and beyond .
In addition , as the standard of education increases , and more research and development is conducted , the likelihood of technological advancement is higher .
Advancements in technology can improve the healthcare of the elderly , as more or better treatments for illnesses due to old aged are discovered .
Thus , public spending should be diverted to the education sector and to promoting research and development , which can improve the welfare of the elderly in both the long and short run .
However , new or improved treatments arising from advancements in technology will incur higher health care costs .
This is simply due to fact that setting a limit that is too low may result in some elderly not receiving adequate medical care and home care , and setting a limit that is too high may result in an increased burden on government policies and on the working population in society .
Thus , the government needs to prevent health care costs from escalatng too much and also to decide how much funding should be set aside for the elderly .
Elderly people people who are financially strapped and/or have no spouse or intermediate family members to take care of them , should be taken care of by the government .
The government should then carefully decide the necessary healthcare spending that has to be supported by the public sector , as excessive spending or spending that exceeds the means of the government will lead to the future generation having to pay higher tax , as the successor government is left with huge bill ( Tan Ho , 2008 ) .
In Singapore , the government finances health carehrough a combination of taxation and private or national insurance schemes to provide affordable healthcare to its people ( Lim , 2001 ) . However , with limited resources , the government needs to allocate resources in such a way , so that development in one area will not be at the cost of another .
Thus , public spending on the aged should be limited , so that funds can be used for other developments which can help solve some of the some of the issues that accompany an an aging population .
It also contributes to providing applicable solutions to ease the greying population which is gradually growing in society .
Therefore , it can be said that research and development is the pathway to relieve the ageing process .
A need for expanding social care services for the elderly as well .
In dealing with an ageing population , research and development has pushed countries to move forward in a new paradigm of ageing .
It is a process for utilizing opportunities in health , to enhance the quality of life of ageing citizens .
One of the strategies is to encourage longer employment for citizens and lower barriers for the employment of elderly people .
Based on research , when people work longer , it can offset increasing costs for public pensions due to the
Those who remain engaged in activities involving multiple tasks , requiring communication , interaction and organization , and those who continue learning , and constantly challenge their brains , earn the greatest protection ( Wall Street Journal , 2008 ) .
Hence , is not susceptible to developing old age illnesses and disabilities .
As previously mentioned , an ageing population has a high demand for medications and social care services .
Private practices of healthcare professionals , social care services and organizations for citizens also correspond to the aged .
In Singapore , Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong that the health care system will be restructured for the ageing population .
For instance , he said one key step is to link up acute hospitals with community ones , where patients can receive treatment at the acute hospital , and then recuperate at the community hospital ( Channel NewsAsia , 2009 ) .
However , some policies may not only bring positivity .
The ageing population is often associated with poor health
It will also be harder for to acquire new skills that can benefit industry .
Besides , some older workers cost more than younger workers due to the seniority payment system .
As a consequence , older workers are considered both vulnerable for dismissal , or to be targeted by companies wishing to make workforce reductions . They are also less able to find new jobs should they loose their current work ( Bernard Casey , 1998 ) .
Research and development is relatively important in determining the direction of an ageing population .
Active ageing ,as the new paradigm of ageing , is the key to overcoming healthcare challenges and other problems arising with the ageing population .
Lastly , it is essential for there to be continuity in research and development to be able to create policies that suit the the needs of the elderly .
Ageing is a process that all humans have to go through , but the problems that come along with it are unavoidable .
Looking specifically at the case of Singapore : current research and development R&D and policies such as the employment policies , the public pensions programs and the health care and community development prepared for the aged have greatly helped in easing the problems posed by the ageing process .
Thus , employment policies have made the problems associated with the ageing process negligible .
Another method that the Singapore government has adopted to deal with the ageing process is the use of public pensions programs , more familiar to Singaporeans by the name of Central Provident Fund ( CPF ) .
The CPF policy has seen tremendous success in providing people with sufficient income for future use , and it certainly has lessened the impact that the ageing process has brought about .
And finally , the state has also implemented policies on health care and community development , such as health care insurance schemes and improving facilities and infrastructure for the elderly .
Health care insurance schemes such as the Medisave , Medishield and Eldershield , allows Singaporeans to place aside part of his/her own income for health care needs in the future .
This greatly encourages independence among the elderly in the future , as well as personal responsibility .
Research and Development has also allowed the state to improve public infrastructure , such as the creation of wheelchair-accessible buses , upgrading houses with lifts that access every storey , and the development of retirement housing .
An awareness of more elderly-friendly programs and facilities has also been done through advertisements .
However successful these policies may turn out to be , there are still arguments as to whether these policies are truly effective , and how they may actually bring about other sets of problems .
In providing employment for the elderly , its effects may be reduced
The CPF policy may provide cover for the elderly , but they will not be able to use it wisely if the state does not provide useful information or advice for its usage .
Therefore , the abovementioned policies will not be as effective as when they are implemented on their own ; They needs to supplement each other for it to work .
Certainly , without the policies undertaken by the state , the graying population will bring about problems both in the economy and at home .
Thus , policies such as the employment policies , the social security savings plan and health care and community development , have helped to ease the ageing process by allowing the elderly to enjoy a more vibrant and active life in both social and economical aspects .
These policies are also most effective when working in tandem , whereas on their own , their impact is limited .
The Singapore government has done well in its foresight of the problems regarding the ageing process , but more can be done to achieve better integration between the private and public spheres .
As for now , its policies have certainly kept the ageing process a much more manageable one .
The problem of the increasing aging population has become a major issue now .
( " Singapore is aging fast " , 2004 ) This situation brings various consequences , such as decreasing productivity and the health problems of the elderly .
Actions such as building more hospitals and upgrading home care should not be the most important tasks
With the current economic crisis , the government should be much more concerned about the development of the country .
Thus , limiting spending on the elderly and using the money on others areas , like the economy and technology , to develop the country .
( Shandre M. Thangavelu , 2008 ) As a result , the government should put effort into reforming the country 's economy .
After reforming the economy , the condition of the country can remain the same as before
Then , people can get their own occupation and have a stable income for living .
On the other hand , if the economy crisis becomes more serious , more people will lose their jobs .
Once they have difficulty earning money , they might rob , steal , kidnap , or kill somebody to get money and crime will increase .
Moreover , together with the development of the economy , productivity will also rise .
The government can also increase taxes so that money could be used to maintain welfare programs continuously .
This is why developing the economy is more important and more beneficial .
Besides , developments in technology are more essential when compared with the expenditure to be spent on the elderly .
With more funds from the government , scientists can do more research
From this research , scientists can discover new methods and also invent more products that could bring benefits to society. .
For example , advancements in the medical field can save more people 's lives .
Inventing new machines or having new medical methods to cure diseases not just saves more people and decreases the deaths , it can also help to prolong one 's lifespan .
Thus , the elderly can stay longer with a healthy body , .
In fact , the aging populations who do not have families or who have a disability really need help from others .
When they are sick , because they do not have families or have a disability , they can not take care of themselves .
Thus , the welfare programs will be vital for them .
But this does not mean that the public should spend a lot on helping them .
One of the reasons is that people without families and people with disabilities are just the minority The majority of the elderly have their own families and they will take care of their elderly .
Furthermore , because Singapore is a country influenced by the Confucius way of thinking which emphasizes filial piety , the young generation know their obligation to take care of the elderly .
Thus , limiting public spending on the aging population and diverting the money into other areas of the development of country is one possible solution. .
In conclusion , public spending on the aging population should be limited and diverted to the economy and the technological development of the country .
Economic development can stabilize the condition of the country , increase productivity and government income which could then be used for the elderly , Technological development can also bring people healthier bodies .
Thus , diverting money to other areas of the country 's development will not just solve the problems of the aging population , but will also bring every person in the country a lot of benefit .
To a large extent current policies have helped to ease the aging process .
In terms of research this report will focus on the poor and dependent segment of the aging population who require housing and accessible infrastructure .
One of the basic elements of the well-being of an elderly person is housing
Single people and lonely elderly who do not have any children of their own often stay with their next-of-kin .
The Studio apartments are built small to cater to the independent living of elderly .
Voluntary welfare organizations ( VWOs ) are providing exclusive support services for the occupants ( Committee on Aging Issue [ CAI ] , 2006 ) .
This is also an alternative to the minority of the elderly who prefer to live independently and not burden their child .
Old age is usually associated with physical changes and limitations .
As they start to age , their physical capability starts to reduce and change .
Mobility , which is one of the activities of daily living ( U.S. Department of Health and Human Services , 1984 ) , is hindered by this change of physical capability .
The Housing Development Board has helped to design a more elderly friendly environment through the Project LIFE ( Project to Improve the Living Conditions of the Elderly , HDB , 2005 ) .
For example , housing flats with a high concentration of poor elderly persons have been upgraded with new fixtures and fittings , features such as modified lifts on every level , support hand grips in toilets , tap levers , non-slip floor tiles , and an alarm system .
Such installation of elderly-friendly features enhances the mobility of older residents .
These improvements are fully funded by the government .
can be more assured of the of the elderly
The elderly are encouraged to integrate into the community and be self- dependent ( CAI , 2006 ) .
Being part of the community creates a sense of belonging for the elderly promotes better mental health .
According to the Committee of Aging Issue , making Singapore an " Accessible City " ( CAI , 2006 ) would be the first step to reaching outward to the community .
Creating a barrier free environment would give the elderly person freedom of movement around the community .
This allows the elderly person to integrate into a wider community and lead an active life .
According to the Code of Barrier-Free Accessibility ( BCA , 2002 ) , a barrier-free environment could be created by upgrading the roads and infrastructure between housing and buildings .
The Code of Barrier-Free Accessibility ( BCA , 2002 ) adheres to the conditions of being elderly friendly and barrier-free .
The public transport operators have made adjustments to all the new public buses with low floor step-free and wheelchair-accessibility to allow everyone to use the public transportation system .
The government has also helped to defray the additional cost involved .
Singapore ,being a small country with only 682.7 sq km ( CIA World Factbook , 2009 ) , faces the problems of land scarcity .
There is insufficient land for the construction of basic residential housing , let alone these types of additional housing and infrastructure that caters to the elderly .
Building additional housing and infrastructure would cost a huge amount of money .
These funds come from the tax payer .
Are there sufficient funds left for other areas of national development ?
This would lead to more constraints and limitations rather than solving the issues of an an aging population .
The policies mentioned above have helped to ease the aging process .
The developments of housing and infrastructure have helped to meet elderly people 's physical , social and recreational needs , as well as to facilitate their integration into the community .
However , all these practices should be done with the understanding of the limitations and constraints .
Policy and development should be made at an economical level , not too extravagant to enhance people 's lives , but to improve the necessary condition of the elderly .
Senior citizens have contributed a lot to making what people enjoy today .
From fighting for independence , to paving the way for our generation today to live in comfort , their services are immeasurable .
It is therefore every citizen 's duty to pay back what they have inherited from them .
Thus , public spending has always included spending on elderly .
Unfortunately , there are so many there is public outcry by the younger generations who claim that public spending on the elderly should be limited for the sake of the country 's development .
However , this essay will argue that public spending on the aged should not be limited because not only the elderly will get the benefit from the spending , but indirectly , society will also benefit .
The main reason is that spending on the elderly will stimulate the economy .
This is because limiting public spending on elderly only transfers the responsibility to their family .
Their family has to bear larger financial responsibility to take care of the elderly .
Try to imagine how heavy the burden is for a family to take care of two elderly , or even more .
So , it will be an extra burden to the family and they will have less to spend on other areas such as entertainment .
On the other hand , if there is no limitation on public spending on the elderly , it will definitely reduce the burden for their family and help economic growth .
This leads to another point , which is that the spending of elderly will reduce
As an illustration , the rising cost of health spending will make the burden for the young become heavier and heavier .
Most of the family will not able to afford this and may feel stressed of depressed .
As a result , conflict and argument among family members may occur .
Besides , many other issues such as education and bank loans will become family problems .
On top of that , families and local communities will have to deal with that by conducting various activities such as family days and talks , and the government will have to bear the cost .
Obviously , instead of spending on community activities , why not spend on elderly and build up a good image ?
Another bane of contention is that public spending on education can be reduced .
This is because when there is no limitation on public spending on the elderly
When people less on the elderly , they are able to invest more in their children 's future education by saving for education fees of the education scheme .
Therefore , children today will not face financial problems regarding their education in the future .
Indirectly , the government can spend less to help people in higher education but can still built an intellectual society .
It is clear that the benefits are not only distributed amongst the elderly but also amongst the younger generations .
Thus , not limiting public spending on the elderly , kills two birds with one stone .
Basing the argument on the fact that public spending on aged should not be limited , it is important not to neglect other areas of the country 's development .
Although the tendency is for public spending to be increased , especially for the elderly , it does n't mean that other areas of the country 's development have been taken for granted .
The government should plan their public spending carefully , so that they will not face the problem that they can not afford education , security and economics .
This will be a fairer system instead of limiting public spending on elderly .
The elderly have contributed their whole journey in life for the nation and family so that people today are able to enjoy the fruit .
At the time as enjoying the fruits of their labor , it is important to reflect back on their effort and appreciate it .
In short it is actually payback time .
Senior citizens deservedly need their rest time to bask in the glory of bringing up their children successfully .
So should public spending on the aged really be limited ?
A Reasonable Expenditure on the Elderly Aging population , defined as , " a shift in the distribution of a country 's population towards greater ages ( Wikipedia , 2009 ) , " began to take place in every country and region across the world during the last century .
Due to the large population of elderly , the aging issue is raising more and more concerns in society .
One of the concerns is that governments need to spend more on the elderly to ensure their physical living standard as well as their psychological well being .
However , it has been proposed that such actions can not fully solve the problems .
Therefore , the governments should invest in other areas so that the development of the country will ultimately resolve the aging problems .
Improved will benefit the since technological advancements can enhance productivity , and the economic growth will ensure the continuation of the welfare program .
First and foremost , the progress of technology increases the country 's income so that the country can take better care of the elderly .
History has shown the extraordinary benefits brought about by technology .
In the Industrial Revolution , the arrival of sophisticated machinery " mark [ ed ] the transition from a stable agricultural [ society ] to a modern industrial society ( source,year ) " .
In recent years , computers have been used in every aspect production , ranging from mass production to
The increase in efficiency more revenue to the country and therefore the government can spare more money for the elderly .
Moreover , positive economic growth can ensure the continuation of welfare programs .
The government , together with some private organizations , is one major sponsor for the welfare program .
Generally speaking , the government will spend a certain percentage of its annual income on the welfare .
However , such a large proportional expense can only be achieved under the condition of a stable economic environment .
The Act mainly targets at cutting federal tax , providing benefits for the unemployed and increasing spending on education , health care , and infrastructure .
The total investment on the Act is about $ 787 billion dollars ( Wikipedia , 2009 ) , which make up a large proportion of the total income .
Therefore , ,
Although the government should invest its expenditure on the country 's development , it does not mean that the government should cut pension payments .
Unlike traditional Asian families which play a key role in taking care of the old , most western families have a looser connection among their family members .
The elderly , in most cases , live separately from their descendants .
Besides , some old single women have a very low income to support their life .
Hence , not only the family but also the government should bear the responsibility of taking care of the old .
The government needs to spend a reasonable amount of money on pensions and elderly facilities .
To sum up , the government should control the expenditure on pension costs and make more of an effort to develop the country economically .
Many people agree with the idea that public spending on the aged should be limited so that money can be diverted to other areas of the country 's development .
It is undeniable that society is aging , and there will be increased needs for more healthcare , pensions , homes , and other social welfare considerations for the elderly .
Addressing other issues that contribute to a country 's development such as economic growth , education and the military is just as important .
An important issue that affects a country 's development is economic growth .
According to a sample of OECD ( Organization for Economic Co- operation and Development ) countries , which consists of 30 large economies , One percent a year increase in output growth over the next 50 years might only just ease the increase level .
Thus , substantial increases in economic growth would be needed to offset the increased costs of aging ( Visco , 2008 ) .
Education in Singapore aims to shape citizens to be " responsible to family and country , " and to " have courage and conviction in facing adversity . " It also aims to shape the potential leaders to be " committed to improving society " and " be able to forge breakthroughs in a knowledge-based economy ( Ministry of Education , 2009 ) . "
Within the 12 pillars of competitiveness , education takes up 2 pillars , health and primary education and higher education and training , in determining the country 's economic competitiveness ( Schwab , 2009 ) .
An educated and skilled workforce contributes to the knowledge-based economy .
Studies link education to economic growth as it contributes to improving productivity which leads to higher income and improved economic growth ( The World Bank , 2009 ) .
Education also reduces crime , and promotes equality , justice and intercultural understanding ( The World Bank , 2009 ) .
It is very important that Singapore should maintain its education system to ensure the political and social stability as well as the economic prosperity of the country in the future .This is also of great importance to the country 's development and to its aging society .
Singapore should also realise that youths are treasured assets in aging societies .
Hence defence and military strategies should be carefully thought out to prevent the loss of lives .
Singapore should look at more substitutions
The military could also look at offering immigrants citizenship in return for service , as well as hiring freelance mercenaries from foreign countries ( Jackson , Howe , Strauss , Nakashima , 2008 ) .
Given the dropping birthrate , Singapore should take greater care of her young men and at the same time , being a small country , she must be able to protect herself .
Hence the military is one important issue that the country should also look at and invest in .
However , it should be understood that not all elderly have families or are able to take care of themselves .
Hence countries should have a margin drawn according to the number of people who really need help from the government before setting the limit for public spending on the elderly to ensure that they are taken care of .
Singapore could set an age limit and look into the cases of each elderly person who might need the help from the government .
Funds should only be given to the elderly if their medishield and medisave are used up , and by judging each case individually , an appropriate amount can be given to the elderly .
There are many that make up a socially and politically stable country .
Instead of merely focusing on public spending for the aged , we should also look at a broader base of challenges that an aging society will bring to us .
Singapore should give equal or more attention to economic growth to solve the aging society ,
Only with balanced , wise and well-planned and governed policies can there be a prosperous and strong nation .
Fast aging populations have increasingly become a serious problem especially for many developed countries .
One of the many causes of a fast aging population is that many people choose to have very few or even no children due to factors such as the high cost of .
Childcare costs in Singapore average $ 670 a month .
Hence , it has been reflected in official statistics , that the replacement rate in Singapore was only 1.29 last year , way below the 2.1 replacement rate for a population to maintain its current size in the long term ( Li X .
This may include people with serious health problems who are often unemployed or unfit to work .
Therefore , these people usually do not have any income
In fact , some of them might even be receiving financial aid from the government .
In addition , older people also tend to have especially during a recession .
For example in New York , workers ages 45 and over actually form a disproportionate share of the hard-luck recession category , the long-term unemployed ( Michael , 2009 ) .
The financial problem faced by these unemployed is also worsened by the high cost of living in developed countries .
For example , in Singapore , the high cost of living is actually caused by spending on necessities like financial products and transportation ( Tan , 2008 ) .
Hence , with such a high cost of living , the income of these elderly is just enough to feed themselves .
Therefore , public pensions and government incentives will be a vital source of money to support the elderly that are among those without savings .
It is important for society to show its appreciation for the contribution made by the elderly .
" The elderly , in their younger days , have made many important contributions to society .
As pioneers who arrived in a relatively unknown Singapore , the elderly toiled and contributed to its success today .
Since the majority of the older people believed that the government should provide for them as they are at their most vulnerable ( Shanas , 1980 ) , the reduction in public spending on them will set up a framework for criticism against the government show no appreciation for the sweat and toil that they have willingly given .
Every individual should try to play their part in dealing with the problems of an aging population .
Therefore , other strategies should also be introduced to cope with the problem of an aging population .
For example , the better-off should try to support their own elderly parents through ways such as giving them a monthly allowance etc. Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong of Singapore also made a National Day Rally Speech this year to stress filial obligation for parent maintenance .
In addition , the money spent on the country 's development in the area of education and economy can also help to solve the problems of an aging population .
In conclusion , it will definitely be better if public spending on the aged is not limited
However , when making decisions on government spending , the government should also take into consideration the existence of other problems and the need to improve other areas of the country .
The majority of the population is still the young who are now sweating and toiling for the country , just like the aged did in the past .
Hence the government should also divert some of its resources to improving the lives of the aged for example by providing subsidies for having children which not only reduces the cost of having a child but also encourages people to have more children , thus increasing the replacement rate .
On the other hand , strategies such as means-testing , currently adopted by the Australian Government , should also be implemented in other affected countries , to ensure that all public spending is necessary ( Peter G. Peterson ) .
Ageing populations are a fact
It is foremost a consequence of the " baby boom " - the rapid increase in birth rates and then its decline after the Second World War . [ 1 ] This period of increased fertility lasted for thirty years and the number of people born in this era was unusually large .
Such demographic changes might bring about severe consequences , most importantly national budgets might be under pressure as a growing number of elderly persons are supported by fewer younger persons .
The debate is now whether the nation state should limit its public spending so that the saved resources can be utilized on other areas of the country 's development .
This essay will strongly argue that yes , the state should indeed limit its spending and focus more on economic growth so as to not to discriminate against the elderly , but rather to aid them in a more fruitful way which is beneficial for both generations .
Economic growth has a " trickle down " effect and accompanies numerous positive externalities which helps the old in more efficient ways than continuous increases in healthcare spending which restrains GDP growth .
The first and foremost positive consequence of economic growth is that it will not only ensure the continuation of the current social welfare programme , but will also increase the total spending on such programmes in real terms .
For instance , if real GDP of a country increases by 3 % , and the spending on welfare programmes is pegged at 2 % of real GDP , then the real spending in such projects will also increase by 2 % .
However , it must also be noted that
In terms of an economic downturn , such policy can actually reduce spending on the ageing population and healthcare to a great extent .
To counter this , the government could actually set down some minimum spending regardless of the economic conditions .
The government could establish a bottom line stating how much to spend , on what aspects of healthcare to spend money on , , and how much of a particular facility an individual could use and to what extent .
For instance , free personal care , such as the washing and dressing of elderly people costs Britain an additional forty million pounds which caused its government to adopt a policy similar to the above .
Another advantage of economic growth is that it raises the real income of people .
As a result , government increases or decreases in taxes could benefit the ageing population .
Since there is economic growth , the government would have more resources and hence require less taxes , and as a consequence a family would be able to increase its spending on its older members .
On the other hand , the state could also receive more taxes , now that people have increased income , and use the money for further betterment of the healthcare system .
To top things off , economic growth would allow an increase in spending in R&D so the medical facilities would be more technologically advanced and be cheaper to produce due to superior technology . Therefore , services from such facilities would become cheaper and hence spending overall would fall .
The immediate effect of limiting spending will cause a rise is societal costs and will make individuals and families responsible .
The societal costs might end up getting shifted back to the public sector .3 Such policies might hurt members of societies who do not have immediate family ties or members with unsound financial management .
Moreover there are also problems of setting limits .
Is the limit set at the right one ?
However these are short term problems , in the long run society would benefit as a whole .
Transitions would be easier if society is better prepared .
Since it is evident that in the long run economic growth allows flexibility , meaning that it does not burden the younger generation and pressurizes the national budget while taking good care of the older generation , it is mandatory that society starts focusing more on the economic growth so that everybody wins in the long run .
These developments have also raised concerns about whether a carrier of a known genetic risk has the duty to inform his relatives about his genetic test results .
Carriers will not be diagnosed with the disease but can pass on the alteration to their children .
On the other hand , it is more logical to believe that carriers have the duty to inform their relatives regarding their tests results so that their relatives can make informed choices related to their genes .
Hence , carriers of known genetic risks should be compelled to reveal their genetic test results to their relatives .
critics perceive that .
Sociologists note that relatives of carriers of known genetic risks may be denied health insurance policies or be made to pay higher premiums since they are at higher risk of developing the disease ( Health Plan One , n.d. ) .
This is because insurance companies being mostly profit-orientated would predict any possible added costs and take pre-emptive measures to avoid these costs .
One reason for this could be that employers may have the misguided belief that they have to spend more in order to ensure the working environment is safe for these employees .
The consideration of extended medical leave that these employees may take in future may deter the employers from engaging their services for fear of loss in efficiency at work and trouble in finding replacements .
As such , companies will tend not to employ individuals who have a medical history of genetic diseases .
Paddock ( 2008 ) asserted that the enactment of laws such as the Genetic Information Non-discrimination Act 2008 in the United States would prohibit insurance companies from rejecting clients due to genetic information and forbid companies from using genetic information for hiring decisions for individuals .
Moreover , a mathematical model to work out the mortality for individuals associated with higher risks of illnesses such as Hungtinton 's disease will guide insurance companies to formulate reasonable levels of premiums ( Watts , 1999 ) .
Hence , genetic information will not be used against family members who apply for an insurance policy or a job .
detractors argue that the genetic information of carriers will cause unnecessary worry for their family members , especially in the case of multi- factorial diseases .
Medical professionals contend that these family members may experience psychological effects such as fear , anxiety and depression , which would affect their lifestyle ( Yap , 2005 ) .
They note that multi-factorial diseases such as coronary heart diseases may occur in isolation , with affected children born to unaffected parents .
Psychologists assert that some family members can consult genetic counsellors about their risk of contracting the disease , and hence overcome their fears ( Adams , 2003 ) .
This measure is usually recommended for multi-factorial diseases as there is a higher possibility of uncertainty in one 's health .
Indeed , carriers of a known genetic risk have the duty to inform their relatives as it would aid their relatives in decision making .
However , such information would encourage them to perform the disease testing in which genetic results may allow them to make informed decisions especially during family planning .
With the acquisition of genetic test results , couples may consider adopting a child instead of conceiving one .
In addition , couples could be mentally prepared for their child 's future as .
In all , carriers have the obligation to inform their family members of their genetic test results since the advantages clearly outweigh the disadvantages .
Genetic testing is the study of a person 's genes , chromosomes and proteins to determine whether the person is prone to a certain kind of disease and whether the person is a carrier or not ( Cancer.net , 2009 ) .
When a person is found to be a carrier though genetic testing , the dilemma arises as to whether the carrier should tell his or her relatives about the result as the carrier will not get the disease but the carrier can pass the disease to his or her children ( Frequently Asked Questions About Genetic Testing , 2009 ) .
Secondly , the carrier can get moral support from his or her family members despite the possibility that the carrier might face discrimination upon disclosing his results .
A carrier should tell his or her relatives as they might be at risk of getting the disease or being a carrier too ( Lea , Williams and Donahue , 2005 ) .
This is because the carrier got the disease through a parent , and thus the carrier 's siblings and the carrier 's children might have also gotten the altered gene .
Hence , it is important to inform the carrier 's relatives so that they can go for the testing to check whether they are carriers or have an inherited disposition toward the disease .
If they were found to be a carrier , they have the chance to choose to not to reproduce or be mentally prepared about their children 's health in the future if they decide to proceed with having children .
After all , taking care of a child with a disease is not an easy task .
They should consider whether they are prepared to look after the child if the child gets the disease as it is not only financially exhausting , but mentally tiring as well .
Thus , by being informed about the genetic results of a carrier , the carrier 's family members can better plan their future and be mentally prepared for the worst .
Another reason why a carrier should tell his or her his genetic results is because his or her relatives might be able to provide support to him .
After all , family members are the closest people to the carrier and only their support can make him or her feel better .
Hence , a carrier should tell his or her relatives of his genetic test result .
Others might argue that by telling relatives about the result , a carrier may face discrimination from his relatives .
This is supported by a survey conducted in 1997 , which has identified more than 200 cases of genetic discrimination out of 917 people who responded ( Genetic Information and the Workplace , 1998 ) .
Some carriers might face problems such as being isolated as if they have a contagious disease , being talked about behind their backs or even being blamed for passing on the disease when relatives are diagnosed positive for the disease ( Finucane , n.d. ) .
These situations will only make the carrier unhappy and hence many choose not to tell their relatives about their genetic results .
However , the situations mentioned above rarely happen within a family .
Most of the discrimination come from employers or insurance companies .
This is proven by another survey which has found that 550 people had been denied employment or insurance due to their genetic defect ( Genetic Information and the Workplace , 1998 ) .
Hence , telling relatives about one 's genetic result will not result in discrimination .
It is only when the public get to know about it will a carrier face discrimination .
Furthermore , family members are the closest people to the carrier and if they do not support each other , no one will support them .
Hence , a carrier should tell his or her relatives of his genetic test result as discrimination by relatives is rare .
In conclusion , a carrier should tell his or her relatives about his genetic result as there is a possibility that they might get the disease or they might be a carrier too and the carrier can get support from them .
Although some might argue that the carrier might face discrimination if he discloses his results , this is generally not the case ; hence , the fear of such discrimination should not prevent one from revealing his genetic result .
With the advancements in medical technology , people can find out and understand the various causes of diseases .
It was not until recently that scientists and researchers found out that human 's genes are the cause of certain diseases such as heart diseases , cancers and diabetics type 1 .
By making use of genetic testing to test one 's genes , one will be able to know whether one will develop any genetic disease or carry any disease-causing genes .
Individuals who undergo such tests will find that the outcome of the tests affect not only them but also their family members .
Hence , the individual faces a dilemma of whether or not to reveal the test results to them as his family members may not accept the fact and will be adversely affected by the harsh reality .
Nevertheless , an individual should be obligated to inform his family members of the outcome of the genetic testing as doing so will bring benefits to both parties , such as enabling them to provide support to each other and to take careful precautions to reduce risks of infection .
In the face of the possibility of getting an incurable disease that will affect a person for life , it is important that family members can accompany and support him along the journey to fight against the illness .
Furthermore , family members will tend to be more understanding toward relatives who are ill and help them financially , such as providing for their daily expenses and medical costs .
If a patient 's family members are not aware of his condition , he will suffer silently and it is more likely for him to succumb to the illness .
For example , a local celebrity , Chew Chor Meng , who is suffering from Kennedy 's disease , has revealed to his family and the public his genetic disease .
Instead of feeling pessimistic towards life and being discriminated against by the public , he has received encouragement from the public and support from his family that has made him more resilient and optimistic in fighting against the disease .
Hence , individuals should be obligated to inform their relatives as it is beneficial for themselves in terms of fighting against genetic illnesses effectively .
there is a saying that " prevention is always better than cure ; " relatives who are informed earlier of the carrier 's genetic results can take earlier health precautions to reduce the risks of infection or the severity of the effects of the disease ( Varga & Sturm , 2008 ) .
For instance , they can change their lifestyle such as changing bad eating habits , saving money for their future and exercising more frequently .
Even if they do not develop the genetic diseases , the precautions taken at an earlier stage of their lives may protect them from other forms of illnesses that may not be caused by their genes .
Some may argue that individuals who have undergone genetic testing should not be obligated to inform their relatives for fear that they will lose their privacy and cause their relatives to suffer from the emotional burden of feeling guilty and anxious about whether they would suffer from the disease .
However , there have been laws set up to prevent discrimination against individuals who suffer from genetic diseases .
For example , the United States Government has implemented the Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act to prevent individuals from discrimination at work and from getting an insurance plan ( Genetics and public policy center , 2009 ) .
with a healthy mindset , they are more likely to win the battle against their illnesses .
In conclusion , individuals should be obligated to inform their relatives of their genetic testing results as they can provide support for each other to overcome the illness more effectively .
If they do not do so , relatives who are kept in the dark may suffer more as they would not know to take earlier precautions to mitigate the effects of the illness .
Many diseases such as Tay-Sachs disease , cystic fibrosis , Huntington 's disease , dementia , Alzheimer 's disease and breast cancer may be identified through genetic testing ( Access excellence 2009 ) .
Even though a positive result on a genetic test only shows a higher risk of developing the disease , such information is very important and crucial as knowing about one 's predisposition to such a disease may help to reduce the risk of developing it as one would then seek to control one 's lifestyle as environmental factors play an important role in the onset of certain genetic diseases .
Thus , if tested positive for these genes , the individual should be obligated to tell his family members .
This is especially true for fatal diseases and diseases which are strongly connected to genes .
This is important to ensure that early steps are taken to reduce the risk of the carrier and his family developing the disease .
In addition , he should also bring his family members along for genetic counseling so as to prevent unnecessary emotional distress due to their possible misinterpretation of the genetic test results .
Firstly , it is beneficial for the individual to inform his family members about his result as his family may help to reduce emotional distress .
While genetic counselors may give advice on how to reduce the likelihood of developing the disease , family members may provide the individual with emotional support .
This is very crucial as emotional distress might lead to a higher chance of developing the disease .
Hence , it is better for the individual to share his genetic test result with his family members .
Some may argue that the individual has the right to protect his privacy by not revealing the information , so it is up to him who to reveal it to .
However , it is the individual 's responsibility to tell his family members regarding his genetic test result .
This is because it might be harmful for him to keep it a secret as he might become emotionally disturbed by it .
According to a survey done on women regarding factor V Leiden ( FVL ) , 77 % of the women were emotionally disturbed by their genetic testing results .
When people are emotionally disturbed , they might not be able to think rationally which may be harmful to the individual 's health as it may result in depression and an unbalanced diet .
Some individuals do not want to reveal their genetic test result to their family as they do not want their family to be worried .
However , not knowing the true reason that caused him to be emotionally affected will cause this family to be even more worried .
In addition , the family may consult genetic counselors to seek for advice on how to reduce .
Diseases like Alzheimer 's and dementia do not show early physical symptoms .
Hence , by informing his family about the known genetic risk he has , a carrier may encourage his family to go for genetic testing too .
This is beneficial as it helps to increase the family 's awareness and preparedness for the disease .
If a person is a carrier of a genetic disease , he might pass it to his offspring .
However , this may be prevented through the In-Vitro Fertilization ( IVF ) method .
Thus , the offspring will not have the defective genes , hence lowering its possibility of developing the disease .
Others may argue that in the case of cancer , the presence of altered copies of the inherited gene accounts for only 5 to 10 percent of all cancers and the majority of people who develop breast cancer or colon cancer did not inherit such genes ( Access excellence 2009 ) .
Thus , there is no need for the individual to tell his family members about his genetic test result as genes do not play a very important role in the development of such diseases .
However , though it is true that environmental factors play a more significant role , the presence of such genes in the case of breast cancer greatly increases the possibility of developing the disease .
Hence , in knowing this information at an early stage , early preventive measures can be taken to reduce the possibility of developing the breast cancer by controlling one 's lifestyle .
In conclusion , a carrier of a known genetic disease should be obligated to inform his family members about it as both he and his family will benefit from it .
some examples of genetic tests are newborn screening , diagnostic testing , carrier testing , prenatal testing and others .
People who undergo the test will be notified of the results .
Some of them may show a positive result as a carrier of a known genetic disease .
If they know about it , should they tell others , especially their relatives ?
I believe that they should tell their relatives .
Firstly , the person should reveal the results to his or her relatives as .
Everyone should be responsible and play an important role in the family .
As we know , Huntington 's disease is incurable and inheritable by the next generation ( Myers , 2004 ) .
If a person shows a positive result for this disease and not reveal to the family , this disease will be passed on to the next generation easily .
It will also cause many people in the family tree to suffer from this disease .
Although some might think the decision to undergo the test is considered as a personal choice ( Norrgard , 2008 ) .
Some might think is the individual 's choice whether to tell the result or not .
However , the responsibility of protecting and saving the family from getting the genetic disease outweighs one 's personal choice .
Thus , in order to protect the family , a person should tell his relatives the result of his genetic testing .
Moreover , the individual should tell his relatives about the result of his genetic testing as it will .
" Prevention is better than cure " is the slogan always used by doctors .
If they know about the , they can seek help from doctors in order to prevent developing the heritable disease ( Takala & Gylling , 2001 ) .
This cancer can develop at a risk of 85 % for the person with the mutated genes ( Wahrman , 2009 ) .
Individuals can reduce the risk of getting this disease .
They can reduce the chance by practicing a healthy lifestyle and through other means .
However , potential carriers can find out about them earlier if a relative who is a known carrier reveals his genetic test results to them .
They can then be prepared for these diseases and not become depressed about them easily .
Thus , in order to apply earlier prevention for the family , the individual should reveal his result .
Finally , individuals should tell the result of their genetic test to their relatives as it is a public issue .
A positive result is not considered as a personal problem or bad luck .
It may involve the family or even the society .
This problem is common to Jewish women of Eastern .
If some kept their disease a secret until death , we would not have known that it posed a serious problem to society .
Although people kept the secret as they were scared of being discriminated against by society and therefore chose to keep the result unrevealed ( Wahrman , 2009 )
, there is an act called the Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act ( GINA ) which can protect people with a genetic problem from discrimination .
They do not need to worry about the discrimination any more .
Thus , people should reveal their genetic test result to their relatives as .
In conclusion , the individual with the positive result in genetic testing which shows he or she is a carrier of a known genetic risk should reveal this .
This revelation of the result can help many people , including the carrier himself .
Therefore , he should not keep it a secret .
Failure to identify and treat Phenylketonuria in time , however , may result in mental illness at the later stages of the babies ' life .
( Schuett , 2008 ) There are some who think that the disclosure of a genetic testing result is unnecessary and they argue that it may bring immense grief and worry to relatives of a genetic disease carrier .
However , without being warned of the possible risk of inheriting these diseases , they would probably not go for their own genetic testing and hence would run the risk of undergoing late treatment for a disease related to a genetic disorder , which may have catastrophic consequences .
Secondly , the choice to undergo genetic testing is a personal one , regardless of the genetic testing result of another family member .
While carriers of such diseases should reveal the results of their genetic testing so as to warn their relatives about the possibility of the latter being carriers as well , it is still up to their relatives to find out whether they themselves had indeed inherited any genetic disorder .
( Norrgard , 2008 ) Since it is never certain that one will inherit a disorder from one 's parents , the disclosure of the result of such a test would therefore not bring any direct harm to one 's relatives .
However , laws such as the Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act ( GINA ) in the United States have been passed so as to ensure this would not happen .
For instance , the less healthy child of a rich tycoon may be discriminated in the choice of a successor .
In addition , some are worried that revealing such information to their offspring may affect the latter 's psychological well-being ( Living with , 2009 ) .
Moreover , efforts have been made by the government to pass laws such as GINA to prevent genetic discrimination .
Hence , with proper guidance such as genetic counseling , a carrier of a known genetic risk should be obligated to tell his or her relatives about his genetic test results .
Yet , not everyone might have the freedom to do so , fearing that family members might not be able to accept the news .
However , decisions to withhold information on one 's genetic test results only have short-term benefits and fail to consider the bigger picture such as situations in which one 's family eventually discovers one 's secret .
This is the time when family support is most essential for one as members can help to share the problem and advise how one should handle the problem .
However , there are cases where one may not have the liberty to share the information with the family due to the unstable condition of another member .
One may also resort to this in order not to further burden that loved one .
Hence , it is essential that one should notify one 's family about one 's condition as soon as possible .
Besides being able to receive family support , letting others know about one 's genetic condition is also a form of relieving unnecessary stress .
Conversely , keeping such important secrets to oneself in the long run might actually develop into stress which may exacerbate one 's current condition and trigger certain stress-induced illnesses such as cancer ( Morin & Huot , 2004 ) .
Critics may feel that individuals may get discriminated even within their which may be a source of stress for them ( Wolff , 1996 ) .
Hence more often than not , one should be frank with one 's family and not withhold any results of the genetic test .
An example of such precautions is to have one 's family shifting from their usual unhealthy diet to a healthier one .
Some note that even though the disclosure empowers one 's relatives to take precautionary measures , it might end up causing anxiety among family members ( Cancer.net Editorial Board , 2009 ) .
Thus , it is crucial that one should tell one 's family about his genetic condition .
In this respect , one should tell one 's about one 's genetic condition . This will enable one to be able to receive emotional concern , to prevent any stress build up and to allow one 's family to take precautions against the particular disease .
There are certain disorders that exist that have adverse effects on the health of individuals .
The issues of privacy and discrimination support the position that the carrier should not be obliged to disclose the information to his relatives .
Firstly , a carrier should not be obligated to disclose his genetic to his relatives as he has the individual right as a patient to privacy .
Everyone has his own right to decide whether his personal information should be revealed to third parties .
Without the right to protect his privacy through withholding genetic information of his disorder , the person would feel violated .
Secondly , discrimination from relatives affects the carrier 's decision in revealing his condition .
One might never know how one 's relatives would react upon knowing the condition of the carrier .
For example , some relatives would have the thinking that the genetic risk of the carrier would bring about a bad reputation to them so they may start to distance themselves and try to eliminate all contact with him .
Discrimination has been found to have harmful effects on people such as putting them at a high risk of depression .
It is already bad for a carrier to have a genetic risk ; it would be much worse if depression strikes him .
Thus , a carrier should not be obligated to tell his relatives about his genetic risk .
( Bioethics Advisory Committee Singapore , November 2005 ) .
However , timing is important so one should think of the consequences before revealing one 's genetic condition .
It would not be the right time to her genetic condition to her pregnant sister as the anxiety caused may affect the foetus .
Timing is also an important factor .
The controversy of whether a carrier of a known genetic risk should be obligated to tell his or her relatives has been highly debated within the bioethics community ( Mehlman , 2009 ) .
In addition , families can also help in reducing the risk for the next generation .
Firstly , revealing the results to their family can have a positive psychological effect on the individual .
Upon receiving the bad news from the test , individuals may feel discouraged and have a negative view of life . This is for those who have a family history of relatives who did not survive the disorder such as ovarian cancer ( Haidle , 2005 ) .
According to Scientific Blogging , statistics show that only nine percent of the mothers received negative responses while most of them received very encouraging responses ( 2009 ) .
In addition , if only one parent has a genetic disorder , the offspring will have a fifty percent chance of getting it ( Mehlman , 1999 ) .
