Lastly , surveillance technology such as RFID ( implantable radiofrequency identification technology ) poses potential health hazards to individuals
RFID in the form of Verichip is used for patient identification to provide healthcare providers with efficient access to patient 's medical history and contact information .
However , since there is a limited number of RFID human implantations performed , there is insufficient data about the possible side effects related to it , recent tests indicate that there are potential health hazards such as cancer , adverse tissue reaction , magnetic resonance imaging incompatibility and infections that could affect the old and feeble individuals .
Hence , since there are many adverse health effects of RFID that is still not known thus the use of surveillance technology to track people should be banned as the implantation of Verichip in patients bring more harm than benefits .
On the other hand , supporters of surveillance technology state that surveillance technology plays an important role in crime detection and prevention thus maintaining the country 's security and prevents terrorist attacks .
In conclusion , it is evident that the use of surveillance technology to track people should be banned as it not only threatens one 's privacy inhibiting them from exercising freedom but the use of surveillance technology also poses unknown potential health hazards to individuals .
In addition , it creates suspicion in individuals causing them to lose mutual trust for one another resulting in breaking of social relationship and family bonds .
Nevertheless , surveillance technology has limited efficiency in crime prevention hence it should not be used to track people since it fails to protect us .
As an unavoidable consequence , it raises ethical issues , which states that such penetrating technology has invaded people 's privacy because more and more personal habits and behaviors are monitored without permission .
It has been demonstrated in hospitals , crimes and workplace .
Firstly , the surveillance technology can be used in hospitals to monitor movements of its patients in case of an emergency .
In conjunction with a video surveillance system to cover different regions of the hospital , it can track the patients ' movements any time at any corner of the hospital .
When one commits a crime , the policemen can track one 's movement and locate one 's whereabouts or extract one 's information or past history .
( ( Christiana.J . et al , 2007 ) ) Furthermore , in New York , RFID is also being used in schools .
According to information released by the Federal Bureau of Justice and Statistics in late November , the crime rate such as school fights and percentage of students bringing weapons to school had indeed fallen since 1990 .
The most controversial issue about the use of surveillance technology would be the ethical issue regarding people 's privacy , which is strongly demonstrated in workplace privacy .
For instance , RFID tags are placed in 80,000 employee uniforms at the Star City Casino in Sydney Australia ( Gruber , J. ) .
Some people say that the installation of such technology reduces the employees to robots , depriving them of their individuality to only-working-machines so as to achieve maximum productivity .
This has intruded upon employees ' privacy and thus should not be used .
In conclusion , I think the surveillance technology should be used as its benefits outweigh its harm .
It is useful in tracking patients in hospitals , criminals after they committed crimes and employees in the workplace .
The individual privacy should be put aside when the benefit to the public plays a more important role .
Surveillance technology such as RFID ( radio-frequency identification ) , GPS ( Global Positioning System ) and security cameras are used to monitor the action of the public .
After the September 11 attack , the use of such technology has become more prevalent so as to increase the security level ( Vedo Soft 2006 ) .
It is also used to monitor those who require special attention such as Alzheimer 's patients to ensure that they receive appropriate and quick medication during an emergency .
Thus , on the whole whole , its advantages clearly outweigh its disadvantages such as an individuals privacy .
The presence of security cameras in public places helps to reduce crime rates as criminals fear that their actions will be recorded .
According to park officials of Balboa park in San Diego , California , nine months after the installation of a surveillance system , the crime rates have reduced in all aspects and more people visit the park as they feel more secure ( Nieto 1997 ) .
One of the common methods to ensure this is by surveillance technology and this has significantly helped Singapore to be one of the countries with the lowest crime rates .
Secondly , surveillance technology has been proven to be effective for social control as it helps to monitor those who need special attention such as Alzheimer 's patients .
According to a TIME magazine article written by Morrissey , a study conducted in 2006 showed that 4 % of the 1,260 mice implanted with RFID developed tumors .
However , none of them were malignant .
" Should the use of surveillance technology such as RFID to track people be banned ?
Radio-frequency identification ( RFID ) technology has advanced from industrial and animal tagging applications to being able to track people 's movements ) .
Some companies have made it compulsory for their staff to wear RFID tags to facilitate personnel identification and access control ( Masters & Michael , 2006 ) .
Knowing that they are being spied on , they will have a lesser tendency to commit crimes .
Unauthorized removal of a baby would trigger the alarm thus enhancing baby safety ( Masters & Michael , 2006 ) .
This has enhanced patient care as nurses have more time for other patients and are notified immediately when patient has fever ( Friedlos , 2009 ) .
During recent years there has been an increase in the use of surveillance technology .
The current technology has made it possible for the surveillance system to be used in our daily lives , such as electronic payment , supply chain management , and livestock .
Some argue that the tracking should be banned for it may cause serious outcomes related to the violation of privacy .
But I do not think it is reasonable to forgo this advanced technology for it really plays a great role in the areas related to healthcare and government , and the potential negative impacts brought by it can be reduced or avoided if the regulations around it tend to be sounder .
First , surveillance is very useful to hospitals and governments .
As healthcare centers , hospitals need to undertake a heavy task in dealing with diseases and maintaining a high level of security .
.
For example , it equips the government with an unprecedented ability to detect the potential criminal activities .
To a great extent , it contributes a lot to the stability of the whole society while only violating the privacy of the criminals .
In fact , many great inventions and breakthroughs in human history have got positive and negative aspects , such as the automobiles which have brought great convenience to people while causing large damage to the environment by emitting pollutant gases .
The only thing we can do is to improve their efficiency and seek new and green power supplies which will make them as environmentally-friendly as possible .
The last two decades have witnessed drastic developments in material science and digital processing technology , which have made Radio Frequency Identification ( RFID ) , an advanced surveillance technology that has been applied in the business and tracking world .
This controversial issue aroused much concern from society , .
For instance , it can be implanted in the elderly who are suffering from degenerative diseases .
( Surveillance Studies Network , 2006 ) Since it is so dangerous for elderly people with dementia to get lost , carrying a RFID chip enables their families to locate them .
Thus , it not only eliminates danger for such elderly people , but also reduces the worry and effort for their families .
Moreover , for some construction projects with high fatality rates , obviously we need more accurate and reliable technology to protect workers during the programs .
RFID enables us to provide an accurate position of every worker who carries its tag .
This high-tech system was used in the second Gotthard tunnel program and other company 's like Kronos Titan , Leverkusen ( Germany ) in the chemical sector for production of hazardous materials .
Secondly , RFID is an efficient and reliable surveillance tool to watch people who maybe a threat .
For the prisoners in custody , it is necessary to watch and track them in case of further crime .
( Surveillance Studies Network , 2006 ) Meanwhile , using RFID to keep watching those employees working in high-security areas confers benefits that are clear and compelling .
Both of these is evidence that the RFID community has done a poor job at conveying to the public , in an accurate understandable form , what technology is and its capabilities .
280-282 ) ) Meanwhile , some believe that it should be banned since it intrudes upon privacy .
We will lose all its advantages and benefits once such a technology is banned , which will lead to more casualties and threats to society .
Furthermore , science and technology development in such areas will be barred once we ban it , which affects human society and civilization further .
In conclusion , RFID as a surveillance technology should not be banned as it protects special groups of people and helps to watch people who are a potential threat to our society .
Citywatcher.com , a surveillance company , is one of those companies to have RFID chips implanted in their employees ' arms ( Gruber , n.d. ) as a safety measure .
Patients are also given RFID tags to wear so that should they collapse , aid can be given to them immediately ( Kanellos , 2004 ) .
The RFID tags are broken once patients are discharged so the bed can be prepared for new patients and waiting time would be reduced .
Hence , these technologies should not be banned as it efficiently locates enemies , saves lives and at the same time ensures that civilians are not harmed by the new regulations .
Firstly , surveillance technology can be used for security and as a deterrent to prevent crimes .
The concept of human tagging has been widely accepted , but one has to take note of its purpose .
For those regions where kidnapping are more prevalent such as Mexico , children tagging can actually help their parent identify them after many years or it can serve as a means to deter kidnapping because parents can locate their children using gadgets ( Wired , February 2000 ) .
It is just used in specific areas or persons who actually benefits from its application such as in the case of child kidnapping .
The reason why it was so difficult to track and record accurately in the past is that in such a big event , it may take about one hour for certain runners to even reach the starting point and start the race .
Thirdly , Terrorism has become an enormous threat to the security of many countries in the world , especially in the US .
Governments have gathered various ways to combat terrorism and RFID is one of its means .
RFID can help the government to gather information such as events involving people , mobile and places into the computer system so that they can watch out and catch suspicious persons
The welfare of the entire populations supercedes the individual rights in the case of terrorist attacks .
In conclusion , surveillance technology should not be banned , but one has to take note of the purposes of its applications .
We have seen that the identification technology has progressed by leaps and bounds over the last few decades .
There are however , a variety of issue associated with the appropriateness to deploy RFID technology to track individuals .
Nonetheless , despite RFID still progressing in its infancy stage , it is seen to possess uncapped potential and can be put to valuable uses , especially in connection with hospital- patient identification , anti-theft tracking as well as in government agencies for identification purposes .
Firstly , RFID system can be utilized widely in hospital in-patient identification.The system can be used to monitor the whereabouts of patients and also medical personnel s in the hospital .
One advantage about the device is that it does not require line-of-sight monitoring .
It ensures a higher level of security and also allows nurses to monitor more patients at a time .
Unlike barcodes , RFID does not need to be placed precisely relative to the scanner .
Swedberg ( 2004 ) cited that countries like New Zealand , Pakistan , as well as Malaysia have embedded RFID chips in their citizen 's identification card .
RFID chips are also being used in identification cards in corporations and schools to control unauthorized access .
With all that has been said , the advantages of the usage of RFID clearly outweigh the drawbacks of the technology .
One needs to understand the benefits brought about by RFID in different sectors .
RFID is Radio Frequency Identification that uses electromagnetic spectrum to transmit signals so that we can locate the exact position of someone .
On one side , some people think that surveillance technology should not be used to track other people because it intrudes into otherr people 's privacy .
On the other hand , some argue that this technology should be used , especially for security purposes .
First , it will intrude into other people 's privacy . For example the usage of RFID in a smart card that includes a microchip that stores ID , phone number , bank account , or address which are such critical information on each individual ( RFID Journal,2003 ) .
The problem arises when there are hackers who can access the information that is stored in a RFID smart card .
Second , the usage of RFID by a company to track other company 's data , such that all fax , telephone , or email are intercepted so that all of the vital and very useful data of one company can be detected by other company ( Bogonikolos,1999 ) .
These conditions will cause unbalanced competition among the companies that will in turn affect many people .
Generally all of these conditions will only bring inconvenience for someone who is being tracked .
By using this technology , all of the activities that are happening can be viewed through the camera so it is important to organize the security of the place ( Burnell,2007 ) .
The other use of RFID that some people think could bring advantage is RFID microchip implanted inside the human body , especially in those who suffer chronic illness such as Alzheimer or Dementia .
This technology will help their family to identify their position whenever they get lost .
In conclusion , the usage of RFID to track other people will affect many people 's lives tremendously. .
Therefore , I agree with the banning of the usage of RFID to track other people because it is such an immoral and irresponsible action that will make other people suffer loss .
For example , the police had to keep the suspect under surveillance by following the suspect physically . The had to send soldiers to the enemy in order to master enemy condition .
Nowadays , we can locate anyone anytime with just a small chip and a reader .
First and foremost , usage of surveillance technology in the hospital can improve the success rate of treatment especially for emergency cases .
RFID tagging can also be used on patients for nurses or doctors to keep an eye on them in case they have inappropriate actions such as moving towards unsafe areas or they suffer from a sudden organ failure .
Also , items are tagged with RFID chips which have unique serial numbers .
Thus , once they are dislocated from their original destination , a signal will be sent to notify the shop assistant .
If the item is stolen out of the shop , it can be traced easily . Therefore not only can the item be recovered , the thief can also be nabbed .
However , critics argued that surveillance technology has greatly intruded their personal space where they have this psychological feeling of 'being watched ' by others every single day .
To think of it , would you rather want a safe environment in which your privacy may be compromised , or to choose privacy over safety ?
Everyone has a differentt perception of privacy .
Therefore it 's biased to say that surveillance technology threatens one 's privacy to a huge extent .
Surveillance is the process of monitoring behaviours and activities , usually of people without their permission .
Lots of surveillance tools are invented , such as CCTV ( close circuit television ) cameras , RFID ( radio-frequency identification ) , GPS ( global positioning system ) , etc. The extensive and growing use of electronic surveillance technology has resulted in considerable debate especially the ethical questions concerning privacy .
Although it appears to breach the privacy of communities , surveillance technology has in fact enabled to track the public 's health , ensured public safety and monitored employees in companies .
First of all , surveillance technology should not be banned as it has enabled the tracking of the health of the public .
Besides that , it can supply detailed body information to hospitals and then the public can alter their behaviours like exercise and diet after interpretation from doctors .
With the implants , RFID chips may convey messages regarding health conditions of patients , such as those with epilepsy , heart disease , or mental impairment , especially for those who are unable to communicate effectively with hospital staff about their medical histories or current complaints when they are in need of immediate treatment .
In addition , it also decreases the slight discrepancy of diagnosis by doctors due to the influence of their experiences .
Thus , surveillance technology to track the health of communities aids in reducing mortality rates due to health problems and also decreasing the misinterpretation of verbal communication by doctors .
This is very crucial to ensure that the productivity and the efficiency of workers are kept to a maximum .
For instance , employees might seem to be surfing the web for business purposes all the time , but what they are actually doing is personal business such as online banking , shopping and chatting .
It may be argued that one 's privacy might be invaded due to surveillance technology ( Heathfield , n.d. , p.2 ) .
It has also been said that surveillance of employees can affect the relationship between employer and employees ( Heathfield , n.d. , p. 2 ) .
Use of surveillance technology has no impact for those focusing on work and doing the right thing ( Heathfield , n.d. , p. 2 ) .
Furthermore , security is very essential for factories manufacturing coins and jewellery .
This can alleviate theft rate in the factories .
As a result , surveillance technology can help employers to monitor their workers to an extent that it does not breach their privacy .
Moreover , surveillance technology is vital in ensuring the safety of the public .
The police can then trace the culprits ' physical appearance and vehicle number .
Thus , the time taken to solve criminal cases is tremendously reduced , compared with the crime not being recorded .
The video recorded becomes a concrete proof to sanction the culprits .
On the other hand , for those having diseases like Alzheimer 's disease , surveillance technology helps find them out if they get lost .
In conclusion , surveillance technology should not be banned as it ensures the health and safety of the public , besides being used to monitor the performance of employees .
If we persist with the banning of surveillance technology , the public will be exposed to a dangerous environment in which crime will happen frequently .
Without surveillance , decreased productivity of workers may bring the unemployment issue to the surface again .
Although until now there are still many debates about the ethical issues of surveillance technology , it after all still benefits the communities in many respects , so banning of surveillance technology should not be initiated .
It has changed many aspects of our lives and has ubiquitously penetrated our society making many of us dependent on it .
Even though technological advances prove to be a marvel as we move faster into the future , they do not only bring about benefits but also negative repercussions if not dealt with properly .
Surveillance has been around for hundreds of years but technology has 'springboarded ' it to a much higher level .
Of course , surveillance technology does have its benefits to the society in terms of safety and security , but does it outweigh the undesirable problems that it brings ?
The use of miniature tracking devices to track the whereabouts of one 's 'target ' has put human rights activism in action .
Yet , many have argued that it is against human rights and thus promoted the banning of tracking devices .
It has also benefitted many through an increased level of safety and in locating their vehicles .
For example , when one is involved in a car accident that is located in a secluded place and does not have any communication devices with him or her , the presence of a GPS installed in his car can give loved ones or the authorities direction on how to search for him .
Therefore , the use of tracking devices can actually bring about benefits if they are used with caution . Thus , tracking devices not be banned .
Furthermore , surveillance technology like RFID has also been used for the safety of personnel as well as the general public .
Oakland Coliseum located in the United States has made use of RFID to track its staff to increase the efficiency in deploying quick response teams in times of need .
In an incident , its staff will activate the respective standby teams depending on the situation
In addition to this , Axcess International has also promoted the use of RFID as a safety measure for tracking each individual .
Miners are given ID tags before their descent into the tunnel .
These ID tags provide real-time location information on the miners ' movement as well as location of the tags during possible cave-in
( Axcess targets RFID for US mining safety , October 1 , 2008 , para 1 ) .
Surveillance technology has also been used in emergencies such as the outbreak of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome ( SARS ) .
One such example in Singapore is the installation of surveillance cameras at homes of affected citizens that are quarantined at home .
Even though it does not comply with human rights law , it is for the better of the society and the government has to take such drastic measures to ensure the preservation of the rest of the society ( Information for Home Quarantine , March 24 , 2003 ) . Therefore ,
Undeniably , surveillance technologies do overlap with human rights , but more often than not , the use of these technologies brings about more benefits than negative consequences .
In conclusion , there should not be a complete ban of the use of surveillance but only adequate control by individuals or a governing body to restrict the abuse of this powerful tool .
Surveillance technology and security has become crucial to each country since the terrorist attacks in the US on Sept 11 .
Surveillance technology is the use of devices to monitor any behaviour , activities or other changing information that is deemed to be important to the security of any government or personnel .
But this has gone too far ; with security came the loss of personal privacy .
Personal freedom is compromised thus with much hesitation , I do not agree that surveillance technology should be used to track people .
We live our own way and nobody has the right to monitor or dictate our actions .
Be it the government 's security reasons or other excuses , still it has no right to impose such a technology on others without our permission .
Secondly , it erodes trust and creates a climate of fear in the person being monitored and the people around them .
Fear causes psychological problems such as anxiety and the loss of a person 's confidence .
Anxiety is a very difficult mental disorder to cure and it takes a very long time for a person to overcome this but with constant disturbances from knowing that he or she is being monitored , it will become a significant problem in their daily lives .
Thirdly , not all surveillance devices are used without the person knowing it ; some of the devices are used with the knowledge of the person .
A very good example is in certain states in the US .
These not only cause distress in a person but also put the whole monitoring agency on high alert if the device malfunctions .
Huge cost and time will be wasted and manpower will be mobilized just to rectify these unfortunate problems .
It is taxpayer 's money we are talking about .
Does n't the public have the right to dictate how the money should be generated and used ?
For the government works for the people , not the other way around .
But this does not apply to certain countries that expect the people to work for them .
Lastly , the use of surveillance technology can be abused by the government and or any agency that uses it .
Like in the case of South Africa during the apartheid period whereby the opposition was monitored using surveillance technology .
Thousands of opposition members were arrested and ill treated by the regime .
The situation became better when Nelson Mandela successfully became the president but at the price of he himself being the victim of their abuse .
Greed and corruption sink in when the people at the very top refuse to give up their power and use underhanded means to keep themselves in power .
With easy evidence at their disposal , they will use the law to suppress any opposition at their will .
In conclusion , surveillance technology should not be used to track people as it can be abused by the people who use it .
Previously , the common practice for surveillance has always been through physical means such as prison guards , but in modern times it has been improved and upgraded through image amplification devices such as binoculars , closed circuit cameras and high-resolution satellite cameras ( Bogonikolos , 1999 ) .
Also , RFID pose the risks of information leak during transmission of information .
Modern surveillance technology has constructed a means for us to gather information readily .
RFID first appeared in 1940 with the primary aim of identifying aircrafts for military purposes .
Tentatively , with surveillance , security is on the whole tightened .
Many would agree that sophisticated surveillance technology has indeed been beneficial in the security arena especially after the September 11th incident and governments has since then diverted their attention to tracking potential terrorists instead of tracking explosive devices or substances .
For instance , in its effort to locate any suspicious character , Britain has over 4 million CCTV cameras installed along almost every street just to keep track of every individual ( BBC News , 2006 ) .
The implementation of such a system has successfully foiled some of the terrorists ' plans .
Furthermore , individuals would behave themselves upon knowing that they are constantly being " watched " , leading to a possible decrease in crime rates .
As far as the government is concerned , with the use of surveillance devices , security is greatly enhanced and discipline is observed .
On the other hand , some argued that such method has inevitably threatened the most basic human rights to freedom as every movement or speech , for more advanced devices , is meticulously monitored .
" ( Schneier B , 2006 ) . Then , there are individuals who abuse the usage of surveillance technology by sending their partners gifts with RFID attached to it so that they will be able to track the location of their partners and know who they are hanging out with .
Obviously such acts are morally wrong and hence the use of surveillance technology to track people should be banned if individuals misuse it
( Lee and Tan , 2007 ) . However , individuals should also have their right to security , which in turn allows the intervention of government .
National security is altogether far more important than the mere privacy entitled to individuals .
RFID is also used to track criminals , detainees or ex-convict .
If Mas Selamat bin Kastari was to have a RFID tag , he would not not have been able to escape and there would not have been so much fear instilled among Singaporeans during the period of his disappearance .
By employing such an operation , government would thus be able to prevent any possible mishap from happening .
An opinion poll conducted among Americans and Europeans has shown that 75 % of the respondents " want more , not less , surveillance " ( BBC News , 2007 ) . Furthermore , " If it prevents criminal behaviour or improves its detection I 'm all for it .
Perhaps , the increases in the number of terrorists attack have proven to us that governments should also tap on the advantages of current technology to counter those sophisticated attacks carried out by the terrorists .
On the minor scale , it is the individuals themselves who are abusing such technology for their own gain .
However , when viewed from a broader perspective , surveillance technology would have been the platform to stop any terrorist attacks or crimes from happening .
In addition , since most people recognize the main objective of surveillance technology , such technology should not be banned even if it includes spying on individuals .
This technology is widely used in public places for security maintenance , as well as for the purpose of identification and tracking of information .
For example , CCTV is installed in airports , banks , department stores , and even streets to prevent crime in those areas , while RFID can be used as an access key within an organization , a means of managing mobile assets of a company , or a tool for identifying and tracking of equipment , staff , and patients in a hospital .
In fact , there are still a lot of applications for RFID in various fields and industries including security , public transport , healthcare , and e-payment that its popularity is increasing rapidly .
An RFID tag incorporated into an item can be read from several distances away .
The individual carrying the item may be unaware of the presence of the tag , thus rendering him vulnerable to privacy breaches ( Bhaskar 2007 ) .
Therefore , regulations should be made to protect the privacy of individuals , such as the need to indicate the existence of tags on customer products and the restriction on information gathering .
For instance , personally identifiable information ( PII ) such as the license plate number of an individual carrying an RFID-enabled card or travel document can be read by a third party without his consent since the unauthorized RFID reader can read the RFID number from the card or document ( US Department of Homeland Security 2008 ) .
However , some may argue that the benefits of surveillance technology actually compensate for the concerns about privacy .
An RFID tag embedded into items or products can help owners to track down their valuable belongings should their items be stolen or missing .
RFID also helps to identify disaster victims , and provide effective treatment for patients in emergency situations in a hospital .
Surveillance technology can be used , for instance , to monitor data exchanges on network or to observe the activity of someone using a surveillance camera .
However , people are mainly concerned with their privacy being violated since they are being tracked down .
It can also give out important information on the individual without any permission from the person .
The first reason is concerned with the idea of individual privacy ( CASPIAN , 2003 ) .
When someone buys a product that is tagged with RFID , the radio wave can still be detected as long as the chip is still active and within the range of detection .
Groups of consumers in UK , France , Germany and Netherlands were polled by a consultancy group named Capgemini and 95 % of the consumers were worried that the information gathered from RFID could be used freely without their consent by third parties ( BBC , 2005 ) .
This survey indicates that breach of privacy is indeed an important concern for people .
Secondly , the information gathered through RFID can be used in a way that can endanger the life of the individual himself or herself ( CASPIAN , 2003 ) .
For instance , terrorists with appropriate equipment can target a high-ranking official by setting a bomb to explode as soon as the target is in the detection range .
Robbers can identify rich persons just by reading the RFID tag on the things the person buys .
All of these can be done in a radius of few meters and these make it even harder for the person to realize that they are being spied upon .
Others argue that RFID can be used to stop terrorists from monitoring the nation 's food supply , hence keeping the food from the terrorists ( Baard , 2003 ) .
However , in this age of digital information , people can easily find an Internet connection and type a few keywords like " remove RFID tag " .
This shows that the RFID tag is not effective in tracking people , particularly terrorists .
To wrap up the discussion on the controversy of using RFID to track people , the examples above show how ineffective is the RFID system on spying people like terrorists since the RFID tag can be removed easily .
On the other hand , some groups of people can even misuse this piece of technology to harm others for the sake of their benefit .
Moreover , a survey by a consultancy group Capgemini shows that the majority of the respondents were very concerned over breach of their privacy particularly on the use of the RFID system to track them .
RFID , also known as radio frequency identification , is a piece of technology which makes use of electromagnetic or electrostatic waves in the radio frequency to identify or pass information through the radio wave .
Like many other pieces of surveillance technology , RFID also infringes on privacy of individuals .
In addition , it also possesses some potential hazards to someone implanted with the chip .
Yet , there are far more important benefits if we incorporate the use of RFID , hence we must not ban it .
It is common to hear that most technologies are like a double-edged sword ; so is RFID .
Scientists have shown that if RFID is implanted in the human body , it will interfere with hospital equipment [ Anonymous , 2008 ] , hence handicapping the doctors in their treatment for the patients .
Thus , it is not encouraged to implant an RFID chip .
However , It will be plain ignorant to ban RFID based on this limitation as there are rooms for improvement since it is still at its developing stage .
The benefits of RFID are its efficiency and the safety it can offer which people in the future will enjoy .
If RFID chips are inserted into prisoners , we can track down escapees thus preventing worst-case scenarios from happening . An example is the case of Singapore 's Mas Selamat who , an important player in terrorism , managed to escape from prison prison .
Another use is to insert it in minors to prevent them from being kidnapped and from going astray .
One recent case study would be the famous case of Jaycee Lee Dugard who was held captive and raped for 18 years by Philip Garrido .
All these tragedies among minors can be avoided if and only if RFID was implanted in them to monitor their movement [ Best , 2004 ] .
For the past years , the controversy of surveillance technology infringing on one 's right to privacy still exists and will continue to be so .
However , there can be some laws passed down to ensure that technologies like RFID are not abused but used in the proper direction .
For example , like the surveillance camera , peeping toms and other criminals commonly use them for crimes , yet why does the government still allow such technology to be used ?
Similarly , RFID , which is more feasible and useful than the surveillance camera since it can cover a wider range of areas than the latter , should not be banned .
It seems obvious that the benefits outweigh the disadvantages , thus instead of banning it when it is not yet perfect , we should encourage the further development of this technology .
Though the debate about the ethical issues of RFID are ongoing , we need to understand that in whatever new piece of technology introduced , there is always a need for us to compromise in some ways since nothing is perfect in this world .
Surveillance technology refers to gadgets that are able to observe and monitor an individuals ' behavior and activity from a distance using electronic equipment .
This essay will argue that this technology should not be used to track people down .
Using surveillance technology gives the general public the feeling that they are being watched all the time and there is no sense of freedom .
Injecting RFID chips into a person it is like imprisoning a person , because there is no place where the person can go undetected .
Many might say that by using this technology location of criminals and medical patients who manage to runaway can be detected .
But the reliability of this gadget has not been tested , and there is no assurance that with the installing of this surveillance technology , all criminals and medical patients can be detected easily .
Another point to be raised is that surveillance technology may not be effective in preventing or reducing crime rates as many people assume that they do .
The usage of the surveillance technology gives people a false sense of security because they feel that with technology looking after them , they are sure to be safe .
However , this may not be the case because surveillance may only help to catch a criminal after the crime has been committed .
Most of the time information from surveillance technology is redundant , because the information recorded during the crime does not provide enough evidence to arrest the criminal .
Furthermore criminals are becoming wiser each day ; they may outsmart the technology by hacking into the system to prevent them from being caught .
Therefore , it is certainly not a wise choice to use surveillance cameras in replacement of security guards .
Another concern about using surveillance is the health issue .
The usages of certain surveillance gadgets such as RFID being implanted in the body of individuals have tested as being harmful to the human body .
Humans that are implanted with these chips have higher incidences of getting cancer ( Layden , J 2007 ) .
Though the possibility of getting cancer is not 100 % , why should humans expose themselves to a higher risk of this deadly disease ?
In conclusion , usage of surveillance technology can be strongly argued against , because it is a invasion to privacy , it does not really reduce crime rates and it raises problems related to health issues .
The money used to futher develop this technology and to implement this technology would be better spent on more useful areas such as education and medicine .
Thus , the controversy over whether or not such use of technology should be banned has been erupted ( Bacchetta & Bacchetta , 2005 ; Marshall , 2009 ; Sade , 2007 ; Two stories highlight the RFID debate , 2005 ) .
Although some people consider such utilization benefits mankind in ways such as security and health care , concerns of loss of privacy and dehumanization , physical risks , as well as problems of identity theft still make it controversial .
RFID is mainly used on tracking employees and patients , neither of which is reasonable .
According to a report on July 19 , 2005 ( Two stories highlight the RFID debate ) , the general workers ' union GMB in the UK required the European Commission to prohibit the tag of RFID on employees .
Though , after weighing the pros and cons , numerous civil rights groups and privacy groups oppose surveillance as a violation of people 's right to privacy , including Electronic Privacy Information Center , Electronic Frontier Foundation ( Wentworth , 2005 ) , American Civil Liberties Union ( 2003 ) as well as the US Department of Justice ( 2008 ) .
However , based on a CEJA report ( Sade , 2007 ) , the American Medical Association officially reported on July 17 , 2007 that RIFD devices contain potential physical risks to the user .
Thus , surveillance technology such as RFID should be banned from tracking people .
In fact , the use of RFID and other surveillance technology has raised issues such as our basic privacy , health and the public security .
Firstly , surveillance technology such as the use of RFID should be banned as it intrudes upon our privacy .
Using surveillance technology to track people violates their privacy ; thus , it is a very serious offence .
This means that the personal data of a person can be easily retrieved and thus one 's privacy is invaded .
Studies showed that when active RFID tags were shifted around 41 important health devices such as pacemakers , they interfered with the devices in 34 tests out of all 123 tests .
And out of the 34 tests , 22 could cause a serious problem to the patients ( Wasserman , 2008 ) .
Despite the convenience of being able to attend to the patients efficiently , the real problem will be that RFID can be interfered by another RFID as well .
Furthermore , studies have shown that when RFID is implanted into mice , it causes the growth of tumour around RFID ( Wasserman , 2008 ) . RFID not only poses a risk to patients , but intensive exposure can be hazardous to a healthy individual too .
Hence , RFID can be a health hazard ; thus , it should not be used .
Opposition argues that with CCTV cameras , criminals will be aware that they are being watched and so the crime rate is reduced .
However , this is not necessarily true .
London has more than ten thousand CCTV cameras ; however , eighty percent of the crimes are left unsolved ( Davenport , 2007 ) .
This substantially supports that surveillance technology does not reduce the crime rate and enhance public security .
To conclude , surveillance technology should not be used as it not only can not help solve crimes and maintain order , it also poses a health threat to the people using it and around it as well .
Shop outlets , employers and even potential crime-doers can use RFID to prey on their desired targets , hence intruding upon their privacy .
Firstly , stores can use RFID to track and identify customers without their awareness and pricey items discriminatively .
The opposition can claim that there is an existing employment law and privacy act to protect employees ' privacy interests .
The law states that an employer is entitled to monitor worker movements and conduct during working hours , so long as the means employed are fair and reasonable and do not unjustifiably disadvantage employees ( Roth 2006 ) .
However , the opposition may argue that another novel surveillance technology will probably be invented to counter against such criminals .
Also , a vicious cycle will be created by the criminals using RFID to attack their targets , followed by the police using RFID to detect those criminals .
In conclusion , the use of RFID to track people should be banned , not only because it violates an individual 's privacy but also because it could encourage more potential criminals to commit atrocities and stir up the greed within businessmen .
In the 21st century , the superman is not the only one who has the power to what is in your bag without asking you , but ordinary people can also have the power to do so. .
By implanting a chip to human body or attaching a tag to a product , the information of a certain person or an object can be scanned easily by a scanner .
However , does a child really want his or her parents to track him or her all the time ?
The convenience and problems this technology brings to us make it hard for us to decide whether it should be legal to track people by using the technology .
Firstly , the RFID technology is still immature , which means we can not guarantee both the accuracy of information we get and the safety of these chips implanted in our body .
Actually , when two or more readers want to scan the same tag , the " signals from their scanners may overlap " which will leave the tag " unable to reply " ( Reported on Techonovelgy.com ) .
When you are implanted with a RFID chip or when you take some objects with RFID tags , the information about your location , your purchase list and so forth can be easily disclosed .
The RFID supporters may argue that a lot of protection is provided in this case .
Thirdly , it is purposeless to track everyone .
It is true that RFID is really helpful for finding lost children or tracing thefts .
It will be meaningless and costly to track everyone just in case some of them may get lost someday .
Based on the three reasons above , RFID is not reliable enough to give correct information about the tracked person .
Meanwhile , it may invade users ' privacy .
Finally , it is costly as well as unnecessary to track people .
It is widely used to monitor an individual 's activities and behaviors , for instance , to reduce theft or to enhance security .
RFID will be the focus in this context .
RFID stands for " Radio-Frequency Identification , " which is a technology that uses radio waves to identify people or objects .
The use of RFID tags on products and humans have raised concerns for unauthorized access and invasion of privacy ( Sottile , 2005 ) .
However , I do not agree that surveillance technology such as RFID should not be used in tracking people because of its important benefits like the prevention of children kidnapping and the improvement of elderly health care .
Mexico ranks the second highest for the number of abductions in each year ( McHugh , 2004 ) .
As the kidnapping rate in Mexico rises , a Mexican firm implemented RFID implants to prevent kidnapping .
Xega , a security firm , offered RFID implantation to help in locating kidnap victims and it has proven to be successful as the business is booming ( Rosenberg , 2008 ) .
In addition , a fashion designer Lauren Scott came out with a line of children 's clothing that uses the RFID tag devices to track a child that has been taken more than 30 feet beyond their home .
Although the parents can keep track of their children through a RFID reader , the safety of children is more important than their privacy .
Thus , RFID can be used to track a child as it can prevent kidnapping .
Researchers from the Georgia Institute of Technology and Intel Research Seattle found out that the caregivers can monitor the seniors ' daily activities through the data received via internet from the RFID readers and record when and which tagged items they have picked up ( Baard , 2004 ) .
This also means that the elderly will lose their privacy as to what they need and what they do .
However , caregivers need the real-time data and the record of an individual 's normal daily routine to identify any significant changes which , according to physicians and experts on aging , often indicate onset of illness and cognitive decline ( Baard , 2004 ) .
Therefore , the use of RFID to track seniors ' daily routine can improve their health care through early detection of health problems when they are at home .
In conclusion , RFID is useful to track children 's activities and seniors ' daily routine to prevent kidnapping and improve health care respectively .
Therefore , surveillance technology such as RFID should be used to track people as some of its benefits are more important than privacy and freedom concerns .
The use of surveillance technology to track people has become possible due to the advancement in technology .
Even though the use of RFID in human tracking could help to improve on the safety and security , there are several threats such as privacy and health hazards that we need to consider .
Therefore , RFID should not be used to track people when threats outweigh the benefits .
One of the main concerns on RFID tracking would be privacy .The use of RFID tags on consumer products could track humans in an indirect way .
The benefits go to the manufacturers and retailers but not to the consumers as the ability to keep track of the products that every single consumer bought would expose the identity of the consumer and intrude upon one 's privacy .
( Hamblen ,2007 ) In hospital , RFID implants have been used to store patients ' clinical information with the claim that they could help to improve medical services .
It is very hard to ensure that patient 's personal information is solely used for clinical purposes .
Both of the previously mentioned usages of RFID face the same distinct problem which is third party tracking .
This is mainly due to the fact that as long as one 's antenna could receive the same frequency as the RFID tag , he would be able to track all the information .
The other main concern would be the health hazards .
According to some of the studies conducted on tissue reactions to microchip implants in laboratory animals , 0.8 % to 10.2 % of laboratory mice and 2 dogs developed malignant tumors caused by implant chips .Although the tests were not done on humans , the result is relevant to humans as humans are naturally subject to malignant tumor in response to foreign body implant .
( Albrecht , n.d. ) One might argue that health hazards could be eliminated if RFID tag is used to replace the implant chips .
Long term exposure to electromagnetic fields emitted by the antenna could be another health hazard that could not be treated lightly .
In conclusion , RFID usage in human tracking is not as simple and beneficial as we may have thought of .
There are a lot of hidden threats such as privacy issue and health hazards which we should really consider .
There is an increase in the use of surveillance technology such as radio-frequency identification ( RFID ) these days especially in passports and hospitals .
These uses of surveillance technology have in many cases , brought about many benefits to mankind but there is also an increasing call for the ban of the usage of surveillance technology to track people as many are concerned with the loss of privacy and the exploitation of personal information .
opponents of this position argue that RFID-installed passport is in fact , less secure than normal passport as anyone may be able to attain someone else 's personal information with an RFID-reader .
They further argue that information in passports can easily be copied and embedded into a forged passport ( Campbell , 2004 ) .
Although the use of surveillance technology in passports may not be perfect , with the rapid advancement in technological research , continuous improvement can be done in order to further enhance the security aspect of a passport .
RFID have proven to be very useful as medical staff will be able to access the patients ' medical and personal information quickly anywhere with just an RFID-reader ( Stein , 2006 ) .
This enables doctors to get to know patients ' medical condition quickly especially in time of emergency and also allows the patient 's family members to be contacted immediately .
To complete a RFID system , a tag which is known as transponder and a reader which is known as a transceiver is used used .
In the case of accidents , the supervisors can get information on the numbers of trapped miners in the mining fields ( KJ-241 personnel and equipments Locating system for mining , 2007 ) and through this be able to plan evacuation routes .
This will greatly increase the efficiency in dealing with emergency .
Therefore , hospitals staff are able to track patients ' movements using the RFID bracelets on them .
The most controversial issue in the used of RFID to track people is the invasion of privacy .
However , the use of RFID to store information can bring about much convenience and efficiency in hospitals .
There are views that it should be allowed on the grounds that such tracking devices actually bring about many benefits , but these benefits come at a heavy price ; our privacy and rights .
Thus the use of surveillance technology should not be allowed .
the installation of surveillance devices is getting common and it is actually a demonstration of the lack of trust between the management and the employee .
The productivity of the employee is a major concern of the company .
Such devices enable the management to keep an eye on the employees ' activities making sure that it is in compliance with the company guidelines and the performance of their duties .
However , the implementation of such a measure by the management is a violation of the employees ' rights and privacy .
It will inevitably strain the relationship between the 2 parties and affect employee commitment and motivation towards their work .
In the end the productivity of the company will suffer as well due to the drastic change in the work culture .
Many surveillance devices like RFID are actually capable of storing information , and hospitals have used it in tagging patient with critical conditions .
The advantage of it is that all the vital medical history of the patient can easily be retrieved if there is a need for emergency procedure .
That would save a lot of preliminary assessment procedures and help avoid many unnecessary complications like allergies .
On the surface the ability of the devices to save life seems remarkable , but it has serious risks of being abused .
The use of such sophistical technology no doubt preserves the integrity of these data , but it gave rise to the concern being tagged against one 's will to be remained employed .
The implantations process is a " quick and relatively simple procedure " , but the removal of it is not .
These chips might migrate over the years or may have been placed too deeply .
It is still commonly used for tagging of endangered animals to aid in the study of their behavior in order to preserve their population .
Such technology has now being shifted from the animals and to be used on humans it is very degrading and this act displays a total lack of respect towards the tagged personnel .
In conclusion , the use of surveillance technology on tagging tagging people people poses a very high risk in leaking out personal privacy data and it is an invasion of personal privacy .
The removal of an implanted chip was not easy even if one wishes to reverse it .
Nowadays in this fast-paced society , everything is required to be precise .
Managers want their employees ' location at anytime ; retailers need information of customers in the store and policeman need identification of the suspicious at the spot .
Therefore , with the emergence of surveillance technology such as RFID , which allows automatic identification of objects , animals or people by incorporating a small electronic chip on its " host " ( Europe 's Information Society , n.d. ) , people 's accurate location can be tracked and returned in time .
This results in furious debate in the society since it brings potential problems about privacy .
no main clause
Companies can make a standard on working time according to the conditions of the workers by putting an RFID tags on the them ( Barker , 2009 ) .
Moreover , for retail companies , RFID is also a possible tool for them to reduce theft and sabotage .
Therefore , RFID can help to keep company assets as well .
On important occasions , when there are a large number of people involved , it is nearly impossible for police and security staff to identify the criminals when crime occurs .
However , with the help of the surveillance technology , policeman can identify the crinimals very fast and catch them or pay attention to the suspicious at first to prevent the crime before it can be committed .
They argue that the potential threat of RFID is substantial since it contains so much private information . Therefore , the abuse RFID will lead to serious consequences .
However , legislation is already in place at national level and data protection authorities have been established to safeguard the unauthorized use of personal data ( RFID Consultation , n.d. ) .
Furthermore , the authorities have elaborate working documents on Data protection Issues about RFID to rigorously guide RFID deployers on application ( RFID Consultation , n.d. ) .
In conclusion , it is apparent that the surveillance technology such as RFID to track people is a useful tool in this modern society .
Additionally , it is an effective effective way for policemen to identify criminals and prevent crimes at the beginning .
Thus , if we can utilize this kind of surveillance technology more appropriately and keep more strict regulation on its application , it will surely be supported worldwide .
As the application of surveillance technology such as RFID is becoming more common and widespread , the community has raised an that the tracking of people of tracking people using these surveillance technologies will harm human rights .
However , I think that the benefits of such surveillance technologies outweigh the cost cost of intruding human 's privacy .
There are several applications of surveillance technologies in the medical field .
This RFID chip plays an important role in letting doctors to access to the patients ' medical information when the patients are incapable to communicate ( Ahuja,A. , 2006 ) .
Furthermore , surveillance technologies can also be used to improve the social security .
In the same time , the United States also implemented the use of surveillance technologies in their prison to control the violence rate .
In addition , these surveillance technologies are also very effective during rescue operations or investigations .
An implanted RFID chip can help the rescue team or investigation team to identify the deceased in case they are disfigured or trapped .
As an example , during the 911 incident rescue operations , the firefighters wrote their badge numbers on their arms so that they could be identified in case they were disfigured or trapped ( { Kanellos } [ HYPERLINK : mailto : michael.kanellos @ cnet.com ] ,M. , 2004 ) .
Although applying surveillance technology on people might lead to the harming of human rights , we can minimise this situation by raising the security level of these RFID chip by encrypting the information it contains .
With surveillance technology , such incidents can be prevented .
Similar situations can be seen in the military vehicles in Singapore .
The opponents of surveillance technology argue that surveillance technology invades privacy .
